CONFERENCE ON </H1>

<H1>DRUGS: DEPENDENCE AND INTERDEPENDENCE</CENTER> <BR>
</H1>

<P>
<CENTER>
<H2>Lisbon, 23 - 25 March 1996</CENTER> <BR>
</H2>
<HR>

<P>
<CENTER>
<H1>THEME N&#186;12 - <B><A NAME="theme2"></A><A NAME="theme6"></A><A NAME="theme8"></A><A NAME="theme9"></A><A NAME="theme10"></A><A NAME="theme11"></A><A NAME="theme12">INFORMATION</A>
SHARING</B></H1>

<P>
The need for up-to-date information on the political, economic
and ecological aspects of drug production
<H3><A HREF="#bianco">Lucia BIANCO - Italy </A> </CENTER></H3>

<H3><A NAME="theme3"></A>Contribution by Lucia BIANCO - Italy
</H3>

<H3>Introduction</H3>

<P>
In theory, at least, the connection should by now be established
between activities linked to the production of, and illicit trafficking
in, drugs and economic, political, social, cultural and ecological
environmental factors concerning the relationship between rich
and poor countries, between North and South.  But this has not
been translated into practical policy or other measures.  Only
a comprehensive approach to the problem of the production, trafficking,
use and abuse of drugs, which also takes into account the relationship
between North and South and global prospects for economic, social
and cultural development, can lead to positive results - whereas
the sectoral and almost exclusively punitive policies pursued
so far are only making the problem worse.
<P>
From this point of view, the dissemination of reliable, rapid
and constantly updated information on the subject is of the utmost
importance, so that increasingly global, integrated strategies
may be adopted for combatting illicit drugs at the following levels:

<UL>
<LI>policy-makers and officials;
<LI>technicians and specialists in the sector;
<LI>the grassroots.
</UL>

<P>

<P>
In order to achieve this aim, it is essential to tackle a number
of fundamental problems:
<P>
1. First of all, it must be acknowledged that scientific data,
relating to illicit drugs and traditional indicators of their
production, trafficking and use, are vital but not sufficient
for understanding all of the problems linked to drugs, both in
producer countries and in consumer countries - even though producer
countries are consuming more and consumer countries are producing
more, especially the synthetic drugs now invading international
markets.
<P>
2. Secondly, it must be established how, in the framework of media
strategies, it is possible to obtain a global and broad view of
the problem, that can bring out the inter-connection between the
production of illicit drugs, economic and social development policies
(in both producer and consumer countries), environment protection
policies, the cultural and anthropological aspects of the use
of such substances, the rights of minorities, the strategies of
criminal organisations and the mafia and, last but not least,
the machinery for laundering money earned through drug trafficking.
 For this purpose, the quantitative data available are highly
reductive and susceptible to manipulation, and must necessarily
be assessed along with qualitative data.  For example, when assessing
the ecological impact of coca cultivation in Andean countries,
it is not enough to consider only the area used to grow coca;
this quantifiable fact must also be put into perspective with
qualitative data: the regions where it is grown, the people growing
it, the means they use, etc.
<P>
3. It must also be established how accurate, correct and reliable
information may be obtained on goods illegally produced for illicit
markets and consumption, for example those drugs considered as
illegal by the 1988 United Nations Convention against Illicit
Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances; which information
sources may be considered reliable in this field: the governments
of producer countries, those of consumer countries, international
organisations (United Nations, WHO, UNESCO, etc), the police,
NGOs, specialised research and study centres, journalists, etc;
and who, and on the basis of which criteria, should select, monitor
and establish the reliability of those sources.
<P>
4. It must also be decided who may have access to this information
and how the information may be disseminated, not only among policy
makers or police forces but also among the grass roots who, in
this way, can be involved in monitoring the strategies implemented
by governments and international organisations to combat the misuse
of legal and illegal drugs - covering not only the stamping out
of narcotics trafficking, prevention and the social rehabilitation
of those involved but also development alternatives in producer
countries.
<P>
5. Finally, ways must be found of keeping open as many information
sources as possible while making them comparable, since data are
often collected in accordance with the aims of the organisations
doing the collecting and the analyses carried out are often founded
on preconceptions or partial data instead of being based on a
scientific research method.  The more approaches there are to
the problem, the broader the vision, the less the bias and the
smaller the risk of an ideological assessment of these phenomena.
<H3>Strategies implemented nationally and internationally</H3>

<P>
Although our list is by no means exhaustive, we shall be outlining
certain strategies and initiatives for the collection, comparison
and exchange of information used so far at various levels.  In
any case, it must first be stated that, despite the national European
and worldwide projects launched, the statistics available to date
have not been homogenous, have often been gathered according to
criteria which render comparison impossible, are often not scientifically
reliable and are difficult to come by.  In many cases, they have
proved limited, as they are essentially based on quantitative
rather than qualitative information.
<P>
At the same time, the data that are available concern, above all,
the phenomenon that we might define as &quot;the tip of the iceberg&quot;,
in other words the number of arrests and convictions for the production,
trafficking and sale of illicit drugs, the quantity of substances
confiscated by the police, not forgetting drug addicts being treated
by public or private bodies and statistics on deaths from drugs
overdoses.  On the other hand, when it comes to what might be
described as the &quot;submerged part of the iceberg&quot;, in
other words, the amount of land cultivated for the production
of illicit drugs, the economic dimensions of the market and trafficking
in narcotics and the overall scale of drug use, we only have estimates,
of varying reliability, or data which are often contradictory.
<P>
We often find a great lack of homogeneity between data from official
sources (governments, police forces, international organisations)
and data gathered by specialists in the sector, special centres,
NGOs and the grass roots.
<P>
In fact, there is virtually no pooling of or complementarity between
the various types of data which might help to build up a complete
picture of the phenomenon, ie:
<UL>
<LI>specific quantitative indicators relating to the &quot;tip
of the iceberg&quot;;
<LI>contextual or qualitative data: information on social, political,
economic, cultural and environmental variables conditioning developments
in the production, trafficking and use of illicit drugs in different
parts of the world;
<LI>data concerning localised operations conducted by the grass
roots and NGOs, facilitating a more qualitative approach based
on the actual experience and perceptions that local organisations,
&quot;producers&quot;, &quot;consumers&quot;, etc may have of
the problem.
</UL>

<P>

<P>
But, as mentioned before, experiments and attempts at liaison
or the comparison, continuous updating and dissemination of information
are being carried out at various levels.  An important example
is undoubtedly the European Monitoring Centre for Drugs and Drug
Addiction (EMCDDA), through the activation both of national networks
of special centres by &quot;focal points&quot; and of the European
REITOX network, which are due to be linked up with other international
bodies dealing with this subject: UNDCP, WHO, Pompidou Group,
CCC, EUROPOL and INTERPOL.  There are also other information exchange
systems dealing with the prevention of drug trafficking, such
as Teledrug, Dosis, Interpol, Europol and others, all accessible
to the police forces of the countries linked to them.
<P>
The United Nations, on the other hand, publishes yearly Human
Development Reports compares and contrasts social, political and
economic data as well as information on the respect of rights,
in order to determine the level of human development in various
countries in the world.
<P>
Among NGOs, in the North and South alike, several gather data,
focusing on their activities in the sector - the Northern and
Southern countries where they work - and there have been experiments
in their liaison aimed at a continuous exchange of data, nationally
or at European or international level, such as the European Committee
of Drugs and Development NGOs, the network of NGOs which took
part in the European Information Campaign &quot;Coca 95&quot;,
the Geopolitical Drugs Observatory, Acci&oacute;n Andina, NGO
Committees (including the NGOs recognised by the United Nations)
etc.  Alongside them, UNESCO, thanks to dissemination of the ISIS
data gathering programme, has offered an efficient instrument
for collecting and exchanging information: through it, information
exchange networks have already been established, mainly for exchanges
between NGOs.
<P>
Another reality which must be taken into account is that of the
information already available on INTERNET:
<UL>
<LI>a number of activists involved in the reform of drug policies
are linked up to information about their own organisations and
activities (the Cannabis Action Network, the Multidisciplinary
Association for Psychedelic Studies, The Drug Reform Co-ordination
Network, etc);
<LI>In the field of drugs policies, one of the most comprehensive
networks is the one run by the International Foundation for Drug
Policy and Human Rights, which contains information on the relevant
policies pursued by The Netherlands and those of other European
countries and the United States.  The United Nations support the
International Narcotics Control Board Web, in liaison with the
Commission on Narcotic Drugs, etc;
<LI>as for the use and abuse of drugs, networks have been set
up by official organisations such as the National Clearing House
for Alcohol and Drug Information, a section of the United States'
Department of Health and Human Services, and others set up by
NGOs or even anonymous persons, such as the WWW Drug Information
Server;
<LI>there are other information pages on risk limitation strategies,
such as the Habit Smart Agency and the Netherlands Drug Text Site.
</UL>

<P>

<P>
What all of these information systems have in common is that they
rely on sources that cannot be checked, since it is not clear
who rung the Internet services or who guarantees the reliability
of the data entered into them.  Most of the initiatives we have
listed offer no global and qualitative information on the production,
trafficking and use of illicit drugs and nor are they able to
set up connections between North and South.
<H3>Some ideas on alternative strategies and practices</H3>

<P>
Both locally and internationally, where there is an overdose of
information and sources distributing information, it is increasingly
difficult to find adequate information -by which we mean information
on the production of illicit drugs, although the same goes for
other fields - and strategies must be developed for liaison, and
the comparison, updating and dissemination of data, designed to
guide everyone, at various levels (local and national government,
international organisations, public and private social workers,
NGOs, grass roots associations), involved in the effort to find
responses to the problems linked to the production, distribution
and use of narcotic drugs, legal or illegal.
<P>
It is not easy to find global solutions to the problem - and it
would be extremely arrogant to think that we can - or out of the
blue to activate information resources that are coordinated and
founded on the same scientific bases or methods for data collection.
 Yet, it is possible to establish a procedure for the collection
and dissemination of information on the production of drugs making
proper use of and developing the existing information networks
and taking account of the following elements, vital for constructing
the methodology:
<UL>
<LI>a global approach to the phenomenon of the production, trafficking
and use of legal and illegal drugs, taking into account the political,
cultural, social, economic and ecological aspects of the problem;
<LI>a co-ordinated assessment of qualitative and quantitative
data on the phenomenon;
<LI>constant comparisons between governmental and nongovernmental
sources;
<LI>constant comparisons between North and South, between producer
countries and consumer countries;
<LI>the data and information collected must be operational; in
other words, they must be designed so that those using them can
determine coherent actions to deal with the gravity of the phenomenon
and assess their impact;
<LI>the scientific reliability of the collection of data;
<LI>accessibility to data.
</UL>

<P>

<P>
Undoubtedly, for this purpose we must bring into operation as
soon as possible the European Monitoring Centre for Drugs and
Drug Addiction (EMCDDA) and develop it.  At European level and
internationally, this Centre could become an increasingly important
reference point for creating a culture, influencing opinion and
ensuring the reliability of data, and enabling everyone working
in North and South, governments, NGOs and international organisations
alike to coordinate their efforts.
<P>
However, on this score, it must be made clear that NGOs in North
and South working on the subjects of the production, marketing,
trafficking and use of drugs should be granted a fundamental role
at the EMCDDA.  Until now, their role and their possibility of
liaising with the Centre have been mainly left to local governments,
often guilty of partiality and not always willing to accept a
plurality of information or of assessment of data on the phenomenon,
since that might throw their own policies into crisis.  Such an
approach, often ideological rather than practical, makes it difficult
to find effective responses to the ever more serious problems
arising in these fields.  After all, by their very nature, NGOs
are able to collect information that could meet the criteria of
usability, globality and high quality which, as we have already
said, are vital for the construction of a network for disseminating
information on the subject.  At the same time, they are a mouthpiece
of the grassroots and the general public and, as such, may genuinely
represent those who experience the problems linked to the production,
use and trafficking of drugs, as well as those who want to play
an active part in the process of change.
<P>
We must also hope for the creation of an NGO committee in the
ECMDDA - representing both European and Southern or Eastern countries
- which could ensure liaison and oversee the assessment and dissemination
of information on the subject gathered in the North and South.
 Since the NGO community working in the sector represents a very
wide range of ideologies and since ideology influences their practical
activities, criteria for selecting NGOs for membership of this
committee must be established.  
<H3>Recommendations</H3>

<P>
By way of conclusion, in response to the questions analysed in
the previous paragraphs, we would like to make some recommendations
concerning the collection, continuous updating and dissemination
of information on the production of drugs.
<P>
1. A global approach must be adopted for dealing with the production,
trafficking and use of legal and illegal drugs, taking into account
the political, cultural, social, economic and ecological aspects
of the problem.  We feel it is important to emphasise that the
phenomenon of the use of substances defined as narcotics because
of the way they act on the individual (physically, psychologically,
in terms of relationships, etc) cannot be understood in all its
complexity if analysis is limited to illicit substances.
<P>
2. It is crucial to analyse together quantitative and qualitative
data on these phenomena in order to reduce the risk of bias and
manipulation and to make sure that they are useful for developing
appropriate intervention strategies.
<P>
3. It is crucial to effect constant comparisons between data from
governmental agencies (central and regional offices of national
governments, police forces, international organisations) and non-governmental
agencies between North and South, between producer countries and
consumer countries.  This can guarantee a genuine pluralism of
information sources and also make it possible to move from a multicultural
approach to another approach, transcultural or intercultural,
so that exchanges on these subject can transcend cultural, ideological
and ethnic barriers, etc.
<P>
4. Constant care must be taken to ensure that the data and information
collected are usable, in other words that they are such as to
enable those handling them to work out coherent measures for dealing
with the gravity of the phenomenon and assess the impact of strategies
already pursued to deal with the problem.
<P>
5. The scientific accuracy of data collection must be guaranteed,
in other words information or data may be integrated in an information
dissemination circuit only if the source, methodology, cultural
and ideological premises and goals for which the information was
collected are declared.
<P>
6. Data accessibility must be guaranteed, in other words politicians
(both government and opposition), civil servants, technicians,
those working in the public and private social services, NGOs
and the grass roots must be able to access the sources and monitor
the information.
<P>
7. The fundamental role played by grass roots NGOs, especially
local NGOs in the producer countries of the South, in the collection
and dissemination of information on this subject must be recognised
and encouraged.
<P>
8. The capacity of existing information networks must be increased
and fully used, and they should be brought into communication
with each other.
<P>
9. The European Monitoring Centre for Drugs and Drug Addiction
must be brought into action more quickly in order to create a
nerve and reference centre, amid the often chaotic plurality of
information sources on the subject of drugs.  The EMCDDA could
act, not only Europe-wide but also internationally, as a reference
centre increasingly creating a culture, influencing opinion, ensuring
the reliability of data and providing co-ordination between those
working in the North and the South, governments, NGOs and international
organisations.
<P>
10. It is fundamentally important to establish, through a committee
of NGOs working as a main partner of the ECMDDA, a system for
the communication and exchange of information between the European
Centre and non-governmental bodies and individuals in the North
and South which can be independent of national governments, so
as to avoid ideological bias and provide a link between the European
Union, local structures and ordinary citizens.
<H4>Note:</H4>

<H5>(1) Green L.A. Internet Resources: Finding Information About
Drugs, Crime and Health Through the World-Wide Web, in Newsbriefs,
May 1995, pp. 15 - 18:</H5>

</BODY>

