<center><H1><A NAME="DDE_LINK1"></A><A NAME="DDE_LINK2"></A> INTERNATIONAL
CONFERENCE ON </H1>

<H1>DRUGS: DEPENDENCE AND INTERDEPENDENCE</CENTER> <BR>
</H1>

<P>
<CENTER>
<H2>Lisbon, 23 - 25 March 1996</CENTER> <BR>
</H2>
<HR>

<P>
<CENTER>
<H1>THEME N&#186;3 - <B><A NAME="theme2">TRADE AND AGRICULTURE
</A> </B></H1>

<P>
Global macro-economic policies, trade policies (WTO), agricultural
policies
<H3><A HREF="#dufumier">Marc DUFUMIER - France </A>- <A HREF="#renebteria">Ib&aacute;n de REMENTER&Iacute;A - Peru </A>
</CENTER></H3>

<H3><A NAME="theme3"></A>Contribution by <A NAME="dufumier">Marc
DUFUMIER </A>- France</H3>

<H3>''Can we stamp out illegal drug crops in the Third World?''
</H3>

<P>
Despite the crackdown on illicit drug producers and dealers, increasingly
large areas are given over to the production of cannabis, poppies
and coca in the poorest regions of the Third World.
<P>
For a long time, these plants were sown or propagated for individual
consumption by the growers in the same way as many cereals, tubers
and fibre plants. Even today, many of the rural communities in
the &quot;Golden Triangle&quot; (Myanmar, Laos and Thailand) still
smoke opium for its analgesic effects in the event of severe pain.
Similarly, coca is traditionally grown in the low Andean valleys
of the Amazon Basin (Peru, Bolivia, etc.) for strictly medicinal
or religious purposes. Coca leaves, which are rich in vitamins
and minerals, are used to make herbal teas, providing a completely
legal remedy for altitude sickness. Coca leaves are also frequently
chewed by undernourished communities to stave off hunger.  Similarly,
khat is grown in Ethiopia and Yemen to suppress the hunger of
the poorest farmers, and enable them to work all day without too
much discomfort.  As for cannabis, it is often used to flavour
soups in south-east Asia, a practice which is in no way frowned
upon.
<P>
In recent decades, the farmers of the most isolated regions have
become involved in international trade.  The &quot;drug&quot;
plants which they used to grow for their own use, and to sell
in local markets, have now become true &quot;cash crops&quot;,
grown for export in the same way as tea, coffee and cocoa in other
parts of the world.  The sale of the drugs made from these plants
has not always been illegal; up until 1956 the French government
awarded itself the monopoly of the trade in opium from French
Indochina, via a body set up specifically for this purpose; the
<I>&quot;r&eacute;gie indochinoise de l'opium&quot;</I>, which
for a long time worked in a similar way to the <I>&quot;r&eacute;gie
des kifs et tabacs&quot;</I> in Morocco.  The fact is that new
outlets have been created by the internationalisation of trade
and the increasing demand for new derivative products (morphine,
heroin, cocaine, etc.), dealing in which is now strictly illegal.
<P>
Small Third-World farmers, whose equipment, in many cases, is
still manual (hoes, spades, picks, machetes, etc.), or drawn by
draught animals (ploughs, etc.), can no longer compete with cereal
farmers in large, industrialised countries whose farming methods
have long included mechanised, motor-driven and chemical systems.
 The productivity of poor farmers growing wheat, corn and rice
in inter-tropical regions is often a hundred times lower than
that of the major producers of the Paris Basin, the North-American
&quot;corn belt&quot; and the Mississippi Delta.  It is therefore
in the interest of many of these farmers to turn to the specialised
production of exclusively tropical commodities, for which there
is less direct competition from temperate regions, i.e. coffee,
bananas and rubber, but also opium and coca.
<P>
This kind of specialisation runs counter to the food security
of the populations in question, whose food is then largely dependent
on the importation of grain and flour which can be delivered for
less cost, even to the least accessible places.  However, it is
a direct result of the &quot;free&quot; trade policies followed
by governments and encouraged by international financial organisations
such as the IMF, World Bank, whose aim is to increase the variety
of types of agriculture in accordance with the &quot;comparative
advantages&quot; of different regions.  The problem is that the
most profitable products for export in the most remote regions
are, therefore, those for which a high price can be obtained for
the smallest volume possible, i.e. hashish, gum opium, cocaine
base paste, etc.  Is it not therefore contradictory to advocate
&quot;free&quot; exchange while at the same time prohibiting the
production and sale of commodities which best meet the criteria
of specialisation according to comparative advantages?  Is it
logical to impose the &quot;free&quot; importation of foodstuffs
on those whose production is declared to be &quot;illicit&quot;?
<P>
The fight against illegal drugs therefore presupposes that Third
World countries have the possibility of protecting their national
agriculture by means of tariffs (customs duty), in order to re-evaluate
(initially upwards) the price of food crops produced for domestic
markets.  However, this selective protection runs counter to the
structural adjustment plans recommended by international financing
organisations, and presupposes real political courage on the part
of the governments concerned, as the resulting rise in the cost
of food would first affect the urban population, who could be
expected to protest in anger at this.  However, this would be
much less traumatic than monetary devaluation, which would immediately
put up the cost of all imported goods, including equipment required
by farmers to update their farming methods.
<P>
Rural credit and input subsidy schemes must be resolutely implemented
to enable the poorest farmers to have access, at last, to the
equipment they need if they are gradually to increase their productivity
without adversely affecting the environment.  Real technological
research and development policies should also be encouraged for
those farmers in the poorest, most remote regions.  These farmers
need a relatively wide range of equipment, and must be able to
set up farming systems with high added value, combining rural
crafts, livestock and crop farming, without excessive specialisation.
 Priority must be given to anti-risk practices and to techniques
aimed at increasing the production of biomass and the recycling
of organic matter.  The increase in productivity obtained by using
new equipment should serve to generally increase the income of
farmers without resulting in the work force being driven out to
urban centres or virgin-forest areas.  In this way, the low-income
Andean farming communities would be able to improve their standard
of living without having to emigrate to the shanty towns of Lima
or La Paz or go down into the &quot;yungas&quot; to crush coca!
<P>
True land reform aimed at redistributing large estates to small
farmers would enable these farmers to set themselves up on the
most fertile land, which they have been deprived of for too long.
<P>
Productivity can be considerably increased by making intra-regional
transport easier.  All projects which aim to make it easier to
acquire beasts of burden, draught animals and carts serve to increase
production, and thus farmers' income, since the time saved in
travel and transport can be turned to good account in the fields,
for the direct purposes of production.  Facilitating intra-regional
trade between farmers whose productivity is much the same almost
always turns out to be more effective than opening up major roads,
the first result of which is to expose the least equipped farmers
to international competition.  Combatting the production of illicit
drugs presupposes that the ways in which small-scale farmers are
involved in trade are reconsidered so that these farmers can effectively
emerge from their &quot;underdevelopment&quot;.<HR>

<P>
<CENTER>
<H1>THEME N&#186;3 - <B>TRADE AND AGRICULTURE</B>  </H1>

<P>
Global macro-economic policies, trade policies (WTO), agricultural
policies
<H6>-  </CENTER></H6>

<H3>Contribution by <A NAME="renebteria">Ib&aacute;n de REMENTERIA
</A>- Peru</H3>

<H3>Introduction</H3>

<P>
In the field of North-South relations, three subjects are the
source of considerable tension: migration, drugs and the environment.
 Recent South-North migration in the post-war period and migration
from country to town in the south were initially the result of
a demand for cheap, unskilled labour and then became a way of
escaping poverty.  This paper does not deal with migration as
such, although it underlies much of what is said since immigrants
and their descendants, the marginalised groups ''par excellence'',
have brought natural drugs with them into the developed countries,
passing on the drug-taking habit, acting as import and distribution
agents and making up a sizeable proportion of users.
<P>
The drug problem becomes an international one - Shanghai Conference
of 1909 - once production is sited in one location catering for
consumption in another - ie the West, or in other words once a
world drug market has been established.  In addition, the delocalisation
of drug production shows that the growing demand by the West over
the last thirty years (1) has been satisfied almost exclusively
by natural drugs such as marijuana, cocaine and opiates, whereas
synthetic psychotropic drugs would appear to have a marginal role
in the illegal use and supply of drugs, in spite of the considerable
development of these substances by the pharmaceutical industry
over the same period (2).
<P>
For developing countries, the &quot;naturalisation&quot;, as it
were, of the use of psychotropic substances and the fact that
they are produced on their own territory has made the drug problem
a largely agricultural one, falling outside the economy.  However,
the agricultural production of drugs has not been caused by international
demand for psychotropic substances alone; a contributory factor
has been the poverty in the rural areas of developing countries
and the failure of traditional forms of agriculture on which they
depend economically.
<P>
There are two aspects to the failure of agriculture in the developing
countries: (a) the loss of food security and (b) the increasing
plundering of their renewable natural resources.  Thus, at the
end of the last decade, out of the 207 countries recognised by
the United Nations, only 28 did not have a deficit in cereals:
13 of the 23 industrialised countries and 15 of the 184 developing
countries.  Of these only Argentina, Hungary, South Africa and
Thailand are exporters whereas the US, Canada, France and Australia
account for 85% of net cereal exports.  In the last ten years,
the world has lost 1.8% of its forests, with the US losing 1.1%;
Canada regained 5.8% and the European Union 3.4%, whereas South
America lost 4.6%, Africa 3.6% and Asia 5.3%.  Forests are therefore
being replaced with inefficient farming and stockbreeding (forestry
operations in fact account for only 1-3% of tree felling in the
developing countries).
<H3>Local impact of international policies</H3>

<P>
In response to the constant increase in the use of and demand
for psychotropic substances, control policies in the post-60s
period were focused predominantly on suppressing the supply (production
and trafficking) of drugs - which proved effective in the industrialised
countries.  The reaction from the drug traffickers has been delocalisation
of the production of psychotropic substances in relation to traditional
markets and naturalisation of consumption.  This has proved to
be a very effective strategy for controlling the risks of legal
sanctions and minimising the costs.  Although the unit cost of
synthetic substances is much lower than that of natural drugs,
the cost of investing in equipment, installations and raw materials,
skilled labour and pharmaceutical technology is considerable in
comparison with the cost of sub-contracting agricultural production
and small or large-scale extraction of natural psychotropic substances
(3).  Moreover, control of these unlawful activities by the criminal
courts is clearly much more lax in the developing countries where
corruption costs are lower.  In short, the delocalisation and
naturalisation of the production and consumption of drugs, which
create the illicit international market and give the developing
countries a role to play in it, are consequences of international
control policies which have put greater emphasis on cutting off
supply than on prevention and treatment of drug abuse.
<P>
The main feature of international agricultural trade, where technically
speaking the production and trafficking of natural drugs fit in,
is the continual fall in food prices  there has been a 50% drop
in the last forty years due to the fact that industrialised countries
have been subsidising farmers and livestock breeders over the
last twenty years, on average to the tune of 44%.  When international
agricultural prices fall below their production costs, farmers
in developing countries, who receive few or no subsidies, and
who furthermore have to compete on their local and national markets
with subsidised imports, have no other &quot;logical&quot; option
but to minimise production costs by cutting down on the use of
agricultural technology available, and then, if they wish to achieve
&quot;economic viability&quot;, to make extensive use of land
and water resources, constantly extending the area they use for
farming and destroying in the process the forests and biodiversity
found therein.
<P>
The general answer from developing countries to the agricultural
policies of the developed countries has been to abandon agricultural
technology and over-exploit renewable natural resources.  The
specific answer from those countries which have the necessary
soil and climate has been to produce natural drugs.  Furthermore,
the great paradox of drug production is that it has a smaller
impact on the environment, since it offers a higher market value
while using fewer natural resources.
<H3>Proposals for alternative polices: towards a new agenda</H3>

<P>
In international relations, the question of psychotropic drugs
has been approached in two different ways: first, the view prevalent
in the industrialised countries that consumption cannot be controlled
unless the supply  ie production in the developing countries 
is cut off; secondly, the view in the developing countries that
drug production and supply cannot be controlled while there is
still a demand in the industrialised countries.  Operationally,
both arguments are valid for the current illicit market, but conceptually,
they are inadequate since they overlook two basic explanatory
facts: (i) suppression of illicit production in industrialised
countries generates demand and (ii) the agricultural and environmental
crisis in developing countries generates supply.
<P>
The illicit production of psychotropic substances has not been
relocated from industry to agriculture in developed countries,
because farmers in those countries have not become impoverished
nor have rural areas been untouched by modern technology.
<P>
Neither the problem of the illicit production of natural drugs
nor the problem of protecting the environment and natural renewable
resources can be resolved outside the international agricultural
market.  The new agenda in North-South relations must deal with
the problem of the production of natural drugs and the plundering
of renewable natural resources in the developing countries in
tandem with the agricultural policies of the developed countries
based on subsidised agricultural production.  It is this which
has led to the developing countries losing their competitive advantages
and has turned them from food exporters into food importers.
<P>
It should not be forgotten that if the supply of natural drugs
and psychotropic substances were to be controlled effectively
but without any control on demand in the developed countries,
then consumers would resort to solvents, petrol and alcohol to
satisfy their desire or need to alter their state of consciousness
or behaviour in the same way as the marginalised and children
do today in the developing countries.  All these substances  alcohol,
psychotropic and natural drugs, solvents and petrol - have the
same function, the ability to satisfy needs.  Consequently, if
there is no real efficient and proactive way to prevent the desire
and deal with the need for psychotropic substances and the only
approach is to seek to suppress the problem, we will witness a
constant change in the pattern of use  naturalisation or artificialisation
 and delocalisation of the production of psychotropic substances
depending on what the situation is regarding the suppression and
illegal supply of these drugs.
<H3>Recommended strategies for a new agenda</H3>

<P>
Alternative development is the only possible strategy for controlling
illegal drug cultivation since it is only in this way that the
poor farmers in the tropical regions of the Third World can escape
from the stranglehold put on them by international drug traffickers.
 Only then will drug traffickers be obliged to take over the risks
and costs involved in directly managing illicit drug cultivation
(which has already happened in some areas of the Andes) or be
obliged to take over the substantial industrial and financial
risks involved in the production of synthetic drugs (which has
also recently been seen).  However, it is not possible to achieve
any significant successes with alternative development, ie lasting,
environmentally-sound successes which can continue indefinitely
if there is no change in the current conditions of the international
agricultural market, which depend on the agricultural policies
of the industrialised countries.
<P>
A strategy for action should present the ecological advantages
of alternative development over drug cultivation, showing the
devastating impact which the agricultural policies of the north
have on the south.  The areas where this needs to be brought home
are primarily the ecological movement and the authorities responsible
for the environment.  Debates on these issues have given greater
prominence to environmental problems which have a less serious
impact on nature or which entail fewer risks for humanity such
as the green label campaign for wood products, the ban on hunting
aquatic mammals, nuclear tests, etc. thereby glossing over more
important and threatening problems such as the destruction of
forests and steppes (land biodiversity) as a result of inefficient
farming and stockbreeding, the over-fishing of seas, rivers and
lakes (aquatic biodiversity) and the pollution caused by processing
of catches, the increasing pollution of all environments caused
by industrial, agricultural, household and other waste, etc.
<H3>NOTES:</H3>

<P>
(1) A demand which began at the turn of the century and escalated
with the first signs of the current economic and cultural crisis
during the 60s and 70s.
<P>
(2) Of the psychotropic substances subject to control, some 180
are synthetic products or derivatives and only half a dozen or
so are natural.
<P>
(3) It should be stressed that the current expansion in the illicit
production of psychotropic substances, or their precursors, is
taking place primarily in the poorer countries of the Third World,
or in the new Third World made up of the former socialist countries
which are also producing natural drugs.
<P>
<B>:</B><HR>

</BODY>

