<CENTER><H1><A NAME="DDE_LINK1"></A><A NAME="DDE_LINK2"></A> INTERNATIONAL
CONFERENCE ON </H1>

<H1>DRUGS: DEPENDENCE AND INTERDEPENDENCE</CENTER> <BR>
</H1>

<P>
<CENTER>
<H2>Lisbon, 23 - 25 March 1996</CENTER> <BR>
</H2>
<HR>

<P>
<CENTER>
<H1>THEME N&#186;9 - <A NAME="theme2"></A><A NAME="theme6"></A><A NAME="theme8"></A><A NAME="theme9">LOCAL
CONFLICTS</A></H1>

<P>
Links between illegal drug production, trade in drugs and local
conflicts
<H3><A HREF="#alain">Alain LABROUSSE - France </A> - <A HREF="#synd">Imran Akbar SYED - Pakistan</A></CENTER>
</H3>

<P>
<B><A NAME="theme3"></A></B>
<H3>Contribution by <A NAME="alain">Alain LABROUSSE </A>- France
</H3>

<PRE>
<I><B>''Drug production and trafficking in local conflicts''</B></I>
</PRE>

<H3>Drug dealing patterns</H3>

<P>
The relationship between conflicts and drugs is as old as man's
use of &quot;mind-altering substances&quot;. Their use is mentioned
in the &quot;Iliad&quot;. From the Inca conquests to the &quot;Opium
Wars&quot;, with the <I>hashishiyun</I> guerillas in between,
drugs have been at the core of many conflicts throughout history.
Two facts account for this relationship: firstly the effect of
the substance on the warrior, whether to raise his fighting mettle
or blind him to danger, or after battle to dispel the extreme
tension born of contests often fought hand to hand. This relationship
still exists in modern local conflicts such as those in Lebanon,
Afghanistan, former Yugoslavia or Liberia. But today, owing to
the added value which drugs acquire through prohibition, warfare
and drugs are related essentially at the economic level.
<H3>Impact on the situation of producers</H3>

<P>
The drug-conflict relationship is dependent on one of the main
characteristics of trade in these prohibited substances, namely
profit escalation: in the production, processing and sale of drugs,
each stage (itself broken up into a multitude of intermediate
operations) has a large profit margin. The more numerous the processing
phases, the higher the profit escalation. In the case of cocaine,
from the producer to the consumer, the price is multiplied by
a thousand on average, and by one thousand five hundred for heroin.
According to the sociologist Alain Joxe, each of these stages
constitutes a nucleus of power, of military might, for soldiers
can be fed with any surpluses.
<P>
For Third World farmers living in conflict-stricken zones, drug
economics have several implications:
<P>
a) given that it is impossible for them to attain the upper echelons
of processing and marketing, they are paid only a tiny proportion
of the profits generated by the drug trade.
<P>
b) they must nevertheless pay the armed factions dues, in general
10%, on the proceeds of sale of the substances destined for use
as drugs (cannabis and khat) or transformation into drugs (coca
leaf, cocaine base, opium) [Colombia, Afghanistan, India, Philippines,
Senegal, Ethiopia].
<P>
c) they may even be forced to grow crops against their will [Peru,
Liberia, Burma].
<P>
d) they must try to survive in crop-growing areas which are often
fought over by the various contenders [Colombia, Peru, Afghanistan,
Burma].
<P>
e) it is notable that the forces of repression [when not actually
associates in the traffic - Peru, Burma] victimise drug farmers
doubly as producers of illicit substances and as accomplices of
the rebel movements (despite the &quot;protection&quot; which
the latter are supposed to give them [Colombia, Peru, Burma, Philippines].
<H3>Impact on the populations at large</H3>

<P>
Most guerilla movements are not content to levy dues on farmers'
production:
<P>
a) They extract levies from the collectors of the base product,
the processing laboratories and the transport networks [Colombia,
Peru, Burma, Afghanistan, India, Turkey, Somalia]. These practices
tend to criminalise the entire population of the areas where rebel
groups operate, and to aggravate the conflicts taking place there.
<P>
b) Other groups have assumed direct control of the laboratories
where drugs are prepared, with the same effect as in point a)
[Colombia, Burma, Turkey, Azerbaijan].
<P>
c) Certain groups look after transport and sale of drugs up to
and including the consumer countries [Sri Lanka, Turkey, former
Yugoslavia, Algeria]. In so doing they take advantage of overseas
communities with which they can merge. Because of this, their
activities do much to fuel the racism and xenophobia afflicting
their compatriots in the consumer countries.
<P>
d) Some of these groups come to form links with criminal organisations,
in particular to obtain weapons in exchange for drugs [Algeria,
Sri Lanka], thereby casting discredit on the cause of their entire
movement.
<P>
Implication of state secret services
<P>
Yet rebel groups are not alone in being implicated in the drug
trafficking associated with conflicts. Even during the Cold War,
the secret services of major powers (especially the United States)
covered up the activities of their allies in Vietnam, Central
America, Afghanistan and Lebanon. The novelty is the democratisation
of these practices, which tend to be adopted by the secret services
of the Third World countries themselves since the end of the Cold
War.
<P>
Use of narcotics trading profits by sectors of state administrations
may primarily serve ends of personal gain. This would seem to
be the case with the Peruvian troops fighting the Sendero Luminoso
(&quot;Shining Path&quot;) movement in the Huallaga valley of
the Amazon region, or certain Nigerian army officers. Usually,
however, drug money goes either to finance arms purchases - the
case of the Burmese junta (SLORC) using the arms to oppose ethnic
insurgency - or for operations to destabilise the enemy, as conducted
by the Pakistan army intelligence (ISI) to subvert India by the
supply of drugs and arms to the Sikh insurgents in the Punjab
and the Muslim rebels in Kashmir.
<H3>Alternative policies</H3>

<P>
Use of drugs as the sinew of conflicts is perhaps one of the fields
where it is most difficult to envisage alternative strategies,
as the root causes of war have to be tackled before all else.
<P>
a) For instance, the international community needs to abandon
the view that the war in Chechnya is exclusively a matter of Russian
internal affairs. There is no doubt that the continuation of this
conflict will influence the formation of criminal networks exploiting
the large Chechen diaspora (Jordan, Turkey) with the aim of funding
resistance. One means of combating drug trafficking is therefore
to rally civil society in the European countries behind a peaceful
solution to this conflict. The same applies to the Kurdish conflict
in Turkey.
<P>
b) Many countries' territories are the scene both of conflicts
and of activities linked to drug production and trafficking. Where
the governments of these countries or sectors of their state administration
are presumed to be implicated in the traffic, the international
community and the nations concluding political and/or economic
agreements with the countries concerned should make it a rule
to subject such agreements to conditions regarding drug traffic
and money laundering. [This type of approach, already employed
in the human rights and environment fields, is to be distinguished
from pressure to implement eradication policies aimed essentially
at the peasant producers].
<P>
By way of a practical example of situations where such policies
could apply in a multilateral relations context, let us mention
the negotiations surrounding Turkey's accession to the European
Union. This country has become the leading producer and exporter
of heroin for Europe, and its gangs play a prominent part in the
process of economic privatisation. In the context of bilateral
relations, there are the French arms sales to Pakistan and the
US and French oil investments (Total-Unocal) in Burma. Since government
policies are dictated as often as not by economic and geo-strategic
interests, the civil society of the European countries must press
for action on these issues by the politicians and the various
governments.
<P>
c) There is far more limited scope for action by the international
organisations and governments where the rebel movements are concerned.
Nonetheless, government and NGO support for demands which are
often legitimate (social or religious rights, respect for minorities,
etc) should be accompanied by pressure to refrain from certain
tactics, recourse to drug money included.
<P>
d) Civil society can avail itself of the argument that the arms
used in local conflicts are more and more frequently paid for
with drug proceeds to pressure governments into exercising more
stringent control over arms sales.<HR>

<H2>Contribution by <A NAME="synd">Imran Akbar SYED </A>- Pakistan
</H2>

<H3>''Links between illegal drug production, trade and local conflict''
</H3>

<H3>Introduction</H3>

<P>
The vast region of South-West Asia which includes India, Pakistan,
Iran, United Arab Emirates, Oman and the Arabian Sea/Gulf Regions,
has lately been considered as a precursor for international terrorism.
In this complicated configuration of religious, ethnic and sectarian
turmoil, which feeds a whole international market of political
and criminal violence, Pakistan is marked for its religious and
criminal hospitality for international terrorists and criminal
groups. The early beginning of unabated violence in the region
started along with the Iranian Islamic Shia change which claimed
more than 50.000 lives between the late 1970's and the early 80's.
<P>
It was followed by the Soviet intervention in Afghanistan and
the assorted geopolitical interests by the USA and its NATO allies
in Europe and the Middle Eastern royalties that launched the largest
intelligence operation, since the Vietnam war, amounting 6 US
billion $ in 8 years. The war in Afghanistan still continues though
officially the Soviet Union has fallen apart. A new trend of violence
has emerged escalating several wars between ethnic, sectarian
groups and nationalities. It was also during the years of the
Afghan war that the world's largest drug trafficking rings were
established dealing in heroin and morphine based processing amounting
to roughly up to 25 billion US $ per year from the region in South-West
Asia now identified as the &quot;Golden Crescent&quot;.
<P>
The result, emerging from the fifteen-year old Afghan conflict,
is the beginning of multi-conflicts in the region on ethnic, sectarian,
religious and nationalist grounds overflowing into Pakistan, India,
China, Iran and Kashmir, proves the massive use of drug money,
heroin production, opium harvesting and affiliated arms trafficking
in the region. What had begun, in the words of US Republican President
George Bush in 1980, &quot;God is with Afghans to defeat infidels&quot;,
in 1995 turned into several regional wars under controlled conditions
limiting to regional territorial disputes. In these existing conflicts,
the motivating reasons are external geopolitical interests and
the huge sums of money transacting from Europe, USA to the United
Arab Emirates and a perpetual effort for destabilisation.
<P>
These geopolitical interests, which range from petroleum companies
to small arms industries, to locate large water resources and
military routes to Central Asia, have created a social disorder.
Pakistan's only port city, Karachi, has witnessed massacres of
5000 persons in two years including those of women and children.
In Baluchistan, bordering Afghanistan, the Gulf and Iran, almost
the same number of massacres has been reported due to diverse
political, ethnic and government interests. In the North West
Frontier Province, nearly 2000 persons die every year in such
conflicts and this does not include Afghan conflict victims on
Pakistani soil. In Punjab, the largest province of the country,
revenge, territorial disputes and sexual discrimination claim
as many lives. This figure does not include political, sectarian
and ethnic rivalries. It is interesting to explain that the total
illiteracy rate in Pakistan is not more than 24% of the total
population of 112 million. Literacy here means those who can sign
their names. An average study shows that the total literacy rate
in the region does not exceed 30%.
<P>
In India, Kashmir could trigger a wave of ethnic, sectarian and
religious conflicts extending as far as the Chinese provinces.
Also in India, East Punjab could be explosive for Pakistan and
India because of the existing terrorist cooperation between Kashmiri,
Sri Lankan, Sikh and African fundamentalist and Muslim integrists.
Indian Narcotics control Board sources claim that in 1994, 154
kilos of heroin were seized from mujahideen routes of infiltrators
in Kashmir from the Pakistani border. On the Iranian frontier
with Pakistan, the Sunni minority movement, Sunni Milli Tehrik&eacute;
Iran, controls strategic zones against the Shia majority. Pakistan's
army is accused of protecting drug barons and trafficking, turning
the region into a pivotal point. At least 39 groups and parties
with theocratic tendencies could be alleged to be involved in
drug-trafficking in South-West Asia, following the fatwa by the
chief clergy of Kaaba, Saudi Arabia. He decreed the use of drug
money legible to combat infidels in a &quot;Mullah jirga&quot;
(Council of Clergy) in Jalalabad in 1983, beside the Pakistani
frontier in Afghanistan.
<H3>Current policies and conventions</H3>

<H4>Internal policies</H4>

<P>
It is more than ten years since different governments in Pakistan
started making amendments to the criminal penal code to include
severe punishments ranging from arrests, long-term prison sentences,
confiscation of properties of the accused and that of their relatives,
seizures of bank accounts and an under-studying proposal of capital
punishment. Furthermore, the creation of the Pakistan Narcotics
Control Board, its annexation in 1994, the creation of the Anti-Narcotics
Task Force, managed by the army, could be considered an integral
part of the anti-narcotics policy.
<H4>Regional conventions and accords</H4>

<P>
The regional states in South-West Asia have signed several anti-narcotics
accords and conventions within different regional cooperation
frame-works. These include the Non-Aligned Movement (NAM), South
Asian Alliance on Regional Cooperation (SAARC), Gulf Countries
Cooperation (GCC), Organisation of Islamic Conference (OIC), Regional
Cooperation and Development between Iran, Pakistan and Turkey
(RCD), and Central Asian Economic Cooperation (CAEC).
<H4>Interstate conventions</H4>

<P>
Pakistan has signed informal and formal protocols and conventions
with India, Mauritius, Iran, United Arab Emirates, Iran, Afghanistan,
Bangladesh, Sri-Lanka, Russia, Central Asia, Azerbaijan, Saudi
Arabia, Thailand and Nigeria. There are also accords between the
Central Asian republics and Turkey, Iran, India and Mauritius,
etc.
<H4>International conventions</H4>

<P>
Pakistan, India, Iran, Afghanistan, United Arab Emirates and Saudi
Arabia are also signatories of international accords such as the
UN Vienna Convention, USDEA, British Customs, European Community,
Organisation of African Countries (OAC) trafficking monitoring
and Francophone states.
<H3>Impact</H3>

<P>
There is no impact or very little impact by the nearly 20 such
treaties, accords, protocols and charters signed by the regional
states on drug-trafficking. There are multiple reasons for this
failure. However, the major issue remains the corruption in the
region which also affects anti-drug units of the &quot;developed
countries&quot; operating in the area. The best example could
be the failure by the USDEA, British intelligence and the French
authorities to come out with an open policy on drug traffickers
in the region regarding their international political affiliation.
Furthermore, the jargon of the &quot;national security interests
- NSI&quot; has been able to keep in safe custody explosive dossiers
on such mysterious cooperations and un-explained factors of the
NSI.
<P>
<B>Examples -</B> The drug trade is operating through two distinct
official and un-official channels today. The startling scenario
that is increasingly emerging is that the official organisations
set up to combat the illegal drug trade are being the means of
perpetuation through clandestine activities. The Pakistani counter-espionage
Inter-Services-Intelligence mounted an operation code-named &quot;jihad&quot;
and created the National Logistics Cell to traffic arms and heroin
during the Afghan war. This strategy, which brought in huge sums
of money, helped to buy new-age weapons demonstrated in two racist-neo-nazi
exhibitions in the USA between 1983-88. In Europe, notably in
Switzerland, such expos were organised by neo-nazi groups, fascist
organisations and extreme right wing anti-Semitic militants. The
South-West Asia freedom fighters are understood to have participated
and purchased short-range weapons amounting to nearly US$ ten
billion. It could be safely estimated that there could be more
than 4 million heroin addicts in the region in South West Asia.
<H3>Alternative policies and practices</H3>

<P>
Expert opinion suggests that the international, regional or inter-state
protocols are obsolete, dating back to the first General Agreement
on Tariffs and Trade (GATT) from the 1890s when the USA, China,
India, Turkey and Iran competed for the international narcotic-drugs
makers. These protocols started taking the shape of an International
Charter from The Hague Convention of 1911, and other such treaties
were politically motivated for colonial access to production and
consumer zones. The rest of the later treaties and charters are
only a prolongation of the colonial accords.
<P>
Treaties and agreements signed to curtail the drug problem have
taken no notice of the reality-based account of the growers. These
landless peasants, who work on a crop price percentage basis actually
get nearly 5% of the total cost of work. They are also like &quot;bonded
labourers&quot; who, from generation to generation, keep multiplying
mortgages to the area chiefs of tribes, or middle-men speculating
on future crops. Most of the middle-men or area chiefs are linked
to political-power lobbies within the governments as seen in Pakistan,
Thailand, India, Bolivia, Peru, Nigeria, Senegal, USA, etc. These
lobbies are linked with groups and lobbies of arms manufacturers,
members of parliaments and secret service agents at the international
level.
<P>
<I>The alternative crop schemes</I> are also a complete failure
with the exception of the pilot projects where international donor
agencies have vested interests to protect certain experiments
in a controlled environment or for data collection. Alternative
schemes like the farming of potatoes, onions or other fruit or
vegetable crops do not bring enough money for a bonded grower
even to buy a square meal a day, let alone the clothes, medicine
or arms to protect themselves from traditional tribal or ethnic
animosities. The result, in most cases, is a widening gulf between
the politico-military governments and those citizens considered
below the international level of poverty. This leads to military
operations for eradication and the money donated by developed
countries for reimbursement to growers, is embezzled by the area
chiefs with the complicity of government officials.
<P>
<I>Anti-Narcotics Agencies</I>, in order to demonstrate their
efficiency to their respective governments and parliamentarian
committees to acquire funds, recruit networks of unaware mules
with the complicity of drug barons as seen in cases in Britain
between 1983-1992. This method is used often when a certain agency
is in the process of making the demand for augmenting its budget
to fight consumption, drug abuse or trafficking. In this sort
of corruption, evidence is erased to protect the chain of drug-barons
who also work as informers and are often known to have political
or military clout in the producing or trafficking state. This,
in return, leads to an informal understanding permitting a certain
amount of drug trafficking in the consumer country. The USDEA
and the French anti-drug agency have also used such techniques.
The victims are recruited on a low percentage like a plane ticket
or hotel expenses. These mules are usually uneducated un-employed,
illiterates and those who simply are given a pocket or a suitcase
at the airport &quot;for a friend&quot;.
<P>
<B>It would be hard to counter such international mal-practices
and corruption among officials.</B> It is also necessary to develop
methods for an out-reach amongst the target-communities. Harsh
penalties have not stopped drug trafficking in states where capital
punishment is common. The difference between classes while planning
a communication or alternative strategies by officials also plays
an important role. The infrastructure of the constitution, administration,
bureaucracy, army, workers rights, human rights and economic policy
do not correspond to the native culture and ethics. In brief,
 a colonial structure which has been personalised on a country-to
-country basis becomes the main obstacle. This might require the
study of the local judicial system and social definitions organised
by councils (panchayat), jirga, fines, economic and barter practices.
<P>
This could only be made possible by establishing a communicator
between bodies' officials, district administrations and effected
groups. The economic gap in such countries has created a class
of experts with little field experience and very little knowledge
of regional, local and cross-border communication patterns. Even
if they are aware of such patterns, it is used against the will
of existing traditions. Traditions such as street theatres, folklore,
its concurrent interpretation and negligence of the social trends
needs to be corrected.
<H3>Strategies</H3>

<H4>Introduction</H4>

<P>
It is evident that <I>the colonial infrastructure cannot be abolished</I>
as this would mean the re-thickening of already existing regional
conflicts based on local, tribal, ethnic, sectorial and religious
norms. Several wars would be needed to settle these issues which
is not the purpose here. To formulate a comprehensive strategy,
it is imperative to devise subtle NGO workings, simplified communication
patterns and message-based economic ideas. This could be achieved
by the creation and use of the field groups to collect intelligence
which should be helpful in communicating the issues to the consumer
states. This would mean the dialogue at three levels: a) Between
the North and the South on an informal basis involving NGOs formed
on meagre resources and run by the local population, recommended
by the North-South field group; b) Between the government and
its functionaries to amend certain laws which only help in providing
large sums of financial assistance from donor agencies contributing
to the high level of corruption; c) To establish a simple communication
pattern already existent in regions between the above-categorised
NGOs to develop cooperation on a barter basis and to form larger
groups of jirga, panchayat and ethnic, caste and sectarian basis.
<H4>Local strategies</H4>

<P>
Such strategies would permit communities, groups and tribes to
start a dialogue, in return for controlled financial assistance
by the donor agencies thus eliminating the possibility of corruption.
These strategies would function through simple, small and controllable
NGOs formed in regions where linguistic dialects differ from one
region to another but the language remains the same. Several test
pilot projects should be envisaged on a controlled risk basis.
These NGOs, formed on recommendations by the North-South Centre,
should be controlled by the experienced and expert field staff
with higher degrees in international relations, ethnology, geopolitics,
micro-macro economic planning with Third World work experiences
in urban / rural transition areas. Students must be included as
part of the <B>alternative administration and communication strategy
training programme (AACTP).</B>
<H4>National level</H4>

<P>
This step could be considered difficult because of the prevalent
mistrust embedded in cultures of certain poverty-stricken regions.
To make things worse, these miseries are a lucrative exploitable
market for the federal, provincial governments and certain donor
agencies. In certain cases, the opposition to such ambitious projects
has come from the parliamentarians, police and the army who see
their zones of influence slipping away. To counter this, instead
of arm twisting through diplomatic effort, out reach is advised
by including in pilot projects members of low income groups from
the ruling tribe or area chief in order to allow cross-flow of
information / intelligence. A comprehensive communication plan
should be made available at the national level through the existing
infrastructure, maybe corrupt, of local government schemes launched
in the regions by the government on a need-to-know basis.
<H4>Regional strategies</H4>

<P>
Following the same infrastructure, a North-South Centre (NSC)
bureaux should be formed on a regional basis to study all social,
ethnic and religious differences existing in a cross-border format.
One example comes from India and Pakistan in a particular zone
of Kashmir which has been the cause of three wars between these
two countries. Another example is the differences between ethnic
Pashtoun and Uzbek identities in Afghanistan and Pakistan. To
achieve this, a maximised level of impartiality would have to
be maintained in order to let the population and the governments
themselves evaluate the staff involved in such projects.
<H4>International level</H4>

<P>
At this level, the North-South Centre is advised to circulate
inter-EU confidential memoranda in order to draw interest. Philanthropic
donor and human rights organisations / institutions are advised
to be contacted to form a protection blanket for pilot projects.
It is strongly advised to include in such projects 60% of women.

</BODY>

