<BODY>

<H1><CENTER> INTERNATIONAL CONFERENCE ON</CENTER> </H1>

<H2><CENTER>DRUGS: DEPENDENCE AND INTERDEPENDENCE</CENTER> <BR>
<CENTER></H2>

<H2>Lisbon, 23 - 25 March 1996</CENTER> <BR>
<CENTER></H2>

<H1>WELCOME</CENTER> </H1>

<P>
This International Conference will focus on the drugs issue from
a global interdependence perspective. It will have an important
educational, information and media component and will take an
integrated approach to this major cause of social disintegration.
The Conference will examine questions in a global interdependence
context and will culminate in policy and action proposals which
will take into account social and environmental objectives as
well as those concerning development and human rights.
<P>
<CENTER>
<P>
<A HREF="#background">BACKGROUND </A>- <A HREF="#objective">OBJECTIVES </A>-
<A HREF="themes.htm">THEMES </A>- <A HREF="program2.htm">PROGRAMME </A>-
<A HREF="#participation">PARTICIPATION </A>- <A HREF="#working">WORKING METHOD </A>-

<P>
<A HREF="#output">OUTPUT </A>- <A HREF="#followup">FOLLOW-UP </A>-
<A HREF="organs.htm">ADVISORY COMMITTEE </A>- <A HREF="themes.htm">AUTHORS AND CONTRIBUTIONS </A>-
<P>
<A HREF="#team">CONFERENCE MANAGEMENT TEAM </A>- <A HREF="program2.htm">PRACTICAL INFORMATION </A></CENTER>
<P>
-<HR>

<H3><A NAME="background">BACKGROUND</A></H3>

<P>
A number of factors have led to the organisation of this event,
namely:
<UL>
<LI>The North-South Centre's history of promoting an integrated
approach to North-South issues, its experience in fostering dialogue
among different partners and its effective awareness-raising activities
in Europe;
<LI>The Council of Europe Pompidou Group's history of adopting
a multidisciplinary approach to drugs and of playing a unique
role as natural intermediary between the various regional groupings
of countries in Europe;
<LI>The European Commission's meetings with policy-makers, scientists,
industry, NGOs, and others; its development of European policy
in this field and its establishment of the European Monitoring
Centre for Drugs and Drug Addiction (EMCDDA).
<LI>The European Parliament's debate on European drugs policy
and its expressed interest in organising an International Conference
to review drugs policies and programmes in a broader and integrated
context.
<LI>NGO interest in such a Conference and, in particular, the
interest shown by members of the European NGO Committee on Drugs
and Development as a forum for interaction with the European Commission,
the EMCDDA, the European Parliament, the Council of Europe and
relevant United Nations agencies.
</UL>
<HR>

<H3><A NAME="objective">OBJECTIVES</A></H3>

<UL>
<LI>To provide an overview of the various issues from different
perspectives (economics, development, environment, human rights,
etc.) with regard to the global interdependence dimension of the
drugs issue. This will add a new dimension to work developed to
date as it puts drugs in a wider international context. The Conference
will also introduce a new type of co-operation between a wider
variety of partners, given that it will involve the North-South
Centre's quadrilogue partners (governments, parliamentarians,
local authorities and NGOs) as well as the media. One of the key
elements for the success of the Conference will be the full participation
of partners from the South who will have the opportunity to put
forward their views and proposals.
<LI>To provide a meeting ground where key policy-makers, researchers,
local authorities and citizens' associations can debate present
and future policy options for Europe on the question of drugs
and development issues. The aim of the meeting is to outline concrete
policy options and proposals for implementation. It should be
action-oriented and aim to change the current reality. In order
to avoid duplication, it should take into consideration all the
work already undertaken by other organisations in this field.
<LI>To provide a framework for a more institutional relationship
between NGOs and international organisations on drugs issues.
The Conference could result in the strengthening of the European
NGO Committee on Drugs and Development as one of several vehicles
for collaboration between NGOs and the European Monitoring Centre
for Drugs and Drug Addiction, the Council of Europe and other
institutions.
<LI>To reinforce the policies of citizens' organisations in the
North (East and West) and in the South with the aim of improving
governmental and international drugs policies and addressing aspects
not covered by public organisations.
<LI>To seek ways to change the current reality, North and South,
East and West, through public information campaigns, educational
programmes, media coverage and appropriate environmental, development
and social programmes and projects.
</UL>
<HR>

<H3><A NAME="participation">PARTICIPATION</A></H3>

<P>
More than 100 participants from all over the world are expected
to attend the Conference. Participants will include:
<UL>
<LI>Local, national, regional and international policy-makers
and officials.
<LI>Citizens' associations (from both the North and the South)
including local organisations concerned with drugs supply or demand,
environment and development NGOs, representatives of indigenous
peoples, women's organisations, youth groups, consumers' associations,
trade unions, religious leaders, educators, etc.
<LI>Representatives of local indigenous peoples' groups in drug
producing areas.
<LI>Scientists and other experts in such fields as international
relations, micro- and macro-economics, agriculture, anthropology,
sociology, history, human rights, health and social issues, law,
etc.
<LI>Media representatives from both the North and the South.
</UL>
<HR>

<H3><A NAME="working">WORKING METHOD</A></H3>

<P>
This will be a working meeting with most of the proceedings taking
place in small working groups, designed to build upon the background
papers, refining policy proposals and developing action strategies.
The Conference will be organised over three days, with opening
and closing plenary sessions at which dignitaries will be invited
to speak.In a period leading up to the Conference distinguished
specialists from different backgrounds from the North and the
South have been asked to provide background papers on the issues
which will be debated during the Conference. Each paper concludes
with recommendations, including policy proposals directed towards
Europe. <BR>
The topics include local economics, trade and agriculture, debt
and structural adjustment, development aid, environment, new producers
and traders, control measures, education and media, international
conventions and information-sharing.<HR>

<H3><A NAME="output">OUTPUT</A></H3>

<P>
The key working group recommendations, including policy proposals,
will be compiled in a Summary Report to be forwarded to the Parliamentary
Assembly of the Council of Europe and to the European Parliament
as well as to all Member States of the Council of Europe. The
background papers, proceedings and outcome of the Conference will
be published in a Final Report for distribution to a wider audience
of concerned citizens and organisations with specific policy proposals
directed towards NGOs in the North (East and West) and in the
South.<HR>

<H3><A NAME="followup">FOLLOW-UP</A></H3>

<P>
Immediately after the Conference, a core group of participants
will begin planning an action strategy to promote the Conference
proposals among various target groups, including local, national,
regional and international policy-makers, industry, trade unions,
consumers' organisations and other citizens' associations especially
in Europe.<BR>
It is expected that, in addition to the policy approach, the Conference
will also result in practical proposals for information, media,
development, environmental, educational and social programmes,
and projects which can be implemented by various actors.<HR>

<H3><A NAME="team">CONFERENCE MANAGEMENT TEAM</A></H3>

<UL>
<LI><U><I><B>Project Directors</B></I></U><B> <BR>
</B>Jos Lemmers, Director, North-South Centre of the Council of
Europe <BR>
Ronald A. Kingham, Director, Environment &amp; Development Resource
Centre <BR>
<U><I><B>Project Co-ordinators</B></I></U><B> <BR>
</B>Isabel Martinho, Deputy Director, NSC <BR>
B&eacute;n&eacute;dicte de Smet, Project Co-ordinator, EDRC <BR>
<U><I><B>Project Assistants</B></I></U><B> <BR>
</B>Muriel Julien, NSC <BR>
M&oacute;nica Mendes, NSC
</UL>
<HR>

</BODY>

