<HR>

<H3><A NAME="ns">The North-South Centre of the Council of Europe
</A></H3>

<P>
The European Centre for Global Interdependence and Solidarity
- the North-South Centre - of the Council of Europe opened its
doors in Lisbon in May 1990. The Centre was created on the basis
of a Partial Agreement of the Council of Europe with the aim of
raising public awareness of Europe's many relations and complex
inter-linkages with the other continents in a world where local
activities are rapidly assuming planetary dimensions.<BR>
<BR>
Although the Centre has member States, it is not run exclusively
as an intergovernmental operation. Instead, it functions on the
basis of a so-called &quot;quadrilogue&quot;, a unique system
of quadripartite management by parliamentarians, governments,
non-governmental organisations and local and regional authorities.
These four partners participate in the planning and implementation
of the Centre's programmes.<BR>
In order to attain its objectives, the Centre organises core projects
and partnership projects. Its activities are divided into the
following three programme &quot;windows&quot;: Public Information
and Media Relations, Education and Training for Global Interdependence,
Dialogue for Global Partnership.<BR>
 
<H3><A NAME="edrc">The Environment &amp; Development Resource
Centre</A></H3>

<P>
The Environment &amp; Development Research Centre is an international
non-profit association established in 1988. Membership consists
of individuals working on the interface between ecology and economics.
The purpose of the Centre is to promote global sustainable development
- in our view a development which is ecologically sound, socially
just and respectful of cultural diversity.<BR>
EDRC promotes co-operation between the environment and development
movements -North, South, East and West - as well as co-operation
between activists and researchers, between NGOs and the private
sector, and with policy makers.<BR>
Other activities of EDRC concern European environment and development
policies related to Amazonia, Africa, Asia and Central and Eastern
Europe as well as global NGO action organised as a follow-up to
the 1992 &quot;Earth Summit&quot;. EDRC also serves as the secretariat
for the European NGO Committee on Drugs and Development. <BR>

<H3><A NAME="eu">European Monitoring Centre for Drugs and Drug
Addiction</A> </H3>

