<HEAD>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word ">

<META NAME="BUILD" CONTENT="Feb 10 1995">

<TITLE>PROGRAMME</TITLE>

<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Jovan Kurbalija">

<META NAME="OPERATOR" CONTENT="Jovan Kurbalija">

<META NAME="CREATIM" CONTENT="1995:3:27:15:34:">

<META NAME="VERSION" CONTENT="2">

</HEAD>

<BODY>

<P>
<B>MEDITERRANEAN ACADEMY </B>OF DIPLOMATIC STUDIES
<P>
<I>Diplomacy &amp;</I>
<P>
<I>Information Technology</I>
<P>
PROGRAMME 1995<HR>

<P>
This Programme  is prepared and coordinated by Mr. Jovan Kurbalija,
Head of Unit for Computer Applications in Diplomacy.<HR>
<HR>
<HR>

<P>
For more information please contact:
<P>
Unit for Computer Applications in Diplomacy
<P>
Mediterranean Academy of Diplomatic Studies
<P>
University of Malta
<P>
Address: Msida MSD 06, Malta
<P>
Phone: +356-483090 or +356-3290-2817
<P>
Fax: +356-483091
<P>
E-mail: mads@unimt.mt<HR>

<P>
<B>&#169;  1994, Mediterranean Academy of Diplomatic Studies</B>
<HR>

<P>
<I><B>INTRODUCTION</B></I>
<P>
Following decades of rapid technological development, information
technology (IT) enters into a new phase of growing applications
in most areas of human life. The lower cost and increasing performance
of hardware, as well as the power and easy use of software, have
all come together in a way that will fundamentally alter the way
most people live and work. 
<P>
Diplomacy like many other human activities is profoundly transformed.
Moreover, since the key ingredients of diplomacy - <B>information
</B> and <B>interaction </B>- are nowadays highly automated through
digitalization and networking, the changes in diplomacy is even
more substantial. The development of IT will compel diplomats:
<UL>
<LI>to work in <I>the new social,  political and economic environment
</I>characterized by the changes in the concept of sovereignty,
the emergence of the global economy and global information infrastructure;
<LI>to deal with  <I>new topics</I>  such as protection of intellectual
property on a multilateral and bilateral level, and 
<LI>to use <I>the new tools </I>made available by information
technology, such as automation of office activities, global networking,
 etc..
</UL>

<P>

<P>
These three areas of the interaction between diplomacy and  information
technology are the  conceptual foundation of the Unit for Computer
Applications in Diplomacy.  The Unit's Programme for 1995 focuses
on the following major activities:
<UL>
<LI>Course in Diplomacy and Information Technology
<LI>Research Projects on Diplomacy and Information Technology
<LI>Application Development and Electronic Publishing for Diplomacy
</UL>

<P>
<HR>
<HR>

<P>
<I><B>CONTENTS</B></I>
<PRE WIDTH=132>
                                                                   

                                                                   

<I>Part I</I>                                                             
<I>Course in Diplomacy &amp; Information</I>                                  
<I>Technology</I>                                                         

New political, social and economic                                 
environment for diplomatic activities                              

New topics at diplomatic agendas                                   
New tools for diplomatic activities                                

                                                                   

