The impact of Technology on International Relations                

                                                                   

<I>Part III</I>                                                           
<I>Application Development and Electronic Publishing for Diplomacy</I>    

Database of International Law                                      

Computer-Assisted Learning Course in Diplomacy                     

Computer-Assisted Learning Course in Diplomacy and Information     
Technology                                                         


</PRE WIDTH=132>

<P>

<P>
<I>PART I</I>
<P>
<I><B>COURSE IN DIPLOMACY AND INFORMATION </B></I>
<P>
<I><B>TECHNOLOGY</B></I>
<P>
The Course is based on the comprehensive and interdisciplinary
approach to information technology and diplomacy.  Beside providing
training in the use of the computer as a working tool,  the Course
focuses also on various issues raised through the use of information
technology. Thus the main objective of the Course is to provide
participants with proper conceptual and methodological skills
for working in the new international environment which is shaped,
to a large extent, by information technology.
<P>
The Course is divided into the following three areas:
<OL>
<LI>New political, social and economic environment for diplomatic
activities;
<LI>New topics on diplomatic agendas;
<LI>New tools for diplomats.
</OL>

<P>
<I>1</I><HR>

<P>
<I><B>NEW POLITICAL, SOCIAL AND ECONOMIC ENVIRONMENT FOR DIPLOMATIC
ACTIVITIES</B></I>
<P>
The development of  IT  has made the modern world increasingly
interdependent and interconnected. Today's trends and characteristics,
which are likely to endure, will bring about deep changes of economic,
political and social structures in nation states as well as in
international relations.  The impact of these changes on diplomacy
is in the focus of this part of the Course.
<P>
<I>IT AND CHANGES IN MODERN SOCIETY</I>
<P>
The key question:<I><B> How will IT affect the way people live,
work and learn?</B></I>
<P>
Diplomats should have an understanding of the profound changes
in the production processes, and social structure. They  should
also be aware of conceptual  frameworks and tools for  the analysis
of the modern world. These issues are analyzed in proper economic,
political, philosophical and sociological perspectives. The main
schools of thought explaining these phenomenon is presented and
reviewed.
<P>
<I>IT AND SOVEREIGNTY</I>
<P>
The key question: <I><B>To  what extent will the development of
IT  affect the ability of states to assert their sovereignty in
the international arena and over their national destiny? </B>
</I>
<P>
Diplomacy is directly affected by the changes in the concept of
sovereignty. One of the main function of traditional diplomacy
has been to protect the sovereignty of states. Is this going to
remain the main function of diplomacy? Given that sovereignty,
the key element of state, has been seriously challenged by modern
processes, it is necessary to provide diplomats with a general
understanding of these processes as well as of the future of diplomacy
in new constellation of power. 
<P>
<I>2</I><HR>

<P>
<I>IT AND INTERNATIONAL RELATIONS (CONCEPT OF POWER</I><B>)</B>
<P>
The key question: <I><B>Is it likely that &quot;provinces&quot;
and &quot;backwaters&quot; in the forthcoming period will not
be countries with geographical disadvantages, but countries without
access to the networks, or, for instance, with IT-illiterate elites?
</B></I> 
<P>
Professional education of diplomats and foreign-policy decision
makers has been based on the traditional approaches to international
relations (e.g. realist and idealist). The main purpose of this
module of the Course is to provide some alternative approaches
and to bring the diplomats' attention to new perspectives of analyzing
international relations.  Special emphasis is paid to the importance
of geographical elements  in international relations.  It is likely
that the predominant determinant of a country's economic and overall
success is, among others, the skills in managing information and
data instead of controlling territory or important geographical
locations like it used to be during the history of mankind.<B>
</B>
<P>
<I>IT AND CULTURAL DIVERSITY</I>
<P>
The key question: <I><B>How will the growing movement of information
in digital form across national borders affect cultural, religious
and other values. Is Huntington's clash of civilization going
to happen in cyber-space? What should be the function of diplomacy
in this respect?</B></I>
<P>
Artifacts in digital form imposes a new form of communication
between individuals within the society as well as between societies.
IT will endanger traditional means for protection and promotion
of national culture and, at the same time, create new ones. The
special importance to this question is in multi-cultural societies
and regions (the Mediterranean), where the issue of the protection
of national cultures has a high political importance.
<P>
<I>3</I><HR>

<P>
<I>IT AND INTERNATIONAL ECONOMY</I>
<P>
<I>The key question</I>:  <I><B>How will the transition from a
commerce/industry economy towards an &quot;information economy&quot;
influence the diplomats'  task to promote the economic interests
of their countries?</B></I>
<P>
Classical economic theory and practice was build upon commerce/industry
economy. &quot;Information economy&quot; will require a new theoretical
and practical framework The features of this new framework are
in the focus of  this part of our Course. 
<P>
<I><B>NEW TOPICS ON DIPLOMATIC AGENDAS</B></I>
<P>
The growing centrality of IT-issues in international relations
has raised new and complex topics for diplomats and foreign policymakers.
Information Technology, which already takes a huge share of economic
transactions, requires proper international legal and political
framework.  Creating this framework, both on bilateral and multilateral
level, is one of the major tasks of diplomats.  In order to perform
this important function, diplomats should have a broad knowledge
of the various aspects of IT-related issues from a technological,
economic and legal point of view.
<P>
<I>IT COMMODITIES AND SERVICES</I>
<P>
The key question: <I><B>What are the most important IT commodities
and services? What are their major characteristics?</B></I>
<P>
The major aim of this part of the Course is to provide the basic
knowledge of IT commodities and services with special emphasize
on those that have or will have high importance in international
trade. The brief survey of major IT commodities and services is
provided, with special consideration of the protection of software.
 As far as software is concerned the special attention is paid
on various components of the protection of software such as: source
code, operation systems, compilers, executable elements of software,
etc.
<P>
<I>INTERNATIONAL ORGANIZATIONS, FORUMS AND CHANNELS FOR REGULATION
IT-RELATED ISSUES</I>
<P>
The key question: <I><B>What are the major international organizations,
forums and channels for discussing and regulating IT-related issues?
</B></I>
<P>
This part focuses on  international institutional framework for
regulating IT-issues. The survey will start with the established
international organizations and forums such as International Telecommunication
UNION (ITU), The World Telecommunication Forum, International
Standard Organization (ISO), American National Standards Institute
(ANSI), European Computer Manufacturers' Association (ECMA), etc.
It will also consider existence of the number of important NGOs,
such as  Electronic Frontier Foundation.
<P>
<I>TRANSFER OF INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY</I>
<P>
The key question<B>:</B><I> What are the various channels for
the transfer of IT from developed to developing countries?</I>
<P>
Transfer of technology, including IT, is one of the core topics
of the modern international economy. It has special importance
for north-south relations, development, etc. The major task of
this part of Course is to make a survey on the current policy
of transfer of technology and to identify all those aspect which
have a special importance for diplomacy and international relations.
Special emphasize is given to GATT activities and the newly-established
 WTO (World Trade Organization).
<P>
<I>PROTECTION OF INTELLECTUAL PROPERTY IN BILATERAL </I>
<P>
<I>RELATIONS (SPECIAL EMPHASIS ON SOFTWARE)</I>
<P>
The key question: <I><B>What are the methods used for the protection
of software in bilateral relations between states? </B></I>
<P>
Analysis of the current practice of the United States and other
developed countries in this respect is provided. Special emphasis
is placed  on the position of developing countries in their attempts
with developed countries to enable bilateral protection of software.
 The problem of linking bilateral protection of software to the
transfer of technology is also addressed
<P>
<I>PROTECTION OF INTELLECTUAL PROPERTY IN MULTILATERAL </I>
<P>
<I>CONTEXT (SPECIAL EMPHASIS ON SOFTWARE)</I>
<P>
The key question: <I><B>What are the safeguards used for the protection
of software in the available multilateral mechanisms (e.g. GATT,
World Intellectual Property Organization, EU, etc.). </B></I>
<P>
The Uruguay Round of GATT and  the formation of the World Trade
Organization is taken as a case study on multilateral protection
of software.  Positions of developed and developing countries
with regards to the protection of intellectual property is tackled
with special considerations on the  pros and cons for certain
forms of protection of intellectual property.
<P>
<I>OTHER  INTERNATIONAL LEGAL AND POLITICAL TOPICS RAISED BY THE
DEVELOPMENT OF IT</I>
<P>
Besides  the above mentioned topics the development of IT will
bring a number of a new issues that should be tackled on the international
level (e.g. transboundary disputes related to IT, protection of
privacy, limiting of free communication in the interest of international
public order, etc. )
<P>
<I>7</I><HR>

<P>
<I><B>NEW TOOLS FOR DIPLOMATIC ACTIVITIES</B></I>
<P>
Today, computers are more widely available to a large community
of users due to its lower cost. In diplomatic circles, the use
of computers was the privilege of the most developed countries.
Now, the use of computers in diplomacy can be afforded by any
country. Moreover, small States and other countries with limited
economic means for running their foreign affairs will find computers
a real necessity.
<P>
This part of the Course considers the practical use of computers
in conducting diplomatic activities. It focuses on  the use of
computer technology for:
<UL>
<LI>the automation of traditional methods of performing diplomatic
functions; and
<LI>re-engineering of diplomatic procedures.
</UL>

<P>

<P>
<I>INTRODUCTION</I>
<P>
<B>Introduction into the computer science </B>
<P>
history of computers, basic operations, major components, distinction
 between hardware and software, etc.
<P>
<B>Use of  the operating system</B> 
<P>
brief survey of existing operating systems; special emphasise
on MS-DOS and Windows;
<P>
<B>Use of word-processor</B>
<UL>
<LI>typewriter vs. word processor; 
<LI>use of word processor for typing texts;
<LI>advanced options related to text-management, such as: language
and linguistic assistance, desktop-publishing, group editing;
tagging languages and compound document architecture (e.g. SMGL,
ODA, etc.). 
</UL>

<P>

<UL>
<LI><I>Practical work</I>: texts typed by students in the framework
of other courses is analyzed with regard to form, graphical presentation,
utilisation of fonts (serif - san serif, etc.)
</UL>

<P>

<P>
<B>Use of spreadsheet applications</B>
<UL>
<LI>accounting software, statistical operations, quantitative
analysis;
<LI><I>Practical work</I>: students are asked to make small application
that will cover part of one diplomatic mission.
</UL>

<P>

<P>
<B>Use of database</B>
<UL>
<LI>filing cabinet vs. databases
<LI>fast and punctual access to information as a key element of
diplomatic activity; 
<LI>various types of databases; internally-housed and remote databases;
other systems for modern management of data - hypertext and knowledge-based
software;
<LI><I>Practical work</I>: students are asked to build  small
database that should contain information of academicians interested
in their particular countries searchable through the name of person,
country and topic of interest.
</UL>

<P>

<P>
<B>Use of graphics software</B>
<P>
utilisation of graphics software for PR and country promotion.
<P>
<I>COMPUTER APPLICATIONS IN DIPLOMACY</I>
<P>
<B>Model of the computerisation of diplomatic activities</B>
<P>
The model of computerisation of diplomatic activities developed
at the Academy is analysed with special emphasise on: the flow
of information, interaction and interchange among various departments,
interaction between the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the other
ministries and governmental departments, etc.
<P>
<B>Creating specialized databases for international law, international
relations, diplomacy, etc.;</B>
<P>
Interdisciplinary study provides students with knowledge about
tools available by IT in handling data related to international
law, international relations and diplomacy.
<P>
<I>Practical presentation</I> and use of the Database of international
legal materials developed at the Academy.
<P>
<B>Creating knowledge-based systems for international law, international
relations, diplomacy, etc.;</B>
<P>
Interdisciplinary study of implementation of artificial intelligence
in areas of interest.
<P>
<I>Practical presentation</I> of the Project related to Expert
System for Responsibility Under International Environmental Law.
<P>
<B>Use of other type of software (simulation of negotiations,
political and economical analysis, etc.);</B>
<P>
Students are instructed how to use the software for simulation
of negotiations as well as for  various political and economic
analysis.
<P>
<B>Use of computers in preparation and conducting international
conferences (GATT and UNCED)</B>
<P>
Study of experience from GATT and UNCED related to use of computers
in preparing and conducting  international conferences.
<P>
<I>USE OF  COMPUTERISED DATA SOURCES FOR INFORMATION GATHERING
RELATED TO DIPLOMATIC ACTIVITIES</I> 
<P>
<B>Concept of International Information Systems  (types,</B>
<P>
<B>technical requirements, etc.)</B>
<P>
Access remote databases - necessary technical requirements;
<P>
<B>Internet</B>
<P>
Introduction
<P>
<I>Issues:</I> history and concept of Internet; basic terminology;
way of connecting to Internet.
<P>
E-mail
<P>
<I>Issues</I>: function of E-mail; basic terminology; technical
requirements; confidentiality and protection of E-mail; use of
E-mail in diplomatic communication;
<P>
Telenet and FTP
<P>
Issues: functions of these two services; technical requirements.
<P>
Gopher,  Archie, World Wide Web
<P>
<I>Issues</I>: concepts and functions of the above mentioned services;
future of World Wide Web as a innovative method for handling information.
<P>
Electronic conferences
<P>
<I>Issues</I>: concepts and functions of electronic conferences;
electronic conference as a means for the exchange of information
and promotion of national  interests;
<P>
Internet resources for diplomats
<P>
Issues: Internet services of special interest for diplomats and
specialists for international relations available in international
organizations (UN, UNDP, NATO, EU, etc.), educational institutions,
governments, etc. <HR>

<P>
<I>PART III</I>
<P>
<I><B>RESEARCH ON DIPLOMACY AND INFORMATION</B></I>
<P>
<I><B>TECHNOLOGY</B></I>
<P>
Research projects  are directed towards exploring the dynamic
interaction between diplomacy and IT. They are interlinked with
the Course in Diplomacy and IT and developing applications for
diplomacy. The major focus in this period is on the following
two research projects:
<P>
<I>CREATING THE MODEL FOR THE COMPUTERISATION OF MINISTRIES OF
FOREIGN AFFAIRS</I>
<P>
The Model of the Computerization of Ministries of Foreign Affairs
is based on the analysis of diplomatic activities and their adaptation
to information technology. The  knowledge and experience developed
for business information systems are suited  to the needs of diplomatic
activities. Model focuses on:
<UL>
<LI>the automation of traditional methods of performing diplomatic
functions; and
<LI>the re-engineering of traditional diplomatic procedures when
it is possible. 
</UL>

<P>

<P>
Major parts of this Model are:
<UL>
<LI>automation of routine and repetitive activities
<LI>supply of data and information
<LI>automation of knowledge-intensive activities; and
<LI>human resource building
</UL>

<P>

<P>
The Model provides a general framework that could be  adjusted
to the particular needs of Ministries of Foreign Affairs and other
institutions involved in performing diplomatic activities.
<P>
<I>THE IMPACT OF TECHNOLOGY ON INTERNATIONAL RELATIONS</I>
<P>
This research project which is still in initial phase should tackle
the following issues:
<UL>
<LI>the increasing integration and disintegration of the international
system - a highly paradoxical environment
</UL>

<P>

<UL>
<LI>the impact of information technology and real-time access
to information on the international system;
</UL>

<P>

<UL>
<LI>the increased importance of networking netweing for new systems
of governance
</UL>

<P>

<UL>
<LI>the emergence of a new moral order from the transcendence
of the environment-development paradox
</UL>

<P>

<UL>
<LI>integration theory and neo-functionalism as a theoretical
framework for analysing the role of networks in international
relations.
</UL>

<P>

<P>
<I>PART III</I>
<P>
<I><B>APPLICATION DEVELOPMENT AND ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING FOR DIPLOMACY
</B></I>
<P>
One of the major objectives of the Unit for Computer Applications
in Diplomacy is to create tools that will help diplomats in their
training and performing diplomatic functions. Based on these starting
points the Unit developed the following applications:
<P>
<I>DATABASE OF INTERNATIONAL LAW</I>
<P>
The main motto in creating this database has been the need to
have a complete coverage of international legal rules, starting
from their adoption on the international level to their implementation
in relations among/between states or within states. Thus each
international legal instrument (convention, treaty) in the Database
has:
<UL>
<LI>basic information (title, date of acceptance, place of acceptance,
etc.);
<LI>full text;
<LI>list of countries that signed and/or ratified particular instrument
with texts of reservations, declarations, notifications, etc.;
<LI>indication of implementation of the instrument within the
internal legal system (solutions for both, monistic and dualistic
legal systems);
<LI>theoretical explanations for political and legal concepts
used in instruments;
</UL>

<P>

<P>
Technically speaking this application uses database and hypertext
technology. The current version of Database has 2000 international
legal instruments.<HR>

<P>
<I>15</I><HR>

<P>
<I>COMPUTER-ASSISTED LEARNING (CAL) COURSE IN DIPLOMACY </I>
<P>
CAL Course in Diplomacy is developed in order to support the teaching
of Diplomacy at the Mediterranean Academy of Diplomatic Studies.
It uses hypermedia technology for presenting teaching material.
 This application will be further developed in order to become
a self-contained Computer-based course in Diplomacy.
<P>
<I>COMPUTER-ASSISTED LEARNING (CAL) COURSE IN DIPLOMACY &amp;
INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY</I>
<P>
It is considered appropriate to have the Course on Diplomacy and
IT taught by using new tools made available by IT. Consequently
the application for the support of this course has been developed.
</BODY>

