<P>
<CENTER>
<H2>Lisbon, 23 - 25 March 1996</CENTER> <BR>
</H2>
<HR>

<P>
<CENTER>
<H1>THEME N&#186;2 - <A NAME="theme2">FINANCIAL FLOWS</A> </H1></center>

<P><center>
the global macro-economics of drugs, the role of illegal money
flows in international exchange<B> </B>The micro-economics of
drugs in Europe, in particular in those sectors most affected
by economic crisis
<H3><A HREF="#santino">Umberto SANTINO - Italy </A>- <A HREF="#blixen">Samuel BLIXEN - Uruguay </A>-
</H3></center>

<H2>Contribution by <A NAME="santino">Umberto SANTINO </A>- Italy
</H2>

<H3>Illegal accumulation and world economy</H3>

<P>
In the recent past, the international drug market has further
spread and has become more complex. New consumption markets have
formed in the Third World and in the former socialist countries,
new criminal groups were born and the number of psychoactive substances
has grown. Drug trafficking is one of the most important fields
of transnational crime, because the activities of this traffic
(production, trade, laundering of illegal capital) have a world-wide
scale.
<P>
Even if the estimates are uncertain and contradictory, it is certain
that the illegal accumulation, derived not only from drugs but
from many activities (arms, nuclear materials, toxic waste, counterfeit
products, control of illegal immigration, &quot;organ commerce&quot;,
etc.) is comparable to that of big multinationals. According to
data from research institutes and the UN, the annual proceeds
of drug trafficking would be between 300 and 500 billion dollars
(but UNDCP indicates values between 500 and 1000 billion) and
the annual turnover of the large criminal organisations would
be 750 billion dollars.
<P>
The laundering of illegal money is promoted by the computerisation
of the financial channels and by the peculiarities of the international
economy. Last March, the DDA (Direzione Distrettuale Antimafia)
of Catania arrested a man above suspicion, making a banking transaction
of 1 billion dollars. The liberalisation of the circulation of
capitals, the creation of large regional markets (UE, NAFTA, APEC)
and the world-wide financial economy increase the possibility
of symbiosis of dirty and clean money. Every day in the world
financial market, there are transactions amounting to about 1.000
billion dollars, but the real exchanges are only a small part.
The majority is wandering capital going in search of more remunerative
income and an undeterminable share is formed by illegal capital.
<P>
In the opinion of the international organisations (e.g. the UN
World Conference on Organised Transnational Crime in Naples, 21-23
November 1994), the main cause of transnational crime is the anomalous
development of capitalism in new areas, notably different from
the &quot;classical&quot; countries (Western countries, USA, Japan).
In many countries, for instance in the former socialist countries,
there is a sort of &quot;jungle&quot;, i.e. a market without State
and without law. This analysis overlooks the fact that organised
crime started first in Western countries, both in peripheral-semiperipheral
areas, for instance Sicily and Southern Italy, and in central
areas, for instance USA. In this context, the new capitalist countries
follow the example of the Western countries.
<P>
My working hypothesis is that transnational crime is not pathological-anomalous
but a structural aspect of capitalist economy in its current phase,
definable as &quot;capitalism without alternatives&quot;. The
capitalistic globalisation and the international organisations'
policies (structural adjustments, dismantling of economic branches,
privatisation of public properties, unemployment, exchange liberalisation)
increase territorial disequilibria and social gaps and offer considerable
advantages to the illegal capital.
<P>
Therefore, we can say that, in marginal areas (the Souths of the
world, even the Souths in the Norths), illegal accumulation is
the &quot;criminal way to capitalism&quot; and in the central
areas (the Norths), it is the &quot;criminal way of capitalism&quot;.
<H3>Official policies</H3>

<P>
On 8 November 1990, the Council of Europe approved the Strasbourg
Convention on laundering, research, sequestration and confiscation
of criminal proceeds, signed by about 20 States. The European
Community studied the problem of organised crime through a board
of inquiry in 1991 and, in June of the same year, approved directive
n.328 on laundering the proceeds of illicit activities. Only a
few countries (Bulgaria, the Netherlands, the United Kingdom,
Switzerland, Italy, i.e. only three of the members of the EU)
ratified the Strasbourg Convention and, among the States that
have accepted the directive, some (France, Spain, Portugal) limited
the application to the proceeds of narcotraffic. Only Italy, Germany,
Belgium, Ireland, The Netherlands and the United Kingdom consider
as crime the laundering of the proceeds of all criminal activities.
The United Kingdom has excluded Jersey and Guernsey, the British
Isles best known as tax havens.
<P>
The international conference on prevention and control of laundering
dirty money and use of the proceeds of crime (Courmayeur 18-20
June 1994) showed the general lines of anti-crime world policy
resuming the Vienna Convention, the Basel Declaration and the
recommendations of FATF.
<P>
The Conference identified some priorities: introduction of the
crime &quot;laundering proceeds of drug traffic&quot; in the legal
system of the States subscribers of the Vienna Convention; restrictions
of banking secrecy; application of the rule of the Basel Declaration
&quot;Know your client&quot; and of FATF recommendations, especially
the abolition of the anonymous accounts and the identification
of the &quot;front men&quot;; the notification of suspicious transactions;
the control of the financial companies and professional offices
that offer financial services; the confiscation of proceeds of
illicit activities.
<P>
The UN Conference (Naples 21-23 November 1994) proposed the internationalisation
of the Italian crime &quot;associazione a delinquere di tipo mafioso&quot;.
However, the participants didn't come to an agreement on the abolition
of banking secrecy and on the laundry of dirty money. The opposers
were, above all, the small States that acted as tax havens, near
the United States and Europe.
<P>
It is impossible to treat problems so complex with precarious
committees and episodic recommendations, mostly doomed to remain
on paper, or with meetings whose utility is inversely proportional
to their cost. It is necessary to establish permanent organisations,
for instance a European monitoring centre on organised crime and
the laundering of dirty money; to bring into operation Europol,
until today paralysed by the divergences of the Member States;
to institute the formation of a European and international criminal
law.
<H3>Alternative Policies</H3>

<P>
An alternative policy must place the accent on prevention, acting
on the causes and on the forming process of illegal accumulation.
For this claim, it is necessary:
<P>
1) to change the economic policies of the frame the abolition
of prohibition, which acts as an incentive for criminal groups
to share out the drug business and criminalises the consumers.international
organisations. We must change from the present phase, which we
can name the &quot;dictatorship of profit and transnational corporations&quot;
to a new phase of &quot;economic democracy&quot;, based on local
development. Obviously, an economic democracy is impossible without
political democracy. All this is valid both for the UN and for
the EU. We must work to change from the superpower of some States
to the peoples' and citizens' community;
<P>
2) to develop the legal economy in the more marginalised countries,
starting from the local resources: raw materials, cultural goods,
human abilities;
<P>
3) to redefine and strengthen international cooperation, as collaboration
among equals and not as an imposition from the outside of foreign
and distorted patterns;
<P>
4) we must put inside this
<P>
Regarding the laundry of dirty money, it is necessary to stop
or at least to control the liberalisation of capital circulation,
reduce the circulation of speculative capital (tax forms, stock
exchange regulation, etc), abolish any form of obscurity of the
financial system: banking secrecy, tax havens, financial innovations,
etc.
<P>
It is evident that these policies are in counter-trend regarding
the present policies. If we do not want to cultivate a pious hope,
we must state a problem: with what forces, what means, what modalities
can we carry out such an ambitious alternative plan?
<P>
To set off on this way, we must strengthen the grass-roots organisations
(NGOs, citizens' associations) and help to create local, national
and international organisations based on real participation.
<H3>Proposals</H3>

<P>
1. To create a permanent network of NGOs and citizens' associations,
a grass-roots EU, open to other countries and continents, which
concentrate on the problems of alternative development, identifying
financial resources, collaborating in projects, forming the necessary
skills. This network must be at European, national and local levels.
We can name them: Alternative Development Laboratories.
<P>
2. To found alternative financial channels (for instance, the
Green Banks in Germany, the Italian Banca Etica and MAG: Mutua
Auto Gestione) for development projects in marginalised areas.
<P>
3. To bring into operation the network among the documentation
centres of European NGO Council on Drugs, and
<P>
4. to found, within this framework, a European monitoring centre
on the illegal accumulation and laundering dirty money. The tasks
of this centre could be the following:
<UL>
<LI>examining critically the laws in force and the international
conventions;
<LI>putting forward proposals to reform rules and conventions;
<LI>collecting documents: judicial and investigative acts, press
reviews (newspapers and magazines skilled on financial problems),
other sources;
<LI>publishing a bulletin;
<LI>organising information and education campaigns;
<LI>elaborating a project for the use of confiscated properties
to finance development projects and even the centre.
</UL>

<H3>Palermo, December 1995</H3>
<HR>

<P>
<CENTER>
<H1>THEME N&#186;2 - FINANCIAL FLOWS </H1>

<P>
the global macro-economics of drugs, the role of illegal money
flows in international exchange<B> </B>The micro-economics of
drugs in Europe, in particular in those sectors most affected
by economic crisis
<P>
<H2>Contribution by <A NAME="blixen">Samuel BLIXEN </A>- Uruguay
</H2></center>

<H3>&quot;Drug capital in a neo-liberal world&quot;</H3>

<P>
Ten years after Ronald Reagan signed an executive order declaring
&quot;war on drugs&quot; the figures speak for themselves: far
from shrinking, the consumer market worldwide has expanded; it
has levelled off in the United States and Europe but new &quot;national
markets&quot; have been won in the cities of South America and
Africa. Drugs supply has been diversified with new synthetic drugs
coming onto the market, and a trend towards a more sophisticated,
in other words more destructive and deadly, consumption.
<P>
The area given over to poppy growing in Colombia has grown considerably
in only three years and cocaine production in Peru, Ecuador and
Bolivia has remained steady, despite the policy of destroying
crops and replacing coca plantations.
<P>
Major drug seizures have fallen in absolute terms while, simultaneously,
new drug trade routes have appeared and the number of outlets,
especially on the Atlantic side of South America, has increased.
<P>
The dismantling of the Medellin cartel and the supposed neutralisation
of the Cali cartel have not had any marked effect on Colombian
exports of drugs; quite the contrary, the huge increase in heroin
production confirms that producers are competing for European
markets, traditionally supplied from south-east Asia. Similarly,
there is an attempt to promote diversification of consumption
in the United States. In addition, other mafias, especially in
Bolivia, Brazil and Mexico, have enjoyed a meteoric rise.
<P>
Political and administrative corruption have led to new and even
juicier scandals, but this problem has kept on growing worldwide
and is now directly linked to illicit capital flows, especially
of drug capital.
<P>
The combination of these factors has stimulated, as in any self-respecting
free market, a trend towards higher prices, defying the very laws
of that free market since supplies have grown and there are rarely
any temporary shortages.
<P>
The general evolution of the drugs market reveals the ineffectiveness
of the current policies intended to &quot;eliminate the problem&quot;.
One possible explanation for this failure is that, whereas repressive
measures are concentrated in the areas of production or distribution
(increasingly involving massive participation by the military),
the financial aspect, ie the mobilisation of capital, its legalisation
and the use of profits, is somewhat lax. This discrepancy is baffling
to say the least, since it is now widely accepted that capital
is the driving force of the drugs trade and that its high rate
of return explains its vitality.
<P>
Drugs always have been, and still are, an excellent trade product,
booming despite the apocalyptic tone of official rhetoric, calling
into question the effectiveness of repressive strategies. Together
with smuggling and the arms trade, with which it has many connections,
it is one of the most profitable forms of trade. Drugs trafficking
is a decisive factor in maintaining certain driving forces of
some regional economies, cycles which tend to consolidate so-called
&quot;marginal economies&quot;. Capital from the drugs trade supports
a social structure where the state is conspicuous by its absence,
as is the case in the forests of eastern Peru, in the Chapare
(Bolivia), in some Amazonian regions of Brazil and central-eastern
Colombia. In these rural regions (as well as some inner-city neighbourhoods),
drug money is the cornerstone of consumption, funding production
and trading activities.
<P>
Laundering drug capital is the main medium of this trade, the
keystone to the whole structure, a factor even more vital than
the availability of production resources or other prerequisites
for the production process.
<P>
Both these factors - the industrial factor of production resources
and the financial factor of profit and investment - are directly
related to the will (or lack of will) demonstrated in world centres,
wherever they are, to give priority to tackling drugs trafficking
and drugs consumption.
<P>
The steady growth of large-scale drug-capital laundering and the
remarkable inability of developed countries to prevent, repress
and eliminate the laundering of drug money, points to contradictions
in attitudes whereby determination fails, impetus is undermined
and good intentions undone whenever attempts are made to intervene
in that murky and deliberately complex universe called the world
financial system. If it were possible to describe those paralysing
contradictions, even only sketchily, it might be possible to offer
an explanation for the failures of policies designed to combat
the problem of drugs trafficking and consumption.
<P>
As long as there is no orchestration of effective action plans
to put a stranglehold on financial movements of drug capital,
it will be difficult to stamp out the other manifestations of
the phenomenon. This, at least, is what can be deduced from ten
years of declared war on drugs trafficking.
<P>
This aspect of the problem which offers a decisive role to financial
operations must first be dealt with thoroughly, even if it seems
obvious: those responsible for financial transactions linked to
drug trafficking are not the same people who oversee production
and organise the traffic. The former work in the business world
and enjoy the prestige resulting from their legal activities,
an increasingly elastic and &quot;pragmatic&quot; legality.
<P>
Laundering capital takes advantage of a certain impunity given
that the borderline between legality and illegality is vague in
the world of finance, a world which worships a new religion whose
first commandment is success. Arms manufacturers never give a
thought to the consequences of their use and rarely bother to
find out how certain arms end up in the hands of people who should
never have received them. The same goes for chemical agents and,
in particular, money: the universally accepted norm is an attempt
to turn secrecy into a sacred value as far as the identity of
the investor, capitalist or holder of a bank account is concerned.
Since no norm is a norm unless it is widespread or universalised,
the risk of illegal manipulation is accepted and considered an
exceptional consequence.
<P>
But in practice, it is by no means an exceptional consequence:
experts think that larger and larger proportions of worldwide
financial activity are accounted for by the movement of proceeds
from illegal activities. Certain codes distinguish between &quot;grey
capital&quot; and &quot;black capital&quot;, in order to differentiate
between money produced by tax evasion, fraud linked to over-invoicing
or under-invoicing of merchandise, on the one hand, and kickbacks
in government spheres, the capital raised from smuggling merchandise
and arms, drug trafficking and the white slave trade.
<P>
The very existence of this distinction encourages the gradual
abandonment of scruples: certain money laundering operations are
not seen as criminal and are not condemned by society; they are
seen as a tolerable means of increasing profits, i.e. a way of
achieving more success.
<P>
The explicit discrimination practised by American anti-drug agencies
is not unrelated to this situation: they focus their effort and
pressure on governments to tighten up their legislation against
drug dollars but rule out any initiative aimed at stamping out
any other kind of money laundering. The bilateral agreements signed
over the last two years between the United States and Latin American
governments, in order to bring about practical judicial co-operation,
clearly limit initiatives to crimes related to drug money laundering.
<P>
Incidentally, this attitude - accepted by most Latin American
governments - has led to embarrassing situations. For example,
in the recently-created Mercosur organisation (the Common Market
of the South), the process of economic integration suffers from
periodic problems because Uruguayan legislation on the free circulation
of capital facilitates tax evasion in Argentina, Brazil and Paraguay.
The consequences are not only regional: the advantages of the
Uruguayan tax haven made possible the biggest-ever tax evasion
operation in Belgium's history.
<P>
A number of recent episodes in Latin America point to flaws in
the South American approach: tax evasion, trade racketeering and
drug dollars often form capital laundering circuits and deliberately
use multiple transfers, bank deposits and financial investment
to cover up the origin of the money and so make it &quot;clean&quot;.
<P>
Certain triangular financial operations between Argentina, Uruguay
and Bosnia have made possible arms sales and, at the same time,
the laundering of capital identified as coming from drugs traffic.
Money laundering has become a cornerstone of financial movements
in Latin America whereas official statistics reveal a steady fall
in investment and production.
<P>
Speculation flows of &quot;hot money&quot; have led to competition
for attracting it, so that there is now a trend towards the progressive
liberalisation of capital movements, the gradual removal of all
control mechanisms and the strengthening of secrecy, be it banking,
administrative or registration secrecy. Since this &quot;hot money&quot;
disappears as quickly as it appears, Latin American financial
markets maximalise this play of facilities. Since money laundering
goes hand in hand with certain kinds of political and administrative
corruption there has been an increase in the mechanisms for protecting
information to counter demands for greater transparency.
<P>
The need to preserve institutional stability has led to a trend
towards greater secrecy. Banking secrecy is now seen as necessary
for the stability of the financial system, but it can also be
used to ward off crises in the political system rocked by corruption
scandals. The message being sent by governments is clear: the
facilities given to capital transfers are in step with the economic
trend towards total deregulation.
<P>
Although this strategy has not borne the fruit expected of it
and macro-economic indicators are disappointing, the policies
pursued have amplified this trend so that in Latin America, at
least, speculative activity has dominated the financial sector.
<P>
Inevitably, capital laundering has increased to a point where
capital of illicit origin is used to finance certain essential
aspects of current economic policies. In certain countries it
has been claimed that capital raised from the drug trade has been
used to support the privatisation of public undertakings; in other
cases, the steady flow of this capital has made it possible to
implement monetary policies designed to reduce inflation; in yet
other cases, it has been used to end the in-fighting between different
sectors of authority or used to fund fraudulent operations for
implementing politico-military strategies at regional level.
<P>
In this way, the proceeds from drug trafficking have been used
to finance economic policies designed to promote the full liberalisation
of markets as well as a deregulation of the commercial and financial
sectors. Behind these strategies we can detect the hand of multilateral
lending bodies or the guidance of American specialist agencies,
which in turn highlights a new paradox: while certain American
agencies are putting pressure on governments to limit banking
secrecy vis-&agrave;-vis drug trafficking offences, others oppose
any change designed to slow down any opening of the market or
liberalisation.
<P>
This has been the case, for example, of certain international
loans which have been subjected to a restructuring of central
banks towards deregulation of the financial system.
<P>
In Latin America, at least, those involved in drug trafficking
are fervent defenders of so-called neo-liberal policies because
they undoubtedly are in their interests. Of course, it is not
our intention to establish a cause-and-effect relationship between
neo-liberalism and drug trafficking, but it cannot be ignored
that these neo-liberal policies have resulted in record levels
of corruption.
<P>
The strategy to weaken the state and encourage the privatisation
of public companies has fostered kickbacks: witness the organised
systems of pay-offs for authorising certain transactions between
state bodies and private companies. This corruption boom has boosted
the influence wielded by the drug cartels' money-men.
<P>
Inevitably, drug trafficking capital seems to be linked to the
major financial scandals and, as is the case in Colombia or Mexico,
they even seem to be involved in manipulation for the purpose
of forming governments or influencing the outcome of electoral
campaigns.
<P>
Consequently, it could be said that drug capital takes the front
seat in economic processes, leading to yet another paradox inherent
in the worldwide drug problem: maintaining neo-liberal strategies,
supporting the principle of deregulation and extreme liberalisation
tends to strengthen the role of drugs traffic two-fold. It props
up the marginal aspects of official markets as well as providing
a source of financial resources in long periods of recession.
Some analysts believe that drug dollars are also used, occasionally
to honour external debt repayments.
<P>
Certain Latin America specialists and analysts claim that the
role played by illegal capital in national and regional economic
processes has reached a point where to do without it would probably
trigger total collapse. Others try to play down this role, qualifying
it as influential but not decisive. Whatever the conclusion, there
does not appear to be a genuine desire in official circles to
stamp out the problem, whether in international decision-making
centres or national governments.
<P>
To do something effective, a determined action plan is needed
in order to lift certain legal smokescreens designed to increase
all kinds of secrecy, the basis of financial activities linked
to drugs trafficking.
<P>
The abolition of banking secrecy and the installation of controls
on capital movements would be the main planks of any strategy
designed to stifle the drug traffickers' financial activities.
But this would entail co-ordination at various levels between
governments and major private financial institutions, on the basis
of solid and sincere agreements.
<P>
Otherwise these habits will continue in Latin America, especially
in tax havens: governments will introduce control rules but they
will not be applied. Following their example, private institutions
will tend to relax their own preventive controls instead of tightening
them. Is it possible to implement such sincere and solid agreements?
In theory, yes, although for that purpose it will be necessary
to eliminate political obstacles associated with current economic
models. The challenge is all the greater because these obstacles
are highly structured, and based on economic and political correlation
and dependence.
<P>
Any other solution, such as the definition of new economic crimes,
together with sanctions (many countries do not consider money
laundering a crime) may prove partial and inadequate and, even
worse, may be scorned by the drug traffickers. They have already
demonstrated &quot;genius&quot;, audacity and shamelessness in
dodging armies, deriding controls, violating borders and corrupting
<U>urbi et orbi</U>.<A NAME="theme3"></A><HR>

