<P>
- Convention on LongRange Transboundary Air Pollution. (13th November
1979).
<P>
- Vienna Convention on the Protection of the Ozone Layer. (1985).
and Montreal Protocol
<P>
on Substances that Deplete the Ozone Layer. (1987).
<P>
- United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change (1992).
(not yet in force).
<H5><B>6. LIST OF CASES</B></H5>

<P>
The Barcelona Traction Case (2nd Phase) 1970 ICJ3.
<P>
The Corfu Channel Case -1948 ICJ15
<P>
The Island of Palmas Arbitration 22AJIL (1928)875
<P>
The Lake Lanoux Arbitration 53AJIL (1959) 156171 (1957) ILR101.
<P>
The Trail Smelter Arbitration (1938)(1941) UNRIAA VOL III 1905.
<A NAME="mark3"></A><HR>

<H3><B>DISCUSSION</B></H3>

<P>
<B>Professor Attard</B> said the two Maltese proposals are complementary
because the proposed group would identify and assess the environment
of extra-territorial spaces whilst the Trusteeship Council would
be given the task to protect them.
<P>
<B>Dr. Boldirev</B> noted that, as the Trusteeship Council proposal
is a Maltese initiative, the steps envisaged in the first paper
could be undertaken by the Maltese Government without the Rio
Conference's endorsement. But where does the group of eminent
persons fit in?
<P>
<B>Professor Attard </B>explained that the two concepts are indeed
complementary but should be dealt with separately during a first
stage. They should not be dependent on each other because if one
does not materialise, this should not affect the other.
<P>
<B>Dr. Boldirev</B> noted that in this case the Colloquium could
reaffirm its support for the group of eminent persons and also
support the Trusteeship Council initiative.
<P>
<B>Professor Attard </B>suggested that one could go one step further
and add that in its discussions the group could also consider
the possible role of the Trusteeship Council.
<P>
<B>Dr. Boldirev</B> proposed the following:
<P>
1. In respect of Prof Attard's proposal, if such a group is to
be established, then it should be &quot;in consultation with ther
executive heads of the other specialised agencies concerned&quot;.
<P>
2. With respect to the Trusteeship Council proposal, in the second
paragraph there is mention of assistance. This should be changed
to &quot;scientific and technical advice and any assistance...&quot;
<P>
<B>Dr. Keckes</B> said that most of the problems in extra-territorial
spaces have their origins in national jurisdictions. Control here
is within the hands of governments. Thus what would be the best
strategy to follow?
<P>
1. Demonstrate that there is a real problem with solid arguments.
<P>
2. Identify problems of spaces, activities and resources which
are beyond national jurisdiction in one respect but within it
as regards others in a limited way. (Some are of the opinion that
these have already been identified).
<P>
3. Create a very competent group of people to prompt the United
Nations General Assembly into action. This would necessitate a
variegated composition of the group which should include legal
experts as well as scientists and specialists in other fields.
For many studies separate groups would be necessary which in some
cases already exist.
<P>
4. Try to merge the advice obtained from the experts into political
action. Here someone has to examine the adequacy of existing law
and judge what has to be done.
<P>
How to get it done is the diplomatic process but this should be
separate from the legal and scientific approach.
<P>
<B>Mr. Savior Borg</B> said that the transformation of the Trusteeship
Council would necessitate amending the UN Charter which is obviously
very difficult.
<P>
<B>Professor Kappeler</B> noted that what was being proposed merged
beautifully together. The group of eminent persons could be the
perfect people to see where the advice is located and how to obtain
it.
<P>
<B>Professor Birnie</B> asked how the group of eminent persons
is to be funded and how the role of the Trusteeship Council could
be changed without amending the Charter?
<P>
<B>Mr. Saviour Borg </B>said that the three stage approach he
had suggested might help in paving the way for overcoming the
final difficulty of amending the Charter.
<P>
<B>Professor Attard</B> noted that if the General Assembly decides
to set up the group a budgetary provision would be made for it.
<P>
<B>Professor Birnie</B> suggested that UNCED should prove to be
a very fertile ground for other proposals.
<P>
<B>Professor Attard </B>asked Dr. Boldirev whether member States
would have the capacity to request the Secretary General of the
World Meteorological Organization to produce a study on the atmospheric
environment of the extra-territorial spaces.
<P>
<B>Dr. Boldirev</B> answered that if a statement is requested
the Executive Council of the Organization would definitely have
to be involved, but if the requeste comes from a State, one would
have to see. Whatever proposal will be endorsed by Rio and accepted
by the General Assembly, this would help the aim of this Colloquium.
Should everything fail the group of eminent persons would remain
the only available option. The Colloquium could suggest that:
<P>
1. A high level organ of the UN be made to support the proposal
to appoint a group of eminent persons;
<P>
2. The proposal to enlarge the mandate of the Trusteeship Council
should be considered.
<P>
<B>Professor Attard</B> was of the opinion that a group of persons
with special expertise in their field was necessary to produce
a report and to ascertain whether there is a problem and whether
it should be tackled or not.
<P>
<B>Professor Birnie</B> suggested that any conclusion should take
into account that:
<P>
1. Further studies are required urgently.
<P>
2. This is a very complex problem.
<P>
3. Any initiative for such a study should be endorsed but one
cannot neglect any of the various proposals being made.
<P>
A draft conclusion was then proposed by <B>Professor Kappeler
</B>and circulated for consideration by the participants.
<P>
