<BODY>

<H2><B>FRIDAY, 22nd MAY</B></H2>

<H2><B>SECOND AFTERNOON SESSION</B></H2>
<HR>

<UL>
<LI><A HREF="#mark1" >Closing speach made by the Hon. Dr. Stanley Zammit  
</A>
<LI><A HREF="#mark2" >Adoption of a preliminary report with conclusions of the Colloquium  
</A>
</UL>

<P>
<B>Chair</B>: Professor Kappeler
<P>
<B>Subject</B>: Adoption of a preliminary report with conclusions
and closing of the Colloquium
<P>
The Chairman guided participants through the draft document which
had been circulated to them. A number of amendments were proposed
and accepted. As time did not suffice, the Chairman suggested
that participants submit such further amendments as they might
wish to suggest in writing. For this purpose the revised document
was circulated after the end of the Colloquium.
<P>
The Chairman then welcomed Dr. Stanley Zammit, Parliamentary Secretary
for the Environment and invited him to deliver the closing speech.
<A NAME="mark1"></A><HR>

<H3><B>CLOSING SPEECH BY THE PARLIAMENTARY SECRETARY IN THE MINISTRY
OF THE ENVIRONMENT, THE HON.DR. STANLEY ZAMMIT M.D, M.P.</B></H3>

<P>
Mr. Chairman, distinguished delegates, ladies and gentlemen. I
have been informed of and followed with great interest the deliberations
made during this colloquium and I am indeed, to say the least,
surprised with certain data which your good work has unfolded.
Information of this nature is the one which has set the world
community to think about our future as well as that of generations
to come.
<P>
A marked difference is easily noticeable from the results of colloquia
such as this and other international fora where the representative
delegates are more often than not faced with the laborious task
of reaching compromises with the obvious resultant effects. In
meetings such as this, however, the personal views of the participants
have a key role and do in fact provide the opportunity to discuss
issues which are not on the agenda of international meetings.
This forum again departs from the necessary formalities of international
conventions by successfully hosting a dialogue between the scientist
and the drafter. The scientist who, alarmed by the findings of
certain data and who logically expects an immediate action to
halt further harm to the environment, is more often than not overwhelmed
by the number of hurdles which obstruct his path: development,
politics, negotiations and funding among many others. Indeed the
dangers unfolded by the scientist must necessarily be given a
meaning by enacting legislation which would create sanctions against
the promoting of such dangers. The drafter's role then becomes
indispensable. He is the representative, the lawyer and the negotiator
of his country faced with various issues which present themselves
as hurdles to the creation of a legally binding instrument, possibly
the same obstacles faced by the technical person whose preoccupations
would have, by then, reached unprecedented dimensions.
<P>
We all know and understand the difficulties present in the creation
of international treaties and it comes as no surprise that a number
of these instruments are devoid of any sanctions against an offending
party. However at this late hour, should we not be less concerned
about issues of sovereignty beyond the areas of national jurisdiction?
Recent history of mankind has proved beyond any doubt that activities
within areas of national jurisdiction are the main source of damage
to the environment of those extraterritorial spaces. That which
occurs within the areas of national domain and which is harmful
to the environment without, is of common concern of mankind a
phrase which has bounced back and forth within the four walls
of this same venue. In UNEP's Meeting of Senior Government Officials
Expert in Environmental Law held in Rio de Janeiro in October/November,
1991, some of the delegates put forward a proposal to include
in UNEP's programme for this decade, the development of legislation
against environmental crime.
<P>
The Kuwaiti oil wells set on fire before the withdrawal of Iraqi
troops and the deliberate spillage of oil in the Gulf were all
too recent examples of voluntary damage to the environment which
inspired, indeed motivated, this proposal. I was informed however,
that other delegations turned down this idea on the basis that
UNEP should not be concerned with the laws of war and that other
remedies exist for such eventualities. If I may be allowed to
speak with the same frankness as you have been doing in these
past two days, I do not share the same opinion on the matter and
I do believe that the time is ripe to move towards the concept
of accountability a concept which relies heavily on the work of
the diplomat for its success, for it will have to break the old
traditions of sovereignty in some degree or other.
<P>
You have been discussing the Legal Protection of the Environment
Beyond the Limits of National Jurisdiction and it results quite
clearly that the protection of the environment immediately addresses
the issue of effectiveness or otherwise of present legislation.
But, to borrow a few lines from our mutual friend Dr. Tolba, there
is a tendency to measure success in the field of environmental
law more in terms of legal acts than in terms of actually improving
the environment. The most basic question in this regard was whether
the situation on the ground was better now or at least likely
to be better than it was before the signing of a convention. Dr.
Tolba was quoted as saying in the Rio Conference that in the last
Governing Council of UNEP he was forced to conclude that &quot;the
efficiency and effectiveness of environmental legal regulations
leaves much to be desired&quot;. Where does this take us, ladies
and gentlemen? I must admit that I am happy to hear of an alternative
which could implement the work achieved to date. I say &quot;implement&quot;
because I believe that all that has been achieved to date, with
all its merits and demerits, should not go to waste. It is not
a matter of starting afresh but rather of finding other methods
of enhancement.
<P>
You have dealt with the subject of environmental diplomacy an
alternative which is of recent origin and which I believe to be
an indispensable tool for the creation of mechanisms for the protection
of the environment beyond the areas of national jurisdiction.
This meeting has given due recognition of the need to resort to
this new area. The environmental diplomat must be trained to bring
together the various facets involved not only in negotiating treaties
of environmental nature but also be instrumental in implementing
notions of accountability of States towards environmental issues.
<P>
In bringing an end to this colloquium, may I thank you for having
devoted so much of your precious time to bring forward your knowledge
and experience.
<P>
As one of the speakers stated, a good lawyer always starts by
a quoting an excerpt from some literature. Well, I am not a lawyer,
but I will quote Tennyson who said in one of his works that &quot;the
old order do the change the yielding place to new&quot;. If this
were a fact in Tennyson's time then it is a perplexing uncertainty
today and should commit the world community to strive in order
to save the environment for the future generations.
<P>
Ladies and Gentlemen, I bring this meeting to an end and I thank
you again for your valuable endeavour.
<P>
After the speech the Chairman thanked Dr. Zammit in the name of
the participants. He also congratulated and thanked the latter
for the important work they did over the two days of the Colloquium.
<A NAME="mark2"></A><HR>

<H3><B>SUMMARY REPORT AND CONCLUSIONS</B></H3>

<P>
The Colloquium was convened by the Mediterranean Academy of Diplomatic
Studies and co-sponsored by the Graduate Institute of International
Studies in Geneva. The organiser and convenor was David J. Attard,
UNEP Professor of Environmental Diplomacy at the Academy.
<P>
The Colloquium considered the following agenda:
<P>
1. Which are the spaces beyond national jurisdiction?
<P>
2. Scientific aspects of environmental degradation and remedies
for it.
<P>
3. The current status of the law relating to environmental protection
in general and in the Mediterranean in particular.
<P>
4. Strategies likely to produce international regimes and mechanisms
for the future.
<P>
5. The role of diplomacy in implementing effective legal environmental
protection.
<P>
The Colloquium noted that most environmental processes transcend
the distinction between national spaces and areas beyond national
jurisdiction, both as regards their causes and their effects.
The relevance of the distinction only lies in the fact that States
still are attached to the concept of national sovereignty and
therefore tend to conduct their diplomacy accordingly. As any
remedies against environmental damage must be decided and implemented
by States, and as most damaging events have their source on State
territory, the
<P>
delimitation between the latter and spaces beyond State jurisdiction
still matters.
<P>
Understanding environmental processes is a multi-disciplinary
affair which involves many scientific disciplines. Dealing with
prevention and remedy of degradation is essentially the business
of diplomats, national decision-makers and officials and international
institutions which mainly function as providers of data, monitors,
fora and advisers. Dealing with environmental issues therefore
can only make sense when following a holistic approach, which
means communication and mutual understanding of all involved.
<P>
Scientific understanding of environmental processes progresses
rapidly. This does not mean that predictions regarding the outcome
of such processes and their interaction are easy. Often more knowledge
only leads to the need for more research. But even fully understood
phenomena can produce diverse results depending on time and location.
The valuation of possible outcomes is obviously a subjective matter
which depends on the organ or even individual entrusted with it,
its priorities and its general outlook, and its regard for the
cautionary principle.
<P>
Although there is no comprehensive legal coverage of environmental
issues, there is a great number of more or less sectoral or even
specific regulations, some in the form of legal obligations undertaken
pursuant to a treaty, others adopted as resolutions and recommendations
of a persuasive nature. One reason for this situation is that
the urgency of dealing with such problems as climate change and
preservation of the ozone layer is such that immediate action
is required which cannot wait until the complex process of negotiating
global regulations can be completed.
<P>
The Colloquium noted with concern that whereas States are often
willing to negotiate and sign treaties, they do not always implement
them, both as regards legal and administrative action and providing
the necessary financial means. One can even note an accumulation
of regimes with similar or even overlapping aims none of which
results in much practical action being undertaken by those concerned.
<P>
As in the case of regulations there is equally a plethora of institutions
dealing with environmental matters both at national and international
levels. The
<P>
Colloquium noted that very often these institutions do not communicate
properly or even ignore each other deliberately. Very often lack
of communication and coordination at international level has its
source in the same lack of communication at national levels, as
a result of which different institutions get different signals
from the same countries.
<P>
In the Mediterranean region, the Barcelona Convention System constitutes
a framework of comprehensive cooperation between coastal States.
Whereas the Convention only concerns itself with the waters of
the Mediterranean, several Protocols are both more precise and
broader in territorial scope, concerning themselves with land-based
sources of pollution as well as with their impact on the sea.
Under the Barcelona Treaty system progress appears to have been
made in stressing the persuasive aspect of the law and the public
interest aspect of actions undertaken, wherein the concept of
public trust could be usefully employed. The Mediterranean Action
Plan has contributed a lot to help individual countries take the
required steps to implement their treaty obligations. This has
lately been facilitated by the availability of funds from the
World Bank and the European Development Bank.
<P>
The Colloquium was provided with detailed information on the initiatives
Malta has undertaken at the United Nations to promote strategies
concerned with global environmental protection. It supports the
proposal that a Group of eminent specialists, including scientists,
consider the requirements for the proper protection of the environment
beyond national jurisdiction and in areas under partial State
control and to propose possible strategies and institutional arrangements
to meet these requirements. The Colloquium also noted with interest
the proposal of Malta's Deputy Prime Minister and Minister of
Foreign Affairs to transform the role of the UN Trusteeship Council
into that of a Guardian of the &quot;Global Commons&quot; for
present and future generations. Although its realisation is likely
to raise many problems, this proposal should be further studied,
among other possible institutional arrangements.
<P>
The Colloquium discussed the specific characteristics of environmental
diplomacy and of the diplomats required for the purpose. It noted
the
<P>
importance of proper understanding of scientific issues and of
proper briefing by all national agencies concerned. It also noted
that environmental negotiations are difficult because overall
consensus must be achieved without prejudicing the clarity and
effectiveness of regulations adopted. A greater sense of solidarity
of mankind is required in this context, in order not to allow
strictly national interests to block discussions.
<P>
As regards strategies, the Colloquium identified the following
salient issues:
<P>
1. Identification of spaces, resources and activities under limited
national jurisdiction or beyond it.
<P>
2. Identification of environmental problems of such spaces, resources
and activities.
<P>
3. Assessment of the adequacy of the present international legal
agreements to deal with the environmental problems thus identified.
<P>
4. Formulation of proposals for legal and institutional arrangements
such as changing the mandate of the UN Trusteeship Council, elaboration
of new overall conventions etc.
<P>
The Colloquium also adopted the following conclusions:
<P>
1. The Colloquium supports the idea that environmental problems
of areas beyond national jurisdiction be examined within the United
Nations framework at a high level. It supports the proposal made
by Malta to appoint a Group of eminently competent persons for
this purpose and suggests the following:
<P>
a. The persons should be selected through the Executive Director
of UNEP and in consultation with the executive heads of all other
specialised institutions and agencies
<P>
concerned. They should be chosen on account of their high level
of expertise in the various relevant scientific and other areas
involved.
<P>
b. The Group should as a first step gather all relevant scientific
information from the various specialised institutions and agencies
able to provide this. For this purpose, it could establish sub-committees.
On the basis of the data thus accumulated, the Group should then
consider strategies and the legal and institutional framework
for their implementation.
<P>
c. Due regard should be paid to existing legal regimes and institutions
and the manner in which they might be used to implement the strategies
identified. Insofar as any need for additional UN structures may
be ascertained, the Maltese proposal that the Trusteeship Council
assume responsibility for the preservation of the &quot;Global
Commons&quot; for present and future generations should be given
due consideration.
<P>
2. The Colloquium considered the proposal made by the Deputy Prime
Minister and Minister of Foreign Affairs of Malta to enhance the
role of the UN General Assembly as regards the safeguarding of
the &quot;Global Commons&quot; for present and future generations
and his suggestion to entrust that task to the UN Trusteeship
Council. While aware of the serious difficulties involved in amending
the UN Charter, the Colloquium felt that the proposal merits further
consideration and it welcomed the suggestion that the Mediterranean
Academy of Diplomatic Studies be asked to prepare a detailed study
of it. <HR>

