<H1><A NAME="DDE_LINK1"></A><A NAME="DDE_LINK2"></A><CENTER>INTERNATIONAL
CONFERENCE ON</CENTER></H1>

<H1><CENTER> DRUGS: DEPENDENCE AND INTERDEPENDENCE</CENTER> <BR>
</H1>

<H2><CENTER>Lisbon, 23 - 25 March 1996</CENTER> <BR>
</H2>

<H2><CENTER>TITLES OF CONTRIBUTIONS</CENTER> </H2>

<H3><CENTER><A HREF="#theme1">LOCAL ECONOMICS </A>- <A HREF="theme2.htm">FINANCIAL FLOWS </A>-
<A HREF="theme3.htm">TRADE AND AGRICULTURE </A>- <A HREF="theme4.htm">DEBT AND STRUCTURAL ADJUSTMENT </A>-
<A HREF="theme5.htm">DEVELOPMENT AID </A>- <A HREF="theme6.htm">ENVIRONMENT </A>-
<A HREF="theme7.htm">INTERNATIONAL CONVENTIONS </A>- <A HREF="theme8.htm">NEW PRODUCERS AND TRADERS </A>-
<A HREF="theme9.htm">LOCAL CONFLICTS </A>- <A HREF="theme10.htm">CONTROL MEASURES </A>-
<A HREF="theme11.htm">EDUCATION AND MEDIA </A>- <A HREF="theme12.htm">INFORMATION SHARING </A></CENTER><A NAME="theme1"></A>
</CENTER></H3>

<H3><CENTER>THEME N&#186;1 - <A NAME="bianco"></A>LOCAL ECONOMICS
</CENTER></H3>

<P>
<CENTER>The micro-economics of drugs in Europe, in particular
in those sectors most affected by economic crisis</CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><A HREF="#koutous">Michel KOUTOUSIS - Greece </A>- <A HREF="#navarez">Leonel NARV&Aacute;EZ G&Oacute;MEZ - Colombia </A></CENTER>
<HR>

<H2>Contribution by Michel KOUTOUSIS - Greece </H2>

<H3>''From ancestral routes to informal trade on the streets''
</H3>

<H3>&quot;A delinquent is someone who pursues goals that society
values by means that it does not&quot;. R.K.Merton</H3>

<H3>&quot;Couriers&quot; and consumers</H3>

<P>
The last three decades in western urban centres have been characterised
by two constants: the impoverishment of working-class suburbs,
hit by ever-increasing unemployment, and the influx of immigrants
of various origins, today accounting for a large proportion of
the urban population. Since the late 1980s, the homelands of these
scattered populations from central and eastern Europe, the Middle
East or the Maghreb countries have seen a worsening of their troubles
and, especially, a growing autonomy vis-&agrave;-vis the major
powers.
<P>
Having lost their source of funds when the Cold War ended, local
conflicts are now financed from the informal economy. But the
quest for profits, especially where drugs are concerned, has pushed
the warring parties to extend their control of trade from production
to retail sale. Conflicts as distant as those in Kurdistan, Abkhazia
and Algeria therefore have, in this respect, a direct influence
on the streets of Germany, the Netherlands or France.
<P>
All these (often unwitting) messengers of disorder find, at the
end of their journey, another equally dislocated society, that
of deprived urban areas. Paradoxically, these stricken populations
from afar seem closer to that society than the consumer society
alongside it. Drugs therefore enable these &quot;couriers&quot;
to achieve the myth of success and they help those living in deprived
areas to tolerate their exclusion.
<H3>The &quot;short circuits&quot; of the Schengen area</H3>

<P>
So, alongside traditional trafficking by established criminal
organisations, there is now a fragmented drugs economy: in Europe,
Kosovo clans, Chechens or Moroccans; &quot;Afghan&quot; fundamentalists
and Turkish &quot;grey wolves&quot;; Nigerian &quot;students&quot;
and Senegalese immigrant workers; Croatian, Serbian or Bosnian
&quot;fighters&quot;; and Latin-American, Polish or Russian &quot;businessmen&quot;
form networks of dealers outside the traditional distribution
circuits. The party, the brotherhood, family friends, old army
friends or colleagues from information services tell them what
they need to know : the size of the city, local dealers, potential
customers. In most cases, they own the drugs they are selling.
They buy them in Albania, Bulgaria, Turkey, Spain, Egypt or the
Ukraine, and sometimes directly from central Asia. They consider
the whole of Europe a potential market, a target which sometimes
becomes a bone of contention. The fact is that where drugs are
sold, where they bring in the necessary cash, the distribution
channels are fought over. So PKK militants and &quot;grey wolves&quot;,
Danhnak Armenians and Lebanese, Kosovo or Turkish networks are
constantly renegotiating distribution territories, sometimes going
as far as armed battle, as we saw recently in Zurich, Frankfurt
and Berlin. These are not straightforward gangland killings but
military operations conducted by trained troops, brought in specially
for the job, who, after fierce fighting, will dislodge a distribution
network from a whole neighbourhood.
<P>
Others, who are permanently on the move and act as &quot;raiders&quot;,
do not disturb local dealers. Unless they are unlucky (as was
the case in Savoie and in Brittany in 1995), by the time the locals
and the police react to their presence, they are long gone.
<P>
These &quot;short circuits&quot; can be found all over Europe.
In the Netherlands they go from restaurant to restaurant with
false-bottomed cans of orange juice. In France, they tour the
bars, while in Germany it is the caf&eacute;s and saunas. Trains,
stations, gaming rooms and hotel lobbies all become points of
sale. Or, there are those that stay put in high-class hotels,
for example in Salonika, and work by phone, waiting to be contacted;
sometimes they even apply for legal status. They prefer the provinces.
After deprived urban areas, provincial towns, and more particularly
those sleepy, out-of-season tourist resorts such as Deauville,
Verona and Karlovy-Vary (spa towns, ski resorts, seaside resorts
and so on) are beginning to make a name for themselves alongside
Tirana, Sofia and Istanbul.
<H3>Poor man's laundering</H3>

<P>
The symbiosis between immigrants and victims of social exclusion
democratises, to a certain extent, the profits from informal trade,
permeating the neighbouring environment. While the drugs trade
continues, as always, to make a few big shots very rich, it is
also part of a micro-economy resulting from the profits from street
dealing. The negative consequences, particularly among young people,
are well-known: loss of family authority, appeal of easy money,
life in a criminal environment, contempt for knowledge and education,
often leading to unemployment, etc. But on the streets, in the
crisis-stricken family, the immediate effects of the redistribution
of profits from drugs trafficking are not to be under-estimated:
small shops and services reap the benefits. The financial pressure
on families and even on local authorities is relieved. At the
same time, traffickers exert pressure to ensure that the neighbourhood
presents a facade of legality in order to ward off checks: rents
are paid, petty crime stamped out and so on.
<P>
In fact, this redistribution of profits is simply laundering on
a small-scale, corresponding to the situation of the very poor.
It merely reproduces, in miserabilist form, a mechanism which
in other spheres reintroduces far larger profits into the formal
economy.
<H3>Globalisation and micro-economy</H3>

<P>
At both worldwide and local level, drugs today, beyond their more
traditional characteristics, have become a means of escaping from
recession or achieving desirable goals. They are part of a more
global informal trade which is a response to the failures and
marginalisation of some members of our western societies, and
to the confusion of the world in general. The immigrants and the
victims of social exclusion are both hunters and hunted in this
process.
<P>
Just as the gap is widening between words and action within our
inner cities and suburbs, so the psychological constraint of an
all-out war against drugs is increasingly met with a stereotyped
response. Such fixed attitudes stand in the way of any genuine,
global talks on drugs, for as long as we remain increasingly attached
to our national borders and our certainties.
<P>
Before proposing alternative policies, it would be better therefore
to begin with these observations. As simple as they may be, they
do not seem for the moment to be clearly perceived.
<H3>The visible and the invisible</H3>

<P>
This situation focuses our action and reactions around visible
facts. Racism and xenophobia use drugs as a tool and find convenient
solutions by replacing the word xenos with drugs. Once again drugs
become a pretext, a justification for other phobias. Street dealers
and &quot;short circuit&quot; operators tend to be people with
&quot;ethnic&quot; origins, working in horizontal structures where
profits are, always invisibly, both made and spent, whereas the
drugs barons, wholesale dealers and launderers are usually westerners.
Their identity is rarely known, although they are occasionally
unmasked: the most recent example was in January 1996 when several
tons of hashish were seized in Galicia, Spain, and the organisers
and kingpins turned out to be Dutch and Spanish businessmen.
<P>
In fact, the very structure of drugs trafficking tends to be a
joint venture. Its visible parts, fragile and connected to street
dealing, are ingredients of an illegal environment of both users
and dealers. Its invisible parts, like modern businesses, blend
into a legal environment and the formal economy. According to
the World Customs Organisation, the bigger the haul, the fewer
the number of arrests made. While the number of arrests on the
streets among both users and dealers is on the increase, arrests
for international trafficking are stagnant.
<P>
Despite opposing principles, according to which either supply
or demand is regarded as the crucial factor, they must be examined
together as interacting elements.
<H3>Proposals</H3>

<P>
Beyond the universally-approved action to revitalise and rehabilitate
the economic, social and cultural life of deprived urban areas,
it is necessary to examine more closely the nature, extent and
impact of the informal economy on these areas, in the following
ways:
<P>
explain, in order to find solutions, why street dealing attracts
&quot;ethnic&quot; populations and networks;
<P>
break up the rings through which operators exchange drugs;
<P>
guard against certain perverse effects of administrative decisions
which affect user habits and directly influence trafficking; for
example, the introduction of methadone programmes in France caused
an increase in crack use.<HR>

<H2>Contribution by <A NAME="navarez">Leonel NARV&Aacute;EZ GOMEZ
</A>- Colombia</H2>

<H3>&quot;The micro-economics of drugs in the marginalised regions
of the Amazon in Colombia</H3>

<H3>Introduction</H3>

<P>
Contrary to all expectations, coca leaf production has risen significantly
over the last three years in Caquet&aacute;, an Amazonian region
in southern Colombia which stretches over some 90,000 square kilometres
and is the focus of this paper.
<P>
By the end of 1995, between 40 and 45,000 hectares of coca had
been planted in the region (this is at odds with the naive figure
quoted by the Colombian Government of 38,000 hectares for the
whole country). This makes it one of Colombia's leading coca regions.
<P>
On the micro-economic front, this paper will attempt to reply
to the following question: Are there viable alternatives to coca?
Are government operations effective and, if not, what steps need
to be taken? The relationship between poverty, coca and damage
to the environment is clear.
<P>
The Amazon region's coca growers have, as a rule, been expelled
from richer areas as they did not own any land and thus find themselves
in absolute poverty. What is more, this trend is on the rise,
with the population of Caquet&aacute; climbing by 12% in 1994.
<P>
The region's natural environment is vulnerable and there is scarcely
any government presence, which, in turn, means no regional planning,
credible production alternatives or basic transport, supply and
market infrastructure.
<P>
Coca, on the other hand, has not only adapted miraculously to
the Amazon soil and climate, but would currently appear to be
the only viable crop. Profitability and a weekly cash-flow, albeit
fluctuating, are by far its most attractive features. What is
more, in spite of the major risks inherent in the coca economy
- for one thing it is illegal, and for another, everything is
controlled by &quot;guerrilleros&quot; groups and drug traffickers
- the crop offers unparalleled logistics in terms of financing,
technical assistance, production facilities and markets.
<P>
In January 1996, the total production cost (guerilla fees included)
of one kilo of coca base in Caquet&aacute; was US$ 393 and it
could be sold for US$ 1100, providing a return of 250%.
<P>
Of the US$ 1100 it fetches, 65% goes to the producer, 20% to the
labourer and 15% on production costs. That means that a family
of four with an average of four to five hectares of land can make
US$ 690 a month per person from coca, which is much better than
the barely tapped alternatives. Cocoa, for example, provides a
monthly income of US$ 90 and rubber US$ 225. Colombia's current
minimum wage lies somewhere in the region of US$ 142. Although
coca prices fluctuate more, the crop can easily be stored while
producers await better days.
<P>
Yet coca has a social cost and is synonymous with illegality,
total state neglect, crime, loss of civic responsibility, violence,
family breakdown, prostitution and alcoholism. It also has certain
indirect economic costs stemming from the inflationary trend triggered
by over-consumption of goods that are not produced locally, thereby
forcing the whole population to take up the coca trade, whether
to be able to keep up with wage levels or to respond to the increase
in wages in the countryside or to buy basic goods imported from
other regions.
<P>
Clearly the coca economy has brought no benefit to the region.
A telling example is provided by the people of Remolinos del Cagu&aacute;n,
which boasts the region's most dynamic coca trade, who are poorer
now than they were 20 years ago when the illegal trade did not
exist. There is minimal provision of education, health care and
services and no community and civil organisation. What is more,
people live in a climate of fear for the region's future.
<P>
Many peasants are willing to forego coca profits provided they
can rewrite the script of the tragedy which they are currently
experiencing.
<H3>Current policies and trends</H3>

<P>
Forced eradication (military persecution and fumigation) coupled
with substitution programmes (the PLANTE national alternative
development plan, the PNR rehabilitation plan and the INCORA Agrarian
Reform Institute) are the only policies the Colombian Government
has managed to come up with, under pressure from the US administration.
But everything has remained at the stage of well-meaning intentions
with no effective implementation and the only results have been
a temporary fall-off in the intensity of the coca trade and its
shift to the darkest depths of the forest. The peasants have learned
by themselves to predict the behaviour of coca prices and increase
or reduce their crops accordingly. In the meantime, they have
refined agronomic techniques for growing coca and have boosted
output figures.
<P>
The government has no regional planning blueprint to reverse the
ongoing trend of the local economy. The measures it did sketch
out were paternalistic, inconsistent, weak and out of step with
reality.
<P>
Other productive sectors in the region apart from coca, whether
extensive livestock rearing or logging (activities that are extremely
harmful to the environment), are becoming less and less attractive.
Unemployment is on the rise because of the scarcity of suitable
wood, the drop in demand for cattle both locally and internationally
and the fact that people are scared off from investing in the
region for fear of kidnapping or extortion and a general lack
of safety.
<P>
At regional level, there are neither development plans nor sources
of funding. The &quot;regional government&quot; simply does not
exist and the local political classes work only on the basis of
patronage. Local governments are very weak and have no steering
body that can plan ahead; they thus map out short-term strategies
with no effective sustained policy to achieve credible regional
development. This being the case, coca still remains the only
means of survival.
<P>
The main government programme for replacing and eradicating coca
is called PLANTE, but parts of it are strikingly paternalist and
populist. What is more, it is not at all clear and enjoys neither
local backing nor local participation. The programme, which is
to run over three years (1995-7), is based on vague figures, and
is targeted more at forced uprooting than substitution. It is
actually divided into two phases: the &quot;stick&quot; (fumigation
and armed intervention) and the &quot;carrot&quot; (loans, technical
assistance and the market). Loans do not work because the body
which is responsible for them (the Caja Agraria) is hampered by
the many formalities blocking access to credit. Technical assistance
comes under the municipal technical assistance units (Umatas),
which are totally ineffective and bereft of alternatives, given
that the Amazon regions do not have a credible production system
and that the professionals are not up to standard as they are
appointed on the basis of political quotas.
<P>
The market is still the main bottleneck for all peasant economies.
There is no infrastructure or transport network in the forest.
A region of 90,000 km2 has only some 800 kilometres of roads,
which are in a pitiful state and located only in a livestock-rearing
area. Under the PLANTE programme, the market is planned over two
years, which is far too short a time-frame to stabilise production
and write off the cost of the infrastructure needed for such a
project. At the end of the day, PLANTE is nothing more than a
policy to generate figures, be they accurate or not, for the United
States Government, which naively insists that thousands of hectares
of coca be destroyed without suggesting any alternative.
<H3>Practical alternative policies</H3>

<P>
Setting in motion a development process is the only way to eliminate
coca and avert an ecological tragedy. Without coca, peasants would
be forced to destroy vast swathes of forest to make room for traditional
crops and grow enough to earn as much as they did with coca. Attempting
to eradicate coca by armed force in a region where the guerilla
reigns supreme is a sign of acute naivety.
<P>
A logical and effective substitution plan calls above all for
long-term planning. In this scenario, the first and most urgent
thing to be done is to plug the gap in terms of production, processing
and marketing techniques. With no processing industry, the Amazon
regions will never manage to export their products. Technical
staff must therefore be trained to oversee the planning, transfer
and management of production systems at different levels of production,
processing and marketing. Clearly, substantial financial resources
are vital for implementing such programmes, which can, on no account,
be scheduled over the short-term but only over long periods. If
such a scheme were not feasible, legalisation would seem the most
appropriate alternative, yet even if coca were legalised, the
process outlined above could not be put off indefinitely.
<H3>Recommendations</H3>

<P>
People are increasingly coming to speak as one on the need for
any effective illegal crop eradication strategy to be &quot;mainstreamed&quot;,
that is to say to cover all aspects of people's lives in Amazon
regions.
<P>
<I>Priority should therefore go to:</I> 
<P>
programmes to encourage a return to civic and ethical values;
<P>
encouraging the growth of community organisations by fostering
an economy based on solidarity and a sense of belonging to the
country and the whole of its judicial, economical and political
system;
<P>
identifying and introducing Amazon products which can generate
a reasonable level of liquid assets and profitability. This would
involve basic research and technology transfer operations;
<P>
expanding national and international markets for legal products.
This would include upgrading technical facilities, road links,
storage capacities and transport;
<P>
working towards the industrialisation and processing of Amazon
products, without which the enthusiasm of farmers for new crops
would be dampened;
<P>
providing social infrastructure (schools, bridges, hospitals,
water etc). Such amenities may help integrate people into civil
society and limit peasants' resistance to substitutes for coca
by making up for income lost from new alternative crops.
<P>
At international level, the technology required means that foreign
backing and investment as well as sufficient human resources are
needed to work out forms of production tailored to the Amazon
region, along with assistance from and training for national and
local professionals, who might take charge of arranging, establishing,
adapting and transferring such systems.
<P>
At national level, what is urgently needed is an integrated regional
development blueprint consonant with the socio-cultural and agro-ecological
features of the area.
<P>
At regional level, it is crucial to set up and strengthen government
and non-governmental bodies which are capable of bringing production
systems into line with the situation on the ground.
<P>
What are needed locally are integrated training schemes for the
transfer of technologies to suit the community.
<H3>Conclusion</H3>

<P>
Failing this, the likely scenario for the whole of the Amazon
region is another 20 to 25 years of the grim and tragic existence
that goes hand in hand with coca growing, with all its grave implications
for the region, the country and the world. 
</BODY>

</HTML>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT08-B17-26</DOCNO>
