<CENTER><H1><A NAME="DDE_LINK1"></A><A NAME="DDE_LINK2"></A> INTERNATIONAL
CONFERENCE ON </H1>

<H1>DRUGS: DEPENDENCE AND INTERDEPENDENCE</CENTER> <BR>
</H1>

<P>
<CENTER>
<H2>Lisbon, 23 - 25 March 1996</CENTER> <BR>
</H2>
<HR>

<P>
<CENTER>
<H1>THEME N&#186;11 - <B><A NAME="theme2"></A><A NAME="theme6"></A><A NAME="theme8"></A><A NAME="theme9"></A><A NAME="theme10"></A><A NAME="theme11">EDUCATION
AND MEDIA</A></B></H1>

<P>
Information and the role of the media in the prevention of the
consumption and the supply of drugs
<H3><A HREF="#parvex">Ricardo PARVEX - Chile </A> - <A HREF="#piro">Patrick PIRO - France </A></CENTER>
</H3>

<H3><A NAME="theme3"></A>Contribution by <A NAME="parvex">Ricardo
PARVEX </A>- Chile</H3>

<H3>''Education, information and communication strategies in the
drugs sphere''</H3>

<H3>Introduction</H3>

<P>
Developments in the presentday world are moving inexorably towards
the internationalisation of the production, trading and distribution
of a growing number of consumer goods and services.  This fact,
the result of progress in the industrial, transport and communications
fields, has led to the exponential growth in the quantity and
variety of products available to a now worldwide consumer population.
<P>
The international expansion of production and trade obeys no rules
other than those of supply and demand.  This applies as much to
the production of foodstuffs, arms, cultural products, garments
and electronic equipment as to that of drugs.  So geographical
regions and populations completely unfamiliar with certain products
are now being attracted to these new markets, which are becoming
part of their consumption patterns.
<P>
Tribal warfare and local disputes in Africa, Asia and Latin America,
until recently conducted with axes, knives and ancient firearms,
are now efficiently resolved using Kalashnikovs, antipersonnel
mines and shells fired from long range.  In many remote corners
of the planet, illnesses to which traditional medicine and medicaments
were once applied are starting to be treated through modern pharmacy
and medicine.  It would take too long to list the changes under
way in everyday human life, but it would be enough to say that
not only consumer goods and services are affected, but also other
more profound and more complex manifestations of the human being,
such as religious beliefs and practices.
<P>
It is against this background of farreaching change and universalisation
of ways and customs that we have to consider the invasion of our
societies by drugs.  While the developed countries flood the planet
with their highperformance, efficient industrial products, the
disappearance of borders and reduction of distances bring us into
contact with often mysterious and exotic products from elsewhere,
used as perfect instruments for escape.
<P>
As these products are not part of its culture, the western world
lacks the knowhow applied to their use in their places of origin.
 Most of them being prohibited products, they are never marketed
with a &quot;dosage&quot; or &quot;instructions for use&quot;,
unless &quot;word of mouth&quot; gives some guidance rendered
more obscure by its clandestine nature.  A current trend accompanying
the growth in consumer goods is also linked to the appearance
of drugs in our daytoday lives.  Psychologists report sustained
and constant efforts to find a way of overcoming the pitfalls
of ordinary life.  Our contemporaries are less and less willing
to put up with the constraints of illness, pain, old age, distance,
loneliness and boredom.  They think they have found the solution
to every one of these problems, a response all the more effective
for being rapid, complete and absolute.  Psychotropic drugs are
at the fore in this context.
<P>
These developments have led to some concepts being superseded
by others more appropriate to the way in which the world is now
structured.  Citizens now tend to identify with consumer's participation
with consumption, and development with integration into the market.
 Communication, information and - very much so - the failings
of education have played a leading role in this conceptual change
and in these new social practices.
<H3>Current education, information and communication policies
</H3>

<P>
We shall first analyse these three fields, from the general to
the specific.
<P>
<I>Communication:</I> this encompasses every method of transmitting
a message and all the forms it can take: written, oral, audiovisual,
and so on.  It also covers the various approaches used, involving
advertising, teaching, entertainment, etc.  Communication about
drugs problems is part of this, so it is subject to the same rules
as those which govern communication about other aspect of life
in society.  Before turning our attention to communication in
relation to drugs and drug addiction, we shall describe the three
main features of communication in general at the moment: proliferation,
nonspecificity and lack of originality.
<P>
<I>Proliferation:</I> the numbers of messages for &quot;communication&quot;
are proliferating to an extraordinary extent.  This expansion
on every front leads to unstructured jumbles of information, resulting
in confused and garbled messages.  This just makes it more difficult
for an uninitiated audience to understand.  The introduction of
thematic channels might go some way to resolving this problem.
 However, it might well give rise to &quot;elitist&quot; communication
and leave the population groups in greatest need even more cut
off from information.
<P>
<I>Non-specificity:</I> one of the consequences of communication's
role in consumption is that the message is put across to the general
public.  This has at least two consequences.  One is that the
signal given does not go exclusively to its target, leading to
&quot;undesirable&quot; sideeffects.  The best example of this
is films showing violence or sex, which &quot;nonspecific&quot;
transmission makes available to children.  The second is that
the message, often tinged with &quot;consumerism&quot;, reaches
a broader audience than that with access to consumption.  Frustration
and marginalisation may ensue.
<P>
<I>Lack of originality:</I> there being no hierarchical structure
in modern communication, some of the messages deserving particular
treatment and methods lack originality.
<P>
The above three elements only make communication about such a
complex and new problem as that of drugs and drug addiction more
opaque.  Dangerous inefficacity is the inevitable result of the
disorderly and unstructured accumulation typical of this kind
of communication, coupled with a lack of clarity about targets
and a lack of originality in the message.
<P>
<I>Information:</I> this is more than communication, but a message
intended to be received by someone who thereby obtains a certain
amount of data.  This is already an area where there is more of
a target, and of which more direct use may be made for preventive
purposes.  It is nevertheless the case that information on the
subject of interest to us is extremely polarised and fragmentary.
 After studying the information about drugs provided by a good
number of Spanish media, a journalist called Milagro P&eacute;rez
Oliva, who works on the daily &quot;El Pa&iacute;s&quot;, states
that the information given by the media is processed in a way
which corrupts and distorts it.  This is said to happen in three
stages: simplification, homogenisation and generalisation.  The
end result after all three is an extremely inaccurate and tendentious
vision of the problem.  In P&eacute;rez Oliva's view, there are
two reasons for this: the fact that virtually all information
about drugs comes from police sources and the almost irreversible
tendency of &quot;information providers&quot; to regard drugs
issues as purely a matter of crimes or offences.  From this ensues
the advice that a &quot;media moratorium&quot; be adopted in this
field, enabling the conditions for fair and objective reporting
to be restored.
<P>
Noray and Parvex [addressing a seminar on drugs and the mass media
in Vitoria, Spain, in 1993] added a third factor to those mentioned
by P&eacute;rez Oliva.  These are the economic constraints and
requirements to which the media are subjected.  The simplification,
homogenisation and generalisation of drugs information, together
with the police sources and processing thereof, combine to give
a response which matches current trends in the information market
perfectly.  That market is subject to advertisers' dictates and
to the profitability constraints imposed by those in the media
who bear financial responsibility.  Apart from a simplified, not
to say simplistic, reading and a Manichaean treatment of events
with a view to high audience figures, large numbers of readers
and consequently profits from advertising, there is no hope for
information.  In the circumstances, there is no hope for information
intended to educate and raise awareness.
<P>
<I>Education:</I> this means not just informing, but putting information
across on a specific subject with a view to educating a selected
audience and giving it what it needs.  It always involves teaching
with a view to providing a public service.  Drugs and drug prevention
are problems which have been covered by large numbers of educational
efforts, from long-term health education campaigns to more specific
activities intended to prevent drug addiction.  With very few
exceptions, the main weapons so far used in such educational activities
have been fear, the moral aspect and health.  Fear and morality
created a real &quot;educational vacuum&quot;, preventing the
target audience (young people, atrisk groups, etc) from gaining
genuine knowledge of what is involved.  The drug situation was
shown to be independent of our own responsibility, like another
plague visited upon Egypt, bearing more resemblance to a divine
curse than to human behaviour.  This vision gave rise to <U>two
major failings in the educational effort</U>: on the one hand,
drugs seemed to be endowed with a life of their own, making them
unmanageable and quite out of human control; on the other, a stigma
was attached to drug addicts, as if they should be banished from
society.  The resulting impotence and discrimination merely make
the prevention of drug addiction even more difficult.  Good health
advocates abstinence, although it is known that people at risk,
who ought to be the main target of preventive action (weak persons,
drug addicts suffering from illnesses, etc) by definition have
little or no psychological capacity to resist.  If the health
argument were to have any degree of success, this would be vis&agrave;vis
individuals with little inclination to dependency, and certainly
not those who are susceptible.  It is a rather like taking coals
to Newcastle...
<H3>Alternative education policies and recommendations</H3>

<P>
Sensible education about the origins and history of drugs would
make the problem understandable in its historical context, consistent
with the development of our society.  Drugs and drug addiction
must finally be included as aspects of our real world and accepted
as a new part of our culture.  If they are no longer treated as
alien to our civilisation, the ills afflicting us become understandable.
 I shall now highlight a few of the practical ideas we hope to
contribute to the debate:
<UL>
<LI>efforts to dissociate from any ideology both health education
and drugs prevention.  It is a prerequisite that drugs be accepted
as part of our society.  Only by adopting this attitude can there
be ongoing preventive action, rather than temporary, oneoff activities;
<LI>elimination of the demon element so that drugs are treated
as inert and controllable, rather than as something with a life
of its own exempt from the general rules of society.  A prerequisite
is a demonstration and knowledge of every aspect.  This kind of
objective and scientific effort to spread the word should cover
themes such as original raw materials (synthetic or plantderived),
chemical formulae, means of action, pharmaceutical uses, beneficial
uses, risks and contraindications, the context in which they are
produced, manufactured and trafficked, and so on;
<LI>inclusion of such educational activities on official syllabuses
(primary and secondary schools, universities, military academies,
etc);
<LI>publicity for the views of (present or former) victims of
drugs, thereby restoring their citizenship and showing that the
problem is not just one which affects ''other people&quot;;
<LI>obtaining of funds, assistance and support from states and
international institutions for all educational activities (magazines,
films, publications, awareness campaigns, etc) in line with the
principles set out above.
</UL>

<P>

<H3>Puerto Natales, Chile, 2 February 1996</H3>
<HR>

<H3>Contribution by <A NAME="piro">Patrick PIRO </A>- France</H3>

<H3>Can the media take part in prevention?</H3>

<P>
The media are regularly the target of accusations by those dealing
with drug addicts: &quot;they only speak of the punitive aspects&quot;;
&quot;drug addicts are always shown as human wrecks&quot;; &quot;they
always aim for sensationalism&quot;, etc.  To that we should add:
&quot;What can be done so that the media can take part in prevention?&quot;.
<P>
Is this the right question?  Because the media can, to a certain
extent, put pressure on both the public and the authorities, should
they be seen as having to answer to the public, like an elected
representative or a government department.
<P>
The media have no vocation to look after public health or carry
out preventive measures.  Newspapers and magazines are seen, in
simplified terms, as companies doing business by selling news.
 As a result, their survival depends heavily on sales of advertising
space and maintaining a steady readership.  Certain magazines
have no aim other than to make a profit, deliberately focusing
on very specialised markets and exploiting the seedier aspects
of life (violence, sex, gossip, etc).
<P>
As for those famous press ethics, a media safety net, in every
country we have regular evidence that this hardly does anything
to prevent the media sliding into biased information, manipulation,
put-up jobs, etc.
<P>
Should we therefore give up any hope of conveying prevention messages
in the press?  No.  The modern media are formidable mouthpieces
but they are not - at least the mass media - the natural allies
of those who are involved in the field of drugs and drug addiction.
 At most, they are tools or go-betweens and the way to use them
optimally, with all their limitations, must be learnt.
<P>
Also there are media and media.  Television is a visual medium
and therefore ephemeral by nature, incurring considerable risks
but with a major potential for fascination.  Generally speaking,
the public have only limited confidence in it; the radio, the
immediate news medium par excellence, is able to deliver messages
to a very big audience; the press, more in the background, is
weighed down by the fact that it is printed, in our societies
where people swear by the written word.  But public confidence
in the press has been seriously eroded in recent years.
<P>
The media with the biggest audience - and therefore of greatest
interest if we are to convey prevention messages to the most people
- are often the least accessible for this type of exercise: the
bigger the audience, the vaguer and more slender the expectations
and the greater the risk of the audience growing tired of a prevention
campaign, rarely very entertaining, it has to be said, especially
in the case of drugs and drug addiction.
<P>
Furthermore, a prevention message, almost by definition, must
be repeated endlessly if it is to strike home.  Yet, short of
regularly buying pages of advertisements, it is out of the question
for the media to keep coming back to a given subject, however
interesting that subject might be.  News - this is a dogma of
journalism - is necessarily ephemeral and constantly changing.
<H3>Do the media manipulate information and messages?</H3>

<P>
We are all tempted to believe so.  Trick images, sound bites quoted
out of context and provocative articles are not rarities.  Yet,
deliberate malpractices aside, we are sometimes faced with a more
insidious situation: involuntary manipulation by the media.
<P>
Since they tend to meet the expectations of their readers in the
choice of subjects covered or in the way of presenting events,
the media may often be tempted to reproduce conventional or simplistic
rhetoric.  By adopting the prevailing arguments, and elaborating
on them, without detachment, they themselves help to form public
opinion, which then supports the prevailing arguments, which are
taken up again by the media, and so forth.  This leads to a kind
of media &quot;Larsen effect&quot;.
<P>
In turn, we may ask the question: do the media reflect public
opinion or do they help to create it?  Researchers have analysed
the way in which the subject of immigration was presented in 1993
in a daily newspaper published in south-western France.  They
discovered that it was frequently linked to other issues - petty
crime, violence, drugs and drug addiction.  Nothing overtly scandalous,
but an obsessive and regular correlation, working on public opinion
covertly. 
<P>
In an area as full of pitfalls as that of drugs and drug addiction,
this risk is permanent: whether consciously or not, an Algerian
selling cannabis with his uncles and brothers will tend to be
referred to as &quot;the head of an <U>Algerian</U> drug ring&quot;
(whereas a Frenchman in this situation would be referred to as
&quot;the head of a family drug ring&quot;).  Whether consciously
or not, drug addicts tend to be presented in terms of their failing
rather than as human beings worthy of respect, etc.
<P>
On the other hand, the media themselves may be manipulated.  The
fictitious mass graves of Timisoara in Romania or coverage of
the Gulf War are spectacular and disturbing examples.
<P>
This is a result, in particular, of the balancing act imposed
by working methods where urgency dominates but also of the choice
of information sources.  In the field of drugs (in France, in
any case), there are two main sources: the &quot;punitive&quot;
side, the police (along with customs and the courts); and the
&quot;treatment&quot; side, bodies dispensing health care.  For
the media the former source is often the more &quot;attractive&quot;:
it offers opportunities to witness spectacular operations (shadowing
suspects, arrests, seizures, etc) whereas health organisations
are shy of excessive publicity and prefer to work more discreetly.
<P>
It should, therefore, come as no surprise that certain media convey
a biased image of the phenomenon of drugs and drug addiction.
<H3>Is it possible to work with the media? </H3>

<P>
In France, the &quot;Grande Ecoute&quot; association has forged
working links with magazines and radio and television programmes
in order to have articles printed or to work jointly on regular
features.  They mainly work with magazines about the family or
problems facing society, by nature more open to prevention issues.
 Not only drugs are dealt with but wider-ranging issues, connected
with the search for well-being or difficulties facing young people:
How to be an adult.   Why do people commit suicide? etc.
<P>
The much maligned popular television channels do dare however,
albeit only from time to time, to undertake prevention operations.
 In France, for example, the yearly &quot;Sidathon&quot; (AIDS
Telethon) is now becoming a regular television event.
<P>
Apart, of course, from buying advertising space, it may therefore
be possible to work together with the media in the field of prevention.
 Generally speaking, success depends on having a good understanding
of how they work, what their interests are and what constraints
are put upon them.  First of all, they must be considered as partners
and not just recording studios, expected unquestioningly to pass
on the messages delivered to them. 
<H3>Some ideas:</H3>

<UL>
<LI><U>Learning to communicate with the media</U>: how to draft
a good press release, how to present our actions to turn them
into &quot;events&quot; attractive to journalists.  This does
not mean adapting chameleon-like to the demands of the press,
but bringing out the strong points of our activities, highlighting
them, clarifying presentation documents, using clear and direct
language, etc.  Far too often those involved in drug addiction
complain that &quot;the press did not turn up&quot;, even though
nothing had been done to attract it: no press kit, clumsy invitations,
a reluctance to communicate, etc.  As if, amid the mass of news
bombarding it every day, the &quot;press&quot; in question should
have guessed for itself the interest of a particular prevention
activity!
<LI><U>Training journalists</U>, regularly inviting them to seminars,
conferences or working groups. We must learn to see journalists
covering these subjects as &quot;drug/drug addiction&quot; workers
in their own right.
<LI><U>Setting up our own media</U>: very few media cover these
issues, yet the need for basic information is great.  It is interesting
to note that the most evangelistic groups, such as the Patriarch
Community, have their own magazines to publicise their ideas.
 The San Patrignano community, in Italy, publishes a superb monthly
colour magazine, produced to a fully professional standard.
</UL>

<H3>Magazines specialising in information about drugs</H3>

<P>
In 1990, we started up &quot;INTERDEPENDANCES&quot;, a news magazine
about drugs and drug addiction, in order to fill a yawning information
gap, make up for the lack of public awareness and instigate a
responsible debate in this area.  It is a <U>news</U> medium rather
than an <U>opinion</U> medium, because we feel this is what the
public needs most, in an area so full of partisan position-taking.
 The magazine offers balanced information, calling on the public
to accept its responsibilities vis-&agrave;-vis drugs: so that
everyone - as a parent, adolescent, citizen, drug-user, etc -
can have a better understanding of the risks for society and individuals,
going beyond simplistic views, so that they are better equipped
to tackle the issue.
<P>
Early on, the &quot;INTERDEPENDANCES&quot; magazine contemplated
the idea of taking on a European and international dimension.
In 1992, &quot;INTERDEPENDENCIAS&quot;, its Spanish cousin, saw
light of day, with the same basic aims.  In 1995 the first issue
of &quot;INTERDEPENDENZEN&quot;, the German-language version,
came out and three thematic issues of &quot;INTERDEPENDENCES&quot;
have been published in English since 1992.
<P>
Broadly speaking, we are set on showing that drug and drug-addiction
phenomena are complex: they must involve a number of professions
(health, justice, economics, police, education, research, finance,
etc) which must learn to work together in order to come up with
healthier approaches than mere punishment, which has easily shown
its limits, or simple liberalism, whose abuse would lead (if it
were tried out) to similar excesses.  They take a particular interest
in the alternatives to repressive policies being carried out in
Europe, as well as in the Third World or anywhere else.
<P>
For this phenomenon is not only complex, it is also global.  We
have detected several forms of interdependences, linking the individual
to society (the drug addict to anti-drug policies), the globe
to the neighbourhood (from production and trafficking to street-corner
deals).  No social category is safe, no country is exempt.  On
this final point, our various publications emphasise, in particular,
one aspect which tends to be forgotten, ie North-South relations.
 Drugs are a powerful reminder of the flaws in the world economy.
</BODY>

</HTML>
</DOC>
