<H3><B>PROCEEDINGS</B></H3>

<H5><I>THURSDAY, MAY 21st</I></H5>

<H4><B>OPENING SESSION</B></H4>

<P>
<I>Paper of Professor David Attard: &quot;Environmental Protection
of Areas beyond national jurisdiction: Proposal for international
action&quot;</I>
<P>
<B>Chair</B>: Professor Kappeler
<P>
Professor Attard, in his capacity of convenor, expressed his thanks
to the participants and his conviction that this Colloquium would
help in drawing attention to the environment issues beyond national
jurisdiction.
<P>
Professor Attard then read his paper:<HR>

<H4><B>ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION OF AREAS BEYOND NATIONAL JURISDICTION:
A PROPOSAL FOR INTERNATIONAL ACTION</B></H4>
<HR>

<H5><B>Introduction</B></H5>

<P>
The urge to improve the human condition coupled with rapid population
growth and the remarkable technological developments risks upsetting
the global environmental balance upon which, to a greater or lesser
degree, all life depends. Unless timely action is taken, the generations
of the next century - just over 2,500 days away - may inherit
a planet wherein even the very existence of life will be threatened.
In the face of this grave danger, it is not difficult to understand
that environmental protection has become one of the main concerns
of the international community.
<P>
Whilst considerable international action has been taken, or is
under way, there is a major deficiency in this process which has
to be remedied if the battle against environmental degradation
is to succeed. It is useless to improve the environment in areas
falling under national jurisdiction if the so called &quot;commons&quot;,
or, more precisely, areas beyond national jurisdiction (hereafter
referred to as &quot;Extra-Territorial Spaces&quot;) remain inadequately
protected.
<P>
Efforts to protect the environment deal mainly with activities
occurring in areas within State jurisdiction. This is understandable,
particularly as: (i) until recently, a large number of environmentally
harmful activities occurred mainly within States' territories;
and (ii) affective enforcement jurisdiction has traditionally
belonged to States. The absence of an effective international
institutional authority has further encouraged this tendency.
<H5><B>The Problem</B></H5>

<P>
Increasingly, however, it is becoming evident that environmental
damage caused to Extra-Territorial Spaces is a common concern
not just of a State or group of States, but of mankind as a whole.
Activities which cause damage to these spaces may cause prejudice
either to States or the international community as a whole. Polluting
activities occurring in Extra-territorial Spaces could easily
affect areas falling under the national jurisdiction of a State
or States. Even when this occurrence does not take place, it is
still reasonable to argue that such activities may cause harm
which could adversely affect the interest of the international
community as a whole in the said spaces.
<P>
Consequently, improved environmental protection within national
boundaries may eventually prove to be inadequate unless Extra-Territorial
Spaces are subject to effective environmental control. Furthermore,
it is no longer reasonable to argue that any State or entity that
pollutes Extra-Territorial Spaces should not be held accountable
to the international community. The traditional freedom of access
to these spaces and their uses has too often been translated into
freedom to pollute.
<P>
Given the increasing demands of mankind and its rapidly developing
technologies, the areas of common use can no longer be considered
vast enough to accommodate all human uses and needs. The current
state of the High Seas, regulated by the freedom of the seas regime,
demonstrates that intensive shipping, large-scale dumping, greater
resource exploitation and insensitive onshore developments are
threatening to disrupt the delicate ecological balance of this
immense space which covers over 45% of the globe's surface.
<H5><B>Extra-territorial spaces</B></H5>

<P>
There is no general widespread agreement as to which areas can
be characterized as Extra-Territorial Spaces. The area known as
the High Seas, its superjacent air-space, and the international
sea-bed area, are generally considered to be Extra-Territorial
Spaces. More controversial has been the status of Antarctica,
certain parts of the atmosphere, celestial bodies and the geosynchronous
orbits. There are also problems with respect to establishing the
exact geographical extent of these spaces. The extent of the High
Seas, for example, depends largely upon the maritime claims of
coastal States.
<H5><B>International law</B></H5>

<P>
It would be folly if the international community, in its efforts
to develop an effective international environmental law, failed
to fully recognize that the legal regimes regulating mankind's
use of Extra-Territorial Spaces provide inadequate comprehensive
environmental protection. Despite the interdependence of these
Spaces, the said regimes do not reflect this relationship. Furthermore,
even the most evolved - that of the High Seas - is unsatisfactory.
The development of freedom of the High Seas was largely based
on the premise that man could not cause serious, irreparable environmental
damage due to the vastness of oceans in the face of the relatively
limited human uses thereof. The validity of this premise is today
no longer tenable.
<P>
The environmental balance of the High Seas is in danger of being
irreparably upset due to activities ranging from the continuous
disposal of radioactive wastes (adding to the existing radiation
caused by nuclear weapons testing) to oil pollution (some 1.5
million tons of oil are spilled annually). Even the 1982 Convention
on the Law of the Sea does not contain effective institutional
or legal measures to ensure the effective and comprehensive environmental
protection of the High Seas. In fact, the Convention sets up an
institutional framework which is largely concerned with the sea-bed,
ocean floor and subsoil thereof, beyond the limits of national
jurisdiction. Article 135 states that the legal status of the
superjacent waters and air space remain unaffected. Despite some
innovations found in the environmental provisions of the Convention,
the envisaged protection of the High Seas remains insufficient.
<P>
A similar, if not greater, inadequacy exists with respect to the
regulation of other Extra-Territorial Spaces. On the other hand,
it would not be reasonable to deny that some progress has been
made. Reference, for example, can be made to the series of IMO
Conventions, the Outer Space Treaties, the Antarctica Treaties,
the 1963 Nuclear Test Ban Treaty, the 1976 Environmental Modification
Convention, and the 1985 Ozone Layer Convention and its related
1987 Protocol. Neither should the conclusion of these treaties
be overestimated for they raise innumerable social, economic,
political and technical differences.
<P>
Furthermore, this process deals with the problem in a fragmentary
manner often producing haphazard, piecemeal and disconnected measures.
This approach contradicts the interdependence which exists between
Extra-Territorial Spaces. Any response of the international community
to protect these spaces in the interests of present and future
generations must take into account this intimate relationship
and must be global in scope.
<P>
Finally, in considering regimes to protect the environment of
Extra-Territorial Spaces it is particularly important to remember
that a delicate balance has to be struck &quot;between regulating
activities too late and regulating non-existent activities too
soon&quot;. Thus, for example, it does not seem unreasonable to
seek to regulate the use of nuclear materials in outer space,
and the disposal of
<P>
space debris in the region between 160 and 1760 kilometres above
Earth. Similarly, space industry's plans to establish a lunar
colony for 12 astronauts by 2005 to exploit lunar resources for
oxygen, energy and building materials may require more immediate
attention and possible amendments to the Outer Space Treaties.
On the other hand, action with respect to the proposed manned
flight to Mars by 2010 would seem, at least at this stage, premature.
<H5><B>Proposed action</B></H5>

<P>
The magnitude and complexity of the problem calls for immediate
action of a global scale. It is proposed that the United Nations
is the proper forum wherein such action can be planned.
<P>
In this respect, it is suggested that the UN Secretary-General
should be requested - as a first step - to establish (through
the Executive Director of UNEP) a Group of Eminent Persons to
prepare a study which would <I>inter alia</I> make recommendations
with respect to the identification and extent of Extra-Territorial
Spaces, the environmental state of such spaces, the rights and
duties of States and the international community therein, possible
strengthening of relevant existing instruments, and make proposals
on how the effective environmental protection of such spaces can
be best achieved. <HR>

</BODY>

</HTML>
