<H3><CENTER>PROGRAMME OF THE COLLOQUIUM<BR>
</CENTER></H3>

<P>
<CENTER><TABLE BORDER="2">
<TR><TD WIDTH=193><B>TIME</B></TD><TD WIDTH=192><B>SUBJECT</B>
</TD><TD WIDTH=198><B>PARTICIPANT</B></TD></TR>

<TR><TD COLSPAN=3 WIDTH=583>Friday, 22 March 1996</TD></TR>

<TR><TD COLSPAN=3 WIDTH=583>Opening Session</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=193>9:30</TD><TD WIDTH=192><A HREF="papers/DEMARCO.htm">Welcoming address</A>
</TD><TD WIDTH=198>Hon. Prof. Guido de Marco, Deputy Prime Minister and Minister of Foreign Affairs of Malta
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD COLSPAN=3 WIDTH=583>Session One: Mediterranean Cooperation and Security After Barcelona. Perspectives from the European Union and its Member Countries
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=193>10:45 - 13:00</TD><TD WIDTH=192><A HREF="papers/Derisb.htm"><I>&quot;The Euro-Mediterranean Partnership after Barcelona&quot;</I></A>
</TD><TD WIDTH=198>Mr. Jean-Pierre Derisbourg, Advisor to the Director General Mr. Juan Pratt, Directorate General for External Relations DG IB, EU Commission, Brussels
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=193></TD><TD WIDTH=192><A HREF="papers/Lenzi.htm"><I>&quot;European Security and the Mediterranean&quot;</I></A>
</TD><TD WIDTH=198>Dr. Guido Lenzi, Director, Institute for Security Studies, Western European Union, Paris
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=193></TD><TD WIDTH=192><A HREF="papers/ALIBONI.htm" ><I>&quot;Euro-Mediterranean Partnership: An Italian Perspective&quot;</I></A>
</TD><TD WIDTH=198>Dr. Roberto Aliboni, Director of Studies, Istituto Affari Internazionali, Rome
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=193></TD><TD WIDTH=192></TD><TD WIDTH=198>Dr. Alvaro de Vasconcelos, Director, Istituto de Estudos Estrategicos e Internacionais, Lisbon
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=193></TD><TD WIDTH=192><I><B>Discussion</B></I>
</TD><TD WIDTH=198></TD></TR>

<TR><TD COLSPAN=3 WIDTH=583><B>Session Two: Mediterranean Cooperation and Security After Barcelona: Perspectives from the Non-Member Mediterranean countries</B>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=193>14:30 - 15.45</TD><TD WIDTH=192><A HREF="papers/Nabil.htm" ><I>&quot;After Madrid and Barcelona: Prospects for Mediterranean Security</I></A>
</TD><TD WIDTH=198>Ambassador Nabil Fahmy, Political Advisor to H.E. Mr. Amre Moussa, Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Egypt, Cairo
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=193></TD><TD WIDTH=192><I>&quot;</I></TD><TD WIDTH=198>Dr. Assia B. Alaoui, Director of Studies, Centre d'Etudes Strategiques, University Mohammed V, Rabat
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=193></TD><TD WIDTH=192><A HREF="papers/Hamdani.htm" ><I>&quot;Euro-Mediterranean Partnership: A Moroccan Perspective&quot;</I></A>
</TD><TD WIDTH=198>Ambassador Smail Hamdani, Consultant, Institut Nationale d'Etudes de Strategie Globale, Algiers
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=193>16:15 - 17:45</TD><TD WIDTH=192><A HREF="papers/Driss.htm" ><I>&quot;The Cultural Aspects of Cooperation and Security in the Mediterranean&quot;</I></A>
</TD><TD WIDTH=198>Ambassador Rachid Driss, President, Association des Etudes Internationales, Tunis
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=193></TD><TD WIDTH=192><A HREF="papers/Pace.htm" ><I>&quot;Peace, Stability, Security and Prosperity in the Mediterranean Region&quot;</I></A>
</TD><TD WIDTH=198>Mr. Roderick Pace, Director, European Documentation &amp; Research Centre, University of Malta
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=193></TD><TD WIDTH=192>Discussion</TD><TD WIDTH=198>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD COLSPAN=3 WIDTH=583><I><B>Saturday, 23th March 1996</B></I>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD COLSPAN=3 WIDTH=583><B>Session Three: What Cooperation and Security in the Mediterranean ? Lessons from the Past and Prospects for the Future</B>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=193>9:00 - 12:30</TD><TD WIDTH=192><A HREF="papers/Picheca.htm" ><I>&quot;The follow-up of the security aspects of the Barcelona Declaration, with regard to other initiatives in the area&quot;</I></A>
</TD><TD WIDTH=198>Mr. Giulio Picheca, Head, Mediterranean Multilateral Department, Directorate General for Political Affairs, Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Italy, Rome
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=193></TD><TD WIDTH=192><A HREF="papers/LESSER.htm" ><I>&quot;Mediterranean Security and Cooperation: A Transatlantic Perspective&quot;</I></A>
</TD><TD WIDTH=198>Dr. Ian O. Lesser, Senior Analyst, RAND Corporation, USA
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=193></TD><TD WIDTH=192><A HREF="papers/ATTINA.htm" ><I>&quot;Security and Pillars: The European Union, the Mediterranean and the Transatlantic Cooperation&quot;</I></A>
</TD><TD WIDTH=198>Prof. Fulvio Attina, Director, Department of Political Studies, University of Catania
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=193></TD><TD WIDTH=192><A HREF="papers/Joffe.htm" ><I>&quot;Integration or Peripheral Dependence. The Dilemma Facing the South Mediterranean States&quot;</I></A>
</TD><TD WIDTH=198>Prof. George Joffe, Deputy Director, Geopolitics and International Boundaries Research Centre, School of Oriental and African Studies, University of London
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=193>14:00 - 16:30</TD><TD WIDTH=192><A HREF="papers/dejonge.htm" ><I>&quot;The Contribution of the Council of Europe to Cooperation in the Mediterranean&quot;</I></A>
</TD><TD WIDTH=198>Mr. Johannes de Jonge, Head of External Relations, Council of Europe, Strasbourg
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=193></TD><TD WIDTH=192><A HREF="papers/BUSUTTIL.htm" ><I>&quot;Economic Security in the Mediterranean&quot;</I></A>
</TD><TD WIDTH=198>Prof. Salvino Busuttil, Director-General, Foundation for International Studies, University of Malta
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=193></TD><TD WIDTH=192><A HREF="papers/Pace.htm" ><I><FONT SIZE=2>A Euro-Mediterranean Partnership: Whose Security?</FONT></I></A>
</TD><TD WIDTH=198>Dr. Dominic Fenech, Coordinator, Contemporary Mediterranean Studies Programme, University of Malta
</TD></TR>

</TABLE>
</CENTER>
