<html> <head>
<title>Glacier Dynamics</title>
</head>

<body>

<center>
<!-- <a  href="/DCRS/"><IMG SRC="/images/" border=0></a> -->
 <h1>Glacier Dynamics</h1>
</center>

<P>
<b>DCRS contact</b>: <a href="//ms/DCRS/staff/snm.html">Sren Nrvang Madsen</a>, e-mail: <a href="mailto:snm@emi.dtu.dk">snm@emi.dtu.dk</a> and <a href="//ms/DCRS/staff/jm.html">Johan Mohr</a>, e-mail: <a href="mailto:jm@emi.dtu.dk">jm@emi.dtu.dk</a><br>
<p>
<b>Science partners</b>: Niels Reeh, Danish Polar Center (DPC). 
<P>
SAR repeat-track-interferometry applied to Storstrmmen Glacier,
Northeast Greenland; The ice sheets of Greenland and Antarctica
act as long-term reservoirs in the hydrological cycle, and changes
in their size are therefore an indicator of global climate change.
Although glaciers are a much smaller part of the cryosphere, they
are considered an important diagnostics tool as they respond more
rapidly to changing environmental conditions. This is a study
of the capability of SAR repeat track interferometry (RTI) using
multiple baseline techniques to provide spatial measurements of
instantaneous ice velocity and also micro topography of importance
for future measurements of changes of surface elevations and velocities
of glaciers. DCRS is the PI on an ERS-1/-2 investigation
on applying interferometric SAR satellite techniques to glacier
dynamics studies.

<hr>
<address><a href="/DCRS/staff/bbt.html">Bjorn B. Thomsen &lt;bbt@emi.dtu.dk&gt;</a></address>
