<html> <head>
<title>Geologic Mapping in Greenland</title>
</head>

<body>
<center>
 <a  href="/images/JD_geology.jpeg"><IMG align=right SRC="/images/JD_geology2v.jpg" border=2></a>
</center>
 <h1>Geologic Mapping in Greenland</h1>

<P>
<b>DCRS contact</b>: <a href="/DCRS/staff/jd.html">J&oslash;rgen Dall</a>, e-mail: <a href="mailto:jd@emi.dtu.dk">jd@emi.dtu.dk</a><br>
<p>
<b>Science partners</b>: Hans Christian Larsen, Danish Lithosphere Center
(DLC)<br>
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<b>Figure caption</b>
<p>
C-band polarimetric image of 'S&oslash;dalen' at Kangerdlugssuaq (68 N, 32 W) . The intensities of the HV, HH, and VV channels are coded in red, green and blue, respectively. From the glacier in the lower left corner the melt water passes a small lake (Danish: s&oslash;) in the valley (Danish: dalen) before it falls into the Mikis fjord, at the head of which a moraine forms a crescent. To the left of the lake is one of the many faults seen in the area. To the right of the moraine is a 880 m high mountain with concentric contours reflecting the lava bedding. The terrain elevation impacts both the geometry (foreshortening) and the radiometry (bright mountain sides facing the SAR and shadows on the opposite sides). It is believed that the artifact seen as strong yellow and magenta colors behind the sharp mountain rims is due to multiple reflections in the mountain sides.
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<b>Objective</b>
<p>
DLC is studying the
relations between terrain morphology, geologic structures, and
the physical properties of mountain complexes in West Greenland.
DCRS will investigate if interferometric SAR techniques can be
applied to generate topographic maps in the 200 by 200 km
western study area. DCRS will utilise satellite systems (ERS-1/2)
to generate regional size topographical maps at moderate resolution
and the airborne SAR will acquire data to generate local, high
resolution topographic maps. Experiments in East Greenland will
study the application of multi-frequency synthetic aperture radar
techniques including polarimetry to geologic mapping, classification
of the regolith, and mapping of the surface topography in a 400 km
long and relatively narrow area in East Greenland. This study
is the subject of an ERS-1/-2 investigation with DCRS
as PI.
<p>
<b>1994 experiment</b>
<p>
25 by 25 km test site at Kangerdlugssuaq  (68 N, 32 W) was mapped with DCRS's
airborne SAR, EMISAR. Kangerdlugssuaq is located 500 km south west
of Scoresbysund, East Greenland. Fully polarimetric C-band data was
acquired and subsequently processed to 2 by 2 m resolution, one-look
imagery. In rough terrains the internal structures of lithologies
are masked by the topography, while in more gentle areas they are
weathered out and reflected in the SAR images. Here, major structural
elements of gneisses show up quite well, as do faults, dikes, and
bedding in lava successions. However, a lithological classification
cannot be based on the C-band data, because the SAR is sensitive to
the surface morphology, and gneiss and gabbro, for instance, have
similar morphologies due to the glacial smoothing.
<p>
<b>1995 experiment</b>
<p>
This year the polarimetric data was acquired at L-band. Since SARs are
sensitive to features with a size comparable to the wavelength used,
morphologic differences not reflected in the C-band data might show up
in the L-band data. The extreme topography in the Kangerdlugssuaq area
is a major obstacle for the geologic interpretation of the SAR imagery.
Therefore the 1995 test site was extended to a 100 km long strip from
Kangerdlugssuaq to Watkins Bjerge where areas with more gentle
topography are found. For the same reason, EMISAR collected cross-track
interferomety (XTI) data as well. The digital elevtion model to be
generated from these XTI data will allow the SAR imagery to be
geometrically and radiometrically corrected for the topography. 
<p>
<b>Reference</b>
<p>
J. Dall, S.N. Madsen, C.K. Brooks, and T. Nielsen
Geologic Mapping in Greenland with Polarimetric SAR
Proc. of Int. Geoscience and Remote Sensing Symposium, IGARSS'95, Florence, Italy, August, 1995.
<p>
<b>Bibliography</b>
<p>
J&oslash;rgen Dall,  M.Sc.E.E.'84, Ph.D.'89. He has been with the Electromagnetics Institute, Technical University of Denmark since 1984, when he conducted an ESA study of microwave instruments for planetary missions. Among the recent activities are the development of algorithms for polarimetric calibration of the Danish airborne SAR (EMISAR), and technical management of a SAR processing facility for semi-operational processing of EMISAR data. He was responsible for the development of a dedicated onboard full resolution real-time processor for EMISAR, and prior to that he implemented software processors for the SEASAT SAR and EMISAR systems. Other SAR activities have included development of a novel SAR autofocus algorithm, and studies of fast transform and convolution algorithms for SAR processing. He is now leading the SAR processing group at the Danish Center for Remote Sensing (DCRS).

