<html> <head>
<title>The Dynamics of Sand Dunes</title>
</head>

<body>

<center>
<!-- <a  href=""><IMG SRC="/images/" border=0></a> -->
 <h1>The Dynamics of Sand Dunes</h1>
</center>

<P>
<b>DCRS contact</b>: <a href="//ms/DCRS/staff/snm.html">Sren Nrvang Madsen</a>, e-mail: <a href="mailto:snm@emi.dtu.dk">snm@emi.dtu.dk</a><br>
<P>
<b>Science partner</b>: Keld Rmer Rasmussen, Department of Earth
Sciences, <a href="http://www.aau.dk/">University of Aarhus.</a><br>
<P>
An important property of the Earth's
surface is the friction it exerts on atmospheric circulation.
For a given wind it determines the extent of soil removal, loss
of nutrients and seeds from fields, sediment transport in dunes,
dust generation and subsequently desertification by drifting sand.
Aerodynamic roughness is known to be correlated with the textural
properties of the ground -surface roughness- that can
be measured by radar polarimetry. Sediment transport, i.e. the
flux of material per unit width per unit time, is practically
impossible to measure accurately by conventional techniques in
complex dune fields. This study concern the use of interferometric
SAR techniques to derive detailed topographical information for
the Rbjerg Mile dune field at the required vertical resolution.
An important attribute is that radar is weather-independent and
the data processing very efficient. DCRS is the PI on an ERS-1/-2
investigation on applying interferometric SAR satellite techniques
to both this area and a larger dune field in southern California.

<p>
<!-- <b>Project related data</b>: <a href="">Click here</a> (requires password). -->
<p>

<hr>
