<html> <head>
<title>DANMAC</title>
</head>

<body>
<center><a  href="/images/pm005_m14_foulum_chh.gif"><IMG SRC="/images/pm005_m14_foulum_chh.gif" border=0></a>
<h1>DANMAC</h1>
<h2>DANish Multisensor Airborne Campaign</h2></center>
<P>
<b>Science partner</b>: DANMAC group, contact: Harald Mikkelsen, Danish Institute of Plant and Soil Science, Research Centre Foulum (RCF).
<p>
<b>DCRS contact</b>: <a href="/DCRS/staff/hs.html">Henning Skriver</a>, e-mail: <a href="mailto:hs@emi.dtu.dk">hs@emi.dtu.dk</a><br>
<p>
The DANMAC project is a collaboration between a number of Danish
institutions: Danish Institute of Plant and Soil Science (DIPSS),
National Environmental Research Institute (<a href="http://www.dmu.dk">NERI</a>),
Institute of Geography at University of Copenhagen (IGUC),
Danish Information Network in the Agricultural Sciences
(<a href="http://www.dina.kvl.dk">Dina</a>) at the Royal Veterinary
and Agricultural University,
Department of Meteorology and Wind Energy at 
Ris National Laboratory (<a href="http://www.risoe.dk/risoe.html">Ris</a>),
Danish Forest and Landscape Research Institute, and
Institute of Mathematical Modelling
(<a href="http://www.imm.dtu.dk/homepage.html">IMM</a>) 
at Technical University of Denmark (<a href="http://www.dtu.dk/dtu/dtu.html">DTU</a>).
<p>
The purpose of the project is to achieve a better understanding
of the physical conditions and processes at the surface influencing the signal
of both optical and radar sensors. The DANMAC project is a multisensor and
multidisciplinary remote sensing campaign, consisting of four test sites
covering one for agriculture/forestry, two for landscape-ecology/natural type
and one for inland waters (lakes). For each test site extensive ground data
collection takes place together with simultaneous data acquisition by airborne
and spaceborne SAR's and/or optical/infrared sensors. Following the data
collection, data processing, modelling and interpretation take place at the
collaborating institutes in a coordinated effort.

<p>
DCRS is collaborating with the DANMAC-group by undertaking acquisitions by the polarimetric
EMISAR, and by data processing and interpretation as well as microwave modelling.
DCRS also participates in the in-situ data collection. 
The work carried out in the DANMAC-group is closely related to other DCRS
projects: <a href="roughness.html">Aerodynamic Roughness</a>,
<a href="soilMapping.html">Plant and Soil Mapping</a>, and
<a href="landscapeEcology.html">Landscape Ecology</a>.
<p>
<!-- <b>Project related data</b>: <a href="">Click here</a> (requires password). -->
<p>


<hr>
<address><a href="/DCRS/staff/hs.html">Henning Skriver &lt;hs@emi.dtu.dk&gt;</a></address>
