<html> <head>
<title>Microwave Radiometry</title>
</head>

<body>

<center>
<!-- <a  href=""><IMG SRC="/images/" border=0></a> -->
<h1>Microwave Radiometry</h1>
</center>

<P>
<b>DCRS contact</b>: <a href="/DCRS/staff/ns.html">Niels Skou</a>, e-mail: <a href="mailto:ns@emi.dtu.dk">ns@emi.dtu.dk</a><br>

<P>
Today, imaging spaceborne radiometers feature a mechanical scanning
of the antenna. As demands to ground resolution become more severe
large apertures are needed and mechanical scan is impractical.
The Synthetic Aperture Interferometric Radiometer (SAIR) system
is a possible<I> </I>configuration to solve this problem. SAIR
is an instrument which, without scanning, is able to measure complete
images with high resolution. A compromise between high resolution
and side lobe level can be made in signal processing and is no
longer a parameter which is to be chosen while designing the antenna.
<P>
A laboratory instrument has been designed and built to investigate
the SAIR concept. X-band horns can be placed anywhere within a
certain aperture and the output signals from the associated radiometers
are crosscorrelated to yield points of the visibility function.
A multichannel radio camera is simulated by sequential measurements.
A test scene with good radiometric contrast consisting of metal
letters (EMI) with an absorbing background, has been measured,
and an image has been successfully reconstructed. Based on the
above a new Ku band radiometer has been built with emphasis on
stability and calibration precision. In the near future this will
be used in experiments related to the calibration of SAIR instruments.
<P>
Development of a proper L-band (1.4 GHz) radio camera MIRAS has
commenced under an ESA contract with MATRA as the prime contractor.
Eleven antenna elements (with a similar number of radiometers)
are placed on a Y-formed structure with an arm length of approximately
60 cm. The instrument is to be flown on a C-130 aircraft from
the Danish Air Force and can be used for measurement of soil moisture.
Under this project, work with optimal algorithms for signal processing
of data measured with the Ku-band SAIR demonstration model is
carried out. Signal processing comprises work with irregular sampled
spatial frequencies, interpolation, inverse Fourier transformation,
and coordinate transformation. Data from objects placed in the
 near field as well as in the far field of the synthetic aperture
can be processed with suitably chosen transformations.

<hr>
<address><a href="/DCRS/staff/bbt.html">Bjorn B. Thomsen &lt;bbt@emi.dtu.dk&gt;</a></address>
<!-- hhmts start -->
