<html> <head>
<title>New Sensor Developments</title>
</head>

<body>

<center>
<!-- <a  href=""><IMG SRC="/images/" border=0></a> -->
 <h1>New Sensor Developments</h1>
</center>

<P>
<b>DCRS contact</b>: <a href="/DCRS/staff/snm.html">Sren Nrvang Madsen</a>, e-mail: <a href="mailto:snm@emi.dtu.dk">snm@emi.dtu.dk</a> and
<a href="/DCRS/staff/ns.html">Niels Skou</a>, e-mail: <a href="mailto:ns@emi.dtu.dk">ns@emi.dtu.dk</a><br>
<p>
In addition to these activities DCRS undertakes studies addressing
the measurement capabilities, scientific potential, and technical
feasibility of novel remote sensing concepts. These activities
will include active and passive sensors and frequency bands other
than microwaves. The centre plans to take part in the development
of at least two new sensors over the coming years. An interferometric
low frequency (L-band) radiometer MIRAS is presently being developed
in co-operation with Matra/France with funding from ESA. The DCRS
activities include test data collections with the system, development
of processing algorithms, and evaluation of the performance and
utility of the system.
<P>
A candidate for a second new sensor is The Scanning Microwave
Radar &amp; Radiometer (SMRR), which is a line scanner featuring
a combined radar and radiometer system operating around 19, 37,
and 90 GHz. The key word is synergism - in this case trying to
use both active and passive measurements to obtain information
not otherwise available using either one of these alone. This
has been done before using separate radars and radiometers, but
always hampered by lack of simultaneousness and lack of identical
footprints. The 2 offset antenna parabolas scan in syncronism,
the receiver antenna has the higest gain in order to ensure that
footprints are identical for the radar and the radiometer. The
instrument will be flown in a pod under a Gulfstream G3 able to
cruise at 45000 ft, and will thus be able to sense clouds and
precipitation from above. Also, it will be used for other geophysical
measurements like sea ice classification from suitable flight
altitudes.
<P>
Other candidates under consideration include polarimetric radiometers
and high resolution, high frequency SARs.

<hr>
<address><a href="/DCRS/staff/bbt.html">Bjorn B. Thomsen &lt;bbt@emi.dtu.dk&gt;</a></address>
