<html> <head>
<title>Microwave radiometer signatures of Sea ice</title>

</head>

<body>
<center><a  href="/images/pmr-signature.gif"><IMG SRC="/images/pmr-signature.gif" border=0></a></center>
<h4><center>Spectral gradient ratio (34V-17V) versus polarization ratio (34V-34H) from a dataset obtained in the Greenland Sea area on March 24, 1995 with the airborne TUDRAD radiometers</center></h4>
<p>

<h1> Microwave radiometer signatures of sea ice</h1>
<EM>DCRS contact</EM>:

<a href="/DCRS/staff/ltp.html">Leif Toudal</a>,         e-mail: <a href="mailto:ltp@emi.dtu.dk">ltp@emi.dtu.dk</a><br>
<p>

<h3>Purpose</h3> 
It is the purpose of this project to improve the accuracy of sea-ice concentrations derived from satellite microwave radiometer systems. This will be attempted by using data from similar and other passive and active microwave instruments. In particular, data from the synthetic aperture radar on ERS-1 will be exploited as well as ground measurements. Thus, the project will demonstrate the complementarity of microwave data from active high resolution sensors with small areal coverage and coarse resolution data from passive sensors with large areal coverage. 
In this context, it is also the aim to obtain an improved understanding of the passive microwave signatures of sea ice and their regional and seasonal variability.

<h3>Background</h3>
The surface of the Earth emits thermal microwave radiation. The amount of radiation and its spectral composition varies from one type of surface to another. In  particular, the emission from the open ocean and from sea ice are very different resulting in a large signature contrast between ice and water. Microwaves are only to a minor degree absorbed (attenuated) by the atmosphere and thus provides excellent means for observing variations in ice cover independent of clouds. Also, since the thermal radiation is emitted independently of daylight, observations may be carried out 24 hours per day.
<p>
The European Space Agency, ESA, is developing a microwave radiometer (MIMR, Multifrequency Imaging Microwave Radiometer) to be deployed with the Polar Platforms from 1998. One of the main objectives of the instrument is according to the MIMR-instrument panel report [ESA SP-1138, 1990] to provide observations of ice cover for climatological purposes.
<p>
Such types of observations have been carried out since the early 1970s from various American satellites (NIMBUS-5, NIMBUS-6, NIMBUS-7 and at present DMSP) and an almost complete record covering a 20-year period is available, in some parts with daily observations.
NIMBUS-5 and NIMBUS-6 only observed the radiation at one wavelength, but with the NIMBUS-7 SMMR instrument (1978-1987) and the present SSM/I instrument on the DMSP satellites (1987 and onwards) multispectral observations are recorded. This allows corrections for a number of error sources so that an accuracy of ice concentrations derived from these data sets is in the order of 5-8%.
<p>
Various studies, primarily at NASA, have demonstrated the usefulness of these data for large scale analyses, including the compilation of atlases showing the many years of ice cover [Parkinson & Cavalieri, 1989; Parkinson et al., 1987]. Based on these it was investigated whether a trend in the total ice cover in the two hemispheres during the last 20 years could be observed. However, it was concluded that no global change could be observed within the measurement accuracy, whereas regionally certain areas showed an increase in ice cover and other areas a decrease. 
<p>
It may be concluded that a number of important potential applications of the microwave radiometer data still awaits better accuracy of the ice concentrations derived from these data, and that this is essential if data from the future European MIMR instrument is going to be useful for for example climate studies of the total ice cover on the Earth and for studies of the exchange of heat between the atmosphere and the ocean in ice-frequented regions. Since the heat loss to the atmosphere from ice and from the open ocean differs by a factor of 100, it is important to know the ice concentrations with great accuracy for the purpose of numerical modelling, in particular at large concentrations. It is suggested that the accuracy should be better than 2-3%  on a yearly basis.
<p>
The algorithms being used to derive ice concentrations from multispectral observations require calibration in the form of reference observations from areas with "pure surface types", i.e. areas consisting of one surface type only. Such areas of 100% open (ice-free) ocean can easily be found for example in the Norwegian Sea. However, extensive areas of 100% first-year ice or 100% multi-year ice are difficult to find near the Greenland Sea. Instead, observations from a number of areas with different ice/water mixtures are used and the ice concentrations are determined from visible and infrared images or from in situ observations. However, visible and infrared observations can only be used under clear sky conditions (no clouds) so that these references are only available (useful) under certain atmospheric conditions.
<p>
The state-of-the art was reviewed by the Sea Ice Group of scientists attending the ESA Microwave Workshop at San Miniato, Italy, 19-21 September 1990 and recent investigations [Garrity, 1991, Pedersen, 1991, Steffen and Schweiger, 1991, Cavalieri et al. 1991, Burns, 1992] have documented that a very important source of error when deriving ice concentrations from microwave radiometer data is the variation of the emissivity of the ice/snow surface. The algorithms require knowledge of the emissivity of the ice/snow- and the ocean surface and  presently such knowledge originates only from in situ observations taken during occasional field campaigns. Such campaigns are expensive and the number of observations is therefore relatively small.
<p>
The properties of the sea surface are reasonably well known and models giving the emissivity at various wavelengths and polarizations as a function of temperature, wind speed (surface roughness) and salinity exist. However, the situation with respect to the ice is somewhat different. We distinguish between several different types of ice with different emissivities. Existing numerical models [Lee and Kong 1985a and b] are micro-scale models that need modifications in order to be related to the macro-scale applications in question taking into account parameters such as ice-type, temperature, snow cover, roughness, salinity etc. Considering the complexity of the situation only two ice types are normally considered, first-year ice and multiyear ice, with assigned emissivities supposedly valid during the entire year and with no regional variations. Neglecting seasonal and regional variations leads to errors. As an example, the signature of multiyear ice in the Canadian Basin of the Arctic Ocean is quite different from the emissivity of multiyear ice in the Fram Strait and the East Greenland Current. Also, these signatures vary along the Greenland eastcoast due to the varying temperature and precipitation conditions from 80N to 60N [Cavalieri et al., 1991, Pedersen, 1991].
<p>
In order to improve the accuracy of radiometer-based ice concentrations it is therefore necessary to map the seasonal and regional variations in the emissivity of all relevant ice types (including various types of new ice during ice formation) and to use site and season-specific signatures as reference values (tie-points) in the algorithms.
In a number of investigations [Garrity, 1991, Maetzler, Ramseier & Svendsen 1984] variability in surface snow layer(s) is found to be a major contributor to the emissivity variations, in particular at horizontal polarization. Thus, ways to obtain information about surface snow properties should be established. Such information could be obtained by analyzing time sequences of data and incorporating meteorological observations (through a data assimilation model) about temperature variations (melt-freeze cycles) and precipitation.

Brightness temperature (37 GHz. horizontal polarization at an incidence angle of 53 degrees) of sea ice with different types of snow surfaces [Garrity, 1991].

<h3>Methods</h3>
It is proposed to map the variations in ice conditions by means of simultaneous passive and active microwave data. The main instruments will be the SMM/I microwave radiometer on DMSP satellites and the synthetic aperture radar (SAR) on ERS-1.  The SAR allows a very detailed observation of the ice canopy in confined areas compared to that of the passive instrument, and thus provides an excellent complement to the coarse-resolution radiometer data that provides for large areal coverage. 
The SMM/I radiometer has a spatial resolution of 25 km and a swath of approximately 1400 km whereas the SAR scenes reveal 30 meter resolution (in some instances also 140-meter data may be obtained) but in a swath of only 100 km. Thus, a single SAR scene provides a maximum of 16 independent areas to be used for calibration of the radiometer-based ice concentrations and ice types.
<p>
SAR data from different seasons and regions in the Greenland and adjacent seas will be collected and analyzed in order to determine the concentrations of various ice types within the field of view of the microwave radiometer. The radiometer data will be analyzed with the aim of estimating emissivities for the areas covered by the SAR scenes. Data from a number of test cases throughout the year will be analyzed in order to map the seasonal variations. The regional variability will be addressed by using (at each time) a number of scenes reaching from the Fram Strait (81N) to Denmark Strait (65N). Also, it is important to repeat the analysis for more than one year in order to cover interannual variability.
<p>
It must be realized that the use of SAR data is not without problems. The derivation of sea ice concentrations from SAR data is far from trivial, and also requires validation. Thus, it is  important that simultaneous efforts be carried out in order to validate the SAR retrievals. It is the intention to perform this validation using in situ data during the field campaigns, and using visible and infrared satellite imagery under cloud-free conditions.
<p>
The two datasets will be compared in order to map the spectral passive microwave signatures of various ice types. The accuracy in ice concentrations resulting from the synergistic use of both datasets will be further improved using data from other instruments in the visible and infrared parts of the electromagnetic spectrum (AVHRR, ATSR, Landsat, SPOT).  The various data types complement each other, and a synergistic approach is necessary.
The interannual variations will be determined by performing the investigations for a period of three years but with a lower intensity during the last two years. 
<p>
Additional questions related to the signature variations will be investigated during a number of field campaigns in the Greenland Sea and eventually other areas of the Arctic. For these campaigns an airborne and/or ship-mounted microwave radiometer system will be used, preferably in a profiling mode with scaled antenna horns in order to obtain the same spatial resolution at all wavelengths. A system developed at the Electromagnetics Institute [Skou, 1978] will be used supplemented with equipment supplied by other participants. These radiometers may need some modification in order to fit into a smaller aircraft. It is expected that  a single field campaign will have a duration of several days, and that several campaigns will be needed every year in order to monitor both short-term and long-term variations. 
<p>
In order to understand the relationship between the physical ice parameters and the microwave data some of the airborne missions will be planned to coincide with field campaigns in connection with ship opportunities. During these the following parameters will be measured: snow depth, density stratification and humidity, ice salinity profiles, ice temperature profiles etc. [Cavalieri et al., 1991] along with microwave radiances measured from satellite and/or aircraft. Radiative transfer models published in the literature will be exploited to further substantiate the measurements. Observations of surface as well as uppper-air meteorological parameters will be carried out in order to correct  the observations for variations in the amount of atmospheric radiation and in order to relate variations in emissivities to past and present weather situations.

<h3>Data</h3>
Microwave radiometer data from the SSM/I instrument is distributed on CD-ROM by the World Data Centre to a number of interested institutions including the Electromagnetics Institute. The data are organized in a polar stereographic grid as the average value of 24 hours of observations. A single CD-ROM contains approximately 3 months of observations at 4 different wavelengths (0.3 to 1.5 cm). These averaged data will be supplemented by a number of CCT's containing the original orbits recorded at the time of the SAR-scene acquisitions. These data may be obtained through EARTHNET.
<p>
A number of scenes from the SAR on ERS-1 will have to be acquired in order to carry out the proposed activity. The Electromagnetics Institute is recognized by ESA as a Principal Investigator for ERS-1 with special emphasis on sea ice applications, and is a member of PIPOR (Programme for International Polar Oceans Research). Thus, the majority of the SAR-scenes necessary is expected to be available free of charge through this approved activity. 
<p>
As a supplement to the microwave data, Landsat and SPOT data in photographic form will be purchased. These data having a spatial resolution of the same order as the SAR data are intended for verification of the ice parameters. The verification will be qualitative rather than quantitative and thus photographic reproductions will probably suffice.

<h3>Experiences</h3>
This project was initially proposed as a Danish project and has already obtained funds for the initial phase of one year from the Danish Space Research Board. However, it was suggested from several sides that it would be useful as a basis for international cooperation, and that in fact it is already so, since it depends to a great extent on contributions in the form of field campaigns. Also, additional financial support will be required in order that a sufficient number of airborne campaigns may be carried out. The project has therefore been proposed to colleagues for possible participation in various ways.
<p>
The project initiated at the Electromagnetics Institute is based on the experience obtained during several years in analyzing passive microwave radiometer data acquired from satellites [Pedersen, 1991]. Also, experience in processing and analyzing SAR data for ice parameter retrieval is present at the Electromagnetics Institute [Skriver, 1989] and will be developed further in connection with the Greenland Sea Project (GSP) funded by the Danish Space Research Board for 1992 and 1993.
<p>
Furthermore, a number of institutions with experience in microwave radiometry and/or sea ice and snow research has expressed interest in joining the project. <p>At the present time the following institutions/persons (listed alphabetically) plan to contribute to the project:<p>
<strong>Alfred Wegner Institute, Bremerhaven, Germany</strong>, (Lemke, Ramseier, on leave from York University, Canada)
<br><strong>Bremen University, Germany, </strong>(Burns)
<br><strong>Chalmers University of Technology , Sweden, </strong>(Askne)
<br><strong>Danish Meteorological Institute </strong>(Fabricius, Valeur)
<br><strong>Technical University of Denmark, </strong>(Gudmandsen, Pedersen, Skriver)
<br><strong>Helsinki University of Technology, Finland, </strong>(Hallikainen)
<br><strong>University of Berne, Switzerland, </strong>(Maetzler, Flueckiger, Gmuender)
<br><strong>Meteorological Institute, University of Hamburg , Germany, </strong>(Schlssel)
<br><strong>Scott Polar Research Institute, England, </strong>(Wadhams)- (Related MAST-2 activity)
<br><strong>York University, Canada, </strong>(Ramseier)

<h3>Schedule and work statements</h3>
The investigations proposed will be carried out from 1992 and onwards. A preliminary schedule is as follows:
<dl>
  <dt>	<strong>1992.</strong> Analysis of SSM/I and ERS-1 SAR data will be carried out. The former data will be treated on an annual basis. In particular, the analysis of SAR scenes will have to be developed to fit to the data and their specific application. In addition, preparation for airborne and field campaigns including modification of microwave radiometer equipment will be made.
	An introductory field campaign will be attempted in connection with the cruise of the American icebreaker "Polar Sea" to North East Water (at about 82N, 12W) and the Kanumas seismic investigations from a ship of the continental shelf of Greenland (70N to 80N) both planned for the period July-August. In this period an intensive acquisition of SAR data is needed in the area and in Fram Strait. Underflights with the Danish airborne SAR at the same frequency and polarizations as that of ERS-1will be included if at all possible. With its 2-meter spatial resolution it will supply very detailed data of the area investigated.
  <dt>		<strong>1993</strong>. The analysis of SSM/I and ERS-1 SAR data will be continued. The data will be related to the overall observation of the Greenland Sea with complementary satellite instruments, including AVHRR data. Also, algorithms will be developed that exploit available satellite data in a synergistic way including oceanographic and especially meteorological data. A pilot field campaign will be carried out in cooperation between the DMI and EMI/DCRS using TUD radiometers. The campaign will test the radiometer installation in a Twin-Otter aircraft ot the DMI/Greenlandair with profiling antennas. Tha campaign will be carried out off the West Greenland coast. 	
  <dt>		<strong>1994.</strong> The analysis of data will continue to the extent that ERS-1 SAR data become available. Airborne campaigns will be organized as in the previous year. Opportunities of field campaigns will be exploited. A field campaign in the Greenland Sea will be carried out with TUD radiometers and DMI aircraft. 
  <dt>		<strong>1995.</strong> The analysis of data will continue to the extent that ERS-1 SAR data become available. Airborne campaigns will be organized as in the previous year. Opportunities of field campaigns will be exploited. A field campaign in the Greenland Sea will be carried out with TUD radiometers and DMI aircraft as well as a Royal Danish Airforce Gulfstream G3 equipped with the DCRS polarimetric C-band SAR.
</dl>


<h3>Additional information</h3>
Three factors play an important role in the accuracy and precision of quantitative sea ice observations using microwave radiometry:
<dl>
<dt>	-	Tie point variability
	<dt>	-	Geophysical noise
<dt>		-	Measurement noise
</dl>
Tie point variability is the most serious limitation to the success of microwave radiometer observations of sea ice. The signature of a given type of ice varies regionally and seasonally to an extent that may cause errors in retrieved ice concentration of at least 10% and make the distinction between old and new ice during major parts of the year impossible. The way to remedy this situation is to obtain knowledge about the variability. Today the variability is not well understood and thus laboratory and field experiments that expand our knowledge about the relation between the variability in ice conditions and the resulting microwave signatures should be carried out. However, prior to such undertakings, additional knowledge should be obtained by combining data from SAR, fine-resolution visible and infrared images (Landsat & SPOT) and passive microwave observations. Such a study, with the aim of mapping the regional and seasonal variability of the ice signatures, will provide a good basis for further field and laboratory experiments, i.e. for defining areas and seasons of specific interest.
Geophysical noise means errors in the retrieved ice parameters due to variations in other geophysical parameters not or insufficiently accounted for in the retrieval algorithm. Cloud liquid water, atmospheric columnar water vapour, ice temperature and wind roughening of the  open ocean are the prime contributors to the geophysical noise. Therefore,  priori knowledge about their variability or even better additional observations of their magnitude should be incorporated into future algorithms for ice parameter retrieval. Such knowledge is  to some extent available from meteorological analysis models that produce gridded fields of the above mentioned parameters every 6 hours. Algorithms to combine observations from a variety of sources should be developed and refined.
<p>
Measurement noise is with the present state of microwave radiometers no problem for ice parameter retrieval. However, the long-term stability of instruments and instrument malfunction or miscalibration are of great importance and it is desirable that programmes be carried out to establish absolute calibration of spaceborne microwave radiometers while in space. The contribution to noise in daily averaged data will be evaluated. Repeated measurements of brightness temperatures of the stable central ice of Greenland may serve as a control of instrument stability.


Standard deviation of (uncertainty in) ice concentration as a result of variability in ice/snow surface emissivity. The Full and the dashed curves correspond to a situation with approx. 90% ice cover, and the two other curves to approx. 10% ice cover. The upper curve in each case corresponds to using 37 GHz. data only (both polarizations) in the retrieval, whereas the lower curve corresponds to using the 18 and 37 GHz. vertically polarized channels. Results obtained from applying estimation theory to the ice parameter retrieval problem [Pedersen, 1991]. Typically the ice emissivities today are known to within 0.01-0.05.

<h3>Summary</h3>
The accuracy of sea ice concentration retrievals by means of multispectral observations of thermal microwave radiation is severely limited by the lack of knowledge about the spatial and temporal variability of the emissivity of the ice.
The variability of the signatures must be taken into account in order to make better use of such data in the future, for example in climate related studies.
<p>
As one venue, the development of methods for calibration of estimated ice concentrations by means of high-resolution data from synthetic aperture radar data from ERS-1 is proposed.
<p>
Also, it is proposed to carry out a number of field campaigns in order to study and understand the temporal and regional variability of the tie point emissivities including the relationship to past and present weather (precipitation, melt, freeze ...) at the location of the ice.
<p>
In addition, the work will be complemented by theoretical studies of sea ice properties.
Algorithms will be developed that allow a synergistic use of data from a number of sources such as microwave radiometry, SAR, visible and infrared instruments and meteorological analysis fields.
<p>
The project will be coordinated with the MAST II project of the EEC in the Greenland Sea if this materializes. A wider group of investigators will thereby be involved with additional opportunities.
<p>
The methods will be developed with particular emphasis on improving the exploitation of the European microwave radiometer MIMR, which is expected to fly on the Polar Platform in 1998. An interaction with the ESA MIMR Science Advisory Group will be established.
 
<h3>References</h3>
