<H1>Editorial<BR>
</H1>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>Since the previous newsletter, issued September 95,
the most outstanding achievement within the DCRS framework is
the successful commissioning of the across track interferometer
(XTI) mode at C-band. We are now entering a phase where more operational
processing and calibration facilities are being developed, and
the absolute geometric error is being evaluated in collaboration
with institutions involved in map making.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>9 flights have been carried out covering primarily
sites in Denmark, but also areas in Greenland and the Faroe Islands
have been mapped. All flights were in support of the DCRS programme,
i. e. no external customers this time.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>The polarimetric radiometer study has entered its
experimental stage and a quite spectacular flight campaign has
started in which the instrument views the sea from a position
on the open ramp of a C-130 Hercules transport aircraft.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>Last but not least: on June 18 S&oslash;ren N&oslash;rvang
Madsen, head of DCRS received &quot;H&oslash;jgaard &amp; Schultz
Jubil&aelig;umsprisen&quot;. The danish Minister for Research
and Information Technology presented the prize during a splendid
ceremony, and the press have been busy writing about S&oslash;ren
and the radar program.<BR>
</FONT>
<H1>C&amp;L-band SAR<BR>
</H1>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>EMISAR, the airborne polarimetric SAR system used
by DCRS, has been operating at C-band since 1993 while the first
test flight with the L-band subsystem was carried out in the spring
1995. Both frequencies have been used for data acquisition since
then but, in addition, the L-band subsystem has been finalized
and the capability for simultaneous dual frequency operation has
been added. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>The upgrade to polarimetry has been supported by
the Danish Technical Research Council (STVF) and the European
Union, represented by the Institute for Remote Sensing Applications
of the Joint Research Centre (JRC), Ispra. The work has been completed
and the final reports to both sponsors have been submitted.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>The major application of the system is data acquisition
for the research of DCRS but EMISAR has also been used to acquire
polarimetric data for EMAC (European Multi-sensor Airborne Campaigns)
organized and sponsored by the European Space Agency, ESA. This
has involved the processing of a large quantity of SAR scenes
which have been completed and delivered to ESA.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>Polarimetric and radiometric calibration is an important
issue for a SAR system intended for remote sensing and this objective
has been persued by acquiring calibration data from scenes with
reference corner reflectors at all flights. The SAR includes an
internal calibration system and the quality of the overall performance
is evaluated by the residual calibration error after internal
calibration. The conclusion is that a single external calibration
per mission suffices.  The results indicate that external calibration
is hardly a necessity on each mission; however, it is still desired
as a means to confirm and possibly improve the calibration performance.
The more important performance parameters and the results of the
calibration verification are summarized in the two attached tables.
<BR>
</FONT><CENTER>
<TABLE BORDER=1>
<TR><TD COLSPAN=3 WIDTH=408><BR>
