<P>
<P>
navigational information. A tightly coupled INS/GPS system which
will improve the attitude accuracy significantly, is presently
being integrated into the system.
<P>
The interferometric processor simultaneously processes the two
interferometric channels which are then motion compensated to
a common reference line. The processor also includes automatic
determination of the absolute phase. The output products include
co-registered amplitude data, height map, correlation map, and
for calibration runs also absolute phase maps.  Usually output
products are generated at 5 or 10&nbsp;m ground range pixel spacing.
<BR>
<H1>Flight Campaigns<BR>
</H1>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>In the period September 1995 to June 1996 nine flights
have been conducted in support of the DCRS technology and Earth
science research, see Table 4.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>Table 4.  EMISAR flights<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<IMG SRC="IMG00002.GIF">
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>Three of the March flights were part of a campaign
to Greenland while the others covered areas in Denmark.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>On November 23, data sets from six different sites
were collected. At Vejle, Hvorslev and Fur the National Survey
and Cadastre (KMS) has generated accurate Digital Elevation Models
by photogrammetric techniques and they are conducting pilot projects
providing reference data that are valuable for DCRS.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>During the Greenland campaign sea ice was mapped
at Kap Farewell (KF) and in the Greenland Sea (GS). The data from
the Daug&aring;rd Jensen Glacier (DJ) are mainly intended for
RTI applications as are the R&aring;bjerg Mile data.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>The flights in June were recorded by Danish Televison.
The recordings are to be used for a children's programme called
the Curious Camera.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>Some of the flights have served a technological purpose
in addition to the Earth science purpose. In November XTI data
were acquired from both 41.000 ft. and 25.000 ft. altitude in
order to examine the performance of the system and to improve
the XTI calibration. On April 22 simultaneous L- and C-band data
acquisition was tested for the first time, and on April 23 and
June 18 several ILS experiments were conducted.<BR>
</FONT>
<H1>Soil and Plant Studies at Research Centre Foulum<BR>
</H1>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>Soil moisture data collected during the 1995 field
experiments over Research Center Foulum showed that soil moisture
varied spatially within the field scale. The estimated standard
deviations of soil moisture contents using more than 60 independent
samples were up to 4% in a field. This relatively large variation
sets a lower bound for the estimation of the SAR retrieved soil
moisture in the field scale.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>SAR data acquired at C-band during 1994 and L- &amp;
C-band during 1995, as well as the field measured soil and plant
data have been integrated. Six algorithms, including the theoretical
Integral Equation Model, have been used to retrieve soil moisture
and surface roughness with the data set. Dubois's algorithm showed
a reasonable solution better than the others, but the discrepancy
is still large between the measured and retrieved values with
RMS-errors up to 8 %.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>Simultaneous with the L- &amp; C-band EMISAR flight
during April 22-23 1996, an extensive field experiment at Foulum
has been performed based on the improvement of skills in moisture
and roughness measurements. Four bare fields and a wheat field
were involved. A quasi-flat surface within a bare field was rolled
in order to test the roughness influence on SAR backscatter. The
scanning laser altimeter developed at RCF was used to perform
eight 2-meter transect roughness measurements. Soil moisture data
along five transects in the fields were collected at every 10-20
meters with TDR and ring methods. Roughness data have been processed
and the results showed a large variation in autocorrelation lengths
like that investigated with the 94-95 data. Soil moisture data
have just arrived and a preliminary check showed that the spatial
variation is reduced by the precisely controlled measurement compared
to the 1995 experiments.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>Multi-temporal and multi-frequency signatures for
agricultural crops have been studied. The signatures show a significant
variation during the growing-season, enabling the discrimination
between the crops. Also, some variation is observed between the
fields for the individual crops, especially in the early spring,
where the backscatter from the surface strongly depends on plowing
and sowing directions relative to the flight track. Furthermore,
the variation at L-band is seen to be significantly larger than
at C-band. The polarimetric parameters, phase difference and correlation
between HH and VV show good potential for discimination between
the crops. A Ph. D. study has been initiated as a collaboration
between DCRS and the Danish Institute of Plant and Soil Science.
The study is funded under the DANMAC project and aims at studying
discrimination methods for agricultural crops using polarimetric
and interferometric SAR data.<BR>
</FONT>
<H1>Glacier Dynamics Studies<BR>
</H1>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>A prototype repeat track interferometer processor
for airborne as well as satellite SAR data has been tested. The
airborne EMISAR data from 1995 have been processed and the data
look promising for extraction of velocities; not yet demonstrated
elsewhere with any airborne system.  Tandem mode interferometry
data from the ESA satellites ERS-1 and ERS-2 have also been processed.
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>The ERS satellites are operated in a tandem mode
such that, seen from the Earth, ERS&#173;2 repeats the ERS&#173;1
trajectory with a one day delay.  The satellites are in a 35&nbsp;day
repeat cycle, thus allowing the generation of one interferogram
with a one day temporal baseline every 35&nbsp;day for any area.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>The raw ERS data are processed with the new improved
processor, with an additional front-end correcting for missing
lines and sampling window changes. In Figure&nbsp;2 a raw interferogram
covering a 100&nbsp;km by 200&nbsp;km area around the Storstr&oslash;mmen
glacier is shown.  On the left the interferogram phase is shown,
on the right the amplitude. The phase is color coded and is repeated
for each <IMG SRC="IMG00003.GIF">, in this case corresponding
to either a change in the terrain height of 800&nbsp;m or a line
of sight motion of 2.8&nbsp;cm/day.  </FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>Manually counting the fringes on the mountains shows
that a minor tilt of 1-2 fringes is still present.  It is also
noted that the topography in this area can account for at most
2&nbsp;fringes.  Thus the fringe pattern on the upper part of
the glacier (with an eastward flow) must be due to a horizontal
surface velocity of approximately 300 m/y in the central part
decreasing to approximately zero at the sides.  This is in good
agreement with the velocities measured by the Danish Polar Center
by repeated GPS survey of stakes drilled into the glacier. The
almost vanishing fringe pattern on the lower part (with a southward
flow) can not easily be interpreted.  The interferometric techniques
relies on the measurement of small range shifts in the line of
sight direction from image acquisition to image acquisition. 
Thus only motion perpendicular to the orbit can be measured and
the sensitivity to a southward flow parallel to the orbit is zero.
 </FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>Two interferograms with a 35&nbsp;day separation
have presently been generated, in principle allowing the separation
of motion and topography induced phase.  However, one of the interferograms
is rather difficult to phase unwrap, likely due to temporal decorrelation
caused by surface melting, thus resulting in a low correlation
interferogram.  This is hoped to be eliminated in the three tandem
data set acquired later in 1995, just received from ESA.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<IMG SRC="IMG00004.GIF"><BR>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>Figure 2.  Raw Interferogram from ESA ERS-1/2 tandem
data acquired late July, 1995.  From having an eastward flow (upper
left corner) at an altitude of 600 m a.s.l. the glacier splits
into a northern branch, Koefod-Hansen Br&aelig;, and a southern,
Storstr&oslash;mmen.  Just south of the white rectangle, the airborne
test-area, it merges with Bistrup Br&aelig;, turns to the east
and terminates in steep calving front.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>As opposed to the satellite data phase unwrapping
has until now proven very easy with the airborne EMISAR data.
 The major issue is a low frequency, drift in the Inertial Navigation
Unit measuring the airplane flight path.  If not compensated,
this drift will be misinterpreted as a movement of the glacier,
from the first day to the second.  The bulk part of this drift
has been identified as linear drift in the acceleration biases,
and has been estimated.  It is believed that the remaining uncertainty
of some centimeters, also originates from drift, but this still
has to be confirmed. </FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>In Figure 3, two interferograms from the EMISAR August
mission to Storstr&oslash;mmen is shown.  The upper interferogram
mainly reflects the topography, the lower topography and flow.
 The remaining uncertainty on the spatial baselines inhibits an
extraction of the flow, but it is seen that the flow are significantly
slower than at higher elevations.  Also note the feature in the
lower right corner with a dense fringe pattern.  This might be
caused by a tidal uplift of the glacier.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<IMG SRC="IMG00005.GIF"><BR>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>Figure 3.  Interferograms from EMISAR images acquired
over Storstr&oslash;mmen August 22 &amp; 23, 1995.<BR>
</FONT>
<H1>Geology<BR>
</H1>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>L-band polarimetric data and XTI data acquired over
an area from Kangerdlugssuaq to Watkins Bjerge (East Greenland)
in August 1995 are currently analysed. In all, a stripe of 120
km in length was covered, at a ground width of 12.6 km with the
polarimeter and 8.6 km with the interferometer. A visual inspection
of the polarimetric data in comparison to a detailed geologic
map of the Kangerdlugssuaq area indicates that the L-band radar
signatures of different geological lithologies are difficult to
distinguish as are, according to previous analyses, the C-band
signatures. In general, the radar signatures seem to be more variable
at L-band than at C-band. Outcrops of lava on the sides of the
mountains, on the other hand, show up more clearly in the C-band
images from 1994. It is planned to correct the L- and C-band polarimetric
data geometrically and radiometrically utilzing a topographic
map generated from the XTI data. On the basis of geologic maps,
the polarimetric responses of different geological units (as,
e.g. moraines, alluvial sediments, lavas and intrusions) will
be analysed as a function of the local radar incidence angle.
The results of these analyses will help to assess the possibility
of using SAR images in the geological research of Arctic areas.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>During the first days of June, Dr. Tom Farr from
the Jet Propulsion Laboratory visited the DCRS and gave a presentation
about SAR data applied to geology. Dr. Farr&iacute;s research
work focuses, among others, on analysing the microtopographic
evolution of lava flows and the structure of alluvial fans in
desert areas. In a number of discussions, Dr. Farr gave stimulations
for our geology project at DCRS. During one of these meetings,
Louise Hansen from the Geological Museum in Copenhagen presented
a summary of her work on Pleistocene depositional environments
on Jameson Land (East Greenland). The possibility of acquiring
polarimetric and XTI data over these environments was discussed,
since the deposits are characterized by different surface morphologies
which probably can be distinguished in the radar images, and a
lot of field data are already available which could be the basis
for analysing the radar signatures.<BR>
</FONT>
<H1>Sea Ice Studies<BR>
</H1>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>On January 1, DCRS and the Danish Meteorological
Institute (DMI) started a joint project concerning applications
of microwave remote sensing data in operational ice monitoring
in South Greenland waters. During the project we will investigate
the possibilities of using coarse resolution microwave radiometer
observations from satellite to extend traditional ice maps (based
on weather-dependent visual and infrared techniques) into cloud
covered regions. A pilot experiment to gain initial experience
was carried out in connection with a cruise by the German research
vessel Valdivia into the Greenland Sea in April-May 1996.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>Another side of the project concerns the use of Synthetic
Aperture Radar (SAR) data in operational ice monitoring. Both
DMI and DCRS are Principle Investigators on the recently launched
Canadian RADARSAT satellite which carries a SAR with the ability
to map large (500 kilometer) areas on each satellite pass. In
March 1996 (12-15) DMI &amp; DCRS carried out a joint underflight
experiment with the aims of evaluating RADARSAT capabilities and
to study polarimetric SAR signatures in south Greenland Waters.
The experiment consisted of a flight around Kap Farvel with two
aircraft, the G3 Gulfstream of the RDAF equipped with DCRS's polarimetric
C-band SAR, and a Twin-Otter aircraft of the DMI equipped with
video recording and photographic equipment as well as trained
ice observers from DMI.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>Also on January 1, DCRS participation in the European
Commissions European Sub-polar Ocean Project - phase 2, started.
DCRS obligations are production of microwave remote sensing based
ice maps of the Greenland Sea and sorrounding waters, and determination
of ice motion from satellite SAR images of The Greenland Sea.
These activities are in support of a large physical and chemical
oceanography experiment that takes place from the summer of 1996
and runs for at least two years.<BR>
</FONT>
<H1>Polarimetric Radiometry<BR>
</H1>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>Until a few years ago it was assumed that a measurement
of the vertical and the horizontal brightness temperature exhausted
the radiometric possibilities for a given frequency and geometry.
Lately, it has been proven that in some cases independent, new
information is available by measuring the third Stokes parameter
(related to the correlation of the vertical and horizontal electrical
fields). This has first been noticed for the ocean surface where
it seems possible to measure wind speed and direction with a polarimetric
radiometer. The observations have led to resent activity in the
radiometer community, and for example JPL is carrying out aircraft
measurements and model work. The JPL aircraft program employs
a staring radiometer pointed towards the sea surface while the
aircraft makes full 360&#176; turns. Thus the radiometric signature
as a function of look angle relative to the wind direction is
investigated.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>However, one thing is to find the signature using
a staring radiometer with a long integration time hence good radiometric
sensitivity (and having the benefit of full circles), another
thing is to be able to directly determine the wind direction pixel
for pixel based on data from an imager with its inherent short
integration time hence inferior sensitivity. This is of course
the situation for a potential future satellite wind sensor, and
aircraft test experiments with a realistic radiometer configuration
are highly warranted.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>The existing EMIRAD airborne, scanning antenna system
has been combined with the also existing correlation radiometer
(developed for synthetic aperture radiometry work) into an imaging,
polarimetric radiometer system. During May 1996, two  flights
over Danish waters were carried out with low to moderate winds,
while a third attempt had to be cancelled due to low winds. Passes
over a target area were carried out in the imaging mode but also
some circle flights were performed. Data has not yet been analysed
in depth, but an initial inspection of the circle flight data
confirms the JPL measurements and confirms that the radiometer
system performed well during the experiments.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>Further experiments will be carried out during the
fall in the Atlantic off the coast of Brittany. It is hoped and
expected to encounter moderate to high wind conditions.<BR>
</FONT>
