<H1>DCRS</H1>
<H2>Danish Center for Remote Sensing</H2>
<H3>newsletter</H3>
September 1995
<hr>
<P>
<!-- This newsletter also exists as a <a href="/DCRS/newslet-9412.ps">Postscript document</a>.
<P>
<hr> -->
<P>

<P>
<U><B>   </B></U>
<H3>Editorial</H3>

<P>
The winter/spring of 95 has marked an important change concerning
the activities of quite a few DCRS personnel: from working primarily
with development of the EMISAR system to working more and more
on using the system for geophysical experiments and interpretation
of data.
<P>
The L-band system has been finalized and after a brief commissioning
phase entered regular service. The C-band across-track interferometer
option has been implemented and checked out. Thus EMISAR is now
a very powerful instrument with C and L-band fully polarimetric
capability as well as C-band across-track interferometry.
<P>
This instrument has been used extensively for the busy 1995 flight
campaign featuring 21 flights utilizing all possible modes of
the radar. The processing group of DCRS will not find themselves
out of work for some time, not to mention the science group and
external partners eager to work on the data.
<H3>C&amp;L-band SAR</H3>

<P>
An L-band polarimetric SAR system has been developed as part of
the dual frequency (L &amp; C-band), polarimetric, airborne EMISAR
system. During the past winter the L-band SAR was completed and
the first flights were carried out over Denmark. The SAR features
a unique combination of fine resolution (2 x 2 m) and wide swath
(9.3 km). The transmitter power is 6 kW. From a flight altitude
of 41000 ft the range of the radar is 64 km with a noise equivalent
sigma naught of - 20 dB.
<P>
Combining the relatively wide bandwidth of 100 MHz at L-band with
a flat array antenna concept is somewhat a challenge. A stacked
microstrip patch array concept has been used. The feed structure
is on the back side of the antenna panel to reduce unwanted radiation.
The cross polar level is below -35 dB.
<P>
The polarization switch is a relatively conventional PIN diode
switch matrix able to sustain the 6 kW peak power from the transmitter
still exhibiting low loss (0.3 dB) and high isolation (more than
50 dB). Thus system cross talk (between polarizations) is dominated
by antenna cross talk and is some -35 dB.
<P>
The L &amp; C-band polarimetric EMISAR instrument is one of the
key sensors in the JRC EARSEC initiative aiming at being able
to supply state-of-the-art remote sensing data to European scientists.
<H3>Across-track Interferometry (XTI)</H3>

<P>
For some time now, DCRS has planned to establish an across-track
interferometric capability operating at C-band. XTI has many potential
applications both as an instrument which provides scientific measurements
and as an operational sensor in the mapping business. An across-track
interferometer consists of two antennas, preferably at the same
along-track position on the radar platform (in this case an aircraft).
The two antennas will observe the radar scene from slightly different
elevation angles and this makes it possible to determine the 3-dimensional
location of all targets. However, whereas shifts in photographic
stereo image pairs are determined from the actual resolution of
the photos, the image to image displacement of an interferometric
radar pair is determined from the phase shift of the radio frequency
signals. This makes it feasible to measure displacements of targets
on the order of millimeters or less and that makes "radar
stereo" very powerful for height determination even if
the baseline is as small as a meter. And contrary to repeat track
interferometry (RTI) where the image pair is obtained on consecutive
flight passes the XTI images forming a pair are acquired simultaneously
thus even the 3-dimensional location of moving targets (e.g. a
sea surface or leaves on trees) can be determined. The radar measurement
of topography is a powerful complement to photogrammetric height
determination for many reasons such as: 1) All weather, day and
night capability; 2) efficient processing schemes; and 3) works
well in areas with little visual contrast (e.g. over inland ice,
sand dunes, and other homogeneous areas) where optical stereo
fails or performs poorly.
<P>
The antenna installation consists of two flush mounted fairings
designed and fabricated by the Air Materiel Command of the Danish
Air Force and two polarimetric microstrip antennas designed and
fabricated at DCRS by Johan Granholm and Kenn Christensen. The
antennas are looking to the left and the interferometric baseline
is 0.94 um horizontally and 0.64 um vertically for a
total baseline length of 1.14um and an orientation inclined
34 degrees with respect to horizontal. The antenna system incorporates
switches which will allow any one of the two antennas to be operated
as a fully polarimetric antenna sequentially transmitting a horizontally
and a vertically polarized signal and simultaneously receiving
both polarizations. The antenna system supports both signal transmission
and reception on both the upper and the lower antenna, at either
polarization.  The XTI modes initially implemented: 1) The
single-baseline mode, transmitting on one antenna (lower or upper)
receiving the echo on both (two channels); 2) The double-baseline
mode, transmitting and receiving on one antenna then transmitting
and receiving on the opposite (two channels); and 3) The
dual-baseline mode, transmitting on one antenna, receiving on
both, then transmitting on the opposite antenna and receiving
on both (four channels). The VV or the HH polarization can be
chosen as desired.  The single baseline mode is well suited for
mapping the topography in very rough terrain (such as many places
in Greenland), the double baseline mode will optimize the topographic
sensitivity in gentler terrain, where the maximum height accuracy
is required (e.g. in Denmark), and the dual-baseline mode will
allow for certain experiments with measuring the topography and
simultaneously estimating the penetration depth of the radar signal
which could potentially provide information of forest or canopy
depth.
<P>
The interferometry installation was first tested in April this
year. Unfortunately the installation is fairly close to the ports
used to measure the static air pressure on the aircraft. The test
flight revealed that the antenna installation changed the barometric
altitude measurement by up to a 1000 feet when flying at 41000
feet which is not acceptable for air safety reasons. This instigated
a cooperative effort between the Air Materiel Command and DCRS
to develop correction circuitry in the air data computer which
can be switched on when the interferometric antennas are installed.
Unfortunately this unforeseen problem prevented us from collecting
interferometric data over the summer as originally planned. The
additional circuitry for the air data computer was developed by
the end of July and a new test flight performed on August 15th
demonstrated that the correction worked as designed.  The installation
was then approved by the Air Force for data collection flights
and the XTI mode was used extensively in this years data collection
mission to Greenland, August 21-26. During this mission topographic
data were collected over both rough mountain ranges in eastern
Greenland and over glaciers in Northeast Greenland. This falls
activities will include processing and evaluation of the data.
<H3>Flight Campaigns Spring-95</H3>

<P>
The spring and summer '95 were very busy. Twenty-one flights covering
areas in Southern Denmark, Sweden, Norway, Finland, the Faeroe
Islands, and Greenland were carried out. Ten flights were used
for DCRS science data collection, seven flights were requested
by ESA, and four flights were used for testing new system features.
<P>
The first DCRS science flight took place on March 24 where C-band
polarimetric data were collected over the sea-ice in the Greenland
Sea. On April 27, C-band repeat track interferometry (RTI) data
were collected at the Raabjerg Mile area, and C-band polarimetric
data were collected at &Aringlborg, Foulum, and Kal&oslash;. On
April 28, L-band RTI data were collected at Raabjerg Mile, and
polarimetric L-band data were collected at Aggersborg, Foulum,
Kal&oslash;, and Gjern. On June 8, L-band polarimetric data were
collected at Foulum, Kal&oslash;, and Copenhagen. On July 4, C and
L-band polarimetric data were collected at Raabjerg Mile (RTI),
Foulum, Kal&oslash;, and Gjern (L-band only). 
<P>
The Greenland mission consisted of three flights used for data
collection over Greenland, and two transit flights used for data
collection over the Faeroe Islands and Southern Denmark. On August
21, cross track Interferometry (XTI) data were collected at Kal&oslash;
and at Thorshavn on the Faeroe Islands, and L-band polarimetric
data were collected at Copenhagen and Thorshavn. 
<P>
On August 22, L-band RTI data and C-band XTI data were collected
at the Storstr&oslash;mmen glacier in north-east Greenland. XTI
data were also collected at Zackenberg in east Greenland. On August
23, the August 22 flight was repeated. On August 24, C-band XTI
data and L-band polarimetric data were collected in an area 500
km south of Scoresbysund, and C-band XTI data were collected in
an area near Scoresbysund. On August 25, L-band polarimetric data
were collected at Raabjerg Mile, Foulum, and Thorshavn.
<P>
The flights requested by ESA are a part of the European Multi-sensor
Airborne Campaign (EMAC-95). Four areas were covered. The Nopex
area near Uppsala in Sweden was covered on May 1-2 and July 5-6.
One area near Okstindan in Norway was covered on March 22-23,
May 1-2, and July 5-6. Two areas near Oulu in Finland were covered
on March 22-23 and May 1-2. All areas were mapped by the C and
L-band polarimetric system. 
<P>
The purpose of the two first test flights was to test the new
L-band system. On March 2, data were collected at the test sites
at Foulum and Kal&oslash;, and on March 21, test data were collected
at Raabjerg Mile, Foulum, and Kal&oslash;. The third test flight
took place on April 26. The purpose of this flight was to test
the new two-antenna installation that makes it possible to acquire
cross track interferometry data. Data were collected at the sites
at Raabjerg Mile, Foulum, and Kal&oslash;. The final XTI test flight
took place on August 15, where data were collected at Raabjerg
Mile.
<P>
An additional flight is planned to take place in November. C-band
XTI data will be collected over four locations in Southern Denmark.
<H3>Soil and Plant Studies at Research Centre Foulum</H3>

<P>
The soil and plant measurement campaigns over Research Centre
Foulum (RCF) have been continued during 1995. In 1994 data were
collected at C-band (5 cm wavelength) at four different
times during the growth season (28/4, 23/6, 29/7, and 27/8). These
data showed the very significant variation over the growth season
in the radar backscatter and the polarimetric signatures. This
year the addition of the polarimetric L-band (24 cm wavelength)
channel has provided substantially different data as the longer
wavelength is characterised by a much larger penetration depth.
Data at both L- and C-band have been collected during the period
March through August. The data analyses is still in the preliminary
stage but as expected the 24 cm channel is much more reliable
in relation to measurements of soil properties. It now seems feasible
that spatial soil moisture measurements can be provided by airborne
radar with an accuracy on the order of 3-5% (volumetric water
contents), and indications are that the surface roughness can
also be measured quite accurately. Key elements in the measurements
are absolute backscatter calibration and polarimetric capability.
At RCF a scanning laser altimeter system has been developed and
tested which will for instance scan the surface roughness over
a 2 by 0.5 m area with a horizontal resolution better than
1 mm and a vertical resolution better than 0.2 mm.
This instrument in combination with dielectric measurement will
be instrumental to providing in-situ measurements needed for electromagnetic
modelling work which will commence this fall in a Ph.D. study.
This work will eventually lead to better models for relating geophysical
parameters to the radar backscatter signatures measured by a high
resolution polarimetric SAR system. Early results from the Foulum
studies were presented in two papers at the IGARSS'95 conference
and at the PIERS'95 conference.
<H3>Landscape and Ecology Studies at Kal&oslash;</H3>

<P>
The Kal&oslash; site is on the same flight line as the Foulum site,
thus data have been collected on the same acquisition dates. As
in the soil and plant studies the addition of a longer wavelength
has provided data which are substantially different from C-band
data. In particular it seems that the longer wavelength will be
of importance for the forest studies which are important in relation
to this project. The longer wavelength, for instance, means that
it takes much larger biomass densities to saturate the radar backscatter
which is generally an increasing function of the biomass per square
kilometer.
<H3>Applications of SAR Repeat-track Interferometry for Sand Dune
Dynamics and Glacier Dynamics Studies</H3>

<P>
Data collections in the repeat-track interferometry (RTI) mode
have included several missions to the Raabjerg Mile test area
and two missions to the Storstr&oslash;mmen Glacier in North East
Greenland. In the RTI mode the aircraft is flown by the radar
control computer based on real-time P-code GPS navigation data
via an interface to the aircraft ILS (instrument landing system).
Aircraft control algorithm improvements have brought the accuracy
with which the aircraft tracks the desired reference line from
the ten meter level achieved in 1994 to 1 to 2 meters this
year. A second significant achievement is that RTI data can now
be collected at L-band. The longer wavelength has many advantages
which includes: 1) Less temporal decorrelation from track
to track (as L-band tends to see the ground that is stationary
whereas C-band is more sensitive to for instance leaves that are
usually non-stationary on a wavelength scale); and 2) the longer
wavelength allows the use of larger baselines without making the
phase unwrapping process exceedingly difficult.
<P>
Presently, photogrammetric reference data from 1994 covering the
test area at Raabjerg Mile are being reduced to a reference Digital
Elevation Model (DEM) which will be used to evaluate the performance
of the radar generated DEM's. The first step of the Sand
Dune Dynamics study involves developing radar interferometric
techniques that will allow us to generate submeter level DEM's
over a dune field (which has little optical contrast) during all
times of the year. Selected L-band RTI data and C-band XTI data
acquired over Raabjerg Mile during 1995 will be processed to topographic
data during the fall.
<P>
The Storstr&oslash;mmen Glacier was mapped with L-band RTI as well
as with C-band XTI on two consecutive days in late August. The
purpose of the Glacier Dynamics Study is to investigate whether
SAR interferometry can be used to measure both glacier topography
and glacier velocities, parameters of importance to inland ice
mass balance calculations. This years data collection is considered
to be a major improvement over last years C-band RTI data for
several reasons. First of all the addition of the XTI mode provides
us with an independent measurement of the glacier topography whereas
the RTI measurement only provides a measurement which is both
influenced by topography and displacements in the scene. If only
RTI data are available then the two effects can only be separated
if multiple linearly independent baselines are available. Secondly,
the use of the longer L-band wavelength allowed the use of tracks
which are spaced further apart (e.g. 50 m) which in combination
with near repeat tracks provides for a better separation between
topography and velocity. Thirdly, by flying on consecutive days
the time baselines available are extended from the range of 20 minutes
to 2 hours available in 1994 up to 24 hours which further
improves the ability to separate topography and velocity effects,
and this also improves the velocity sensitivity by more than an
order of magnitude. Work on the interferometric processing algorithms
is continuing and significant progress has been made in the fields
of motion compensation both with respect to synchronization of
navigation and radar data, in relation to integrating GPS and
INS (inertial navigation system) data and with respect to extracting
information from the data itself. We presently believe that we
can estimation the instantaneous baseline variation over a 30 km
track with an accuracy on the order of 2 cm which is, however,
not quite satisfactory. Work is on-going to use the data themselves
to further improve on this crucial baseline estimate.
<H3>Geology</H3>

<P>
A polarimetric analysis has been applied to the C-band data acquired
from the Kangerdlugssuaq area in 1994. This analysis has confirmed
the preliminary conclusion made after a visual inspection of the
imagery: a geologic classification cannot be based on the polarimetric
C-band data. The morphology of weathered gneiss and gabbro, for
instance, are so similar that the backscatter coefficients, polarization
signatures, polarimetric decompositions etc. of these two lithologies
are indistinguishable.
<P>
The extreme topography in the Kangerdlugssuaq area has proved
a major obstacle for the geologic interpretation of the SAR imagery.
Therefore the 1995 test site was extended to a 100 km long strip
from Kangerdlugssuaq to Watkins Bjerge where areas with more gentle
topography are found. For the same reason XTI data were acquired.
The digital elevation model to be generated from these XTI data
will allow the SAR imagery to be geometrically and radiometrically
corrected for the topography.
<P>
The polarimetric data were acquired at L-band this year. Since
SARs are sensitive to features with a size comparable to the wavelength
used, morphologic differences not reflected in the C-band data
might show up in the L-band data.
<H3>Sea Ice Studies</H3>

<P>
Sea ice research has been concentrated within two areas: development
of methods to analyse data from airborne and satellite microwave
instruments, and application of these methods in process and/or
climate oriented studies.
<P>
Analysis methods:
<P>
In order to make full use of microwave remote sensing data of
sea ice and ocean surfaces a major part of our work has been in
studying and understanding microwave signatures of these surfaces.
The variability is large, and we are in the process of getting
an improved understanding of the physical properties of the ice
that gives rise to the variations. Satellite SAR data from the
Greenland Sea for a two year period has been studied in detail
in order to map the seasonal variability of the backscatter coefficient
at VV polarization.
<P>
First results from the August 1994 flight with the C-band polarimetric
SAR were presented at IGARSS-95. A field experiment with two aircraft
was carried out on March 25, 1995. The RDAF Gulfstream was equipped
with the Polarimetric C-band SAR, and a Twin Otter of the Greenland
Ice Branch of the Danish Meteorological Institute was equipped
with DCRS's 3-channel profiling microwave radiometer, video cameras,
and hand held cameras for aerial photography. The experiment coincided
with an ERS-1 SAR passage of the area. Data are now being analysed.
<P>
Application projects:
<P>
DCRS participate in a number of projects where satellite microwave
remote sensing data are applied in an attempt to solve climate
related problems. In ESOP (European Subpolar Ocean Project, EU
MAST-2) we use microwave radiometer data from the NIMBUS-7 and
DMSP satellites to map large scale sea ice conditions in the Greenland
Sea area for a 16 year period, and we use a combination of SSM/I
and ERS-1 SAR data to monitor the processes going on in the Greenland
Sea during the winters of 1993, 1994 and 1995. In PELICON (Project
for Estimation of Long term Ice CONcentration, EU ENV) we develop
methods for intercalibration of long time series of microwave
radiometer data from the Wedell and Bellingshausen seas around
Antarctica. In the NEW project (North East Water)  we apply visible
and infrared data from NOAA AVHRR, ERS-1 SAR and passive microwave
satellite data in order to map the development of the North East
Water polynya.
<p>
<hr>
<p>

