<H1>DCRS</H1>
<H2>Danish Center for Remote Sensing</H2>
<H3>newsletter</H3>
December 1994
<hr>
<P>
This newsletter also exists as a <a href="/DCRS/newslet-9412.ps">Postscript document</a>.
<P>
<hr>
<P>
<H3>Editorial</H3>
<P>
This is the first issue of the DCRS newsletters that will provide
a bi-yearly overview over activities at the Danish Center for
Remote Sensing (DCRS). DCRS is established at the Electromagnetics
Institute, Technical University of Denmark, with a 5 year grant
from the Danish National Research Foundation (Danmarks Grundforskningsfond).
The purpose of the center is to conduct research relating to instruments
for remote sensing and their application to Earth observation
and Earth Science. DCRS commenced its operation on February 1,
1994, taking over a number of activities already on-going in EMI's
radar group. The inauguration of the center took place on November
23.
<P>
The center's current activities include enhancing EMI's
airborne polarimetric C-band SAR with an L-band channel and augmenting
this system with interferometric capabilities, which will allow
DCRS to generate 3-D and velocity images. One important achievement
in 1994 was the successful testing of a system which allows the
radar control computer to steer the aircraft very accurately using
GPS as the navigational reference. This capability is extremely
important for repeat-track-interferometry data acquisitions. Other
important achievements within sensor techniques have been the
development of interferometric (synthetic aperture) radiometer
systems and associated processing algorithms.
<P>
Besides the system development activities, 1994 has been a very
busy year for DCRS with several data collection campaigns. The
agricultural test area in Foulum, Jutland, was for instance mapped
on 4 occasions during the period April 28 to August 27. Other
sites in Denmark which were mapped include Kal, Gjern and
Rbjerg Mile. The drifting sand dunes at Rbjerg Mile
was mapped using both polarimetric and repeat-track-interferometric
techniques and a Digital Elevation Model (DEM) based on radar
data alone has been generated. In August a very successful data
collection campaign was also conducted in Greenland. The scientific
applications included mapping of glacier dynamics, geologic mapping,
and sea ice signature studies.
<P>
DCRS has also been very successful with its ERS-1/-2 proposals.
DCRS is the principal investigator on 4 studies and co-investigator
on one. In all studies the comparison of satellite data and airborne
high resolution polarimetric data is an important ingredient.
<P>
An important New Years event is the integration of DCRS and EMI's
Remote Sensing Unit which was headed by professor Gudmandsen until
his retirement in October. The integration will officially take
effect by January 1, 1995.
<P>
On behalf of all of us at DCRS we wish you a Merry X-mas and happy
and productive New Year!
<P>
Sren Nrvang Madsen &amp; Erik Lintz Christensen
<P>
<H3>DCRS Inauguration</H3>
<P>
The formal inauguration of the Danish Center for Remote Sensing
took place on November 23, eventhough the Center started its work
on February 1, 1994. After welcome addresses by the director of
EMI (Bent Knudsen) and the director of the University (Hans Peter
Jensen), the director of the Danish National Research Foundation
(Peder Olesen Larsen) gave a short keynote address about the background
for the center.
<P>
The head of DCRS (Sren Nrvang Madsen) gave a lecture
about the Center primarily based on its research plan.
<P>
After that, a reception took place at the premises of EMI, and
the invitees had a chance to see the facilities of DCRS like the
key sensor (the SAR) and hardware development laboratories as
well as the processing lab.
<P>
Some 60 persons attended the inauguration.
<P>
<H3>Flight Campaign 1994</H3>
<P>
During 1994 eight missions covering areas in Southern Denmark,
Sweden, Faroe Islands, and Greenland was carried out. The first
mission took place on April 28. The purpose was to acquire radar
data at the DCRS test sites in Southern Denmark. Repeat track
interferometry (RTI) data was collected at the Raabjerg Mile area,
and C-band polarimetric data was collected at the test sites at
Foulum and Kaloe.
<P>
The second mission took place on June 23. This mission was ordered
by the European Space Agency, and the purpose was to acquire data
at the Nopex test area near Uppsala in Sweden. C-band polarimetric
data was collected at three sites in the Nopex area and at the
DCRS test sites in Foulum, Gjern,and Kaloe.
<P>
The third mission took place on July 28. The purpose of this mission
was to acquire data at the DCRS sites in Southern Denmark. RTI
data was collected at the test area in Raabjerg Mile, and C-band
polarimetry was collected at the DCRS test areas at Foulum, Gjern,
and Kaloe. Polarimetric data covering Aalborg airfield was also
collected.
<P>
The Greenland campaign consisted of three missions covering the
DCRS test areas in Greenland, and two transit missions used for
data collection over Southern Denmark. 
<P>
On August 21 RTI data was collected at the Raabjerg Mile area,
and C-band polarimetric data covering Thorshavn on the Faroe Islands
was acquired. On August 22 RTI data was collected at the Storstroemmen
glacier in Northeast  Greenland. On August 23 C-band polarimetric
data was collected in a 25 by 25 km area at Kangerdlugssuaq 500
km south of Scoresbysund in East Greenland. On August 26 C-band
polarimetric data covering a 500 km strip of sea-ice was collected.
On August 27 C-band polarimetric data covering Thorshavn, Skagen,
Foulum, and Copenhagen was collected.
<P>
<H3>Repeat-Track Interferometry</H3>
<P>
Repeat track interferometry (RTI) was first demonstrated using
satellite data from the SEASAT SAR. Later studies have used ERS-1
and J-ERS-1 satellite data. Applications have included
topographic mapping, change detection, and studies of dynamic
phenomena, e.g. earthquakes and glaciers. Despite the fact that
airborne systems have several advantages compared to satellite
systems when it comes to studies and demonstration programs, similar
application have not been demonstrated using aircraft data. The
reason is that aircraft are very difficult to navigate on multiple
passes and the required small and parallel baselines are seldom
achieved. Typically baselines less than 100 m are required
and standard aircraft navigation accuracy is on the order of a
kilometre.
<P>
DCRS has designed, implemented, and tested a tight coupling of
navigation, radar control, and aircraft flight management system
to meet the requirements for an aircraft RTI system. This allows
the radar to control the aircraft through one of two redundant
Instrument Landing System (ILS) interfaces installed on the aircraft.
The polarimetric Cband system developed at EMI is operated on
a Danish Air Force Gulfstream G-3 aircraft at a nominal altitude
of 12.5 km. A slant range swath in excess of 9 km
is mapped in the high resolution mode (1.5 m pixel spacing).
<P>
The basic functionality of this aircraft control system is: 1)
A desired reference track is input into the radar control computer,
as well as cross-track and height off-sets -these are typically
in the range 0 to 100 m. 2) The radar control computer (RCP)
reads a real-time P-code Global Positioning System (GPS) receiver
and compares the actual positions with the desired track and calculates
horizontal and vertical off-sets. 3) The RCP generates emulated
ILS signals which are feed to one of the on-board flight management
systems. An important element of the implementation is the servo
loop that calculates the ILS control signal based on the above
mentioned position and velocity inputs and a model of the aircraft
dynamic behaviour.
<P>
The system was tested on a number of flights during the summer
of 1994, and data was collected over several test sites. One data
set has been reduces to a Digital Elevation Model. The achieved
baselines as estimated from the radar data have been compared
to the desired baselines and baselines predicted from the GPS
data and the preliminary analysis shows that it is possible to
bring the aircraft to within 1 m of the reference. Currently
the uncertainty on the reference is somewhat larger, on the order
of 15 m.
<P>
The RTI capability is particularly important for two of the Center's
scientific studies. One is the investigation: <B>The Dynamics
of Sand Dunes;</B> conducted in collaboration with Keld Rmer
Rasmussen, Department of Earth Sciences, University of Aarhus.
An important property of the Earth's surface is the friction
it exerts on atmospheric circulation. For a given wind it determines
the extent of soil removal, loss of nutrients and seeds from fields,
sediment transport in dunes, dust generation and subsequently
desertification by drifting sand. Aerodynamic roughness is known
to be correlated with the textural properties of the ground -surface
roughness- that can be measured by radar polarimetry. Sediment
transport, i.e. the flux of material per unit width per unit time,
is practically impossible to measure accurately by conventional
techniques in complex dune fields. This study concern the use
of interferometric SAR techniques to derive detailed topographic
information for the Rbjerg Mile dune field at the required
vertical resolution. With a time series of such data sets the
sediment transport can be estimated. An important attribute is
that radar is weather-independent and the data processing very
efficient. DCRS is the PI on an ERS-1/-2 investigation
on applying interferometric SAR satellite techniques to both this
area and a larger dune field in southern California.
<P>
The second study relying heavily on the RTI capability is <B>Glacier
Dynamics: SAR Repeat-track-interferometry Applied to Storstrmmen
Glacier, Northeast Greenland,</B> a collaboration with Niels Reeh,
Danish Polar Center. The ice sheets of Greenland and Antarctic
act as long-term reservoirs in the hydrological cycle, and changes
in their size are therefore an indicator of global climate change.
Although glaciers are a much smaller part of the cryosphere, they
are considered an important diagnostics tool as they respond more
rapidly to changing environmental conditions. In this study the
capability of SAR repeat track interferometry (RTI) using multiple
baseline techniques to provide spatial measurements of instantaneous
ice velocity and also microtopography is being studied. This is
of importance for future measurements of changes of surface elevations
and velocities of glaciers. Also this study is the subject of
an ERS-1/-2 investigation at DCRS.
<P>
<H3>Preliminary Results from Foulum</H3>
<P>
The intensively monitored fields of Research Centre Foulum (RCF)
and the neighbouring Tjele Estate constitute a suitable test site
for DCRS's research in plant and soil as well as aerodynamic
roughness.
<P>
In 1994 EMISAR acquired C-band polarimetric SAR data from the
Foulum area on April 28, June 23, July 29, and August 27. Simultaneous
ground truth observations of surface roughness, soil moisture
etc. were collected, and radar reflectors were deployed in order
to allow the polarimetric calibration of EMISAR to be verified.
<P>
The SAR data have been focused, calibrated and distributed to
the DCRS partners in a full resolution scattering matrix format
and a multi-look gamma nought format. These digital data were
accompanied by hardcopies showing the intensity of the three independent
polarimetric channels in a colour representation. The colour balance
changes radically during the season, and even the effect of irrigation
and fertilisation is visible in the SAR imagery thus proving the
great potential of polarimetric SAR for vegetation monitoring.
<P>
An automatic classification of the SAR imagery has been attempted
by DCRS. Using the concept of polarimetric contrast the pixels
in eight different training fields were classified with a confidence
of 95 to 99 per cent. The classification confidence is significantly
less for fields that are not members of the training set, one
reason being the incidence angle variation. Currently, DCRS is
studying techniques to remedy this effect. So far, the classification
has been based on the July 29 data, but a great improvement is
expected when the classification algorithm is extended to exploit
multi temporal data.
<P>
The aerodynamic roughness (AR) has been measured by anemometers
mounted on a mast deployed at RCF. Initial analyses show a high
seasonal correlation between the AR and the HH channel intensity
of the wheat field beneath the mast.
<P>
<H3>Geology in Greenland</H3>
<P>
The application of Synthetic Aperture Radar (SAR) for Geologic
mapping in Greenland is investigated by the Danish Center for
Remote Sensing (DCRS) in co-operation with the Danish Lithosphere
Centre. A pilot project was conducted in August 1994, where the
Danish airborne polarimetric C-band SAR, EMISAR, acquired data
over a 25 by 25 km area at Kangerdlugssuaq 500 km south west of
Scoresbysund, East Greenland.
<P>
The area was covered by three partly overlapping swaths, and one
swath was mapped from the opposite side as well. Three trihedrals
distributed over the middle swath served as a supplement to EMISAR's
internal calibration facilities. Data was acquired in fully polarimetric
mode, and processed to 2 by 2 m resolution, one-look imagery.
<P>
Due to the extreme topography in the area, major areas are obscured
by shadowing. Other areas are obscured by lay-over and severe
foreshortening, which badly deteriorates the ground resolution
and affects the radiometric calibration  accordingly. However,
in terrains with more gentle topography the internal structures
of lithologies are weathered out and reflected in the SAR images
via the morphology. In the gentle areas dikes and faults in moderate
concentration show up quite well, and areas of gneisses, major
structural elements of gneiss areas, and bedding in lava successions
are readily identified.
<P>
The preliminary results do not indicate much polarimetric information.
The VV/HH intensity ratio is close to unity and fairly constant
over the entire scene. Also, the intensities of the cross-polarised
channels are quite low, typically 10-12 dB below the intensities
of the co-polarised channels. An artifact characterised by high
cross-polarisation is observed behind many of the sharp maintain
rims. Preliminary investigations suggest the phenomenon to be
caused by multi-path propagation.
<P>
<H3>Papers, Conferences, Workshops</H3>
<P>
Jrgen Dall, Henning Skriver, and Niels Skou participated
in <I><B>the</B></I> yearly remote sensing conference, IGARSS
(International Geoscience and Remote Sensing Symposium) and read
3 papers on DCRS research:
<P>
Dall, J., Skou, N., Christensen, E., L.: "Pulse Based Internal
Calibration of Polarimetric SAR".
<P>
Skriver, H., Dall, J., Madsen, S., N.: "External Polarimetric
Calibration of the Danish Polarimetric C-band SAR".
<P>
Laursen, B., Skou, N.: "A Spaceborne Synthetic Aperture Radiometer
Simulated by the TUD Demonstration Model".
<P>
SNM participated in the GGU workshop on "Early detection
of changes on the Greenland ice sheet and understanding their
causes", GGU, November 16-18, Cph. He gave 2 presentation,
one with Niels Reeh of the Danish Polar Center on "SAR
Repeat-track-interferometry experiment on Storstrmmen Glacier,
Northeast Greenland" and on request a second improvised
presentation on the activities of DCRS was given.
<P>
