<html> <head>
<title>EMI Image Header and I/O System version 3.0</title>
</head>

<body>
<h1>EMI Image Header and I/O System version 3.0</h1>

<b>Sorry</b>, but the user and reference manual has not been ported to
HTML yet, since the report has not yet been finalized.
<p>
The purpose with the EMI Image Header and I/O System is to provide users with
a detailed image header and an easy and uniform programming interface to
remote sensing image files.
<p>
Some of the features of the EMI Header and I/O System are:
<ul>
  <li> Detailed image header containing information about the acqusition, map
       projection, calibration etc. of the image.
  <li> Support of <i>18</i> different image data types, including 8, 16, and
       32 bit integers; 16, 32, and 64 bit floating point; and complex data
       types.
  <li> Programming interface for C++ and FORTRAN that simplifies the file
       input/output.
  <li> Includes interface to other scientific image formats, such as HDF and
       CHIPS.
</ul>
<p>
Until the final version will be available, excerpts from the report is written
below. This gives an <a href="emiheader.html#overview">overview</a> of the system as well as a few <a href="emiheader.html#examples">programming
examples</a>.
<p>
Please feel free to download the <a href="ftp://ms/pub/emiheader/v3/emiheader.doc.tar.gz">draft version</a>, available in PostScript.
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<h2><a NAME="overview">Overview of the system</a></h2>
(Excerpts from Chapter 2)
<p>
For the programmer, the header system can be regarded as a black box,
consisting of two units, a function interface unit and a EMI header and file
input/output unit.
<p>
<center>
<img src="fig1.gif">
<p>
<i>Fig 1. <b>Block diagram of the EMI Image Header system</b></i>
</center>
<p>
The third box shown in figure 1 labeled <i>Application code</i>
is the code written by the programmer, the rest is accesible through the
header system library.
<p>
The programmer asks the header system library to perform tasks through
interface functions. These tasks includes
<p>
<ul>
 <li> Open image files
 <li> Read header information
 <li> Read image data
 <li> Create new image files
 <li> Write image data
 <li> Add optional header information
 <li> Perform transformation between rectangular map coordinates and
       geographical coordinates
</ul>
<p>
For each image, the application wants to work with, a block of memory has to
be allocated by the library in order to control access to the image from the
application. The application receives a reference or <i>handle</i> to this
control block, which is used to access this memory space through the interface
functions. This handle is implemented differently when used in C++ and FORTRAN
respectively.
<p>
This implementation makes it possible to reference as many images as the
amount of memory on the computer permits.
<p>
<center>
<A HREF="fig2.eps"><img BORDER=1 src="fig2.gif"></A>
<p>
<i>Fig 2. <b>The image header system in use for reading an existing image A
          and writing a new image B.</b></i>
</center>
<p>
The usage of the image header system is shown in Figure 2. In the
figure, image A already exists on the mass storage, and the application 
wants to read it. The image related information is stored in the header. This
information is read into memory with the interface function <tt>iopen</tt>, which 
also prepares the file for reading and writing of data.
<p>
When the image has been opened, the application can access all the information
through set/get functions, that writes and reads respectively information
between application variables and the memory space controlled by the library.
<p>
There is <i>no</i> direct access to the header information stored in the
library, i.e. the application cannot manipulate the memory controlled by the
library. All access has to go through the interface functions.
<p>
A subset of the image data (or the whole image) can be transferred to an
appropriate data area in the application (data area 1 in
Figure 2). This is done using the reading interface function
<tt>iread</tt>. The read
function can read image data of all 18 supported types: 
<p>
<ul>
 <li> Signed or unsigned 1, 2 or 4 bytes integer,
 <li> 2, 4 or 8 bytes floating point,
 <li> Complex number versions of above mentioned data types.
</ul>
<p>
The data type of the data area are limited to a subset of these data types.
It must be one of the data types supported by the language. See
Table 1 for a reference.
<p>
<center>
<img src="table1.gif">
<p>
<i>Table 1. <b>Valid data types for data areas. Signature: <IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="sup.gif"> Supported, <IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="polsup.gif"> Supported by the <tt>pol_cmpx</tt> class, and <IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="notsup.gif"> Not supported.</b></i>
</center>
<p>
The image B in Figure 2 is a new image that the application
is going to create. In data area 2 the image data that the application has
computed is stored. The application has also computed the image related
information, which is set in the library memory by the interface functions.
Using the interface routine <tt>icreate</tt> the image file B is now
opened and the library memory information is copied into an image header in the
image file.
<p>
A subset of the image data (or all image data) stored in data area 2 can now
be copied into the image file using the interface function <tt>iwrite</tt>. As
 for the reading function
this writing routine can write the image data in all 18 data types to the
image file.
<p>
<a name="examples"><h2>Two C++ examples</a></h2>
(Excerpts from Chapter 5)
<ol>
  <li> This is a very simple <a href="example1.html">example</a> that shows how to open an existing image, and,
depending on the error status, write out some header record values.
  <li> This <a href="example2.html">example</a> creates a new image if it does not exist already.
</ol>
<hr>
<address><a href="/DCRS/staff/njb.html">Niels Bagger</a>  <a href="mailto:njb@emi.dtu.dk">&lt;njb@emi.dtu.dk&gt;</a></address>
<!-- hhmts start -->
