<html> <head>
<title>ESOP-2 at the Danish Center for Remote Sensing</title>

</head>

<body>
<h1><center>ESOP-2 at the Danish Center for Remote Sensing</center></h1>
<table>
<tr>
<td>
<a  href="http://www.dcrs.dtu.dk/"><IMG ALT="ESOP2logo" SRC="http://www.dcrs.dtu.dk/images/emilogo.gif"  border=2 align=center >
</td> 
<td>  
<a  href="http://www.smr.uib.no/"><IMG ALT="emilogo" SRC="http://www.dcrs.dtu.dk/images/esop2-logo.gif" border=2 align=center></a>
</td>
<td>  
<a  href="http://www.dtu.dk/"><IMG ALT="dtulogo" SRC="http://www.dcrs.dtu.dk/images/dtulogo.gif" border=2 align=center >
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<br>


<h2><center>European Subpolar Ocean Project phase 2 under MAST-III</center></h2>
<center>ESOP-2 is an EEC project under the MAST III programme, contract MAS3-CT95-0015</center>
<h2>Overall project description </h2>

The goal of <a href="http://www.smr.uib.no/">ESOP-2 </a>is to understand the thermohaline circulation in the
Greenland Sea, its sensitivity, and impact on global ocean circulation,
building on a unique combination of novel experimental
techniques, modelling and experience gained under ESOP-1.
<br>

<h3>Role and contribution of DTU (DCRS)</h3>
The Danish Center for Remote Sensing contributes with large scale ice mapping in the Greenland Sea
based on passive microwave information, and with detailed studies of the ice formation and decay in
the Odden area based on Active and Passive microwave observations.
<ul>

<li>  <a href="ftp://www.dcrs.dtu.dk/pub/ssmi/icemaps/1996">Ice in the Odden area 1996</a>
<li>  <a href="/DCRS/latest-ice.html"> Latest ice and met-observations</a>
<li>  <a href="/DCRS/history-odden.html"> Historical ice information</a>
			     
<h3>Project related data</h3>
<p>
<LI> <a href="ftp://megasat.emi.dtu.dk/pub/ssmi/icemaps/">Daily gif images from the Greenland Sea, 1992-1996</a>
<LI> <a href="http://www.dmi.dk/oiweb/esop2/">ESOP-2 at DMI</a> (the Danish Meteorological Institute)
 <p>
 <hr>
<address><a href="/DCRS/staff/ltp.html">Leif Toudal &lt;ltp@emi.dtu.dk&gt;</a></address>
