<HEAD>
<TITLE> Comiso (frequency) algorithm</TITLE>
<meta name="description" value=" Comiso (frequency) algorithm">
<meta name="keywords" value="article">
<meta name="resource-type" value="document">
<meta name="distribution" value="global">
</HEAD>
<BODY><P>
 <BR> <HR><A NAME=tex2html153 HREF="node9.html"><IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="next" SRC="/u/emilib/lib/perl/latex2html/icons/next_motif.gif"></A> <A NAME=tex2html151 HREF="node4.html"><IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="up" SRC="/u/emilib/lib/perl/latex2html/icons/up_motif.gif"></A> <A NAME=tex2html145 HREF="node7.html"><IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="previous" SRC="/u/emilib/lib/perl/latex2html/icons/previous_motif.gif"></A> <A NAME=tex2html155 HREF="node1.html"><IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="contents" SRC="/u/emilib/lib/perl/latex2html/icons/contents_motif.gif"></A>  <BR>
<B> Next:</B> <A NAME=tex2html154 HREF="node9.html"> NASA algorithm</A>
<B>Up:</B> <A NAME=tex2html152 HREF="node4.html"> Algorithms</A>
<B> Previous:</B> <A NAME=tex2html146 HREF="node7.html"> Comiso (polarization) algorithm</A>
<BR> <HR> <P>
<H3><A NAME=SECTION00031400000000000000> Comiso (frequency) algorithm</A></H3>
<P>
This algorithm is equal to the polarization based Comiso algorithm from the
<A HREF="node7.html">previous section</A>, except that it is using the (37V,19V) channels, and it is 
therefore called the frequency based Comiso algorithm (COMFREQ).
It is using the same channels as the  
<A HREF="node6.html">NORSEX algorithm </A>, and in the case, where the linear transformation is applied 
to the tie-points in the NORSEX algorithm, the COMFREQ and NORSEX algorithms produces
the same results, since they both solves the same three equations with the same three
unknowns.
<P>
<BR> <HR>
