<BR> <HR> <P>
<H3><A NAME=SECTION00031500000000000000> NASA algorithm</A></H3>
<P>
The NASA algorithm by <A HREF="node17.html#gloersen">[Gloersen and Cavalieri, 1986]</A> is a further development of an earlier version
of the same algorithm <A HREF="node17.html#cavalieri">[Cavalieri and Gloersen, 1984]</A>.
It uses the satellite data to calculate two ratios: the polarization ratio (PR) and 
the spectral gradient ratio (GR):
<P><IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="_35212_equation211.gif"><P>
<P><IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="_35212_equation217.gif"><P>
where <IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="_35212_tex2html_wrap898.gif">, <IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="_35212_tex2html_wrap900.gif"> and <IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="_35212_tex2html_wrap902.gif"> are the brightness temperatures in the
37V, 19V and 19H channels, respectively.
These ratios are supposed to be largely independent of physical temperature
<A HREF="node17.html#cavalieri">[Cavalieri and Gloersen, 1984]</A>.
A typical PR-GR plot is shown in <A HREF="node9.html#figNASA">Figure 1</A>. <P><A NAME=748>&#160;</A><A NAME=figNASA>&#160;</A><IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="_35212_figure231.gif">
<BR><STRONG>Figure 1</STRONG> The geometry of NASA algorithm (from <A HREF="node17.html#gloersen">[Gloersen and Cavalieri, 1986]</A>)<BR>
<P>
<P>
