<B> Previous:</B> <A NAME=tex2html175 HREF="node10.html"> Tie-point selection</A>
<BR> <HR> <P>
<H1><A NAME=SECTION00040000000000000000> Algorithm comparison</A></H1>
<P>
A total of 5 microwave radiometer algorithms to calculate the ice concentration
and the multi-year ice fraction have been compared.
The algorithms are described in the <A HREF="node4.html">previous sections</A>,  and the
calculations have been performed in 7 areas, the 4 areas shown in <A HREF="node11.html#figareas">Figure 4</A> and the 3 areas shown in <A HREF="node10.html#figtiepoints">Figure 2</A>. <P><A NAME=301>&#160;</A><A NAME=figareas>&#160;</A><IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="_35212_figure298.gif">
<BR><STRONG>Figure 4</STRONG> The 4 mixed areas<BR>
<P>
The areas are chosen so all combinations of open water (W) multi-year ice (MY)
and first-year ice (FY) are present.
The area selection is based on knowledge by the author, in which areas the different 
ice types exist.
The method of using real radiometer data from different areas does not guarantee, 
that only the expected ice types are present in the areas, but it gives the 
possibility of comparing different algorithms on real radiometer data.<BR>The areas of W, MY and FY are the same as used in the tie-point calculation.
<P>
<BR> <HR>
<UL> 
<LI> <A NAME=tex2html185 HREF="node12.html#SECTION00041000000000000000"> Total ice concentration in January and February 1993</A>
<LI> <A NAME=tex2html186 HREF="node13.html#SECTION00042000000000000000"> Multi-year ice fraction in January and February 1993</A>
<LI> <A NAME=tex2html187 HREF="node14.html#SECTION00043000000000000000"> Algorithm sensitivity to physical temperature</A>
<LI> <A NAME=tex2html188 HREF="node15.html#SECTION00044000000000000000"> Algorithm sensitivity to measurement noise</A>
</UL>
