<H1><A NAME=SECTION00310000000000000000> init_geometric</A></H1>
<P>
   init_geometric - Initializes the coordinates conversion functions.
<P>
<H2><A NAME=SECTION00312000000000000000> Synopsis</A></H2>
<P>
 C:
<pre>
int init_geometric( imgID, skip, mag )
   PID   imgID;
   <a href="node4.html#SECTION00314000000000000001">Rect</a>  skip;
   Rect  mag;
</pre>
Inputs
<pre>
     imgID The partition identifier
     skip  The skip factors used.
     mag   The pixel magnification used.
</pre>
<P>
 FORTRAN:
<pre>
SUBROUTINE INIT_GEOMETRIC( IMGID, SKIPL, SKIPS, MAGL, MAGS, IRC )
   INTEGER*4  IMGID
   INTEGER*4  SKIPL, SKIPS
   INTEGER*4  MAGL, MAGS
   INTEGER*4  IRC           (Return value)
</pre>
Inputs
<pre>
     IMGID        The partition identifier
     SKIPL, SKIPS The skip factors used, resp. in line and sample.
     MAGL, MAGS   The pixel magnification used, resp. in line and sample.
     IRC          The function return code.
</pre>
<P>
<H2><A NAME=SECTION00313000000000000000> Description</A></H2>
<P>
 The <tt>init_geometric</tt> and it's related functions are used to convert
 between line/sample coordinates for a specific image (referenced by the
 <tt>imgID</tt> partition identifier) and latitude/longitude coordinates.
<P>
 The function is part of the EMI Image Header System <A HREF="node15.html#EMI">[1]</A>. In order for
 the function to work properly in C, the <tt>getcom_()</tt> function <em>must</em>
 be called prior to <tt>init_geometric</tt>.
<P>
 If the referenced image is accesed with line and/or sample skipping and
 possibly pixel magnification in line and/or sample direction, the 
 conversion functions can be instructed to adjust the coordinates. This is
 done by scaling the pixel spacing (<tt>PSPAX</tt> and <tt>PSPAY</tt>) parameters
 stored in the partition:
<P>
<P><IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="_24619_displaymath1504.gif"><P>
 where <IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="_24619_tex2html_wrap1506.gif"> is the original pixel spacing in the line respectively the 
 sample direction, <IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="_24619_tex2html_wrap1508.gif"> the number of lines resp. samples to skip <IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="_24619_tex2html_wrap1510.gif">,
 <IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="_24619_tex2html_wrap1512.gif"> the pixel magnification factor in line resp. sample direction, and
 <IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="_24619_tex2html_wrap1514.gif"> the scaled spacing.
<P>
 The convertion functions are able to use an elliptical Earth for the
 projection. The elliptical parameters are those discussed
 in <A HREF="node15.html#ttwsparmwswsvaltt">[2]</A>[p. 9]usgs. The parameters has to be located in one or more
 optional header records labeled <tt>&amp;&amp;</tt>. Each record can contain
 one or more of the elliptical parameters, separated with a whitespace
 character, and they can be placed in any
 order. Each parameter definition must have the following syntax:
<P>
<pre>
                    [ws] parm [ws] = [ws] val
</pre>
 where <tt>[ws]</tt> is optional whitespace (ie. space or tab characters),
 <tt>parm</tt> is the parameter identifier (ie. 'A', 'B', ...), and <tt>val</tt>
 is the parameter value which is either a floating point number or a string of 
 characters.
<P>
 The possible values for <tt>parm</tt> are:
<P>
<table>
<td ALIGN=left><tt>A</tt><td ALIGN=left>Semimajor axis or equitorial radius. <tr>
<td ALIGN=left><tt>B</tt><td ALIGN=left>Semiminor axis or polar radius. <tr>
<td ALIGN=left><tt>F</tt><td ALIGN=left>Flattening. <tr>
<td ALIGN=left><tt>RF</tt><td ALIGN=left>Reciprocal flattening. <tr>
<td ALIGN=left><tt>E</tt><td ALIGN=left>Eccentricity. <tr>
<td ALIGN=left><tt>ES</tt><td ALIGN=left>Eccentricity squared. <tr>
<td ALIGN=left><tt>NAME</tt><td ALIGN=left>Ellipse name. <tr>
</table><P>
 As stated in <A HREF="node15.html#usgs">[2]</A>, only the needed parameters should be defined, the
 rest should be left undefined. Does any parameter occur more than once, then
 the <em>last</em> definition is used. Refer to Appendix <A HREF="node14.html#appellps"><IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="gif" SRC="/u/emilib/lib/perl/latex2html/icons/cross_ref_motif.gif"></A> for
 a list of possible ellipse names.
<P>
<H2><A NAME=SECTION00314000000000000000> Structures</A></H2>
<P>
<pre>
<A NAME=SECTION00314000000000000001>/* Rectangular map structure */</A>
typedef struct {
   int  l;  /* Line direction */
   int  s;  /* Sample direction */
} Rect;
</pre>
<P>
<H2><A NAME=SECTION00315000000000000000> Return value</A></H2>
<P>
 On success, the function returns 1, otherwise 0.
<P>
<H2><A NAME=SECTION00316000000000000000> Example</A></H2>
<P>
 Optional Header Record:
<P>
<pre>     &HEADPROJ& A=6370997.0 ES=0.0</pre>
<P>
 This could also have been specified with:
<P>
<pre>
     &HEADPROJ& ES=0.0
     &HEADPROJ& A = 6370997.0
</pre>
<P>
<H2><A NAME=SECTION00317000000000000000> See Also</A></H2>
<P>
 <em>getcom_()</em>, <em><a href="node5.html#SECTION00320000000000000000">init_proj()</a></em>, <em>ird</em>xx<em>()</em>, <em><a href="node6.html#SECTION00330000000000000000">map()</a></em>, <em><a href="node12.html#SECTION00390000000000000000">world()</a></em>
<P>
<BR> <HR>
<P><ADDRESS>
<I> Niels J. Bagger <BR>
Mon Jan 16 15:44:42 NFT 1995</I>
