<BR> <HR> <P>
<H1><A NAME=SECTION00320000000000000000> init_proj</A></H1>
<P>
   init_proj - Initializes the USGS projection.
<P>
<H2><A NAME=SECTION00322000000000000000> Synopsis</A></H2>
<P>
 C:
<pre>
void *init_proj( pid, parm, ellps )
   int              pid;
   double *         parm;
   <a href="node5.html#SECTION00324000000000000001">EllipseStruct</a> *  ellps;
</pre>
Inputs
<pre>
     pid   Projection identifier (1xx-5xx).
     parm  The projection parameters.
     ellps A pointer to the Earth Shape structure. NULL = spheric earth.
</pre>
<P>
 FORTRAN:
<pre>
SUBROUTINE INIT_PROJ( REF, PID, PARM, A, B, F, RF, E, ES, NAME, FLAG )
   INTEGER*4  REF                 (Return value)
   INTEGER*4  PID
   REAL*8     PARM(8)
   REAL*8     A, B, F, RF, E, ES
   CHARACTER  NAME*32
   INTEGER*4  FLAG
</pre>
Inputs
<pre>
     PARM  The projection parameters.
     A     Semimajor axis or equitorial radius.
     B     Semiminor axis or polar radius.
     F     Flattening.
     RF    Reciprocal flattening.
     E     Eccentricity.
     ES    Eccentricity squared.
     NAME  Ellipse name.
     FLAG  Usage flag (DO_xx). 0 equals spheric earth.
</pre>
<P>
<H2><A NAME=SECTION00323000000000000000> Description</A></H2>
<P>
 <tt>init_proj</tt> must be called first to select and initialize a projection.
 The parameters <tt>parm</tt> are those cartographic parameters discussed in the
 projection sections of <A HREF="node15.html#usgs">[2]</A> and <A HREF="node15.html#proj4">[3]</A> and the tables in
 Appendix <A HREF="node13.html#appproj"><IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="gif" SRC="/u/emilib/lib/perl/latex2html/icons/cross_ref_motif.gif"></A>.
<P>
 The order of the parameters in <tt>parm</tt> must be
 identical to the order the parameters have in the tables.
<P>
 The projection identifier <tt>pid</tt> is the number listed in table <A HREF="node13.html#tabcyl"><IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="gif" SRC="/u/emilib/lib/perl/latex2html/icons/cross_ref_motif.gif"></A>-<A HREF="node13.html#tabmisc"><IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="gif" SRC="/u/emilib/lib/perl/latex2html/icons/cross_ref_motif.gif"></A>.
<P>
 To specify the Earth's elliptical figure constants the <tt>EllipseStruct</tt>
 structure is used in C or the corresponding parameters in the FORTRAN call.
 See [p. 9]usgs for information on the parameters.
 Not all parameters are used simultaneously, setting the <tt>flag</tt> parameter
 specifies which parameters are to be used. A
 set of constants (<tt>DO_xx</tt>) are defined which explicit identify the
 individual parameters. Refer to Appendix <A HREF="node14.html#appellps"><IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM ALT="gif" SRC="/u/emilib/lib/perl/latex2html/icons/cross_ref_motif.gif"></A> for
 a list of possible ellipse names.
<P>
<H2><A NAME=SECTION00324000000000000000> Structures</A></H2>
<P>
<pre>
<A NAME=SECTION00324000000000000001>/* Ellipse structure */</A>
typedef struct {
   double  a;         /* Semimajor axis or equitorial radius */
   double  b;         /* Semiminor axis or polar radius */
   double  f;         /* Flattening */
   double  rf;        /* Reciprocal flattening */
   double  e;         /* Eccentricity */
   double  es;        /* Eccentricity squared */
   char    name[32];  /* Ellipse name */
   int     flag;      /* Usage flag (DO_xx) */
} EllipseStruct;
<P>
/* Ellipse structure flags */
#define  DO_A     0x0001
#define  DO_B     0x0002
#define  DO_F     0x0004
#define  DO_RF    0x0008
#define  DO_E     0x0010
#define  DO_ES    0x0020
#define  DO_NAME  0x0100
</pre>
<P>
<H2><A NAME=SECTION00325000000000000000> Return value</A></H2>
<P>
 On success, the function returns a pointer to the initialized projection
 structure to be used in calls to <tt>proj</tt>.
<P>
 On error, the function returns <tt>NULL</tt> (<tt>REF</tt> = 0 in FORTRAN).
<P>
<H2><A NAME=SECTION00326000000000000000> Example</A></H2>
<P>
 C:
<pre>
#include <proj.h>
void          *ref
EllipseStruct ellps;
double        parm[] = { -20.0, /* lon_0 */
                        0.0,   /* lat_0 */
                        75.0,  /* lat_1 */
                        75.0   /* lat_2 */
                       }
ellps.a = 6378206.4;
ellps.b = 6356583.8;
ellps.flag = DO_A | DO_B;
ref = init_proj( 301, parm, &ellps ); /* Lambert Conformal Conic */
</pre>
<P>
 FORTRAN:
<pre>
      INTEGER*4 REF
      INTEGER*4 PID
      REAL*8 PARM(8)
      REAL*8 A, B
      INTEGER*4 FLAG, ZERO


      ZERO = 0
      PID = 301
      PARM(1) = -20D0
      PARM(2) = 0D0
      PARM(3) = 75D0
      PARM(4) = 75D0
      A = 6378206.4D0
      B = 6356583.8D0
      FLAG = 1 + 2
C Initialize the Lambert Conformal Conic Projection
      CALL INIT_PROJ( REF, PID, PARM, A, B, ZERO, ZERO, ZERO, ZERO,
     +   ZERO, FLAG )
</pre><P>
<H2><A NAME=SECTION00327000000000000000> See Also</A></H2>
<P>
 <a href="node4.html#SECTION00310000000000000000"><em>init_geometric()</em></a>, <a href="node11.html#SECTION00380000000000000000"><em>proj()</em></a>.
<P>
<BR> <HR>
