<H1><A NAME=SECTION00360000000000000000> projlbl</A></H1>
<P>
   projlbl - Returns a descriptive label for the projection
<P>
<H2><A NAME=SECTION00362000000000000000> Synopsis</A></H2>
<P>
 C:
<pre>
char* projlbl( pid )
   int  pid;
</pre>
Inputs
<pre>
     pid The projection ID.
</pre>
<P>
 FORTRAN:
<pre>
SUBROUTINE PROJLBL( PID, LBL )
   INTEGER*4     PID
   CHARACTER*60  LBL  (Return value)
</pre>
Inputs
<pre>
     PID  The projection ID.
     LBL  The projection label.
</pre>
<P>
<H2><A NAME=SECTION00363000000000000000> Description</A></H2>
<P>
 The <tt>projlbl()</tt> function returns the name of the projection. In C the
 string is allocated by <tt>projlbl()</tt> and must be deallocated by the caller.
<P>
 The information is found in the <tt>.projections</tt> database file found in
 the <tt>$EMIDBDIR</tt> directory.
<P>
<H2><A NAME=SECTION00364000000000000000> Return value</A></H2>
<P>
 On success, the function returns the name of the projection. On
 failure, it returns the <tt>NULL</tt> pointer in C, and the empty string
 in FORTRAN.
<P>
<H2><A NAME=SECTION00365000000000000000> See Also</A></H2>
<P>
 <a href="node5.html#SECTION00320000000000000000"><em>init_proj()</em></a>
<P>
