<H1><A NAME=SECTION00370000000000000000> projparmlbl</A></H1>
<P>
   projparmlbl - Returns a descriptive label for the projection parameter
<P>
<H2><A NAME=SECTION00372000000000000000> Synopsis</A></H2>
<P>
 C:
<pre>
char* projparmlbl( pid, index )
   int  pid;
   int  index;
</pre>
<tt>  </tt>Inputs
<pre>
     pid    The projection ID.
     index  The parameter index.
</PRE>
<P>
 FORTRAN:
<pre>
SUBROUTINE PROJPARMLBL( PID, INDEX, LBL )
   INTEGER*4     PID
   INTEGER*4     INDEX
   CHARACTER*20  LBL    (Return value)
</pre>
<tt>  </tt>Inputs
<pre>
     PID    The projection ID.
     INDEX  The projection parameter index.
     LBL    The projection label.
</pre>
<P>
<H2><A NAME=SECTION00373000000000000000> Description</A></H2>
<P>
 The <tt>projparmlbl()</tt> function returns the label of the given projection
 parameter. In C the string is allocated by <tt>projparmlbl()</tt> and must be
 deallocated by the caller.
<P>
 The information is found in the <tt>.projections</tt> database file found in
 the <tt>$EMIDBDIR</tt> directory.
<P>
<H2><A NAME=SECTION00374000000000000000> Return value</A></H2>
<P>
 On success, the function returns the name of the projection parameter. On
 failure, it returns the <tt>NULL</tt> pointer in C, and the empty string
 in FORTRAN.
<P>
<H2><A NAME=SECTION00375000000000000000> See Also</A></H2>
<P>
 <em><a href="node5.html#SECTION00320000000000000000">init_proj()</a></em>
<P>
