<html> <head>
<title>Example 1</title>
</head>

<body>
<h1>Example 1</h1>

In this example, the imageclass variable <tt>ic</tt> is created with default
values (i.e. no arguments in the definition). Using the first program argument
<tt>argv[1]</tt> as a filename, the image file is opened with <tt>iopen()</tt>.
<p>
If the file exists, and is a valid image file, the error flag is not set, and
<tt>ok()</tt> returns true. Two of the HEADFORM record values are retrieved with
the function <tt>Size()</tt> and written to standard output.
<p>
On the other hand, if <tt>ok()</tt> returns false, an error message is retrieved
with the help of <tt>errormsg()</tt>, and the text is sent to standard error.
<p>
<pre>
#include &lt;cimage.h&gt;
#include &lt;iostream.h&gt;

int main (int argv, const char* argv[])
{
  imageclass  ic;

  // Open the image
  ic.iopen(argv[1]);

  // Check the error status
  if (ic.ok()) {
    cout &lt;&lt; "# of lines: " &lt;&lt; ic.Size().l &lt;&lt; " ";
    cout &lt;&lt; "# of samples: " &lt;&lt; ic.Size().s &lt;&lt; endl;
  }
  else {
    // Error occured
    cerr &lt;&lt; "ERROR: " &lt;&lt; ic.errormsg(argv[1]) &lt;&lt; endl;
    return -1;
  }

  // Everything went ok
  return 0;
}
</pre>
<p>

<hr>
<address><a href="/DCRS/staff/njb.html">Niels Bagger</a>  <a href="mailto:njb@emi.dtu.dk">&lt;njb@emi.dtu.dk&gt;</a></address>
