<BODY BACKGROUND="paper1.gif">

<H1>NIRS CAMPAIGNS</H1>

<P>People often ask us, what exactly is NIRS' role, what do you do?</P>

<P>Besides serving as the national information and networking center for
grassroots anti-nuclear/environmental groups (which means about 200 phone
calls daily, dozens of faxes and e-mails, and a lot of mail to boot), NIRS
also initiates campaigns to address specific issues.</P>

<P>Current campaigns include:</P>

<UL>
<LI><B><A HREF="dtwsam.htm">Don't Waste America.</A></B> Our largest campaign:
this focuses on unnecessary and unsafe radioactive waste dumping and transportation.
Encompassed in it are our efforts against &quot;interim&quot; radioactive
waste storage and against new radioactive waste dumps such as Ward Valley,
CA and Sierra Blanca, TX. </LI>

<LI><B><A HREF="/moxtritium/moxtrit.htm">Military-Industrial-Utility Complex.</A></B>
This is a new campaign to stop the use of Mixed-Oxide (or plutonium-based)
fuel in commercial reactors as well as the production of tritium for nuclear
weapons in commercial reactors. </LI>

<LI><B><A HREF="/reactorproject/reacproj.htm">Reactor Watchdog Project.</A></B>
The recent emphasis of this campaign has been to close the dangerous Haddam
Neck and Oyster Creek reactors. This project is also responsible for our
work on Thermo-Lag, reactor aging, and more. Look for some more bombshells
on fire protection issues in coming months. </LI>

<LI><B><A HREF="/utilityrestructuring/nirsderg.htm">Utility Restructuring.</A></B>
This new campaign is our effort to bring nuclear sanity to the utility
deregulation process and to help ensure that restructuring does not reduce
safety margins. During 1997, look for a major report on these issues, and
how grassroots activists can effectively address &quot;stranded costs,&quot;
reduced maintenance, power production over safety, and more. </LI>

<LI><B><A HREF="/easternnis/eastnis.htm">Eastern Europe/Newly Independent
States.</A></B> This is another new campaign. Basically, we are bringing
the same level of services we provide to U.S. grassroots activists to the
East--specifically to local activists fighting the most dangerous and entrenched
nuclear community of all: that found in Eastern Europe and the Newly Independent
States. Not surprisingly, the enemies are often the same: Westinghouse,
GE, ABB, Siemens, and so on. </LI>

<LI><A HREF="../../pepcobge/pepbge.htm">Pepco/BG&amp;E merger.</A> For
local DC area activists, NIRS is working to stop the proposed merger of
Pepco and Baltimore Gas &amp; Electric. Rather than preparing to offer
lower electricity prices in response to competition, these utilities want
to merge to avoid competition. And Pepco ratepayers would get stuck with
all the costs associated with BG&amp;E's Calvert Cliffs reactors! It's
a bad deal all around. </LI>
</UL>

<P>Contributions to specific campaigns are always welcome, as are volunteer
help, community organizing and outreach, production of fact sheets and
other materials, occasional backrubs, and whatever other services and encouragement
you can donate or provide....</P>

<P><A HREF="nhome.htm">nhome.htm</A> <A HREF="nhome.htm"><IMG SRC="nirslog2.gif" HEIGHT=58 WIDTH=130></A></P>

</BODY>
