<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE>links</TITLE>
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0Gold (Win95; I) [Netscape]">
   <META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Preferred Customer">
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFBF0">

<H3>Linkages</H3>

<P>1. <A HREF="linkus.htm">National and grassroots organizations (U.S.)
working for a sustainable future</A></P>

<P>2.<A HREF="linkintl.htm"> International environmental/safe energy movement</A></P>

<P>3. <A HREF="linksus.htm">Sustainable energy-related sites</A></P>

<P>4. <A HREF="linkpeac.htm">Other nuclear-related sites</A></P>

<P>5. <A HREF="linkgov.htm">U.S. government sites</A></P>

<P>6. <A HREF="linkoth.htm">Other sites of interest</A></P>

<H3>Link to U.S. organizations working for a sustainable future. </H3>

<P><A HREF="http://www.citizen.org/CMEP/">Public Citizen's Critical Mass
Energy Project</A> Alerts, fact sheets, and lots of info. </P>

<P><A HREF="http://www.greenpeace.org">Greenpeace</A> The world's largest
and most important enivronmental organization. Alerts, articles, audio--it's
all here; one of the best websites of any kind anywhere. </P>

<P><A HREF="http://www.ucsusa.org">Union of Concerned Scientists</A> Info
on renewable energy, sustainable development, and more, from a scientific
perspective.</P>

<P><A HREF="http://www.essential.org/orgs/FOE/FOE.html">Friends of the
Earth</A> Varied environmental info, including the text of the Green Scissors
report--ways the U.S. can stop wasting taxpayer dollars on activites that
harm the environment.</P>

<P><A HREF="http://www.ratical.com/radiation/CNR/">Committee for Nuclear
Responsibility</A>. Actually, this site is run by the RatHaus, but it contains
the pioneering and essential work on radiation hazards conducted by Dr.
John Gofman. New pieces are added regularly.</P>

<P><A HREF="http://www.ieer.org">Institute for Energy and Environmental
Research.</A> Expert analysis and research on nuclear-related issues. And
don't miss a visit with Dr. Egghead!</P>

<P><A HREF="http://ecologia.nier.org">Ecologia</A> Especially interested
in Eastern European, former USSR issues. </P>

<P><A HREF="http://www.2020vision.org">20/20 Vision </A>Citizen activism.</P>

<P><A HREF="http://www.igc.apc.org">IGC networks</A> Includes EcoNet, PeaceNet,
and more. Very comprehensive. </P>

<P><A HREF="http://www.envirolink.org/orgs/wardvalley">BAN Waste Ward Valley
home page</A>. Info on the proposed Ward Valley, California radioactive
waste dump, and how to stop it!</P>

<P><A HREF="http://www.sfo.com/~rherried/welcome.htm">Abalone Alliance
website</A>. Lots of info on Ward Valley, plus renewable energy, nuclear
history and more.</P>

<P><A HREF="http://home.acadia.net/cbm/">Center for Biological Monitoring</A>
Interested in radiological monitoring and related issues, especially in
Maine.</P>

<P><A HREF="http://www.igc.apc.org/RWMA/">Radioactive Waste Management
Associates</A>. Technically a company, not a grassroots group (tho it consults
to many grassroots groups), but home to some of the most expert info on
radioactive waste anywhere.</P>

<P><A HREF="http://oraibi.alphadc.com/necona">National Environmental Coalition
of Native Americans</A>. Information on radioactive waste and transportation,
especially as it affects Native American communities. Lots of links to
Native American groups.</P>

<P><A HREF="http://www.igc.apc.org/redwood/">Redwood Alliance.</A> Lots
of info on nuclear issues and renewable energy from this veteran Northern
California organization.</P>

<P><A HREF="http://www.earthisland.org">Earth Island Institute.</A> This
organization is involved in just about everything, and so is their web
site. Read Earth Island Journal or check out the progress of any number
of environmental campaigns. </P>

<P><A HREF="http://www.downwinders.org">Downwinders.</A> Organization of
people who lived downwind of Nevada Test Site during above-ground nuclear
testing years. Site has info on nuclear and radiation issues.</P>

<P><A HREF="http://essential.org/freetheplanet/home.html">Free the Planet.</A>
Campus-based movement to &quot;confront corporate lawlessness and government
inaction through local, regional, and national action. Working on &quot;Webstock&quot;--web-based
activism November 1-4, 1996. FTP has been prominent in working to stop
the &quot;Mobile Chernobyl Act.&quot;</P>

<P>
<HR></P>

<H3>Link to the international environmental/safe energy movement </H3>

<P><BR>
International <A HREF="http://www.t0.or.at/~C+10">No More Chernobyls web
site</A>. Information on the worldwide campaign around the Chernobyl 10th
anniversary, April 1996.</P>

<P><A HREF="http://antenna.nl/~wise">WISE</A> World Information Service
on Energy. Site includes regularly updated news from around the world and
a growing section on uranium--mining, processing, etc. </P>

<P><A HREF="http://www.io.org/~ee/folkkampanjen">Folkkampanjen,</A> the
Swedish anti-nuclear movement. </P>

<P><A HREF="http://guhy.ee.ntit.tw/~lanyu/english.html">Campaign against
nuclear dumping on Orchid Island, Taiwan</A> </P>

<P><A HREF="http://cci.glasnet.ru/KOI/SEU/ANTINUC/INDEX.HTM">Russian anti-nuclear
campaign</A> (Russian language only) </P>

<P><A HREF="http://www.t0.or.at/~global2000/">Global 2000</A>, information
on the Mochovce reactor and other European environmental issues. </P>

<P><A HREF="http://www.knooppunt.be/~fme/wae/waeidx.html">Europe anti-nuclear
walk.</A></P>

<P><A HREF="http://www.zetnet.co.uk/oigs/n-base">Northern European Nuclear
Information Group</A>. News and analysis primarily on the United Kingdom
civil nuclear industry.</P>

<P><A HREF="http://bufo.fns.uniba.sk/zmz/index.html">For Mother Earth Slovokia.</A>
Dedicated individuals fighting the Mochovce nuclear complex and a very
repressive government. Give them a hand here. Note: Slovokian phone lines
don't always work; if you don't get through the first time, try again.</P>

<P><A HREF="http://www.grida.no/ngo/bellona/ehome/index.htm">Bellona</A>.
Information on Norwegian safe energy issues, and radiation contamination
in Russia. Bellona has risked a lot (including arrests) to get this info.</P>

<P><A HREF="http://miya.ecn.fpu.ac.jp/monju-a2e.htm">Stop Monju Breeder
Campaign</A>. The Monju Breeder reactor recently suffered a severe accident
that will probably keep it shut down for some time. Join this group in
an effort to keep it closed for good. They already have collected more
than 1,000,000 signatures on Monju shutdown petitions--you can add your
name at this site.</P>

<P><A HREF="http://www.deev.com/ccnr">Canadian Coalition for Nuclear Responsibility</A>.
Lots of info on plutonium, radioactive waste issues and CANDU reactors.</P>

<P>
<HR></P>

<H3>Link to sustainable energy-related sites</H3>

<P><A HREF="http://solstice.crest.org">Solstice</A> Just about everything
you wanted to know about energy efficiency and renewable energy. </P>

<P><A HREF="http://www.homepower.com">Home Power Magazine.</A> Small-scale
solar and other renewable energy design. If you ever wanted to learn how
to convert your home to solar power, this is the place. Lots of good links,
too.</P>

<P><A HREF="http://www.iclei.org/co2">Cities for Climate Protection Campaign.</A>
Some 150 cities across the world, from Little Rock to Leipzig, have joined
in the Cities for Climate Protection Campaign. These cities will be trying
to improve energy efficiency and reduce fossil fuel use. This site provides
info on what cities are doing, how to get financing for improvements, and
a lot more.</P>

<P><A HREF="http://www/igc.apc.org/awea/">American Wind Energy Association.</A>
The trade organization of the U.S. wind energy industry. Lots of info on
windpower and the industry.</P>

<P>
<HR></P>

<H3>Link to other nuclear-related sites</H3>

<P><A HREF="http://www.nci.org/nci/">Nuclear Control Institute</A>, information
on nuclear proliferation </P>

<P><A HREF="http://www.fas.org/pub/gen/fas/">Federation of American Scientists</A>,
nuclear proliferation, government secrecy and more </P>

<P><A HREF="http://www.prop1.org">Proposition One</A>, includes map and
remarkable database of all nuclear sites in U.S., prepared by Grey Panthers
&amp; Hiroshima/Nagasaki Peace Committee of DC, as well as other nuclear-related
sites.</P>

<P><A HREF="http://www.halcyon.com/tomcgap/welcome.html">Government Accountability
Project.</A> GAP provides legal and other professional assistance to nuclear
and governmental whistleblowers, especially at DOE nuclear weapons plant
sites.</P>

<P><A HREF="http://www.web.apc.org/~pgs/">Physicians for Global Survival,
Canada</A>, Info on World Court Project, on Abolition 2000 and more.</P>

<P><A HREF="HTTP://NEOG.COM/atomic/">Bulletin of Atomic Scientists</A>
Must reading on the Atomic Age from the founders of the Doomsday Clock.</P>

<P><A HREF="http://www.brook.edu/fp/projects/nucwcost/weapons/weapons.htm">U.S.
Nuclear Weapons Cost Study Project</A> Info on this major study on the
true costs of 50 years of nuclear weapons construction, lists of weapons
sites, and more.</P>

<P><A HREF="http://www.discovery.com/DCO/doc/1012/world/science/chernobyl/chernobylopener.html">Discovery
Channel Online: Chernobyl + 10 site</A>. Excellent and well-designed series
on the Chernobyl disaster and its consequences. Note: graphics-heavy (and
very impressive); best with fast modems.</P>

<P><A HREF="http://www.cnduk.org/cnd">Campaign for Nuclear Disarmament.</A>
Venerable British organization working for a nuclear-free Great Britain.</P>

<P>
<HR></P>

<H3>Link to government sources of information.</H3>

<P><A HREF="http://www.nrc.gov">Nuclear Regulatory Commission</A> Info
on commercial nuclear power, radioactive waste. </P>

<P><A HREF="http://www.doe.gov">Department of Energy</A> Includes info
on radiation experiments, renewable energy, and more. </P>

<P><A HREF="http://www.sustainable.doe.gov">DOE's Center for Excellence
for Sustainable Development</A>; ways to reduce energy operating costs
for homes and businesses, create jobs, and use sustainable energy resources.</P>

<P>DOE's <A HREF="http://www.eia.doe.gov">Energy Information Administration</A>
Statistics and energy info. </P>

<P><A HREF="http://thomas.loc.gov">US Congress</A> Information on legislation,
Congressional Record, e-mail addresses to Congress, and more. </P>

<P><A HREF="http:www.epa.gov">Environmental Protection Agency</A>. Info
on EPA's Green Lights and Energy Star energy efficiency programs, as well
as the whole gamut of environmental issues.</P>

<P><A HREF="http://www.eren.doe.gov">Energy Efficiency and Renewable Energy
Network</A>. DOE's computer gateway to info on sustainable energy information.</P>

<P>
<HR></P>

<H3>Other web sites of interest.</H3>

<P><A HREF="http://www.publicshelter.com">Public Shelter</A> Wild and very
fun page from the producer of <I>Atomic Cafe.</I></P>

<P><A HREF="http://www.essential.org/monitor/monitor.html">Multinational
Monitor.</A> Database on activities (including nuclear-related) of multinational
corporations; back issues of Multinational Monitor magazine.</P>

<P><A HREF="http://www.fair.org/fair/">Fairness and Accuracy in Reporting.</A>
FAIR reports on media bias; tries to set the record straight. Reports on
media coverage of nuclear issues.</P>

<P><A HREF="http://www.goodmoney.com">Good Money</A>. News and information
about socially responsible (non-nuclear) investing.</P>

<P><A HREF="http://www.webactive.com">WebActive.</A> Clearinghouse for
progressive web sites. Also home of RealAudio!</P>

<P><A HREF="http://www.macronet.org">Macrocosm. </A>Another progressive
web site clearinghouse. Also has photos, schedule and info on Nuclear Waste
Cask tour.</P>

<P><A HREF="http://www.interactivism.com">InterActivism. </A>Get active!
Grassroots organizing on the Web. From this site you can send faxes, e-mail,
etc. on a number of different issues. </P>

<P><A HREF="http://www.emagazine.com">E/The Environmental Magazine.</A>
E is a slick but non-profit magazine covering environmental issues and
the environmental movement. This site contains the full contents of the
current issue, back issues, and more. We like E a lot.</P>

<P><A HREF="http://home.earthlink.net/~envirovideo/">EnviroVideo</A> produces
a lot of videos--on nuclear power, nukes in space and many other environmental
issues. They're of high quality and are shown frequently on cable TV. They're
also great for local organizing meetings, discussion sessions, etc. You
can get descriptions and the full list of available videos here.</P>

<P><A HREF="http://www.ora.com">O'Reilly &amp; Associates.</A> NIRS uses
WebSite 1.1 web server software, WebBoard conferencing software, and PolyForm
form-creation software to run our website. All of these products are from
O'Reilly &amp; Associates. We don't normally plug commercial firms, but
we're making an exception in this case. </P>

<P><A HREF="nhome.htm"><IMG SRC="nirslog2.gif" HEIGHT=58 WIDTH=130></A></P>

</BODY>
