<HEAD>
<TITLE>Chernobyl +10 basic sheet</TITLE> 
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Preferred Customer">
</HEAD>
<BODY><H1>Chernobyl + 10</H1> 
<P><IMG SRC="nomore2.gif"></P>
<HR> 
<H2>April 1996--A Month of Remembrance, Reflection, Assistance and Action</H2> 
<P>On April 26, 1986, the Chernobyl nuclear reactor exploded, spewing deadly
radiation across the Ukraine, Belarus, eastern and western Europe, and
ultimately the entire globe. The full dimensions of the Chernobyl nuclear
disaster--the worst single accident of the industrial age--are unknown to this
day. But nearly ten years later, the suffering continues. And the possibility of
another nuclear accident remains.
</P>
<P>Consider these facts (taken from a November 28, 1995 Reuters article):
</P>
<P>At least nine million people in the Ukraine, Belarus and Russia have been
affected by the Chernobyl disaster; several million still live in contaminated
zones.
</P>
<P>The contaminated area of Ukraine and Belarus is about 61,780 square
miles--the size of England, Wales and Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>Birth rates in Belarus have fallen 50 percent.
</P>
<P>Thyroid cancer, particularly among children, is up 285 percent in Belarus.
</P>
<P>About 7,000 people in Russia alone are believed to have died from the
accident (The Ukraine Ministry of Health estimates as many as 125,000 deaths in
the Ukraine).
</P>
<P>Belarus spends 20 percent of its annual budget coping with Chernobyl's
aftermath; Ukraine, four percent; Russia, one percent.
</P>
<P>The United Nations trust fund for Chernobyl victims is &quot;virtually
empty.&quot; The World Health Organization estimates it alone needs $200 million
over the next 20 years, but only a fraction of that is likely to be made
available.
</P>
<P>During April 1996, citizens across the world will remember the Chernobyl
accident, and will take action to expose its full impact, help relieve the
suffering, and hasten the end of the nuclear age.
</P>
<P>U.S. activities are being coordinated by Nuclear Information and Resource
Service (NIRS) and Greenpeace.  </P>
<HR> 
<P><IMG SRC="new.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="worldend.htm">Chernobyl Diary
1996: This is How the World Ends,</A> article from April 1996 <I>Nuclear
Monitor</I>, on the Kiev conference and a trip to Chernobyl, Pripyat and the
Dead Zone.</P>
<P><IMG SRC="new.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="confstat.htm">Statement of
International Lessons of Chernobyl conference</A> in Kiev, April 20-22, 1996.</P>
<P><A HREF="http://www.discovery.com">The Discovery Channel website</A> is
running a special section on Chernobyl through May 15, 1996. Titled &quot;The
Apocalpyse is Now,&quot; it's beautifully done. Don't miss it.</P>
<P><A HREF="chereso.htm">Resources on Chernobyl and its aftermath</A>  
</P>
<P><A HREF="youcando.htm">What you can do</A> to help the victims of Chernobyl</P>
<P><A HREF="cherlist.htm">Activities and local group contacts in U.S. for
Chernobyl + 10</A> Updated regularly! 
</P>
<P><A HREF="relsupp.htm">Chernobyl relief supplies: what is needed---and why</A>
Please help.</P>
<P><A HREF="mobchern.htm">Stop a Mobile Chernobyl!</A> Key Senate vote coming
up soon, perhaps by Memorial Day.</P>
<P><A HREF="cherfact.htm">Chernobyl fact sheet</A></P>
<P><A HREF="nhome.htm"><IMG SRC="nomore3.gif"></A></P>
<P><A HREF="nhome.htm">return to NIRS home page</A> 
</P></BODY> 
