<HEAD>
   <TITLE>Utility Deregulation</TITLE>
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0Gold (Win95; I) [Netscape]">
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="paper1.gif">

<H2>NIRS and Utility Deregulation</H2>

<P>1997 and 1998 will see one of the messiest, knock-down, drag-out fights
ever experienced in the United States Congress. That battle will be played
out on a backdrop of similar struggles in dozens of state legislatures.
The issue is huge and the bedfellows are likely to be very strange indeed.
It's utility deregulation, and if you thought deregulating a few phone
companies was rough, wait til Congress and the States take on a couple
hundred electric utilities!</P>

<P>NIRS' primary interests in utility deregulation issues are to ensure
that deregulation does not increase nuclear risks, that uneconomic nuclear
reactors are closed rather than artificially allowed to continue operating,
and that ratepayers are not stuck paying for continuing nuclear mistakes.
We also believe that deregulation should help bring about a new reliance
on renewable sources of energy--although closing unsafe and uneconomic
nuclear reactors remains the best way to encourage utilities to go renewable.
</P>

<P>There already are many fully-indexed and searchable files available
on deregulation issues in the Economics section of <A HREF="/htdocs/nirsbbs.htm">NIRSNET
on the Web</A>. Here you'll find the highlights, as well as NIRS' positions
on these issues. And don't forget to use <A HREF="http://www.nirs.org/webboard/$webb.exe">NIRS'
WebBoard</A> if you have questions, comments, or want to give your own
opinion on deregulation.</P>

<P><A HREF="../../nirscamp.htm"><IMG SRC="nirslog2.gif"  ALIGN=BOTTOM></A></P>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
<DOC>
