<HEAD>
   <TITLE>radiation</TITLE>
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0Gold (Win95; I) [Netscape]">
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#FFF0F0" BGCOLOR="#008080" LINK="#FFFF00" ALINK="#0000FF">

<P><IMG SRC="nirsweb.gif" HEIGHT=60 WIDTH=300 ALIGN=BOTTOM> 
<HR></P>

<H1>Radiation</H1>

<P>This area includes files on radiation, its health effects, and government
standards for &quot;acceptable risk&quot; from radiation. We hope this
area will grow rapidly, and will include not only government documents,
but also the work of scientists from around the world. We welcome your
submissions to this area (as we do for all areas of NIRSNET on the Web).
Please send in .txt or .html format to <A HREF="mailto:nirsnet@igc.apc.org">nirsnet@igc.apc.org</A>.</P>

<P>Many people are surprised to learn that federal standards regulating
radiation exposure are much laxer than those regulating other hazardous
materials. For example, the Environmental Protection Agency, Food and Drug
Administration and other regulatory bodies routinely require that public
exposure to hazardous materials lead to a 1 in 10,000 to 1 in 1,000,000
lifetime chance of death (levels themselves routinely criticized as too
weak). Federal radiation standards promulgated by the Nuclear Regulatory
Commission, however, are the equivalent of a 1 in 285 lifetime chance of
fatal cancer. This means that of people who receive the full legal maximum
dose allowed by the NRC, 1 in 285 are predicted to die as a direct result
of receiving this dose.</P>

<P>Because radiation is as the heart of the entire nuclear controversy,
every other file area on NIRSNET on the Web is related to this issue. Please
feel free to look around. This area is indexed, <A HREF="radindex.htm">click
here to access </A>the index.</P>

<P><FONT SIZE=+3>Recent Highlights</FONT></P>

<P>NRC releases <A HREF="Sy96172.txt">final air emissions standards for
non-power reactors</A>. NIRS had sued the agency over its similar standards
for reactors, but lost in federal court. Secy paper dated August 5, 1996,
but released to public November 1996.</P>

<P>
<HR></P>

<P><A HREF="nirsbbs.htm"><IMG SRC="nirslog2.gif" HEIGHT=58 WIDTH=130></A></P>

