   <TITLE>Toolbox: general</TITLE>
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0Gold (Win95; I) [Netscape]">
   <META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Preferred Customer">
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#DBDB70" LINK="#6F4242" BACKGROUND="1q.jpg">

<H1>THE NIRS TOOLBOX</H1>

<P>
<HR></P>

<H4>Human history becomes more and more a race between education and catastrophe.
~ H.G. Wells</H4>

<P>A ~ indicates that this Toolbox entry contains information relevant
to the health effects of low-dose and/or long-term exposure to radiation.
</P>

<H4>There are two ways to order materials from the NIRS&nbsp;toolbox:</H4>

<H4>1. The fast way: fax your order to NIRS at 202-462-2183. Include your
Visa, Mastercard or Discover Card number, expiration date, and signature.
</H4>

<H4>2. The slow way: mail to NIRS at 1424 16th Street NW, #404, Washington
DC 20036. Please make your check payable to NIRS. Thank you.</H4>

<H4>Unfortunately, due to problems collecting payment on invoiced orders,
all orders must now be prepaid (we're not a collection agency after all,
we're an environmental group...)</H4>

<P>
<HR></P>

<H2>GENERAL</H2>

<P><B>G-1000 </B>$.40 4pp </P>

<P>1994 Map of Commercial Nuclear Power Plants </P>

<P>NEI Detailed maps, by section of nation. Updated annually. </P>

<P><B>G-1001</B> $1.60 16pp 1993 </P>

<P>World List of Nuclear Power Plants </P>

<P>Nuclear News </P>

<P>List of plants on-line, under construction, and on order. </P>

<P><B>G-1002</B> $3.90 39 pp updated annually </P>

<P>&quot;Nuclear Power Plants in the United Stabs&quot; and &quot;Historical
Profile of US Nuclear Power Development&quot; NEI/USCEA </P>

<P>List of nuclear plants, detailing ownership, status, location, type,
size and year of commercial operation. Summarizes cancellations and contains
maps of reactor sites. The second publication contains information on plant
orders placed, construction permits, cancellations and more. </P>

<P><B>G-1003</B> $8.70 87pp 5/88 &quot;How Practical is Nuclear Power:
Now and for the Future&quot; Association of Media Accuracy Extensive report
that concisely covers many aspects of nuclear power in a pro/con format.
A great source of information. </P>

<P><B>G-1004 </B>$2.90 29pp 9/91 </P>

<P>&quot;You Don't Have to be a Scientist...&quot; </P>

<P>Peter Montague, ERF </P>

<P>This packet helps make big problems understandable by using comparisons
to help readers understand the meaning of numbers. It includes some very
useful conversion factors. Also included is a fact sheet on the precautionary
principle. </P>

<P><B>G-1005 </B>$1.60 1 pp 1994 </P>

<P>&quot;Nuclear Power: Three Decades of Public Opinion&quot; </P>

<P>Eugene Rosa and Riley Dunlap, Public Opinion Quarterly </P>

<P>This poll concludes that while approval of nuclear power declines sharply
after accidents, there is usually a &quot;rebound&quot; effect. But the
study further concludes that as a general trend, public support of nuclear
power is falling lower and lower over time. </P>

<P><B>G-1006 </B>$2.30 23pp 12/85 </P>

<P>&quot;Nuclear Power in America&quot; </P>

<P>William Lanouette, The Wilson Quarterly </P>

<P>A history of the early days of nuclear power, dominated by cost overruns,
accidents, and over-projection of electrical demand. </P>

<P><B>G-1007 </B>$5.00 1987, update 1993 </P>

<P>Teachers' Resource Guide, NIRS </P>

<P>The guide provides secondary school teachers with a list of many resource
media on topics from nuclear weapons to nuclear energy and the environment.
Distributors and publishers for these media are also listed. </P>

<P><B>G-1009</B> $.40 4pp no date </P>

<P>&quot;Nuclear Power Pollutes&quot; </P>

<P>Concerned Citizens of Manitoba Campaign for Nuclear Phaseout </P>

<P>This fact sheet takes the reader through a nuclear life cycle-from uranium
mining to reprocessing. It contends that nuclear power is dirty from start
to finish and highlights the health effects of radioactivity. </P>

<P><B>G-1010</B> $11.30 113 pp 10/52 </P>

<P>Reactor Science and Technology: A Journal Devoted to the Science and
Technology of Nuclear Reactors and to Related... Atomic Energy Commission
</P>

<P>Released through the National Technical Information Service, this is
the definitive documentation on the original military connection to the
&quot;Peaceful Atom.&quot; Position papers from Monsanto Chemical Company,
Union Electric, and more, support and develop the &quot;Plutonium-Power
Feasibility Study,&quot; showing the intent to use nuclear technology for
military and civilian purposes simultaneously. Certain portions are illegible
because of poor quality of original AEC copy. </P>

<P><B>G-1011</B> $2.20 22pp 10/90 </P>

<P>Nuclear Words and Terms </P>

<P>Miles Goldstick </P>

<P>A list of words and terms, types of nuclear reactors, resources etc.
A good general reference guide for those becoming involved with nuclear
issues and for those already involved but who want more technical expertise.
</P>

<P><B>G-1012 </B>$.10 1pp 1995 </P>

<P>Map of Reactors and SNF Storage Sites </P>

<P>A United States map showing the location of spent nuclear fuel storage.
</P>

<P><B>G-2000</B> $2.30 23pp 7/89-9/89 </P>

<P>&quot;What We Must Do: A Grassroots Offensive Against Toxics in the
'90's&quot; </P>

<P>Peter Montague, Director ERF, The Workbook </P>

<P>Written as a history of the environmental movement, this article is
fairly comprehensive and covers all toxic issues, not just nuclear pollution,
although strategies for fighting dumps and other toxic pollution are often
the same. It also provides tips at the national and local level for stopping
up the &quot;industrial toilet&quot;. </P>

<P><B>G-2001 </B>$.10 1p 9/5/93 </P>

<P>&quot;Activists are Misunderstood as Grumpy Zealots&quot; </P>

<P>Jason Salzman The Sunday Camera </P>

<P>A wonderfully inspiring article for any activist! </P>

<P><B>G-4000</B> $1.50 15pp 1/92 </P>

<P>Communicating with the Public About Radiation </P>

<P>USCEA (now part of NEI) Public Opinion Research </P>

<P>Using a poll conducted by the Gallup Organization, the USCEA attempts
to show how uneducated the public is on nuclear issues. While the numbers
might be right, the USCEA's interpretation of the numbers is colored by
their interest in preserving the nuclear power industry. </P>

<P><B>G-4001</B> $.40 4pp 1/89-2/89 </P>

<P>&quot;The Resurgence of Nuclear Power in America&quot; </P>

<P>Michael Mariotte, NIRS, Multinational Monitor </P>

<P>The author discusses the nuclear industry's attempt to rejuvenate itself
using the greenhouse remediation argument. The author explains why this
argument is not sound and also discusses the travesty of advanced reactors,
one-step licensing and deregulation of nuclear waste. </P>

<P><B>G-4002</B> $.40 4pp 12/90 </P>

<P>&quot;Nukespeak&quot; Nathaniel Mead and Ray Lee, The Progressive</P>

<P>Presents an introductory critique of the industry's claims that nuclear
power is clean and necessary. </P>

<P><A HREF="toolhome.htm"><IMG SRC="nirslog2.gif" HEIGHT=58 WIDTH=130></A></P>

