<H1>THE NIRS TOOLBOX</H1>

<P>
<HR></P>

<H4>Human history becomes more and more a race between education and catastrophe.
~ H.G. Wells</H4>

<P>A ~ indicates that this Toolbox entry contains information relevant
to the health effects of low-dose and/or long-term exposure to radiation.
</P>

<H4>There are two ways to order materials from the NIRS&nbsp;toolbox:</H4>

<H4>1. The fast way: fax your order to NIRS at 202-462-2183. Include your
Visa, Mastercard or Discover Card number, expiration date, and signature.
</H4>

<H4>2. The slow way: mail to NIRS at 1424 16th Street NW, #404, Washington
DC 20036. Please make your check payable to NIRS. Thank you.</H4>

<P>Unfortunately, due to problems collecting payment on invoiced orders,
all orders must now be prepaid (we're not a collection agency after all,
we're an environmental group...).</P>

<P>
<HR></P>

<H2>ALTERNATIVE ENERGY</H2>

<H3><B>General</B></H3>

<P><B>ALT-1000</B> $10.00 Periodically updated </P>

<P>Renewable/Sustainable Energy Packet </P>

<P>NIRS </P>

<P>Compilation of articles, reports, technical documents on renewable energy
sources. Included is &quot;Powering the Midwest&quot; by UCS. </P>

<P><B>ALT-1001</B> $.60 6pp not dated </P>

<P>Nuclear Power: No Alternative to Oil Imports </P>

<P>Critical Mass Energy Project </P>

<P>Inefficiency, cost overruns, waste disposal and inability to substitute
for oil used in cars are among the reasons why nuclear power is not an
option for replacing imported oil as an energy source. </P>

<P><B>ALT-1002</B> $2.70 27pp 3/95 </P>

<P>Energy and Power, Alternative Energy and Its Implications, WISE, Special
Edition </P>

<P>A very well-done, informative and thought-provoking work for anyone
wondering what's taking so long for use of alternative energies to become
widespread. It addresses many social, political as well as economic issues.
</P>

<P><B>ALT-1003</B> $.30 3pp 3/7/94 </P>

<P>&quot;Nuclear Fade-out: Last Stand on Prairie Island&quot; </P>

<P>Harvey Wasserman, The Nation </P>

<P>The author talks about the nuclear power plant and the opposition it
has sparked from Native Americans, farmers, local politicians and the Minnesota
state government. </P>

<P><B>ALT-1004</B> $.40 4 pp not dated </P>

<P>Nine Different Electricity Sources: Some Environmental Consequences
This fact sheet briefly reviews basic laws of physics and energy and compares
different energy types and resulting environmental consequences. </P>

<P><B>ALT-1005</B> $.70 7pp 1/91-2/91 </P>

<P>&quot;Conquering US. Oil Dependence&quot; </P>

<P>Christopher Flavin </P>

<P>The Persian Gulf War was labeled by many people as a war for oil. Here
is why the World Watch Institute believes this is at best only part of
the issue. This article gives an in-depth look at the US. growing dependence
on oil in the '80s. It also poses some alternatives to imported oil. </P>

<P><B>ALT-1006</B> $.50 5pp Fall 1990 </P>

<P>&quot;Bridging the Gap to New Energy Era&quot; </P>

<P>John Gibbons, et. al., FARPP </P>

<P>This article describes the &quot;bridge fuels&quot; the fuels we should
look at to get us from fossil fuels to a solar based fuel system. Energy
efficiency and methane (natural gas) as better for the environment than
oil and coal. These fuels and uses are described in some detail. The article
does take a pro-nuclear stand when looking at future energy supplies-but
the main focus of the article is on bridge fuels. </P>

<P><B>ALT-1007</B> $.40 4pp 1990 </P>

<P>&quot;Renewable Power: Confessions of a Proactive Utility&quot; </P>

<P>Gerald Braun, PG&amp;E </P>

<P>Despite their operation of two nuclear power plants, Pacific Gas and
Electric is a leader in building and supporting renewable energy facilities.
They started using renewables as a demand side management technique, but
also use it for generation. This statement by Braun tells why. </P>

<P><B>ALT-1008</B> $3.80 38pp 4/92 </P>

<P>&quot;Renewable Energy: Future Or Fiction&quot; </P>

<P>Greenberg-Lake Analysis Group </P>

<P>Executive summary of a poll of blue and white collar men and women on
energy and the environment. The survey concludes that many people support
use of renewable energy sources and view current oil and utility companies
as impeding implementation of energy efficiency and renewables. </P>

<P><B>ALT-1009</B> $.30 3pp 3/92-4/92 </P>

<P>&quot;Energy Policies for a Clean and Prosperous Future&quot; </P>

<P>Michael Brower and Alden Meyer, Solar Today </P>

<P>An overview of policies to move the US towards a sustainable energy
future. </P>

<P><B>ALT-1010</B> $.60 6pp 6/29/86 </P>

<P>&quot;The Soft Path of Amory Lovins&quot; </P>

<P>Brad Lemley, Washington Post Magazine </P>

<P>Profile of the nation's leading &quot;soft&quot; energy advocate and
one of the most articulate critics of nuclear power. </P>

<P><B>ALT-1011</B> $3.00 112 pp </P>

<P>Sustainable Energy Budget, 1995 and A Sustainable Energy Blueprint </P>

<P>These two publications are a collaborative effort by activist groups
detailing a feasible sustainable energy budget for 1995 and outlining steps
toward sustainable energy use. </P>

<P><B>ALT-1012</B> $2.20 22pp 10/23/90-10125/90 </P>

<P>German/American Conference on Environmental Externalities </P>

<P>Richard L. Ottinger, Pace University </P>

<P>Entertains the idea of &quot;pricing&quot; the environment as incentive
for industry to pollute less. Since this cost would be reflected in the
consumer goods price, many think that industry would attempt to cut pollution
output to stay competitive. </P>

<P>
<HR></P>

<H3><B>Solar Power</B></H3>

<P><B>ALT-2000</B> $.70 7pp 4/92 </P>

<P>&quot;Solar Eclipsed&quot; </P>

<P>Julie Gozan, Multinational Monitor </P>

<P>This article traces the events which led to the bankruptcy of LUZ International,
a solar company which generated 95% of the world's solar electricity. </P>

<P><B>ALT-2001</B> $.30 3pp 3/92-4/92 </P>

<P>&quot;Overcoming Institutional Barriers&quot; </P>

<P>John Ryan, Richard Sellers, Solar Today </P>

<P>The solar industry explores ways to overcome institutional barriers
to its technology in two arenas. The first is military/DOD implementation
of solar and the second is the Federal Buildings program. Both institutions
have been introduced to the benefits of solar, but neither one has taken
full advantage. </P>

<P><B>ALT-2002</B> $.90 9pp 4/9/91 </P>

<P>Testimony by Scott Sklar of Solar Energy Industries Association House
Ways &amp; Means Committee </P>

<P>This testimony uses recent solar energy statistics to try to convince
the committee to continue tax credits. </P>

<P><B>ALT-2003</B> $.30 3pp 7/91 </P>

<P>&quot;New and Traditional Methods for Teaching Sun Mechanics&quot; </P>

<P>Norbert Lechner, Solar Today </P>

<P>Two tools for understanding the seasonal angles of the sun for building
designs incorporating solar energy systems. </P>

<P><B>ALT-2004</B> $.90 9pp 10/91 </P>

<P>&quot;Here Comes the Sun: Envisioning a Solar Future&quot; </P>

<P>Flavin and Lenssen, World Watch Magazine </P>

<P>A concise overview of solar, wind, geothermal, and hydrogen based energy
systems. </P>

<P><B>ALT-2005</B> $.50 5pp Spring 1986 </P>

<P>&quot;Small is Sensible: Richard Munson on the New Era of Electricity
Generation&quot; </P>

<P>RAIN Newsletter </P>

<P>Interview with founder of Solar Lobby on status and future prospects
of small-scale electrical generation. </P>

<P><B>ALT-2006</B> $.80 8pp 9/90 </P>

<P>&quot;Energy from the Sun&quot; </P>

<P>Weinberg and Williams, Scientific American </P>

<P>Various forms of solar energy, including wind and biomass, offer environmentally
benign ways to generate electricity and make fuels. Some technologies will
be cost competitive before the year 2000. This article gives an excellent
introduction to solar power. (Solar power includes wind and biomass since
the energy originally comes from the sun.) </P>

<P><B>ALT-2007</B> $.50 5pp not dated </P>

<P>&quot;Healthy Solar Buildings: A Natural Combination&quot; </P>

<P>Richard L. Crowther, FAIA, Solar Today </P>

<P>&quot;An architect ecologist and conservationist describes two of his
buildings that achieved the goals of environmental health within the context
of energy-efficient solar design.&quot; </P>

<P><B>ALT-2008</B> $.70 7pp 1/91-2/91 </P>

<P>&quot;Sunrise on Solar Power&quot; and &quot;Wind Power Today: Inexpensive
and Profitable&quot; </P>

<P>Harvey Wasserman, Harrowsmith </P>

<P>This article predicts that wind and solar will take the lead in energy
production because oil coal, and nuclear pollute. The author interviews
people with LUZ, then a leading solar power company and U.S. Windpower.
</P>

<P><B>ALT-2200</B> $.30 3pp 5/92-6/92 </P>

<P>&quot;Utility Interactive Residential PV: Lessons Learned&quot; </P>

<P>Russell and Kern, Solar Today </P>

<P>Analysis of three utility PV projects, including Gardner, MA, for residential
power. </P>

<P><B>ALT-2201</B> $.40 4pp 10/87 </P>

<P>&quot;Sizing Up Photovoltaic Systems&quot; </P>

<P>Ken Olsen, PV International </P>

<P>The five steps to design a PV system. </P>

<P><B>ALT-2202</B> $.40 4pp 8/91 </P>

<P>&quot;Innovative 100 KW Grid-Connected PV Installation&quot; </P>

<P>Nordmann, et al, Solar Today </P>

<P>Swiss Photovoltaic grid system incorporated into sound barriers on highways.
</P>

<P><B>ALT-2203</B> $.30 3pp 4/92-5/92 </P>

<P>&quot;Will the Sun Shine on Your Solar Modules All Winter?&quot; </P>

<P>Steve Willey, Home Power </P>

<P>Instructions on how to build your own solar device for PV panels. </P>

<P><B>ALT-2204</B> $.80 8pp 1/91-2/91 </P>

<P>&quot;Whatever Happened To Solar?&quot; </P>

<P>Louis Peck, Garbage Magazine </P>

<P>Highlights of New England Electric's power project supplying the grid
from photovoltaic units installed on residential and commercial buildings
in Gardner, Massachusetts. </P>

<P>
<HR></P>

<H3><B>Miscellaneous Sources</B></H3>

<P><B>ALT-3000</B> $.60 6pp 2/88 </P>

<P>&quot;Cogeneration Capacity: The Elusive Numbers&quot; </P>

<P>IRT </P>

<P>Looks at how energy, industry and utility groups perceive and predict
the impact of cogeneration in replacing traditional utility-based electricity.
</P>

<P><B>ALT-3500</B> $1.20 12pp 11/3/91 </P>

<P>Geothermal Energy </P>

<P>Los Alamos National Lab seeking to tap heat from earth's molten core
and radioactive decay by pumping water deep beneath the earth's surface
and harvesting steam. Articles from the New York Times, Discover Magazine,
and others discuss the progress and validity of the project. </P>

<P><B>ALT-4000</B> $.20 2pp 7/92-8/92 </P>

<P>&quot;Fuel Cells: A Clean Method of Storing Clean Energy&quot; </P>

<P>David Lapp, Powerline/Environmental Action </P>

<P>Fuel cell cost and ability are discussed as well as certain forces that
work against universal fuel cell use. </P>

<P><B>ALT-4001</B> $.20 2pp 3/1/92 </P>

<P>&quot;The Quest for Fuel Cell Commercialization&quot; </P>

<P>Leonard Greenberger, Public Utilities Fortnightly </P>

<P>The Electric Power Research Institute and American Public Power Association
allied to promote high efficiency and low emissions fuel cells. </P>

<P>
<HR></P>

<H3><B>Hydro Power</B></H3>

<P><B>ALT-4500</B> $.80 8pp 11/91-12/91 </P>

<P>&quot;Power in a Land of Remembrance&quot; </P>

<P>Harry Thurston, Audobon Magazine </P>

<P>The Cree people struggle to preserve traditional ways and stop the mega-hydroelectric
project on James Bay in northern Quebec. </P>

<P><B>ALT-4501</B> $.30 3pp 1/89 </P>

<P>&quot;Hydro Siting&quot; </P>

<P>Paul Cunningham, Home Power #8 </P>

<P>Introductory article that explains how to determine the hydroelectric
potential at a site with running water. </P>

<P><B>ALT-4502</B> $.70 7pp 8/88-9/88 </P>

<P>&quot;A Working MicroHydro at Journey's End Ranch&quot; </P>

<P>Harry Rakfeldt, Home Power #6 </P>

<P>A working example of self sufficient small hydroelectric generator.
</P>

<P><B>ALT-4503</B> $1.30 13pp 8/83 </P>

<P>&quot;How Small Hydro Is Growing Big&quot; </P>

<P>William Loeb, Technology Review </P>

<P>A look at small hydroelectric projects in New England. </P>

<P><B>ALT-4504</B> $.90 9pp 1/12/92 </P>

<P>&quot;Power Struggle&quot; </P>

<P>Sam Howe Verhovek, New York Times </P>

<P>The indigenous people and environmental struggle surrounding the Canadian
Hydro Quebec massive hydroelectric facility on James Bay </P>

<P>
<HR></P>

<H3><B>Hydrogen</B></H3>

<P><B>ALT-5000</B> $3.00 30pp 7/10/91 </P>

<P>&quot;Energy for the Post Fossil Fuel Era: The Solar Hydrogen Economy&quot;
</P>

<P>lowa Senator Tom Harkin </P>

<P>Sen. Harkin's 'Dear Colleague' letter in support of SB 1269: The Renewable
Hydrogen Energy Research and Development Act. </P>

<P><B>ALT-5001</B> $.10 1p 2/11/93 </P>

<P>&quot;Scientist Envisions a Hydrogen Economy&quot; </P>

<P>Gautam Naik, Wall Street Journal </P>

<P>Dr. James Schwarz works on a way to store hydrogen safely inside carbons.
</P>

<P><B>ALT-5002</B> $.40 4pp 4/90 </P>

<P>&quot;Hydrogen: An International Transportation Fuel Alternative&quot;
</P>

<P>Peter Hoffman, Pennsylvania Energy </P>

<P>Pollution free fuel for transportation. </P>

<P>
<HR></P>

<H3><B>Global Warming</B></H3>

<P><B>ALT-5500</B> $1.10 11pp 11/89-12/89 </P>

<P>&quot;Greenhouse: Me, You, and C02&quot; </P>

<P>Garbage </P>

<P>Short overview of greenhouse gases and where they come from, namely
our lifestyle. The E.E. section briefly describes how to conduct an energy
audit of your house. </P>

<P><B>ALT-5501</B> $3.00 30pp 12/88 </P>

<P>&quot;Greenhouse Warming: Comparative Analysis of Nuclear and Efficiency
Abatement Strategies&quot; </P>

<P>Bill Keepin and Gregory Kats, Energy Policy </P>

<P>This paper argues that reviving nuclear power would be an inefficient
and expensive way of mitigating and decreasing carbon dioxide output. </P>

<P><B>ALT-5502</B> $3.10 31 pp 1988 </P>

<P>A collection of four articles from WorldWatch, Public Power, Newsweek
and Fortune </P>

<P>Describe problems associated with global warming and offering a few
solutions. The solutions go along with the publications fairly predictably.
Put together, these provide a good introduction to the issue. </P>

<P><B>ALT-5503</B> $.80 8pp 4/29/91 </P>

<P>&quot;Nuclear Power: Time to Choose&quot; </P>

<P>John Greenwald et al. Time Magazine </P>

<P>This article discusses the resurgence of nuclear power in wake of global
warming concerns. It also follows-up on the Chernobyl accident and discusses
the predicament of environmentalists opposing nuclear power but also wanting
to mitigate greenhouse warming. </P>

<P><B>ALT-5504</B> $10.00 Periodically updated </P>

<P>NIRS Global Warming Packet </P>

<P>NIRS </P>

<P>A collection of the best information we have on global warming, with
special emphasis on why nuclear power is not a viable solution. This packet
is updated periodically. Packet includes a World Watch article on why reviving
nuclear power is a bad idea. </P>

<P><B>ALT-5505</B> $.40 4pp Winter 1988 </P>

<P>Nuclear Solution to the Greenhouse Effect? </P>

<P>Dr. Bill Keepin, The Elmwood Newsletter </P>

<P>In these two pieces, Keepin debunks the myth that nuclear power can
be a cost-effective way to curb the greenhouse effect. He argues that constructing
nuclear power plants would be prohibitively expensive and would not address
the great output of greenhouse gases from autos. </P>

<P>
<HR></P>

<H3><B>Energy Efficiency</B></H3>

<P><B>ALT-6000</B> just $5 1992 </P>

<P>The NIRS Energy Audit Manual Andrea Carlson, NIRS </P>

<P>This manual walks you through an energy audit of most buildings to ensure
you use the least energy in the most efficient way. </P>

<P><B>ALT-6001</B> $.90 9pp 9/90 </P>

<P>&quot;Efficient Use of Electricity&quot; </P>

<P>Fickett, Gelling, Lovins, Scientific American </P>

<P>A good introduction to energy efficiency. It gives facts on what other
countries are doing, as well as examples of new technology in lighting,
motors, and refrigeration. </P>

<P><B>ALT-6002</B> $2.70 27pp 9/12/90 </P>

<P>&quot;Energy Efficiency As a Coordinated Environmental and Energy Strategy&quot;
</P>

<P>California Legislature Joint Committee </P>

<P>When California designed their energy efficiency plan, they asked representatives
from the environmental, utility and civil communities what they wanted.
This is the committee's summary based on these groups' responses. The recommendations
provide a guideline for other states doing the same thing. </P>

<P><B>ALT-6003</B> $.70 7pp 8/90 </P>

<P>&quot;Energy Efficiency: Economic and Environmental Profit&quot; </P>

<P>Ted Flanigan IRT Supplement </P>

<P>This article reviews some energy efficiency measures for offices. Potential
savings estimates are also given. </P>

<P><B>ALT-6004</B> $.40 4pp Summer 1990 </P>

<P>&quot;Energy and the States: Bay States&quot; </P>

<P>Barbara Kates-Garnick, FARPP </P>

<P>Describes some of the changes in the Massachusetts power plant building
process. The new system allows for an increased dependence on energy efficiency,
rather than new power plants in the wind-poor Northeast. </P>

<P><B>ALT-6005</B> $.50 5pp 7/87 </P>

<P>&quot;Power to Spare: A Plan for Increasing New England's Competitiveness
Through Energy Efficiency&quot; </P>

<P>New England Policy Council Executive Summary </P>

<P>This paper initiated a movement in New England to invest in &quot;negawatts&quot;
(energy efficiency), as opposed to traditional power plants. It also correctly
predicted energy savings which New England utilities are now achieving.
</P>

<P><B>ALT-6006</B> $.80 8pp 4/88 </P>

<P>&quot;Energy Efficient Buildings&quot; </P>

<P>Rosenfeld and Hafemeister, Scientific American </P>

<P>This article discusses how energy efficient buildings can be constructed
for no more to build than current wasteful structures. According to the
authors, if 50 years from now all commercial space has adopted these methods,
the need for 85 power plants will have been precluded-at no additional
cost </P>

<P><B>ALT-6007</B> $.30 3pp 5/7/88 </P>

<P>&quot;Energy Efficiency: Less Means More: Fueling a Sustainable Future&quot;
</P>

<P>Janet Raloff, Science News </P>

<P>Expresses the importance of an environmentally sound energy strategy
to ensure a sustainable society and gives realistic, accessible ways to
attain energy efficiency. </P>

<P><B>ALT-6008</B> $3.40 34pp 5/7/92 </P>

<P>&quot;Toward Utility Rate Normalization on Demand Side Management Issues&quot;
</P>

<P>Eugene P. Coyle, Ph.D. </P>

<P>This testimony before the Public Utilities Commission of California
is offered as insight into the principles underlying utility DSM programs.
One kilowatt-hour (kWh) reduction in a utility's demand should correspondingly
eliminate the need for the utility to produce one kWh. </P>

<P><B>ALT-6009</B> $.20 2pp 2/2/89 </P>

<P>&quot;Energy Use Efficiency and Nuclear Generation as Competing Supply
Sources&quot; </P>

<P>Charles Komanoff, Public Utilities Fortnightly </P>

<P>Op ed by the noted energy analyst addressing energy efficiency vs. nuclear
power as solutions to greenhouse effect. </P>

<P><B>ALT-6010</B> $.50 5pp Spring 1991 </P>

<P>&quot;Office Space Designed for Energy Savings&quot; </P>

<P>Robert Watson, FARPP </P>

<P>Article on Natural Resource Defense Council's renovations of their New
York City office building and equipment with energy efficiency features.
</P>

<P><B>ALT-6011</B> $1.40 14pp 4/90-5/90 </P>

<P>&quot;New Push for Energy Efficiency&quot; </P>

<P>Leslie Lamarre, EPRI Journal </P>

<P>The Electric Power Research Institute projects that by the year 2000
the US could save as much as 47% of residential electricity and 49% of
commercial electricity through energy efficiency. </P>

<P><B>ALT-6012</B> $.50 5pp Spring 1991 </P>

<P>&quot;Energy Efficiency: Key to Solving Economic, Environmental Problems&quot;
</P>

<P>Ted Flanigan, FARPP </P>

<P>Coupling energy efficiency technology with innovative regulation and
financing, energy consumption in the U.S. can be cut by 75% </P>

<P><B>ALT-6013</B> $.70 7pp 1/18/90 </P>

<P>&quot;In Support of Demand Side Management&quot; </P>

<P>Thomas Chema, Public Utilities Fortnightly </P>

<P>Cheaper more abundant energy is to be found in the 'end-use sector'
through efficiency technologies that is more strategically advantageous
than the 'supplyside end.' </P>

<P><B>ALT-6014</B> $.40 4pp 11/88-12/88 </P>

<P>&quot;Lighting City Hall&quot; </P>

<P>Jill Kunka, Public Power </P>

<P>Improved lighting efficiency in city offices saves money for taxpayers
and utility customers. </P>

<P><B>ALT-6015</B> $.40 4pp 3/92-4/92 </P>

<P>&quot;Shaping Demand Side Management&quot; </P>

<P>Leslie Lamarre, Solar Today </P>

<P>Utility DSM strategies that promote energy efficiency and reduce the
utilities' environmental impact. </P>

<P><B>ALT-6016</B> $.60 6pp not dated </P>

<P>&quot;High-Efficiency Lighting Technologies For Brightening Up Your
Profits&quot; </P>

<P>Claudine Schneider, Reports from Washington </P>

<P>A fact sheet on how to save 80-90% of electricity normally required
to provide optimal lighting services. </P>

<P><B>ALT-6017</B> $.50 5pp 3/86-4/86 </P>

<P>&quot;Negawatts-Rx for Megagoofs&quot; </P>

<P>Amory Lovins, Public Power </P>

<P>Introduction to end-use technologies (efficient lightbulbs, electric
motors, etc.) that make nuclear power obsolete, and at the same time, make
a profit for utilities. </P>

<P><B>ALT-6018</B> $7.60 76pp 11/91 </P>

<P>Increasing the Efficiency of Electricity Production and Use: Barriers
and Strategies </P>

<P>David Moscovitz, et al., Energy Efficiency Issues Paper #5 </P>

<P>The ACEEE finds that failure to explore energy efficiency will ultimately
lower our standard of living since much of our income will go to energy
consumption. They also discuss causes for low investment in energy efficiency
programs and offer a list of alternative policies. </P>

<P><B>ALT-6019</B> $.20 2pp Winter 1994 </P>

<P>&quot;Energy Efficiency Industry Wants Help Finding New Markets, Survey
Finds&quot; </P>

<P>Mark Hopkins, Alliance Update </P>

<P>&quot;The most useful role for the Committee on Energy Efficiency Commerce
and Trade is to conduct market assessments and identify potential markets.&quot;
</P>

<P><B>ALT-6020</B> $.20 2pp 6/3/92 </P>

<P>&quot;Technology Builds A Better Bulb&quot; </P>

<P>Kevin Maney, USA Today </P>

<P>The E-Lamp is the latest in a line of energy efficient &quot;lighting
appliances&quot; that lasts 20,000 hours using 25 watts with an equivalent
of a 100 watt incandescent bulb. </P>

<P><B>ALT-6021</B> $.80 8pp 6/92 </P>

<P>&quot;The E-Lamp Technology and Specifications&quot; </P>

<P>Intersource Technologies </P>

<P>Manufacturer's report on the new lighting appliance that combines the
technology of a low pressure gas discharge light source with advanced radio
frequency electronics. </P>

<P><B>ALT-6022</B> $2.00 20pp 1/92 </P>

<P>&quot;Schoolhouse in the Red&quot; </P>

<P>Hansen Associates </P>

<P>A report on the critical issue of energy cost impacts on our nation's
schools where nearly half do not have energy management programs and over
a third have never performed an energy audit. </P>

<P><B>ALT-6023</B> $2.90 29pp 9/89 </P>

<P>&quot;The Negawatt Revolution: Solving the C02 Problem&quot; </P>

<P>Amory Lovins, Green Energy Conference </P>

<P>A comprehensive and convincing presentation on energy efficiency over
nuclear power as a solution to global warming. </P>

<P><B>ALT-6500</B> $.90 9pp 7/92-8/92 </P>

<P>&quot;The Bridge to Clean Energy&quot; </P>

<P>Christopher Flavin World-Watch Magazine </P>

<P>Natural gas is cleaner than coal and oil and may be the interim fuel
source for ushering in a solar hydrogen economy. </P>

<P>
<HR></P>

<H3><B>Wind Power</B></H3>

<P><B>ALT-7000</B> $2.50 25pp 6/90 </P>

<P>&quot;Excellent Forecast for Wind&quot; </P>

<P>EPRI Journal </P>

<P>This article takes an in-depth look at the wind industry: where it has
been, where it is, and where it is headed. A good source of information
on the nation's most successful new energy source. </P>

<P><B>ALT-7001</B> $.20 2pp 11/17/91 </P>

<P>&quot;Future of Wind Power Gets A Lift&quot; </P>

<P>Thomas W. Lippman, The Washington Post </P>

<P>Wind turbines have decreased in cost and risen in efficiency, making
them competitive in current markets. </P>

<P><B>ALT-7002</B> $.60 6pp 4/91-5/91 </P>

<P>&quot;A Primer on Wind Generators&quot; </P>

<P>Mike Bergey, Home Power #22 </P>

<P>A good introductory article to wind generated electricity. </P>

<P><B>ALT-7003</B> $.20 2pp 11/14/91 </P>

<P>&quot;Putting Windmills Where it's Windy&quot; </P>

<P>Matthew Wald, New York Times </P>

<P>Wind power is making gains In U.S. </P>

<P><B>ALT-7004</B> $.20 2pp 1/92 </P>

<P>&quot;Wind But No Will in France&quot; </P>

<P>Frans Janse, Wind Energy Monthly </P>

<P>France's strong centralized government gives little incentive to small
scale electric production. In addition, nuclear power provides most of
the country's electricity needs and means big business in other countries
as well. </P>

<P><B>ALT-7005</B> $.70 7pp not dated </P>

<P>Economics of Large-Scale Wind Power Development in Egypt </P>

<P>Carlos R. Guerra, et al. </P>

<P>Paper discusses the economic potential of wind power development in
Egypt along the Red Sea coast region. </P>

<P><B>ALT-7006</B> $.70 7pp 3/88-4/88 </P>

<P>&quot;Harvesting the Wind&quot; </P>

<P>Cynthia Pollock Shea, WorldWatch </P>

<P>Shea discusses the development of wind power, how the Danes have fared
using it, and how America has explored its potential. She also gives reasons
why wind is a economically viable energy source, including its potentially
quick construction compared with years of planning for nuclear or coal
plants. </P>

<P><B>ALT-7007</B> $.30 3pp 11/87 </P>

<P>&quot;Wind Power Siting&quot; </P>

<P>Larry Elliot, Home Power #1 </P>

<P>A succinct article on choosing a the site in determining the success
or failure of a wind generator. </P>

<P><B>ALT-7008</B> $.20 2pp 9/6/91 </P>

<P>&quot;Wind Farms May Energize the Midwest&quot; </P>

<P>David Stipp, Wall Street Journal </P>

<P>Wind generated electricity growing in the midwest. </P>

<P><B>ALT-7009</B> $1.40 14pp updated periodically </P>

<P>Wind Energy Potential Information </P>

<P>These articles contain wind energy potential information for many regions
of the United States, claiming that we fail to use our country's full wind
potential. </P>

<P><A HREF="toolhome.htm"><IMG SRC="nirslog2.gif" HEIGHT=58 WIDTH=130></A>
</P>

</BODY>
