<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE>Toolbox: Chernobyl</TITLE>
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0Gold (Win95; I) [Netscape]">
   <META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Preferred Customer">
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<H1>THE NIRS TOOLBOX</H1>

<P>
<HR></P>

<H4>Human history becomes more and more a race between education and catastrophe.
~ H.G. Wells</H4>

<P>A ~ indicates that this Toolbox entry contains information relevant
to the health effects of low-dose and/or long-term exposure to radiation.
</P>

<H4>There are two ways to order materials from the NIRS&nbsp;toolbox:</H4>

<H4>1. The fast way: fax your order to NIRS at 202-462-2183. Include your
Visa, Mastercard or Discover Card number, expiration date, and signature.
</H4>

<H4>2. The slow way: mail to NIRS at 1424 16th Street NW, #404, Washington
DC 20036. Please make your check payable to NIRS. Thank you.</H4>

<H4>Unfortunately, due to problems collecting payment on invoiced orders,
all orders must now be prepaid (we're not a collection agency after all,
we're an environmental group...).</H4>

<P>
<HR></P>

<H2>CHERNOBYL</H2>

<P><B>PCH-1000</B> $10.00 1986 to present </P>

<P>Chernobyl Tenth Commemoration Packet </P>

<P>A very comprehensive collection of articles which cover a range of topics
including what went wrong at the reactor and how the children in the plume
area are coping. A few articles discuss the possibility of a Chernobyl-like
accident here and some explore the effects of international contamination,
especially on health. Articles on decommissioning and economic difficulties
are also included. </P>

<P><B>PCH-2000</B> $.20 20pp 5/12/86 </P>

<P>&quot;The Chernobyl Syndrome,&quot; Newsweek </P>

<P>This article assesses the accident and recalls other accidents in the
US. It discusses what went wrong at Chernobyl, why the Kremlin covered
up, and what this bodes for nuclear power in the US. </P>

<P><B>PCH-3000</B> $35.00 350pp 8/25/86-8/29/86 </P>

<P>&quot;The Accident at Chernobyl AES and its Consequences&quot; </P>

<P>USSR Atomic Energy State Committee, IAEA Expert Conference </P>

<P>The Soviet report on what happened at Chernobyl. Copies may be available
through the DOE so contact them before you order. </P>

<P><B>PCH-4000</B> $2.80 28 pp 1986-1994 </P>

<P>Chernobyl Aftermath: A Collection of Articles </P>

<P>Reports from Wall Street Journal, WISE, Nuke Info Tokyo, Time and more,
on the true health effects of the accident including international contamination,
and rising death and disease rates. </P>

<P><B>PCH-4001</B> $.70 7pp 1/91-2/91 </P>

<P>&quot;Children of Chernobyl&quot; </P>

<P>Andre Carothers, Greenpeace Magazine </P>

<P>An overview of the Chernobyl fallout effects and the Ukrainian acceptance
of outside intervention to fully investigate the health repercussions,
especially among children. </P>

<P><B>PCH-4002</B> $1.10 11 pp 1/14/90 </P>

<P>&quot;The Second Chernobyl Disaster&quot; </P>

<P>Steve Goldstein, Philadelphia Inquirer Magazine </P>

<P>This article is a compilation of interviews with some of the victims
of Chernobyl radiation exposure. </P>

<P><B>PCH-6000</B> $1 .80 18pp 9/20/86 </P>

<P>&quot;What the Chernobyl Accident Means for the US Nuclear Power Program&quot;
James Asselstine, NRC Commissioner </P>

<P>Asselstine speaks at a Post Chernobyl Strategy Session, commenting on
the performance of US reactors and the NRC's regulation of them, and concludes
&quot; we should be pursuing additional measures both to reduce the possibility
of a core meltdown accident and to mitigate the adverse effects of such
an accident.&quot; </P>

<P><B>PCH-6001</B> .$80 8pp 5/13/86 </P>

<P>&quot;Lessons from Chernobyl-A European Perspective&quot; </P>

<P>Bernd Franke, IEER </P>

<P>This work compares the consequences of the Chernobyl accident to a hypothetical
accident at Hanford's N-reactor. Franke includes important radioactive
release figures from Chernobyl. </P>

<P><B>PCH-6002</B> $1.10 11pp 1987 </P>

<P>Chernobyl's Effect on Nuclear Power </P>

<P>Three articles from Science, Environmental Science Technology and Sierra
Club examine the Chernobyl disaster's effect on future nuclear power generation
and the likelihood of an accident here. </P>

<P><B>PCH-6003</B> $1.20 12pp 4/14/91 </P>

<P>&quot;Chernobyl&quot; </P>

<P>Felicity Barringer, et al., New York Times Magazine </P>

<P>In this recount of personal struggles to deal with the health effects
of the radiation release, Barringer interviews many families, some who
must stay in a contaminated area and have few doctors to tend to the increasing
number of maladies. </P>

<P><B>PCH-6004</B> $.70 7pp 12/90 </P>

<P>&quot;Revelations of a Chernobyl Insider&quot; </P>

<P>David Marples, Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists </P>

<P>An interview with Yuri Risovanny who was involved in the clean-up effort
since its inception. </P>

<P><B>PCH-6005</B> $1.70 17pp Summer 1994 </P>

<P>&quot;The Legacy of Chernobyl&quot; </P>

<P>ISAR, Surviving Together </P>

<P>This exceptionally heart-wrenching article is a follow-up on the accident.
It discusses how the Ukrainian people are coping and how local people are
striving to ensure safety wherever possible. </P>

<P><B>PCH-6006</B> $.60 6 pp 9/93 </P>

<P>&quot;Chernobyl's Lengthening Shadow&quot; </P>

<P>David Marples, Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists </P>

<P>A brief encapsulation of the reactor accident, the health effects, the
IAEA assessment, and the charities which have been created to help local
people deal with the on-going nightmare. </P>

<P><B>PCH-6007</B> $2.40 24pp Summer, 1990 </P>

<P>Three Articles on Chernobyl </P>

<P>FARPP </P>

<P>&quot;Chernobyl: Its Effects in the USSR&quot; by David Marples explores
the &quot;dead zone&quot;, public mistrust and anger and health effects
now manifesting. &quot;Chernobyl: A First Hand Account&quot;, by Vladimir
Voina reveals the voice of an angry person, betrayed by his government
and &quot;Chernobyl: Lessons In Nuclear Liability&quot; recaps the liability
laws in the US and reminds us that $7 billion dollars may not be enough
for cleanup if Chernobyl is any indication. </P>

<P><B>PCH-6008</B> $2.30 23pp 1987 </P>

<P>&quot;Chernobyl-A Canadian Perspective&quot; </P>

<P>Dr. V.G. Snell and J.Q. Howieson </P>

<P>Two officials of the Ontario government present an understandable description
of the Chernobyl accident, then look at the Canadian CANDU reactor, &quot;to
see how it stacks up in its ability to tolerate the scores of mistakes
that were made at Chernobyl.&quot; </P>

<P><B>PCH-6009</B> $1.30 13pp Winter 1986/1987 </P>

<P>&quot;Learning from Chernobyl&quot; </P>

<P>Bennett Ramberg, Foreign Affairs Magazine </P>

<P>Discussion of the Chernobyl accident and reactor safety from an international
nuclear policy standpoint which offers suggestions for better regulation.
</P>

<P><A HREF="toolhome.htm"><IMG SRC="nirslog2.gif" HEIGHT=58 WIDTH=130></A>
</P>

</BODY>
</HTML>
