<HEAD>
   <TITLE>Toolbox: Decommissioning</TITLE>
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0Gold (Win95; I) [Netscape]">
   <META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Preferred Customer">
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<H1>THE NIRS TOOLBOX</H1>

<P>
<HR></P>

<H4>Human history becomes more and more a race between education and catastrophe.
~ H.G. Wells</H4>

<P>A ~ indicates that this Toolbox entry contains information relevant
to the health effects of low-dose and/or long-term exposure to radiation.
</P>

<H4>There are two ways to order materials from the NIRS&nbsp;toolbox:</H4>

<H4>1. The fast way: fax your order to NIRS at 202-462-2183. Include your
Visa, Mastercard or Discover Card number, expiration date, and signature.
</H4>

<H4>2. The slow way: mail to NIRS at 1424 16th Street NW, #404, Washington
DC 20036. Please make your check payable to NIRS. Thank you.</H4>

<H4>Unfortunately, due to problems collecting payment on invoiced orders,
all orders must now be prepaid (we're not a collection agency after all,
we're an environmental group...).</H4>

<P>
<HR></P>

<H2>DECOMMISSIONING</H2>

<P><B>DEC-1000</B> $10.00 updated periodically </P>

<P>Decommissioning Packet </P>

<P>Literature includes an IAEA paper on decommissioning as well as a list
of decommissioned nukes and a Groundswell article. </P>

<P><B>DEC-2000</B> $1.80 18pp 1/88 </P>

<P>&quot;Decommissioning at Ground Level&quot; </P>

<P>Dr. M.J. Pasqualetti, Land Use Policy </P>

<P>This paper uses evidence from England's Sizewell Inquiry that associates
generic and geosocial uncertainties with decommissioning. Some conclusions
are that decommissioning costs are underestimated: further nuclear development
should await decommissioning experience; and decommissioning should be
included in all future nuclear policy decisions. </P>

<P><B>DEC-2001</B> $1.00 10pp 7/89-8/89 </P>

<P>&quot;Breaking Up is Hard to Do&quot; </P>

<P>Cynthia Pollock Shea, World Watch Magazine </P>

<P>&quot;Nuclear power may (be pricing) itself out of existence, but that
still leaves the question of what to do with the radioactive remains of
hundreds of worn-out power plants.&quot; This is a good overview of the
decommissioning problem </P>

<P><B>DEC-2002</B> $1.60 16pp 1989 </P>

<P>&quot;Introducing the Geosocial Context of Nuclear Decommissioning:
US. and Great Britain&quot; </P>

<P>Martin J. Pasqualetti, Geoforum </P>

<P>&quot;Public recognition and the potential for public impact on decommissioning
policy is increasing in both countries, although government agencies and
utilities are taking little account of it. This article uses experience
in the US and Great Britain to address the question of what the geosocial
context of nuclear decommissioning is...&quot; </P>

<P><B>DEC-2003</B> $1.50 15pp 1994 </P>

<P>&quot;Some Background on Decommissioning&quot; </P>

<P>Jonathan M. Block </P>

<P>In this study, Block walks through the definition and process of decommission,
examining Yankee Rowe and the &quot;early component removal&quot; program.
Also included is the decommissioning plan for Trojan. </P>

<P><B>DEC-3000</B> $2.70 27 pp Winter, 1987 </P>

<P>Five Articles on Decommissioning </P>

<P>FARPP Energy Issues </P>

<P>These articles individually discuss external and internal decommissioning
funds, TVA and decommissioning as an unresolved problem. Although decommissioning
costs have risen, not much else has changed. </P>

<P><B>DEC-3001</B> $.60 6pp 4/89 </P>

<P>&quot;The Decommissioning of Nuclear Plant&quot; </P>

<P>Gordon MacKerron, Energy Policy </P>

<P>Postponement of decommissioning is caused more by the inadequacy of
&quot;storage&quot; places rather than by design. A balance of environmental
considerations, policy and regulation, will ultimately decide decommissioning's
future course. </P>

<P><B>DEC-3002</B> $1.20 12pp 10/89 </P>

<P>&quot;When a Nuclear Reactor Dies, $98 million is a Cheap Funeral&quot;
</P>

<P>Seth Shulman, Smithsonian </P>

<P>The DOE buries the first commercial reactor, but 50 more are about to
die and there's no cemetery: The dismantling of Shippingport. </P>

<P><B>DEC-3003</B> $.70 7 pp 10/29/87 </P>

<P>&quot;Nuclear Power Plant Decommissioning: Cost Estimation for Planning
and Rate Making&quot; </P>

<P>Bernow and Biewald, Public Utilities Fortnightly </P>

<P>&quot;The authors of this article analyze the differences between site-specific
and generic cost estimates [of decommissioning] and suggest the use of
process contingency factors as a means of providing more accurate projections
of decommissioning costs.&quot; </P>

<P><B>DEC-5000</B> $1.70 17pp not dated </P>

<P>&quot;State Regulation of Decommissioning Costs&quot; </P>

<P>Peter Strauss and James Kelsey, The Energy Journal </P>

<P>The states have the responsibility for setting rates for decommissioning
fund accumulation. This excerpt tells how factors such as plant size, number
of units, and the amount of funding for site restoration, influence state
utility commissions. </P>

<P><B>DEC-5001</B> $1.00 10pp not dated </P>

<P>&quot;Federal Regulation of Decommissioning Economics&quot; </P>

<P>Robert Wood, The Energy Journal </P>

<P>The author introduces us to the regulations and financial considerations
of NRC regarding decommissioning. Among topics discussed are funding methods
and funding assurance in the event of accident or bankruptcy. </P>

<P><A HREF="toolhome.htm"><IMG SRC="nirslog2.gif" HEIGHT=58 WIDTH=130></A>
</P>

</BODY>
</HTML>
