<HEAD>
   <TITLE>Toolbox: Economics</TITLE>
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0Gold (Win95; I) [Netscape]">
   <META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Preferred Customer">
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<H1>THE NIRS TOOLBOX</H1>

<P>
<HR></P>

<H4>Human history becomes more and more a race between education and catastrophe.
~ H.G. Wells</H4>

<P>A ~ indicates that this Toolbox entry contains information relevant
to the health effects of low-dose and/or long-term exposure to radiation.
</P>

<H4>There are two ways to order materials from the NIRS&nbsp;toolbox:</H4>

<H4>1. The fast way: fax your order to NIRS at 202-462-2183. Include your
Visa, Mastercard or Discover Card number, expiration date, and signature.
</H4>

<H4>2. The slow way: mail to NIRS at 1424 16th Street NW, #404, Washington
DC 20036. Please make your check payable to NIRS. Thank you.</H4>

<P>Unfortunately, due to problems collecting payment on invoiced orders,
all orders must now be prepaid (we're not a collection agency after all,
we're an environmental group...).</P>

<H2>ECONOMICS</H2>

<P><B>EC-2000</B> $.20 2pp 2/90 </P>

<P>&quot;Perestroika for Public Utilities&quot; </P>

<P>Sheldon Whitehouse, Public Utilities Fortnightly </P>

<P>Whitehouse describes the New England utilities' conservation methods
and its advantages for the utilities. The article also debates whether
the public service commission should grant a conservation incentive. </P>

<P><B>EC-2001</B> $1.70 17pp 12/92 </P>

<P>&quot;Fiscal Fission: The Economic Failure of Nuclear Power&quot; </P>

<P>Komanoff Energy Associates, Greenpeace Executive Summary </P>

<P>A great comprehensive account of the nuclear industry's cost history-very
important for those who want the bottom-line with just enough detail. </P>

<P><B>EC-2002</B> $1.60 16pp 9/90 </P>

<P>&quot;The Political Economy of Nuclear Power (1945-1990): The Rise and
Fall of an Official Technology&quot; </P>

<P>Steve Cohn, Journal of Economic Issues </P>

<P>Argues the only reason nuclear power is so pervasive now is because
it is an &quot;official technology&quot;, which means the government promoted
it. </P>

<P><B>EC-4000</B> $2.80 28pp 1987 </P>

<P>&quot;Request for Comments on Potential Financial Incentive Mechanism
for Enhanced Nuclear Power Plant Safety&quot; </P>

<P>Summarizes the New York Public Service Commission's proposal for a reward-and-penalty
system with which to encourage greater safety in nuclear power plants.
Recommends an economic incentive based on the SALP procedure. Two comments.
</P>

<P><B>EC-4001</B> $.40 4pp 5/86 </P>

<P>&quot;Unmasking the Myth Brokers: The Real Cost of Nuclear Power&quot;
</P>

<P>Charles Komanoff, Multinational Monitor </P>

<P>Komanoff, director of Komanoff Energy Associates, and author of three
books an) many articles on nuclear power, examines the true cost of nuclear
energy and explains why actual cost is much larger than expected costs.
</P>

<P><B>EC-4002</B> $.60 6 pp 12/23/89 </P>

<P>&quot;Nuclear Generation Companies: A Framework for Reviving Nuclear
Power&quot; </P>

<P>John O. Sillin and John P. Jackson, Public Utilities Fortnightly </P>

<P>Argues that consortia composed of utilities, investors, construction
companies, etc., can overcome opposition and revitalize nuclear power.
Also includes the environmentalists' response in an article from June 7,
1990. </P>

<P><B>EC-4003</B> $.60 6 pp 1/84-2/84 </P>

<P>&quot;The Market Test: Nuclear Power's Financial Meltdown in the US&quot;
</P>

<P>Christopher Flavin, Science for the People </P>

<P>Summary of Flavin's well-publicized 1983 report on nuclear economics.
</P>

<P><B>EC-4004</B> $1.90 19pp 1983 </P>

<P>&quot;Prometheus Bound: Nuclear Power at the Turning Point&quot; </P>

<P>Charles Komanoff and l.C. Bupp </P>

<P>Report finds electricity from new nuclear plants to be more expensive
than from oil plants. These conclusions are even more apropos today. </P>

<P><B>EC-4005</B> $1.80 18pp 2/11/85 </P>

<P>&quot;Nuclear Follies&quot; </P>

<P>James Cook, Forbes </P>

<P>An excellent review of the nuclear industry's failings. The source may
be nuclear-friendly, but the words and tone are unsparing and unforgiving.
The research isn't bad either. In the words of the author, &quot;the U.S.
nuclear power program ranks as the largest managerial disaster in business
history.&quot; </P>

<P><B>EC-4006</B> $2.40 24pp 1981 </P>

<P>Power Plant Cost Escalation </P>

<P>Charles Komanoff </P>

<P>Chapters 1 &amp; 2. Komanoff compares nuclear power costs with that
of coal and refutes the industry claim that nuclear power is cheaper. </P>

<P><B>EC-4007</B> $.20 2 pp 4/84 </P>

<P>&quot;Early Retirement of Nuclear Capacity as a Competitive Strategy&quot;
</P>

<P>Linda C. Byus, Nuclear News </P>

<P>Explores the fiscal benefits of early nuclear plant retirement and if
current or future trends will allow this to be beneficial to the industry.
</P>

<P><B>EC-4008</B> $.80 8 pp 7/90 </P>

<P>''Subsidy to Nuclear Power Through Price-Anderson Liability </P>

<P>Dubin and Rothwell, Contemporary Policy /Issues </P>

<P>This work discusses limited liability placed on the nuclear industry
by the NRC. The NRC has avoided estimating the size of the subsidy but
the author contends that one must ask what the implicit cost of insuring
nuclear power is under Price-Anderson. </P>

<P><B>EC-4009</B> $1.00 10pp 7/3/85 </P>

<P>&quot;Least-Cost Electrical Services as an Alternative to the Braidwood
Project&quot; </P>

<P>Amory Lovins, Illinois Commerce Commission </P>

<P>In this summary of his testimony, Lovins argues that even if it cost
nothing to build the Braidwood plant, it would cost less to write it off
and buy electricity-saving measures instead. A controversial approach,
and an older article, but one every PUC should read. </P>

<P><B>EC-4010</B> $5.50 55pp 1987 </P>

<P>&quot;Review of the Costs of &quot;PG&amp;E's Diablo Canyon Nuclear
Power Plant Project,&quot; California Public Utilities Commission </P>

<P>Report explaining why PG &amp; E should be allowed to recover little
more than a fifth of the construction costs of Diablo Canyon from its customers.
</P>

<P><B>EC 4500</B> $.40 4pp 4/15/91 </P>

<P>&quot;Moving From Irate Rivals to Friendly Partners&quot; </P>

<P>Peter Asmus, Public Utilities Fortnightly </P>

<P>The canceled Rancho Seco nuclear power plant, now host to 2 MW of solar
electricity, is a symbol of cooperation between privately owned utility
Pacific Gas and Electric and the publicly owned Sacramento Municipal Utility
District in California. </P>

<P><B>EC-5000</B> $.50 5pp 7/7/90 </P>

<P>&quot;Do We Really Need Nuclear Generating Companies?&quot; </P>

<P>Bruce Biewald, Public Utilities Fortnightly </P>

<P>Biewald tackles two main industry arguments for continuation/creation
of nuclear generating companies. Are we in danger of electric service blackouts,
if so, would nuclear power be a wise alternative? This article explains
why the author says &quot;no.&quot; </P>

<P><B>EC-5001</B> $1.00 10pp 1983 </P>

<P>&quot;The Negligible Role of Nuclear Power in Reducing Oil Usage Since
1978&quot; </P>

<P>Alan Nogee, Environmental Action Foundation </P>

<P>Study which rebukes industry claims that nuclear power is needed to
reduce U.S. dependence on foreign oil. </P>

<P><B>EC-5002</B> $4.10 41pp 11/87 </P>

<P>&quot;Nuclear Lemon&quot; </P>

<P>Alan Nogee, MASSPIRG </P>

<P>Nogee, using Boston Edison cost estimates, shows how ratepayers would
save as much as $1.5 billion over 25 years by permanently closing the Pilgrim
nuclear plant. This is a good example of a cost analysis report. </P>

<P><B>EC-5500</B> $1.80 18pp 6/24/83 </P>

<P>&quot;Perspective on Electric Utility Capacity Planning,&quot; Congressional
Research Service </P>

<P>Report on potential of conservation and renewable energy to meet increased
electrical demand through the year 2000. </P>

<P><A HREF="toolhome.htm"><IMG SRC="nirslog2.gif" HEIGHT=58 WIDTH=130></A>
</P>

</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
