<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE>Toolbox: Emergency Planning</TITLE>
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0Gold (Win95; I) [Netscape]">
   <META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Preferred Customer">
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<H1>THE NIRS TOOLBOX</H1>

<P>
<HR></P>

<H4>Human history becomes more and more a race between education and catastrophe.
~ H.G. Wells</H4>

<P>A ~ indicates that this Toolbox entry contains information relevant
to the health effects of low-dose and/or long-term exposure to radiation.
</P>

<H4>There are two ways to order materials from the NIRS&nbsp;toolbox:</H4>

<H4>1. The fast way: fax your order to NIRS at 202-462-2183. Include your
Visa, Mastercard or Discover Card number, expiration date, and signature.
</H4>

<H4>2. The slow way: mail to NIRS at 1424 16th Street NW, #404, Washington
DC 20036. Please make your check payable to NIRS. Thank you.</H4>

<H4>Unfortunately, due to problems collecting payment on invoiced orders,
all orders must now be prepaid (we're not a collection agency after all,
we're an environmental group...)</H4>

<P>
<HR></P>

<H2>EMERGENCY PLANNING</H2>

<P><B>PEP-1000</B> $10.00 occasionally updated </P>

<P>Emergency Planning Information Packet </P>

<P>Documents on the 1 0-mile zone, the shadow effect and comments of the
Union of Concerned Scientists regarding the fiscal responsibility for evacuation
plans. </P>

<P><B>PEP-3000</B> $4.70 47pp 1982 </P>

<P>&quot;Ready or Not Il: Public Health Preparedness for an Accident at
Indian Point&quot; </P>

<P>James Murphy and Joan Harriss, NYPIRG </P>

<P>This report by two MPHs surveys hospital emergency departments, and
residential health care facilities within the 10-mile emergency planning
zone for Indian Point. </P>

<P><B>PEP-3001</B> $11.00 110pp 1984 </P>

<P>Indian Point School Evacuation Survey Project </P>

<P>NYPIRG and others </P>

<P>Included is the survey circulated among school personnel inquiring about
evacuation planning in the event of a nuclear plant accident, a citizen
letter urging shutdown of Indian Point 1 &amp; 2, news articles, and letters
which point out glaring mistakes in the evacuation plans (like the absence
of procedures for school children). </P>

<P><B>PEP-3002</B> $4.30 43pp 3/9/83 </P>

<P>Ready or Not III: An Exercise in Futility </P>

<P>NYPIRG </P>

<P>An intervenor observation report which critiques an evacuation exercise
of March 9,1983. The report basically concludes that the evacuation plans
are inadequate and an accident at Indian Point could be disastrous. Even
though this critique was written in 1983, Indian Point has done little
to correct the evacuation plan flaws. </P>

<P><B>PEP-3003</B> $8.50 85pp Summer 1983 </P>

<P>Blueprint for Chaos II: Pilgrim Disaster Plans Still a Disaster </P>

<P>MASSPIRG </P>

<P>A fairly comprehensive criticism of Pilgrim Plant's evacuation plans.
The report covers faulty areas of the plan and makes suggestions for correcting
the shortcomings. Subsequent to this report, nothing was done to address
the issues it raises. </P>

<P><B>PEP-3004</B> $4.00 40pp 1/7/87 </P>

<P>Emergency Evacuation Review Team on Emergency Response Plans for the
Perry and Davis-Besse Nuclear Power Plants </P>

<P>Members of the EERT present their findings and recommendations for evacuation
plans should an accident happen at Davis Besse. They tell why they find
the plans inadequate and make recommendations. Also included in the appendices
are a statement by then attorney general Anthony Celebrezze and EERT's
unresolved issues. </P>

<P><B>PEP-3005</B> $3.70 37pp 1986 </P>

<P>Implications of the Chernobyl-4 Accident for Nuclear Emergency Planning
for the State of New York, MHB Technical Associates </P>

<P>This paper voices concern about similarities between Chernobyl unit
4 and U S reactors, particularly Fitzpatrick, Nine Mile Point 1&amp; 2,
and Shoreham. The report contends that these similarities must be considered
in reassessing the safety systems of plants, the vulnerability of US plants
to serious accidents, and what can be learned about emergency planning
as a result of the Chernobyl accident. </P>

<P><B>PEP-4000</B> $.90 9pp 5/84 </P>

<P>Evacuation Behavior in Response to Nuclear Power Plant Accidents </P>

<P>Zeigler and Johnson, Professional Geographer </P>

<P>This article presents data from a telephone survey of households on
Long Island, NY. The survey's intent was to investigate the emergency response
behaviors of residents for certain action advisories should an accident
occur at Shoreham Nuclear Power Station. </P>

<P><B>PEP-4001</B> $.90 9pp 3/84-4/84 </P>

<P>&quot;Planning for Spontaneous Evacuation During a Radiological Emergency&quot;
</P>

<P>J. H. Johnson, Jr., Nuclear Safety: vol. 25, No. 2 </P>

<P>At the time this article was written, FEMA ignored the possibility of
&quot;spontaneous&quot; evacuation resulting from a nuclear power plant
accident. The article presents empirical evidence that, on average, 39%
of the population of Long Island is likely to evacuate spontaneously and
thus cast an evacuation &quot;shadow&quot; extending 25 miles. FEMA has
not currently addressed the &quot;shadow effect&quot; issue. </P>

<P><B>PEP-4002</B> $.70 7pp 2/16/89 </P>

<P>&quot;Information Planning and the Geographical Context of Radiological
Emergency Management&quot; </P>

<P>Donald Zeigler and James Johnson </P>

<P>Contrary to the contentions of the nuclear industry and official policy
of NRC, this paper contends that informational context of an accident will
not be the main determiner of human behavior with regard to evacuation.
The authors use studies on TMI and Chernobyl disasters as a basis for this
conclusion. </P>

<P><B>PEP-5000</B> $5.70 57pp 9/2/82 </P>

<P>Testimony of Steven C. Sholly Before the Committee on Nuclear Power
Safety, New York State </P>

<P>Steve Sholly, UCS, testifies on behalf of NYPIRG as to why they feel
the emergency evacuation plans in response to a nuclear accident are inadequate.
Among the items discussed are the inadequacy of a 10-mile evacuation radius.
Don't let the date fool you, this piece is timely and wholly relevant.
</P>

<P><B>PEP-5001</B> $1.20 12pp 4/28/87 </P>

<P>Testimony of Michael Mariotte Before the Subcommittee on Energy and
Environment, NIRS </P>

<P>This testimony criticizes the NRC's emergency planning regulations and
guidelines and uses the Chernobyl backdrop to question the safety of operating
plants in the States. NIRS takes to task the NRC proposed rule on local
government cooperation, and cost versus safety considerations. </P>

<P><A HREF="toolhome.htm"><IMG SRC="nirslog2.gif" HEIGHT=58 WIDTH=130></A>
</P>

</BODY>
</HTML>
