<HEAD>
   <TITLE>Toolbox: Government</TITLE>
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0Gold (Win95; I) [Netscape]">
   <META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Preferred Customer">
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<H1>THE NIRS TOOLBOX</H1>

<P>
<HR></P>

<H4>Human history becomes more and more a race between education and catastrophe.
~ H.G. Wells</H4>

<P>A ~ indicates that this Toolbox entry contains information relevant
to the health effects of low-dose and/or long-term exposure to radiation.
</P>

<H4>There are two ways to order materials from the NIRS&nbsp;toolbox:</H4>

<H4>1. The fast way: fax your order to NIRS at 202-462-2183. Include your
Visa, Mastercard or Discover Card number, expiration date, and signature.
</H4>

<H4>2. The slow way: mail to NIRS at 1424 16th Street NW, #404, Washington
DC 20036. Please make your check payable to NIRS. Thank you.</H4>

<H4>Unfortunately, due to problems collecting payment on invoiced orders,
all orders must now be prepaid (we're not a collection agency after all,
we're an environmental group...)</H4>

<P>
<HR></P>

<H2>GOVERNMENT</H2>

<P><B>GOV-1000</B> $10.00 updated periodically </P>

<P>Packet of Proposed Legislation </P>

<P>Includes the bills that would allow Yucca Mountain to open without proper
site suitability established and highly radioactive fuel rods to be transported
on the nation's rails and highways. This is updated as new bills are introduced.
</P>

<P><B>GOV-3000</B> $1.00 10pp 1991/1992 </P>

<P>Nuclear Power </P>

<P>DOE National Energy Strategy </P>

<P>Argues that nuclear power figures prominently into meeting America's
future &quot;base-load&quot; energy needs and sees the industry's salvation
in improved life-cycle economics, advanced reactor designs and &quot;reform&quot;
in the NRC licensing process, among other measures. </P>

<P><B>GOV-3001</B> $.10 1 p 6/13/94 </P>

<P>&quot;Oprah O'Leary&quot; </P>

<P>David Corn, The Nation </P>

<P>This article examines the amiability of Hazel O'Leary and ponders the
motives for her DOE &quot;openness&quot; campaign. </P>

<P><B>GOV-5000</B> $1.80 18pp 10/92 </P>

<P>License to Spend </P>

<P>Michael Mariotte, Bill Magavern, et al, NlRS &amp; USPIRG </P>

<P>This report lists the amount of PAC money received by Congress members,
and their voting records on nuclear issues from 1985-1992. The authors
also encapsulate legislation that was spurred by members receiving this
money such as the &quot;one step licensing&quot; rule. </P>

<P><B>GOV-5001</B> $1.00 </P>

<P>Price-Anderson Act and Amendments </P>

<P>The Price-Anderson Act amended the Atomic Energy Act by limiting liability
in the event of a nuclear accident. Price-Anderson is included along with
subsequent amendments to it. </P>

<P><B>GOV-6000</B> $1.40 14pp 8/27/87 </P>

<P>Control of Hot Particle Contamination at Nuclear Power Plants </P>

<P>NRC Information Notice </P>

<P>Report to plant operators on pathways of workers contamination, a recount
of accidents, and advice on how to prevent radioactive particles from endangering
workers </P>

<P><B>GOV-6001</B> $2.00 20pp </P>

<P>Commission Recommendations Proposing a Restructuring of the NRC </P>

<P>This recommendation resulted from the Kemeny Commission which was formed
to investigate the NRC's role in the TMI accident. The report concludes,
among other things, that the NRC should be restructured into the executive
branch and the present five-member commission should be abolished. </P>

<P><B>GOV-6002</B> $5.00 50pp 12/87 </P>

<P>&quot;NRC Coziness With Industry&quot; </P>

<P>Committee on Interior 8 Insular Affairs </P>

<P>An investigative report resulting from several Congressional hearings
on corruption within the NRC by the House Interior Subcommittee on General
Oversight and Investigations. This report has interesting findings, conclusions,
and recommendations. </P>

<P><B>GOV-6003</B> $5.40 54pp 6/16/81 </P>

<P>The Nuclear Regulatory Commission: Organization History </P>

<P>Robert L Civiak </P>

<P>This report is divided into two parts: the first discusses the AEC's
history, the second deals with the break-up of the AEC and resulting agencies.
</P>

<P><B>GOV-6004</B> $.80 8pp 1/93 </P>

<P>A Short History of Nuclear Regulation, 1946-1990 </P>

<P>J. Samuel Walker Historian, NRC </P>

<P>In this chapter, (chapter 3) many issues especially NRC's public credibility,
are discussed (and whitewashed). </P>

<P><B>GOV-6005</B> $.20 2pp 1995 </P>

<P>&quot;Implications for Seismic Qualification of U.S. Nuclear Power Plants
Resulting form New Data from Kobe, Japan and Northridge...&quot; </P>

<P>NIRS </P>

<P>This briefing paper discusses new data from studies on close-to-the-surface
tremors on secondary faults and implications on basic siting criteria used
to license U.S. reactors. </P>

<P><B>GOV-8000</B> $.40 4pp 9/28/89 </P>

<P>&quot;Jurisdictional Conflicts Under the Nuclear Whistle-Blowers Act'
</P>

<P>David S. Pearson, Public Utilities Fortnightly </P>

<P>The jurisdictional conflict is with section 210 of the Energy Reorganization
Act, which allows whistle-blowers 30 days to file a complaint or the case
is automatically under federal jurisdiction. </P>

<P><B>GOV-8001</B> $.20 2pp Winter 1994 </P>

<P>&quot;Making Waves at DOE&quot; </P>

<P>GAP, Bridging the Gap </P>

<P>This article delineates Hazel O'Leary's positive policy on whistleblowers,
saying that they are a necessary part of safe performance. </P>

<P><A HREF="toolhome.htm"><IMG SRC="nirslog2.gif" HEIGHT=58 WIDTH=130></A>
</P>

</BODY>
</HTML>
