<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE>Toolbox: Weapons</TITLE>
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0Gold (Win95; I) [Netscape]">
   <META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Preferred Customer">
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<H1>THE NIRS TOOLBOX</H1>

<P>
<HR></P>

<H4>Human history becomes more and more a race between education and catastrophe.
~ H.G. Wells</H4>

<P>A ~ indicates that this Toolbox entry contains information relevant
to the health effects of low-dose and/or long-term exposure to radiation.
</P>

<H4>There are two ways to order materials from the NIRS&nbsp;toolbox:</H4>

<H4>1. The fast way: fax your order to NIRS at 202-462-2183. Include your
Visa, Mastercard or Discover Card number, expiration date, and signature.
</H4>

<H4>2. The slow way: mail to NIRS at 1424 16th Street NW, #404, Washington
DC 20036. Please make your check payable to NIRS. Thank you.</H4>

<H4>Unfortunately, due to problems collecting payment on invoiced orders,
all orders must now be prepaid (we're not a collection agency after all,
we're an environmental group...)</H4>

<P>
<HR></P>

<H2>PROLIFERATION/WEAPONS</H2>

<P><B>WE-2000</B> $1.40 14pp Fall 1990 </P>

<P>&quot;In the Shadow of the Bomb: Cleaning Up After DOE&quot; </P>

<P>Dick Russell, The Amicus Journal </P>

<P>This article tracks the bomb making process and interviews workers and
downwinders. It investigates various dump and manufacturing sites of weapons
grade material and discusses the pernicious mess of it all. </P>

<P><B>WE-2001</B> $4.00 40 pp 1/88-2/88 </P>

<P>&quot;We Turn Back The Clock&quot; </P>

<P>Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists </P>

<P>A number of articles provide a good overview of the nuclear weapons
production facilities, including information on the release of radioactive
materials at Hanford during the 1940s and '50s. </P>

<P><B>WE-2002</B> $.50 5 pp not dated </P>

<P>Major Sites Within the Nuclear Defense Complex </P>

<P>A map showing the sites and a list which gives the mission and resulting
environmental degradation are included. The map is from a GAO report and
the list was compiled by Environmental Policy Institute. </P>

<P><B>WE-2003</B> $2.10 21pp 1994 </P>

<P>&quot;Management and Disposition of Excess Weapons Plutonium&quot; </P>

<P>National Academy of Sciences Executive Summary </P>

<P>Recommendations made by the National Academy of Sciences for the dismantlement
and management of excess plutonium and uranium. </P>

<P><B>WE-3000</B> $.80 8pp 8/85 </P>

<P>&quot;Nuclear Proliferation: The Peaceful atom as the Trojan Horse&quot;
</P>

<P>Eckhard Festag, NEIS News </P>

<P>This article recaps the nuclear fuel cycle and illustrates how anyone
with a certain level of civilian nuclear technology could use this knowledge
to manufacture nuclear warheads. </P>

<P><B>WE-3001</B> $.50 5pp 12/85 </P>

<P>&quot;When Reactors Become Weapons&quot; </P>

<P>NIRS, Groundswell </P>

<P>This article discusses the &quot;war-target&quot; dangers of using nuclear
power and the shifting morality which would allow such &quot;targets&quot;
to be used. </P>

<P><A HREF="toolhome.htm"><IMG SRC="nirslog2.gif" HEIGHT=58 WIDTH=130></A>
</P>

</BODY>
