<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE>Toolbox: Radiation</TITLE>
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0Gold (Win95; I) [Netscape]">
   <META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Preferred Customer">
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<H1>THE NIRS TOOLBOX</H1>

<P>
<HR></P>

<H4>Human history becomes more and more a race between education and catastrophe.
~ H.G. Wells</H4>

<P>A ~ indicates that this Toolbox entry contains information relevant
to the health effects of low-dose and/or long-term exposure to radiation.
</P>

<H4>There are two ways to order materials from the NIRS&nbsp;toolbox:</H4>

<H4>1. The fast way: fax your order to NIRS at 202-462-2183. Include your
Visa, Mastercard or Discover Card number, expiration date, and signature.
</H4>

<H4>2. The slow way: mail to NIRS at 1424 16th Street NW, #404, Washington
DC 20036. Please make your check payable to NIRS. Thank you.</H4>

<H4>Unfortunately, due to problems collecting payment on invoiced orders,
all orders must now be prepaid (we're not a collection agency after all,
we're an environmental group...)</H4>

<P>
<HR></P>

<H2>RADIATION AND HEALTH HAZARDS</H2>

<P><B>RHH-1000</B> $10.00 occasionally updated </P>

<P>Radiation and Health Hazards Primer Packet </P>

<P>A good overview of how radiation affects the environment and human health.
Articles from Bulletin of Atomic Scientists, Southwest Research and Information
Center, and Groundswell are included. </P>

<P><B>RHH-1001</B> $10.00 occasionally updated </P>

<P>Environmental Health Effects of Nuclear Power Packet </P>

<P>A compilation of key, detailed studies to determine the impact of nuclear
power isotopic releases on the surrounding public. Studies include research
by Dr. John Gofman, Dr. Ernest Sternglass and more. </P>

<P><B>RHH-2000</B> $.40 4 pp </P>

<P>Radioactive Waste and Its Health Effects in a Nutshell </P>

<P>Carol Brouillet from The Invisible Nuclear War </P>

<P>A fairly in-depth explanation of radioactive health hazards to various
parts of the body and during various stages of life. </P>

<P><B>RHH-2001</B> $1.50 15pp 10/85-12/85 </P>

<P>&quot;The Health Effects of Radiation: The Controversy Continues&quot;
</P>

<P>SRIC, The Workbook </P>

<P>A bit old, but still an excellent primer on radiation standards and
the hazards to workers in nuclear facilities. Detailed list of references.
</P>

<P><B>RHH-2002</B> $1.20 12pp 1/84 </P>

<P>&quot;Coal Energy vs. Nuclear Energy: A Comparison of Radiological Risks&quot;
</P>

<P>V. De Santis and L. Longo, Health Physics </P>

<P>Detailed rebuttal of industry claims that coal plants release more radioactivity
than nuclear plants. </P>

<P><B>RHH-2003</B> $4.50 45pp 1993 </P>

<P>The Invisible Nuclear War </P>

<P>Bertell, Gofman, et.al, Carol Brouillet, ed. </P>

<P>Excerpts from the book bring together many famous scientists and doctors
critical of nuclear technology and give suggestions for combating the nuclear
complex. An order form for the full book is included. </P>

<P><B>RHH-2004</B> $.80 8pp not dated </P>

<P>Low Dose Radiological Research on Child and Adult Health Risks form
Exposure to Low-Level Radiation </P>

<P>Deborah Katz, Citizens Awareness Network </P>

<P>This is a bibliographical list of many good sources on low-dose radiation
and the health risks it poses. A great list of resources. Divided by method
of exposure with special sections on downs syndrome and tritium. </P>

<P><B>RHH-2005</B> $4.20 42pp 1992 </P>

<P>Understanding Radiation Health Effects: A Guide for Communities At Risk
</P>

<P>Dianne Quigley, Childhood Cancer Research Inst. </P>

<P>In this general, yet highly informative publication, Quigley discusses
many aspects of radiation and exposure to it. She discusses different types
of radiation and how these affect the body, where they come from and how
they are measured. She also discusses contaminant pathways and aspects
of epidemiology, including the assessment of risks from long-term, low-dose
exposure. ~ </P>

<P><B>RHH-3000</B> $.60 6pp 4/6/92 </P>

<P>&quot;Acceptable Risk?&quot; </P>

<P>Dr. Karl Z. Morgan, Corporate Crime Reporter </P>

<P>In an interview, Dr. Morgan speaks to the low-dose, long-term exposure
health issue. He also discusses the role of health physicists in this issue
and how many are in the debt of the nuclear industry. </P>

<P><B>RHH-3001</B> $.40 4pp 11/93 </P>

<P>&quot;What Is Humanity's Most Harmful Law?&quot; </P>

<P>Gofman and O'Connor </P>

<P>This is an excellent primer on radiation and health issues. It briefly
explores the meaning of &quot;no safe dose&quot; and the concept of &quot;taxing&quot;
environmental polluters among other moral and legal issues. </P>

<P><B>RHH-3002</B> $10.00 Updated periodically </P>

<P>Radiation Standards </P>

<P>Documents include admission that EPA radiation standards do not meet
proposed Clean Air Act guidelines, a GAO report requested by John Glenn
concerning the currently inconsistent radiation standards and more. </P>

<P><B>RHH 4250</B> $.30 3 pp 6/85 </P>

<P>Dosimetry </P>

<P>Monte Greinetz, PhD </P>

<P>Dr. Greinetz lays out a plant to study the health effects of TMI and
summarizes three of his papers on the subject. He discusses transport models
for Xenon plumes and their touchdowns and thyroid cancers. </P>

<P><B>RHH 4500</B> $.30 3pp Summer 1989 </P>

<P>&quot;More Than 10 Leukemia and Cancer Deaths Per 10,000 Person-Rem&quot;
</P>

<P>Kozo Inaoka, Int'l Perspectives in Public Health </P>

<P>Taken from the reassessment of A-bomb radiation air dose at Hiroshima
and Nagasaki. Inaoka is a member of Union of Scientists Against Nuclear
Power Plants in Japan. With references and tables. </P>

<P><B>RHH-5000</B> $3.00 30pp 1979 </P>

<P>&quot;Radiation Exposure to the Public from Radioactive Emissions of
Nuclear Power Stations&quot; </P>

<P>B. Franke, et al., Univ. of Heidelberg </P>

<P>A study which calls into question the NRC's methods of calculating emissions
from nuclear plants. </P>

<P><B>RHH-5001</B> $2.80 28pp 11/24/87 </P>

<P>&quot;Childhood Cancers in the UK and Their Relation to Background Radiation&quot;
</P>

<P>Drs. Stewart and Kneale Conference paper </P>

<P>Results of two independent data sets, the Oxford Childhood Cancer Study
and the National Radiological Protection Board (UK), conclude that 66%
to 90% of all childhood cancer deaths are due to in utero exposure to terrestrial
background levels of (gamma) radiation. A paper prepared for the International
Conference on Biological Effects of ionizing Radiation, Hammersmith Hospital,
London.~ </P>

<P><B>RHH-5002</B> $2.40 24pp not dated </P>

<P>&quot;Low Dose Epidemiological Findings on Child Health and Adult Risks
of Low-Level Radiation&quot; </P>

<P>Childhood Cancer Research Inst. </P>

<P>In summarized updates, the author presents the findings of recent radiation
studies of nuclear worker exposure and findings in communities near nuclear
facilities and the potential role this exposure has in child health. The
sources include both US and British studies and at the end these results
are summarized.~ </P>

<P><B>RHH-5003</B> $15+$4s+h 342 pp 1995 </P>

<P>Preventing Breast Cancer: The Story of a Major, Proven, Preventable
Cause of this Disease </P>

<P>John W. Gofman, MD, PhD CNR </P>

<P>&quot;The author shows that past exposure to ionizing radiation-primarily
medical x-rays-is responsible for about 75 percent of the breast-cancer
problem in the United States.&quot; The author concludes since irradiation
is preventable, so is breast cancer resulting from it.~ </P>

<P><B>RHH-5004</B> $30+$5s+h 1990 </P>

<P>Radiation-lnduced Cancer from Low-Dose Exposure: An Independent Analysis
</P>

<P>John W. Gofman, MD, PhD CNR </P>

<P>This work refutes claims that very low-dose exposures to ionizing radiation
fail to cause carcinogenesis, indicating that NO level of radiation exposure
is without risk.~ </P>

<P><B>RHH-6000</B> $.70 7pP 1/84 </P>

<P>&quot;Cancer Incidence in an Area of Radioactive Fallout Downwind from
the Nevada Test Site&quot; </P>

<P>Dr. Carl Johnson, Journal of the AMA </P>

<P>This article gives a good summary of existing research about the health
effects of fallout exposure. </P>

<P><B>RHH-6001</B> $1.50 15pp 11/77 </P>

<P>&quot;Radiation Exposures of Hanford Workers Dying from Cancer and Other
Causes&quot; </P>

<P>Mancuso, Stewart &amp; Kneale, Health Physics </P>

<P>The researchers examine the link between low-dose radiation at Hanford
and the incidence of cancer.~ </P>

<P><B>RHH-6002</B> $1.00 l0pp 3/87 </P>

<P>&quot;Leukemia in Five Massachusetts Coastal Towns&quot; </P>

<P>Dr. Sidney Cobb, et.al, American Epidemiologic Society </P>

<P>This is an abstract of a health study which concludes that there is
an excess of leukemia in five coastal towns north of Plymouth which might
be attributable to airborne radioactivity from the Pilgrim nuclear plant.
Interesting concept of radiation circulating out to sea and back with coastal
winds. ~ </P>

<P><B>RHH-6003</B> $1.40 14pp Fall 1984 </P>

<P>&quot;Environmental Influence on Survival of Low Birth Weight Infants
in Wisconsin 1963-1975&quot; </P>

<P>Dr. Rosalie Bertell, Int'l Perspectives in Public Health </P>

<P>Epidemiological study of increased incidence of low birth weight babies
living near nuclear power plants.~ </P>

<P><B>RHH-6004</B> $2.10 21pp 1993/1994 </P>

<P>Radiation and Breast Cancer </P>

<P>Gofman, Sternglass, Gould </P>

<P>Two report summaries, one which examines the relative risks of breast
cancer due to medical radiation exposure (Gofman) and a second which views
breast cancer incidents as related to nuclear weapons fallout and radioactive
releases from nuclear power .~ RHH-6005 $1.10 11pp X-Rays: Health Effects
of Common Exams Gofman and O'Connor In this excerpted chapter, the authors
discuss the controversy of mammography &quot; benefits&quot;.~ </P>

<P><B>RHH-6005</B> $1.10 11pp </P>

<P>X-Rays: Health Effects of Common Exams </P>

<P>Gofman and O'Conner </P>

<P>In this excerpted chapter, the authors discuss the controversy of mammography
&quot;benefits&quot;. ~ </P>

<P><B>RHH-6006</B> $1.30 13pp 1978 </P>

<P>Re-Analysis of Data Relating to the Hanford Study of the Cancer Risks
of Radiation Workers </P>

<P>Kneale, Stewart and Mancuso </P>

<P>In this analysis, the researches find that the data &quot;produced evidence
of cancer hazard from low doses of external radiation even when delivered
at low dose rates.~ </P>

<P><B>RHH-6007</B> $1.30 1 3pp not dated </P>

<P>&quot;The Carcinogenic, Mutagenic, Teratogenic and Transmutational Effects
of Tritium&quot; </P>

<P>Citizens Awareness Network </P>

<P>A brief paper giving information on tritium: what it is, its health
affects and how it affects the citizens of the Deer River Valley area in
Massachusetts. Tritium dumping into the river by the now closed Yankee
Rowe nuclear plant is believed by many to be the cause of the many health
problems plaguing the citizens. An extensive bibliography is included.
</P>

<P><B>RHH-6008</B> $.60 6pp 3/91 </P>

<P>Mortality Among Workers at Oak Ridge National Laboratory </P>

<P>Steve Wing, PhD, JAMA </P>

<P>This study finds that while low mortality was found among white men
working at Oak Ridge for most causes of death, leukemia mortality was significantly
higher. </P>

<P><B>RHH-7500</B> $1.60 16pp 12/83 </P>

<P>&quot;Uranium Legacy&quot; </P>

<P>SRIC, The Workbook </P>

<P>Authoritative overview of what is known about the health effects of
uranium mining and milling. </P>

<P><B>RHH-8000</B> $.40 4pp 1/28/94 </P>

<P>Radiation: Balancing the Record </P>

<P>Charles Mann, Science </P>

<P>This article attempts to &quot;balance&quot; the information on human
radiation experiments by detailing certain procedures and justifying the
means by the medical data that was obtained. The author claims that some
people gave consent and that these experiments and their researchers should
not be anathematized. </P>

<P><B>RHH-8001</B> $1.40 14pp 1985 </P>

<P>&quot;Atomic Survivors&quot; </P>

<P>National Association of Radiation Victims </P>

<P>Profiles of the forgotten victims US. atomic development: veterans,
test site workers, uranium miners, downwinders, and Japanese-Americans
in Japan during World War II. </P>

<P><B>RHH-8002</B> $1.20 12pp 5/84-6/84 </P>

<P>&quot;We're Sick of Being Guinea Pigs&quot; </P>

<P>Laura Reed, Science for the People </P>

<P>Articles examine effects of US atomic testing on residents of Marshall
Islands. </P>

<P><B>RHH-8003</B> $.70 7pp 1994 </P>

<P>Radiation Experiments: Basic Information </P>

<P>A list of radiation exposures, who initiated them and when, and why
they were conducted. A second document announces the current available
database on human research subjects. Information is updated periodically.
</P>

<P><B>RHH-8004</B> $1.00 l0pp 11/19/89 </P>

<P>&quot;America's Radiation Victims: The Hidden Files&quot; </P>

<P>Clifford T. Honicker, New York Times Magazine </P>

<P>Retraces the steps surrounding the government and Atomic Energy Commission
cover-up of a 1946 laboratory accident during nuclear bomb testing. Draws
the conclusion that this incident may have set a precedent of secrecy for
other cases involving atomic veterans and civilians exposed to radiation.
</P>

<P><B>RHH-8005</B> $.90 9pp 1994 </P>

<P>Radiation Experiments at Various Universities </P>

<P>Articles from the New York Times, Washington Post, and more, encapsulate
the radiation experiments at various American universities. </P>

<P><B>RHH-8006</B> $1.40 14pp 3/94 </P>

<P>&quot;US Government-Sponsored Radiation Research on Humans 1945-1975&quot;
</P>

<P>Michael McCally et al., Medicine &amp; Global Survival </P>

<P>This article discusses the revelation of the human radiation experiments,
who was affected including nuclear weapons workers and atomic veterans,
and makes recommendations on handling this atrocity. Also included is a
brochure which introduces the reader to the experiment helpline and provides
a brief background on the subject. </P>

<P><B>RHH-8007</B> $1.00 1994 </P>

<P>National Committee for Radiation Victims Information </P>

<P>Basic information on the Committee and Task Force on Human Rights and
Radiation Exposure. List of Task Force members, and organizational statement
and two news articles. Packet will be updated periodically. </P>

<P><B>RHH-8008</B> $.60 6pp 10/31/88 </P>

<P>&quot;The Nuclear Scandal&quot; </P>

<P>Jerome Cramer, et al., Time </P>

<P>A general article, dealing with the deceptive action of nuclear weapons
manufacturers and government regulatory bodies. Although the article centers
on the Fernald plant in Ohio, it also touches on the effects of many other
weapons plants on human health and the environment. </P>

<P><B>RHH-8009</B> $.90 9pp 9/90 </P>

<P>&quot;Indecent Exposure&quot; </P>

<P>Michele Stenehjem, Natural History </P>

<P>This article addresses the shroud of secrecy which surrounded the Hanford
Engineer works during forty years of weapons production. Reviewed in the
article are the potential and actual effects on the salmon industry, the
storage of radioactive materials in tissue, and the environmental consequences.
</P>

<P><B>RHH-8500</B> $8.20 82 pp 1992-1994 </P>

<P>Rung C. Tang Case </P>

<P>Included are several newsclips, three affidavits from experts who support
Tang's allegations, a copy of Tang's complain and hearing motions. Publications
can be ordered separately if desired. </P>

<P><B>RHH-8501</B> $.20 2 pp 7/94 </P>

<P>Fernald Workers' Lawsuit Settled, DOE News </P>

<P>A brief discussion of the terms of the settlement made by DOE to the
workers of the Fernald Nuclear Weapons plant in Ohio. </P>

<P><B>RHH-9000</B> $1.30 13pp 4/88-6/88 </P>

<P>&quot;Food Irradiation: Its Environmental Threat, lts Toxic Connection&quot;
</P>

<P>Judith H. Johnsrud, The Workbook </P>

<P>A very thorough and accessible background article which discusses the
food irradiation process, the symbol, the DOE's interest in the process
and the potential effects of this radiation on human health. </P>

<P><B>RHH-9001</B> $1.10 11pp 10/88 </P>

<P>&quot;Food Irradiation: Contaminating Our Food&quot; </P>

<P>Richard Piccioni, The Ecologist </P>

<P>&quot;Food irradiation has long been promoted by the nuclear industry
as an effective and safe means of preserving food at minimum risk to the
public. In fact, irradiation not only depletes the nutritional value of
food but also masks the bacterial contamination of rotting food...(it)
exposes the consumer to...carcinogens...(and) is an unscrupulous attempt
to find a commercial use for nuclear wastes.&quot; </P>

<P><B>RHH-9002</B> $3.10 31 pp </P>

<P>Food Irradiation Information </P>

<P>This compilation contains a myriad of food irradiation information.
Among the goodies are an article on resulting health effects, several letters
from organizations protesting food irradiation, a brief fact sheet, and
neighborhood network information so that you can spread awareness of this
and other issues in your community. Also included is a &quot;Byproducts
Utilization Program&quot; brochure and an article explaining why it is
in the DOE's best interest to irradiate our food. </P>

<P><B>RHH-9003</B> $1.70 17 pp 6/87 </P>

<P>Food Irradiation: Excerpts of Testimony </P>

<P>Richard Piccioni, PhD, AREA, Inc. </P>

<P>Testimony before the Subcommittee on Health and the Environment of the
US House Committee on Energy and Commerce, the New Jersey State Assembly
and the Board of Commissioners of Alachua County Florida, stating the potential
dangers and areas of concern regarding food Irradiation. </P>

<P><B>RHH-9004</B> $.50 5pp 3/15/88 </P>

<P>Concerns About the Nuclear Irradiation of Food: Risks to Workers </P>

<P>Carl Johnson, MD, MPH </P>

<P>Johnson discusses actual cases of worker contamination at irradiation
plants and follows up with cancer contraction rates for these workers.
</P>

<P><A HREF="toolhome.htm"><IMG SRC="nirslog2.gif" HEIGHT=58 WIDTH=130></A>
</P>

