<HEAD>
   <TITLE>Toolbox: Radioactive Waste</TITLE>
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0Gold (Win95; I) [Netscape]">
   <META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Preferred Customer">
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<H1>THE NIRS TOOLBOX</H1>

<P>
<HR></P>

<H4>Human history becomes more and more a race between education and catastrophe.
~ H.G. Wells</H4>

<P>A ~ indicates that this Toolbox entry contains information relevant
to the health effects of low-dose and/or long-term exposure to radiation.
</P>

<H4>There are two ways to order materials from the NIRS&nbsp;toolbox:</H4>

<H4>1. The fast way: fax your order to NIRS at 202-462-2183. Include your
Visa, Mastercard or Discover Card number, expiration date, and signature.
</H4>

<H4>2. The slow way: mail to NIRS at 1424 16th Street NW, #404, Washington
DC 20036. Please make your check payable to NIRS. Thank you.</H4>

<H4>Unfortunately, due to problems collecting payment on invoiced orders,
all orders must now be prepaid (we're not a collection agency after all,
we're an environmental group...)</H4>

<P>
<HR></P>

<H2>RADIOACTIVE WASTE</H2>

<P><B>RW-1000</B> $6.80 68pp 11/13/83-11/20/83 </P>

<P>&quot;Forevermore: Nuclear Waste in America&quot; </P>

<P>James B. Steele and Donald L. Bartlett, Philadelphia Inquirer </P>

<P>A reprint of an 8-part series on radioactive waste in the United States.
Two Pulitzer Prize winning reporters investigate commercial and military
waste history and practices, failures and cover-ups. </P>

<P><B>RW-1001</B> $1.70 17pp 3/23/92 </P>

<P>&quot;Civilian Nuclear Waste Disposal&quot; </P>

<P>Mark Hold, CRS Issue Brief </P>

<P>This brief discusses the generation and disposal issues surrounding
the various types of nuclear waste (from HLRW to transuranic to so-called
LLRW). </P>

<P><B>RW-1002</B> $.20 2 pp 3/20/93-3/21/93 </P>

<P>The Big Lie </P>

<P>Mary Olson, NIRS </P>

<P>This fact sheet was created for the New England Environmental Conference
and debunks many industry myths about anthropogenic radioactivity, especially
that in different waste stream classifications. </P>

<P><B>RW-1003</B> $.60 6 pp 3/90 </P>

<P>Managing the Nation's Nuclear Waste </P>

<P>OCRWM DOE </P>

<P>A government document designed to make us think all radioactive waste
streams are being adequately handled. It briefly touches on nuclear power
history, geologic disposal, MRS, transport, and the nuclear waste fund.
</P>

<P><B>RW-1004</B> $5.00 April 1992 </P>

<P>A Mountain of Waste Fifty Years High: The Proceedings of a National
Symposium on Radioactive Waste </P>

<P>Minard Hamilton, ed. </P>

<P>This compilation summarizes presentations made at the symposium by Drs.
Bertell, Johnsrud, Resnikoff, and many others. The symposium was called
to discuss all aspects of radioactive waste including health effects and
&quot;disposal&quot; methods. Many speakers make the point that since the
first waste generation, resulting from uranium purification at the Mallinckrodt
Chemical Works in St. Louis, radioactive waste still haunts us and will
continue to do so. </P>

<P><B>RW-1005</B> $10.00 periodically updated </P>

<P>Independent Presidential Commission Packet </P>

<P>Includes fact sheets, letters from several congress members, governors
and citizens on the call for an independent presidential commission to
review the nation's waste laws. </P>

<P><B>RW-2000</B> $.80 8pp 5/86 </P>

<P>&quot;Incineration: What Comes Out of the Stack?&quot; </P>

<P>Sierra Club </P>

<P>Assesses the radiological and other health hazards of incinerating radioactive
wastes and considers types of waste burned, dioxins, trouble areas, and
alternatives. </P>

<P><B>RW-2001</B> $.40 4 pp not dated </P>

<P>Incineration of Radioactive and Mixed Waste </P>

<P>IEER Fact Sheet </P>

<P>A brief overview of health and environmental concerns of burning radioactive
waste and regulation of this method. </P>

<P><B>RW-2002</B> $2.00 20pp no date </P>

<P>&quot;Environmental Evaluation of Modifications to TVA's Low-Level Radwaste
Management Plans&quot; The study that convinced Tennessee Valley Authority
to abandon plans to incinerate radioactive waste. Invaluable for anyone
fighting a radwaste incinerator in their locality. </P>

<P><B>RW-4000</B> $.50 5pp 1985 </P>

<P>&quot;Problems with Military Nuclear Waste&quot; </P>

<P>William F. Lawless, Bulletin of Atomic Scientists </P>

<P>Article examines problems at DOE's Savannah River Plant and claims the
DOE is careless in their management of waste. Lawless is a former senior
project engineer in DOE's radioactive waste management research and operations.
</P>

<P><B>RW-4001</B> $1.30 13pp </P>

<P>FUSRAP Information (Formerly Utilized Sites Remedial Action Program)
</P>

<P>Includes the abbreviated FUSRAP story of one neighborhood in St. Louis,
MO and one person's rebuttal of a news story that contended the cancers
surrounding FUSRAP sites could not possibly be related to radioactivity
of the material. Also includes a map of FUSRAP sites. </P>

<P><B>RW-4002</B> $1.00 10pp 8/88-9/88 </P>

<P>&quot;Radioactive Waste: Hidden Legacy of the Arms Race&quot; </P>

<P>Robert Alvarez and Arjun Makhijani, Technology Review </P>

<P>A look at the disgraceful handling of nuclear wastes by the nation's
nuclear weapons facilities. One of the best introductions to the subject.
</P>

<P>
<HR></P>

<H2>Deregulation</H2>

<P><B>RWD-8000</B> $3.50 35pp 12/89 </P>

<P>&quot;Imminent Danger: Radioactive Waste Dumping in Minnesota&quot;
</P>

<P>Minnesota PIRG </P>

<P>This paper covers the problems associated with the deregulation of nuclear
waste, and offers a plan of action. Valuable information for citizens groups
or individuals concerned with these issues. With conclusions, glossary
and appendix. </P>

<P><B>RWD-8001</B> $1.00 10pp 9/12/91 </P>

<P>Regarding the Public Health Implications of the Nuclear Regulatory Commission
Policy: BRC, Theodore Davis, M.D. </P>

<P>In his statement before the Energy and Environment Committee, Dr. Davis
gives supporting scientific information why BRC was (and is) a bad idea.
</P>

<P>
<HR></P>

<H2>High Level Radioactive Waste</H2>

<P><B>RWH-1000</B> $10.00 periodically updated </P>

<P>Dry Cask Packet </P>

<P>This packet contains NIRS nuclear waste fact sheet and comments on regulations
concerning storage of irradiated fuel along with a paper on transport by
Dr. Marvin Resnikoff and court decisions. </P>

<P><B>RWH-1001</B> $10.00 periodically updated </P>

<P>Interim Storage Packet </P>

<P>Includes diagrams of shipping casks and artists' conception of an interim
storage facility along with a fact sheet on Yucca Mountain and Groundswell
and Workbook articles. </P>

<P><B>RWH-2000</B> $1.30 13pp Fall 1992 </P>

<P>&quot;For Sale: Nuclear Waste Sites-Anyone Buying?&quot; </P>

<P>Don Hancock, The Workbook </P>

<P>An overview of the DOE's attempt to find a high level radioactive waste
repository site. </P>

<P><B>RWH-2001</B> $.70 7pp 1995 </P>

<P>Cost Basis for Storage of High-Level Nuclear Waste </P>

<P>Donald L. Darling LCDR, USN Retired </P>

<P>Using data from South Texas Nuclear Project, Darling, formerly of the
US Navy, has estimated the cost projection for storage of irradiated fuel
for 100,000 years. This is a conservative estimate in 1994 dollars. Supporting
calculations included. </P>

<P><B>RWH-3000</B> $.60 6pp 3/16/95 </P>

<P>Affidavit of Mary Olson on behalf of PICANS, Down River Alliance, et
al. </P>

<P>Mary C. Olson of NIRS </P>

<P>In this affidavit, Ms. Olson explores the dangers of using faulty casks
to store irradiated fuel rods. </P>

<P><B>RWH-3001</B> $1.60 16pp 5/3/93 </P>

<P>Affidavit of Marvin Resnikoff, PhD </P>

<P>Marvin Resnikoff </P>

<P>In Dr. Resnikoff's affidavit he says an Environmental Impact Statement
is necessary before strong radioactive waste in dry casks at Palisades.
He also mentions uncertainties concerning accident analysis and temperature.
</P>

<P><B>RWH-3002</B> $6.00 </P>

<P>Faulty Cask Information </P>

<P>Compilation includes many news articles and activist group fact sheets.
NRC notice of violation, Mary Olson and Dr. Resnikoff's affidavits are
also included. If you ordered the dry cask packet (RWH-1000), then you
already have this information. </P>

<P><B>RWH-3003</B> $1.70 17 pp 1995 </P>

<P>Multi-Purpose Canister Information </P>

<P>A compilation of four articles. One fact sheet by DOE shows pictures
of the yet-to-be constructed canister and gives an explanation of how it
would work. Also included are remarks of Dr. Marvin Resnikoff at the MPC
Workshop which highlight concerns of creep corrosion cracking of fuel cladding
and a NIRS background paper on the MPC. The fourth is an early item on
the smaller MPC design currently in use. </P>

<P><B>RWH-4000</B> $3.80 38pp 1979 </P>

<P>Accident Hazards of Spent Fuel Storage at Nuclear Power Plants and Off-Site
Storage Facilities Richard Webb, Ph.D. </P>

<P>&quot;An analysis of the accident hazards of storing highly radioactive,
spent fuel rods in spent fuel storage pools at nuclear power plants and
at other off-site, storage facilities, with special reference to the Zion
nuclear power plant near Chicago, Illinois.&quot; </P>

<P><B>RWH-4001</B> $2.60 26pp 1994 </P>

<P>Presentation to the NRC on Susquehanna Steam Electric Station Design
Deficiencies for Loss of Spent Fuel Pool Cooling </P>

<P>Lochbaum and Prevatte </P>

<P>This briefing paper identifies generic design deficiencies in General
Electric Boiling Water Reactors involving the potential failure of cooling
capability for the high level radioactive storage ponds located at each
of the 38 operational BWRs. A newspaper article is also included. </P>

<P><B>RWH-4002</B> $.60 6pp 12/8/86 </P>

<P>Worst Ever Nuclear Waste Storage Accident Occurs in Georgia </P>

<P>Public Citizen </P>

<P>Press Release and background information on the 141,000 gallon spill
of water from the irradiated fuel pool at the Hatch plant in Georgia. </P>

<P><B>RWH-4003</B> $17.00 170pp 1987 </P>

<P>&quot;Beyond Design-Basis Accidents in Spent Fuel Pools&quot; </P>

<P>Brookhaven National Laboratory </P>

<P>Report on the risk of beyond design-basis accidents in spent fuel pools
for a PWR and BWR. Finds that the health consequences of such accidents
are quite serious and proposes preventative measures for these plants.
</P>

<P><B>RWH-5000</B> $.90 9pp 9/85 </P>

<P>Fact Sheet on Monitored Retrievable Storage (MRS) </P>

<P>OCRWM DOE </P>

<P>Prepared by the DOE as a &quot;public service for information and discussion
services.&quot; MRS facilities would serve as temporary storage and packaging
facilities for &quot;spent&quot; i.e., highly radioactive, fuel. This fact
sheet discusses testing of stored waste as well as consolidation and conditioning
for &quot;permanent&quot; disposal. </P>

<P><B>RWH-5001</B> $1.20 12pp 1986 </P>

<P>&quot;The MRS: An Assessment of Its Need and Feasibility&quot; </P>

<P>Summary of a study by E. William Colglazier of the University of Tennessee
in Knoxville. The report looks at the DOE's proposed plan for a MRS facility
for high level nuclear waste. While the document is essentially pro-nuclear
and does not come up with any creative ideas concerning the waste problem,
it does provide insight into the MRS and DOE's conduct. </P>

<P><B>RWH-6000</B> $.60 6pp 2/21/81 </P>

<P>&quot;Salt Will Not Work&quot; </P>

<P>Sierra Club </P>

<P>Review of the problems associated with disposing of high-level radioactive
waste in an underground geologic salt formation, the nuclear industry's
favored solution (at one time) to the radioactive waste problem. </P>

<P><B>RWH-6300</B> $.50 5pp 11/18/90 </P>

<P>'Mountain of Trouble&quot; </P>

<P>William J. Broad, New York Times Magazine </P>

<P>Broad's article recounts a decade-long battle by geologist Jerry Szymanski
to get unbiased scientific review of his data showing there is a good chance
of groundwater welling up from beneath the planned high level radioactive
waste repository. </P>

<P><B>RWH-6301</B> $.40 4pp 8/6/94 </P>

<P>&quot;Burial Insurance&quot; </P>

<P>Margaret Kriz, National Journal </P>

<P>Describes the radioactive waste burial issue as it pertains to Yucca
Mountain and delineates the sides of the issue and the cost of &quot;containment.&quot;
</P>

<P><B>RWH-6302</B> $2.80 28pp 12/22/94 </P>

<P>Yucca Mountain: A Crisis for Policy </P>

<P>James Flynn and Paul Slovic, Energy and Environment </P>

<P>This paper examines the lessons from the failed attempts to site a HLRW
dump in both Tennessee and Nevada and makes recommendations for devising
a new policy. </P>

<P><B>RWH-6303</B> $.55 </P>

<P>&quot;Why Does the State Oppose Yucca Mountain?&quot; and &quot;Scientific
and Technical Concerns&quot; Nuclear Waste Project Office State of Nevada
</P>

<P>These two brochures discuss why Yucca Mountain is technically unfeasible
and other reasons for the state's strong opposition to the proposed high-level
radioactive waste repository. These are fairly general, easily absorbed
publications that include a partial list of available resources. </P>

<P><B>RWH-6304</B> $3.80 38pp 10/87 </P>

<P>&quot;Laying Nuclear Waste to Rest&quot; </P>

<P>Environment Magazine </P>

<P>This issue focuses on the permanent disposal of high-level nuclear waste.
Four authors, including Nevada Governor Richard Bryan, analyst Luther Carter,
waste consultant John Gervers, and Congressman George Brown, Jr. discuss
their views on what to do with high-level nuclear waste. </P>

<P><B>RWH-6305</B> $.80 8pp 3/6/94 </P>

<P>&quot;Out of Sight, Out of Our Minds&quot; </P>

<P>Kai Erikson, New York Times Magazine </P>

<P>This article explores the need for Yucca Mountain and what the rush
to dispose of nuclear waste means to future generations. </P>

<P>
<HR></P>

<H2>&quot;Low Level&quot; Radioactive Waste</H2>

<P><B>RWL-1000</B> $10.00 updated periodically </P>

<P>&quot;Low-Level&quot; Radioactive Waste Packet </P>

<P>NIRS </P>

<P>This packet contains fact sheets on commercial &quot;low-level&quot;
radioactive waste, including decommissioning and transport, profiles of
past and current dumps, as well as recent alerts and an inspirational information
fact sheet for activists. </P>

<P><B>RWL-1001</B> $.20 2 pp 3/92 </P>

<P>&quot;Low Level&quot; Radioactive Waste fact sheet </P>

<P>NIRS </P>

<P>A concise description of low-level waste and the problems with this
classification: what it means, why it's dangerous. </P>

<P><B>RWL-1002</B> $10.00 updated periodically </P>

<P>Ward Valley Packet </P>

<P>This packet includes the Wilshire report which claims that there are
five pathways by which dump contents, including plutonium, can leak into
the Colorado river. Several news clips, reports and fact sheets concerning
the proposed dump and critiques of the National Academy of Science's panel
are included. </P>

<P><B>RWL-2000</B> $.40 4pp 1/93 </P>

<P>Radioactive Waste: The Medical Factor </P>

<P>Minard Hamilton, NIRS </P>

<P>This executive summary outlines the main medical uses of radionuclides
and discusses &quot;low-level&quot; radioactive waste. The whole report
is $20. </P>

<P><B>RWL-2001</B> $.80 8pp 1987 </P>

<P>&quot;Radioactive Waste: Buried forever&quot; </P>

<P>Radioactive Waste Campaign </P>

<P>Profiles the six commercial radioactive landfills, citing generic problems
and history of radioactive leaking with brief discussion of alternatives.
</P>

<P><B>RWL-2002</B> $.80 8pp not dated </P>

<P>A &quot;Low-Level&quot; Nuclear Waste Primer </P>

<P>Radioactive Waste Campaign </P>

<P>This is an excellent primer. Its format is frequently asked questions
about &quot;low-level&quot; radioactive waste and the answers are accurate
and straight-forward enough that non-experts will not get bogged down in
any &quot;nukespeak&quot;. </P>

<P><B>RWL-2003</B> $.80 8pp 1985 </P>

<P>Low-Level Nuclear Waste: Options for Storage </P>

<P>Radioactive Waste Campaign </P>

<P>Reviews and discusses current landfill leads, separation of waste types
and advantages of above ground storage. </P>

<P><B>RWL-2004</B> $.80 8 pp 4/90 </P>

<P>&quot;Low-Level Radioactive Waste: Gamma Rays in the Garbage&quot; </P>

<P>Scott Saleska, Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists </P>

<P>An older but still very informative article on the &quot;low-level&quot;
classification, and a good primer on deregulation and the real reasons
why this policy was so attractive to government agencies and industry.
</P>

<P><B>RWL-2005</B> $1.70 17pp 1992 </P>

<P>French Radioactive Waste Management: A Preliminary Overview </P>

<P>Mary Davis, Fndtn. for Global Sustainability </P>

<P>Material concerning the reality of the French nuclear dumps which is
not reflected in the nuclear industry's public relations campaign. Many
of France's problems parallel United States nuclear problems. </P>

<P><B>RWL-3500</B> $10.00 150pp not dated </P>

<P>Liability Packet-LLRW </P>

<P>Lynn Moorer </P>

<P>This compilation includes laws passed, documents on liability issues,
citizen suits, nuclear insurers and more. </P>

<P><B>RWL-7000</B> $2.70 27pp 1987 </P>

<P>&quot;Low-Level Radioactive Waste Management in North Carolina: An Economic
Analysis of Policy Options&quot; </P>

<P>Dr. Mark Stegeman, Economist </P>

<P>Dr. Stegeman's findings in a recent study of the cost to North Carolina
of withdrawal from the Southeast Compact. He challenges the Ebasco Study
of this issue, claiming that the costs of an alternative disposal technology
could be much less than predicted. </P>

<P><B>RWL-8000</B> $7.10 71pp 6/19/92 </P>

<P>New York vs. US, Supreme Court of the United States </P>

<P>This supreme court decision confirms that Congress overstepped the bounds
of federal authority when it mandated any state or compact that fails to
provide for storage of LLRW must take title to the waste, bearing all financial
responsibilities for it. The court ruled that this &quot;incentive&quot;
violated the 10th amendment of the Constitution. </P>

<P><B>RWL-9000</B> $2.50 25pp 9/89 </P>

<P>&quot;Nuclear Neighbors: The Central Interstate Reactors&quot; </P>

<P>Kemp Houck, Earthnet </P>

<P>A study of the utilities, financial institutions, trade and professional
associations, government agencies, and political affiliations involved
in the Central Interstate Radioactive Waste Compact. </P>

<P><B>RWL-9001</B> $1.30 13pp not dated </P>

<P>West Valley, the Insecure Landfill: A Survey of Problems at the West
Valley, NY Nuclear Center </P>

<P>Carol Mongerson </P>

<P>Gives the background of the Nuclear Service Center and resulting contamination
of soil and groundwater. It also includes a map of the burial grounds and
leak points. </P>

<P>
<HR></P>

<H2>Radioactive Waste Transport</H2>

<P><B>RWT-1000</B> $10.00 periodically updated </P>

<P>HLRW Transport Packet </P>

<P>NIRS </P>

<P>Included are current bills on HLRW transport, NIRS' factsheets on HLRW
and shipping, MPC background paper and a factsheet on the number and type
of shipment through each state. </P>

<P><B>RWT-2000</B> $.50 5pp 5/24/82 </P>

<P>&quot; A Doomsday Scenario on 57th Street&quot; </P>

<P>Harold Holzer, New York Magazine </P>

<P>Explores dangers of transporting radioactive wastes through urban areas
and encapsulates the New York City opposition in particular. </P>

<P><B>RWT-4000</B> $25 250 pp 1/95 </P>

<P>High-Level Nuclear Waste Shipping Route Maps to Yucca Mountain and Shipment
Number Estimates: MPC Base Case, Nuclear Waste Project Office </P>

<P>State of Nevada </P>

<P>This report, commissioned by the State of Nevada and undertaken by the
University out of Las Vegas, uses DOE data to determine the HLRW shipping
routes from the country's nuclear plants to Yucca Mountain NV. Included
are maps of transportation routes for each state number of shipments, etc..
Fact sheets on HLRW and MPC's also accompany the report Individual state
maps can be ordered at $.20 each. </P>

<P><B>RWT-5000</B> $1.70 17pp 3/83 </P>

<P>The Next Nuclear Gamble </P>

<P>Dr. Marvin Resnikoff </P>

<P>Excerpt and summary of 1983 transportation study by Dr. Marvin Resnikoff
</P>

