<BODY>

<H1>THE NIRS TOOLBOX</H1>

<P>
<HR></P>

<H4>Human history becomes more and more a race between education and catastrophe.
~ H.G. Wells</H4>

<P>A ~ indicates that this Toolbox entry contains information relevant
to the health effects of low-dose and/or long-term exposure to radiation.
</P>

<H4>There are two ways to order materials from the NIRS&nbsp;toolbox:</H4>

<H4>1. The fast way: fax your order to NIRS at 202-462-2183. Include your
Visa, Mastercard or Discover Card number, expiration date, and signature.
</H4>

<H4>2. The slow way: mail to NIRS at 1424 16th Street NW, #404, Washington
DC 20036. Please make your check payable to NIRS. Thank you.</H4>

<H4>Unfortunately, due to problems collecting payment on invoiced orders,
all orders must now be prepaid (we're not a collection agency after all,
we're an environmental group...)</H4>

<P>
<HR></P>

<H2>NUCLEAR POWER (GENERAL)</H2>

<P><B>NPG-1000</B> $10.00 updated periodically </P>

<P>Citizens' Monitoring Packet </P>

<P>Tips on how citizens can form a network to monitor nuclear plant radioactive
releases into the environment. Includes examples from current citizen monitoring
networks including Seabrook and TMI. </P>

<P><B>NPG-2000</B> $.20 2pp not dated </P>

<P>Reactor Processes </P>

<P>New York State Power Authority </P>

<P>A schematic and simplified explanation of the reactor at Indian Point,
a PWR and a generic BWR design. </P>

<P><B>NPG-3000</B> $.70 7pp 9/90 </P>

<P>&quot;Energy from Nuclear Power&quot; </P>

<P>Wolf Hafele, Scientific American </P>

<P>Although the author is in favor of nuclear power, this article presents
a good set of reasons why we should not continue trying to develop nuclear
power. Hafele addresses his largest concerns with nuclear power, waste,
safety and proliferation. He presents some solutions-which seem somewhat
idealistic. </P>

<P><B>NPG-3001</B> $1.90 19pp 12/2/84-12/5/84 </P>

<P>&quot;An Ambitious Nuclear Empire Goes Awry&quot; </P>

<P>Chip Brown, The Washington Post </P>

<P>In this four part series, Brown investigates the promise of nuclear
power and WPPSS' attempt to build five nuclear power stations at once.
Their attempt failed for many reasons, not the least of which was lower-than-expected
energy demand; a trend which continues today. </P>

<P><B>NPG-3002</B> $.90 9pp 1/91-2/91 </P>

<P>&quot;10 Blows that Stopped Nuclear Power&quot; </P>

<P>Charles Komanoff, The Electricity Journal </P>

<P>Komanoff, a well-known nuclear critic, provides a brief assessment of
how the nuclear industry failed. He points to 10 occurrences, some within
industry control, some resulting from external events. </P>

<P>
<HR></P>

<H3>REACTOR HAZARDS AND ACCIDENTS</H3>

<P><B>NPHA-1000</B> $1.90 19pp 1987 </P>

<P>NIRS Packet on the Peach Bottom Plant </P>

<P>A compilation of articles and reports generated after the unprecedented
NRC-shutdown of the Peach Bottom Plant after regulators were tipped off
to control room operators' habitual sleeping on the job. Articles detail
Peach Bottom's history of safety violations and its shutdown by the NRC.
Includes comments on lax NRC regulation which allowed such problems to
develop. </P>

<P><B>NPHA-1001</B> $10.00 occasionally updated </P>

<P>General Electric &amp; Mark I Packet </P>

<P>NIRS </P>

<P>A packet consisting of articles and information relating to GE reactors
and the safety problems associated with them. Contains a list of all GE
reactors and their locations. </P>

<P><B>NPHA-1002</B> $10.00 occasionally updated </P>

<P>Advanced Reactor Packet NIRS </P>

<P>This packet gives an overview of the U.S. nuclear industry's &quot;inherently
safe&quot; designs. </P>

<P><B>NPHA-1003</B> $2.50 25pp 5/87 </P>

<P>GE Reed Report Compilation </P>

<P>Cleveland Plain-Dealer stories sparked a brushfire of articles on the
1 2-year old GE study critical of its own reactor designs. A collection
of articles discussing GE reactor flaws and the company's attempts to suppress
reports of them, focusing on the Reed Report and associated memos. </P>

<P><B>NPHA-2000</B> data from 1991, issued May 1994 call for price </P>

<P>&quot;Routine Releases From Operating Nuclear Power Plants&quot; </P>

<P>This briefing paper discusses the &quot;planned releases&quot; of radioactive
materials into the atmosphere and water as a course of routine operation
for nuclear reactors. The NRC policy of &quot;As Low As Reasonably Achievable&quot;
(ALARA) is discussed as it applies to &quot;permissible&quot; radioactive
discharges from nuclear reactors to the environment are provided on a state
by state basis. </P>

<P><B>NPHA-2001</B> $2.00 95pp 1979 </P>

<P>The Nugget File, Union of Concerned Scientists </P>

<P>Classic report from UCS drawn from an internal NRC file on plant accidents
and safety defects. </P>

<P><B>NPHA-2002</B> $5.80 58pp 1986 </P>

<P>O-Rings and Nuclear Plant Safety: A Technical Evaluation </P>

<P>Daniel Ford and Robert Pollard </P>

<P>This paper compares the failure of the space shuttle Challenger and
the dangers of operating nuclear power plants. Both use O-rings, and Ford
and Pollard find that plant operators have failed to recognize the importance
of the O-ring manufacturers' own specifications regarding the temperature
limits within which O-rings will work properly. </P>

<P><B>NPHA-2003</B> $2.90 29pp various dates </P>

<P>&quot;Precursors to Severe Accidents&quot; </P>

<P>Collection of articles about recent Oak Ridge Laboratory research. Through
analyzing reports of actual operating experience, research has found that
severe reactor accidents probably will be more frequent than predicted
by the NRC's computer models. </P>

<P><B>NPHA-2004</B> $2.20 22pp 4/85 </P>

<P>Core Meltdown Probability, US NRC </P>

<P>NRC answers to questions posed by Rep. Markey at April 1985 hearing.
NRC admits probability of meltdown by 2000 is 45%, discusses PRAs and source
terms. </P>

<P><B>NPHA-2005</B> $.30 3pp 9/7/83 </P>

<P>&quot;Weak Links&quot; </P>

<P>J. Earnest Beazley, Wall Street Journal </P>

<P>This article investigated infractions of welders such as selling union
cards and falsifying test results to appear more qualified than they were.
</P>

<P><B>NPHA-2006</B> $15.00 172 pp 1995 </P>

<P>Without Borders: The Consequences of a Severe Accident at Fermi 2 </P>

<P>ILER Research Institute </P>

<P>This is a multi-authored assessment of a catastrophic accident at Detroit
Edison's GE Boiling Water Reactor as viewed from the Canadian side of the
Great Lakes. The principle authors include Steven Sholly/MHB Technical
Associates and Jan Beyea/National Audubon Society. An excellent resource
on the problems with the GE Mark I radiation dose estimates following an
accident, emergency planning and health consequences. </P>

<P><B>NPHA-2007</B> $2.60 26pp 3/28/94 </P>

<P>&quot;Nuclear Plant Terrorism&quot; </P>

<P>Scott D. Protzline, TMI Alert </P>

<P>This booklet brings to light possibility of a terrorist attack on nuclear
facilities. It begins by describing a recent TMI break-in by a mentally
disturbed man and the hunt for him which was only successful after four
hours. Other terrorist incidents and control room take-overs are described
and the lack of regulatory concern is discussed. </P>

<P><B>NPHA-2008</B> $.80 8pp 5/94-6/94 </P>

<P>&quot;Faulty Rods&quot; </P>

<P>Ashley Craddock, Mother Jones </P>

<P>&quot;Why are nuclear fuel rods failing? An engineer thinks a faulty
manufacturing process he helped design may be to blame. Both the Nuclear
Regulatory Commission isn't concerned, and the suspect parts are still
being shipped, with potentially dangerous results.&quot; </P>

<P><B>NPHA-2009</B> $.50 5pp 7/87-8/87 </P>

<P>&quot;Holes in the U.S. Nuclear Safety Net&quot; </P>

<P>Daniel Utroska, Bulletin of Atomic Scientists </P>

<P>A critical review of the industry's private, self-regulating body, the
Institute of Nuclear Power Operations, and its promise to ensure that U.S.
nuclear power plants comply with safety standards beyond those of the NRC.
</P>

<P><B>NPHA-3000</B> $.50 5pp 4/92 </P>

<P>&quot;Breeding Disaster: France's Nuclear Power Program&quot; </P>

<P>Olivier de Marcellus, Multinational Monitor </P>

<P>Marcellus outlines the problems Superphenix has faced and gives a brief
background for French citizens' opposition to not only the ALMR, but nuclear
power in general. </P>

<P><B>NPHA-3001</B> $3.50 35pp 11/1/93 </P>

<P>Isaiah Project Packet (WPPSS), Pacific Northwest Laboratories </P>

<P>The Isaiah Project (swords to plowshares) would finish two mothballed
reactors and use plutonium from dismantled warheads as fuel for electric
power generation. Text and diagrams from Battelle, Pacific Northwest Laboratories,
delineate the Isaiah Project's mission and the process by which this mission
will be accomplished. Also included are several pertinent news articles
</P>

<P><B>NPHA-4000</B> $5.00 1988 </P>

<P>The Aging of Nuclear Power Plants: A Citizen's Guide to Cause and Effects
</P>

<P>NIRS </P>

<P>A NIRS publication that examines the cause of reactor degradation and
attempts to supply citizens with the information to identify such problems
at local reactors. Also criticizes NRC for placing emphasis on plant life
extension rather than solving safety problems. </P>

<P><B>NPHA-4001</B> $.50 5pp 1/94-2/94 </P>

<P>&quot;What the Nuclear Regulatory Commission Won't Tell You: Aging Reactors,
Poorly Trained Workers&quot; </P>

<P>Mathew Freedman and Jim Riccio, Public Citizen </P>

<P>The authors examine industry documents which disclose a myriad of management
and technical problems that currently plague nuclear reactors. The public,
however, has limited access to such information due to coziness between
the NRC and the INPO (Institute of Nuclear Power Operations), an industry
regulation group. </P>

<P><B>NPHA 4002</B> $3.10 31pp 7/83 </P>

<P>Stress Corrosion Cracking in BWR and PWR Piping </P>

<P>R. W. Weeks </P>

<P>Technical article discussing the detection and repair of pipe-cracking
problems. </P>

<P><B>NPHA-5000</B> $2.70 27pp 1986 </P>

<P>&quot;Safety Risks at Babcock &amp; Wilcox Reactors: A Brief Summary&quot;
</P>

<P>Union of Concerned Scientists </P>

<P>This report discusses B&amp;W's PWR design and its weaknesses namely
steam generator design, a relatively small pressurizer and the &quot;non-safety&quot;
classification of certain systems, making them exempt from NRC rules (NRC
document showing this exemption is included). Also included is a partial
chronology of NRC actions concerning the safety of these plants and a UCS
letter which draws comparison between the TMI accident and the Davis-Besse
and Rancho Seco accidents in 1985. </P>

<P><B>NPHA-5001</B> $6.50 65pp 9/93 </P>

<P>&quot;Pressurized Water Reactor Internals Aging Degradation Study&quot;
</P>

<P>Oak Ridge National Laboratory, NUREG/CR-6048 </P>

<P>Prepared for the Nuclear Regulatory commission, this study identifies
and summarizes the effects of aging of vital safety components in Westinghouse,
Combustion Engineering and Babcox &amp; Wilcox reactors. An excellent document
in the argument for early closure of PWRs. </P>

<P><B>NPHA-5002</B> $6.00 50 pp 3/93 </P>

<P>Vessel Head Penetration Cracking in Nuclear Reactors </P>

<P>Greenpeace International </P>

<P>A comprehensive Greenpeace report on the material vulnerability of pressurized
water reactors (PWR) at the reactor vessel head where control rods penetrate
the pressure vessel. This cracking increases the risk of a meltdown accident.
Leaking has been noted in over a dozen PWRs in Europe and the fabrication
of US pressure vessels are similar. </P>

<P><B>NPHA-5500</B> $5.40 54pp </P>

<P>&quot;Boiling Water Reactor Pipe-Cracking&quot; Testimony </P>

<P>Includes testimony by David Schlissel on technical and economic aspects
of a safety problem that is causing long outages and expensive pipe replacements
at many plants. </P>

<P><B>NPHA-5501</B> $5.70 57pp 9/93 </P>

<P>&quot;Boiling Water Reactor Internals Aging Degradation Study&quot;
</P>

<P>Oak Ridge National Laboratory NUREG/CR-5754 </P>

<P>Prepared for the Nuclear Regulatory Commission, this study identifies
and summarizes the effects of aging of vital safety components in General
Electric reactors. An excellent document in the argument for early closure
of BWRs. </P>

<P><B>NPHA-5502</B> $2.40 24pp 5/19/86 </P>

<P>Pressure Suppression Containments in GE BWRs </P>

<P>Public Citizen Press Release </P>

<P>Statements by Robert Pollard and Daniel Ford concerning pressure suppression
containment in GE boiling water reactors. They compare the Chernobyl design
to US reactor designs and maintain the possibility of a Chernobyl style
failure of these US systems. Includes diagrams and a list of BWRs. </P>

<P><B>NPHA-6000</B> $1.10 11pp 2/85 </P>

<P>Radionuclide Release from Severe Accidents at Nuclear Power Plants </P>

<P>Executive Summary </P>

<P>Report from the American Physical Society, which wrecked the industry's
hopes for quick and easy source term reductions. Finds that while some
radiation releases may be smaller that previously envisioned, others could
be larger. </P>

<P><B>NPHA-6001</B> $1.20 12pp 2/85 </P>

<P>Nuclear Accident Source Terms: No Basis for Eliminating Safety Regulations
</P>

<P>Steve Aftergood, Committee to Bridge the Gap </P>

<P>A paper critiquing industry source term research and concluding that
many unresolved issues remain before regulations should be changed. </P>

<P><B>NPHA-6002</B> $1.30 13pp 4/85 </P>

<P>On the Inadequacies of the Nuclear Accident Source Term Research </P>

<P>Steve Aftergood, Committee to Bridge the Gap </P>

<P>Like its sister article this statement made before NRC claims that inadequacies
in source term research make loosening of federal regulations on the nuclear
industry impossible. </P>

<P><B>NPHA-6003</B> $.30 3pp 1/85-2/85 </P>

<P>&quot;The Source Term Debate and Its Implications&quot; </P>

<P>Steven C. Sholly, Groundswell </P>

<P>This article summarizes the source term origins and debates from early
NRC research to attempted revisions and discusses the implications. </P>

<P><B>NPHA-6004</B> $2.00 20pp 1/86 </P>

<P>The Source Term Debate </P>

<P>Sholly and Thompson, Union of Concerned Scientists </P>

<P>Discusses the NRC's use of source term estimates and compares before
and after the TMI accident and their reassessment. The authors also discuss
the neglected aspects of nuclear source term analysis and potential resulting
accidents. </P>

<P><B>NPHA-6500</B> $1.70 17pp 1989 </P>

<P>Four Articles on Risk Assessment </P>

<P>Four very informative articles, published by the Forum for Applied Research
and Public Policy, deal with the issue of risk assessment. Includes chart
showing NRC risk standards are 3-4 times higher than other government agencies.
</P>

<P><B>NPHA-6501</B> $1.10 11pp 2/84-3/84 </P>

<P>&quot;Probabilistic Risk Assessment: Pro and Con&quot; </P>

<P>Technology Review </P>

<P>Two articles on the benefits and uncertainties of using new risk assessment
techniques to calculate the risks of nuclear accidents. </P>

<P><B>NPHA-6502</B> $.50 5pp 10/7/88 </P>

<P>&quot;Perceived Risk, Real Risk: Social Science and the Art of Probabilistic
Risk Assessment&quot; </P>

<P>William R. Freudenburg, Science </P>

<P>The author argues that social and human factors must be accounted for
in risk assessment, stating that often scientists and the public draw ill-advised
conclusions but the public can &quot;also reflect a deeper kind of prudence
than is commonly realized.&quot; </P>

<P><B>NPHA-6503</B> $.60 6pp 12/7/90 </P>

<P>&quot;The Concept of Probability in Safety Assessments of Technological
Systems&quot; </P>

<P>George Apostolakis, Science </P>

<P>This article discusses risk models and risk assessment in general, along
with the dangers and necessities of using expert opinions. </P>

<P><B>NPHA-6504</B> $.20 2pp not dated </P>

<P>The Precautionary Principle &amp; &quot;Alternative Assessment&quot;
</P>

<P>Peter Montague and Mary O'Brien, Environmental Research Fndtn. </P>

<P>This fact sheet calls into question the &quot;prove harm&quot; method
of pollution control for obvious reasons. It also questions methods of
risk assessment which allow justification of certain environmental degradation.
</P>

<P><B>NPHA-6505</B> $1.10 11pp 2/84-3/84 </P>

<P>&quot;Finessing the Risks of Nuclear Power&quot; </P>

<P>James MacKenzie, Technology Review </P>

<P>Takes to task the assumption that probabilistic risk assessment should
help shape policy, criticizes the NRC for using this controversial method
to justify the risk nuclear power production presents. All this is considered
in light of WASH-1400, the massive reactor safety study. </P>

<P><B>NPHA-6506</B> $1.10 11pp 8/89 </P>

<P>IAEA Safety Targets and Probabilistic Risk Assessment </P>

<P>H. Hirsch, et al., Greenpeace Int'l </P>

<P>This excerpted chapter discusses past computer failures at nuclear facilities
and reveals that computer malfunction is not accounted for in PRA. </P>

<P><B>NPHA-8000</B> $2.00 20pp 1995 </P>

<P>Thermo-Lag: The Burning Issue at U.S. Nuclear Power Plants </P>

<P>NIRS </P>

<P>This briefing paper provides an overview and chronology of the ongoing
Thermo-Lag scandal and the Department of Justice indictment of the manufacturer
of the combustible fire barrier installed in 79 U.S. reactors. The paper
focuses on the current vulnerability of U.S. reactors to fire and procrastination
of the NRC to enforce its own fire protection regulations. </P>

<P><B>NPHA-9000</B> $2.10 21 pp various dates </P>

<P>Jumpers and Sponges </P>

<P>Compilation of news and magazine clips on the dangers of radiation exposure
to temporary workers in the nuclear industry. Articles show how increase
in unskilled worker contracts has increased the overall worker exposure
to radiation. </P>

<P><B>NPHA-9001</B> $4.00 40pp 4/90 </P>

<P>Glowing on the Job: Worker Exposure to Radiation at Nuclear Power Plants
</P>

<P>Cleo Manuel and Ken Bossong, Public Citizen </P>

<P>US. Nuclear power plants expose a record 105,000 workers to the equivalent
of over two million chest X-rays of radiation. Executive summary available
also. </P>

<P><A HREF="toolhome.htm"><IMG SRC="nirslog2.gif" HEIGHT=58 WIDTH=130></A>
</P>

</BODY>
</HTML>
