<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Petition to close Haddam Neck</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>NIRS, CAN PETITION NRC TO REVOKE HADDAM NECK'S LICENSE;</H2>
<H2>CHARGE THAT NORTHEAST UTILITIES SHOULD NOT OPERATE ANY REACTORS</H2>
<P>At <I>Monitor </I>presstime, NIRS and the Citizens Awareness Network (CAN)
of Massachusetts and Connecticut were preparing to hold a November 25th press
conference to announce release of a new report and petition to the NRC to
permanently revoke the operating license for Connecticut Yankee's Haddam Neck
reactor.</P>
<P>As reported last issue, Haddam Neck is on the verge of permanent shutdown.
More recently, a Northeast Utilities (operator of and largest shareholder in
Connecticut Yankee) report confirmed that it would be cheaper for
ratepayers--and the utility itself--to close the reactor permanently rather than
to keep it operating.</P>
<P>But Northeast Utilities (NU) has balked at making a final decision on Haddam
Neck, and some of the reactor's owners--apparently worried about decommissioning
costs--reportedly are advocating continued operation of the reactor.</P>
<P>At the November 25 press conference, NIRS and CAN were scheduled to release
a comprehensive report documenting the myriad of safety problems associated with
Haddam Neck, as well as a new formal petition asking the NRC to revoke the
reactor's license.</P>
<P>NIRS and CAN already have submitted a formal allegation to the NRC charging
NU with lying about the design and installation of a key reactor safety
component--which has gone unchallenged for some 28 years.</P>
<P>NIRS and CAN have called for a full investigation of NU's truthfulness in
this matter. The component in question, a critical sump screen, was apparently
not discovered to be mis-installed and not of the &quot;standard&quot; design
claimed by NU until July 1996--although NU steadfastly had claimed it was a
standard set-up since reactor start-up in 1968.</P>
<P>In July, the NRC discovered tons of debris potentially clogging the
reactor's Emergency Core Cooling System as a result of holes in the screen and
other problems related to initial installation.</P>
<P>If NU is found to have deliberately lied to the NRC, then the utility's
qualifications to continue operating its Millstone and Seabrook reactors lie in
serious doubt.</P>
<P>NIRS' report on Haddam Neck detailed a litany of safety problems with the
reactor, ranging from the utility's 1986 admission that it could not afford to
replace its failing steam generators to more recent instances of operator and
mechanical failure to a decades-long failure of NU to maintain the critical
Updated Final Safety Analysis Report--the basic document which describes the
essential condition of the reactor and upon which all operator procedures and
responses are based.</P>
<P>The NIRS/CAN report concludes that Haddam Neck must be permanently shutdown,
and that it would not be economically feasible to even attempt to bring the
plant to NRC safety standards.</P>
<P>The report, and accompanying petition prepared by CAN, also argues that NU
has not shown that it can safely operate the Millstone reactors, which have been
closed since Spring for a variety of safety and management problems.</P>
<P>Particularly galling has been NU's continued pattern of harassment and
intimidation of whistleblower s who have attempted to set NU straight on basic
safety issues.</P>
<P>Northeast long has attempted to claim that it is too reliant on nuclear
power to close its reactors. But this summer, with all four of its Connecticut
reactors closed, the lights stayed on....</P>
<P>A copy of the NIRS report is available <A HREF="cypaper.htm">here</A>, or
on paper for $10 from NIRS.</P>
<P><A HREF="mononl.htm"><IMG SRC="nirslog2.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A></P></BODY></HTML>
