<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//SQ//DTD HTML 2.0 HoTMetaL + extensions//EN">
<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>U.S. Ecology threatens to sue U.S. Scientists</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>U.S. ECOLOGY THREATENS TO SUE U.S. SCIENTISTS OVER WARD VALLEY TESTS</H2>
<P>In an unprecedented move, U.S. Ecology, the state-chosen contractor for the
proposed Ward Valley radioactive waste dump, has threatened to sue scientists
working under contract for the U.S. government for conducting their
government-sponsored research.</P>
<P>The dispute has stopped all scientific research on the proposed Ward Valley
site.</P>
<P>The U.S. Department of the Interior (DOI) is attempting to carry out tests
on Ward Valley safety issues, especially the possible migration of radionuclides
into the Colorado River--the major drinking water source for southern
California.</P>
<P>The Department had hired two scientists under contract, and the Lawrence
Livermore Laboratory, to conduct the tests.</P>
<P>But U.S. Ecology wrote to the scientists, according to the Los Angeles Times
stating, &quot;should you continue your participation in Interior's ill-advised
project, please do so based on the knowledge that US Ecology intends to seek
compensation from any persons or entities whose conduct wrongfully injures its
interests in this manner.&quot;</P>
<P>That was enough to stop the scientists from working. Martin Mifflin, one of
the National Academy of Science members working on the project, told the <I>Los
Angeles Times</I>, &quot;In my experience, it is unprecedented to get that kind
of letter for considering a contract to do applied science. It's my profession.
But even if a legal action is entered into just for harassment purposes, the
court costs could be more than the entire contract is going to pay me.&quot;</P>
<P>The U.S. government is not allowed to indemnify private contractors--which
these scientists are--from lawsuits from private firms.</P>
<P>U.S. Ecology, which already has received a license from the State of
California to build the shallow landfill dump, apparently wants Congress to pass
legislation to transfer the federal land where the dump would be built to
California--which would hire US Ecology--without further tests.</P>
<P>But the Department of Interior, which has control of the land, has, under
pressure from grassroots activists, Sen. Barbara Boxer, and others, insisted the
tests are necessary before any land transfer can be made.</P>
<P>In this case, U.S. Ecology may have overreached. The proposed Ward Valley
dump is unpopular among California voters--it obtains support primarily from
Governor Wilson's administration and a few pharmaceutical companies and nuclear
utilities.</P>
<P>And the suit may harden Clinton administration opposition to Ward Valley.
Deputy DOI Secretary John Garamendi called the US Ecology letters &quot;raw
intimidation,&quot; and said, &quot;It's a disgusting effort to deny the people
of California scientific assurance that the Ward Valley site won't put their
health and safety at risk.&quot;</P>
<P>Considering that Congress has not been able to pass legislation turning the
site over to California, US Ecology's latest move smacks of desperation--it is
unlikely to convince Congressmembers who might prefer objective scientific
evidence about the suitability of the site to contractor scare tactics. And it
may cause some Members to ask if U.S. Ecology is trying to hide something.</P>
<P>As reported earlier in the <I>Monitor</I>, US Ecology is said to be in
serious financial trouble. This seems to have sparked a new emphasis on
confronting opponents to its plans. Recently, the firm went so far as to sue a
local Texas environmental group, Mothers Organized to Stop Environmental Sins
(MOSES), which has complained about a deep-well injection site for hazardous
waste operated by the firm.</P>
<P><B>WHAT YOU CAN DO</B></P>
<P>Write to President Clinton and demand that he stand firm against U.S.
Ecology and its scare tactics. Address: The White House, 1600 Pennsylvania
Avenue, NW, Washington DC 20500</P>
<P>Nuclear Monitor, November 1996</P>
<P><A HREF="mononl.htm"><IMG SRC="nirslog2.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A></P></BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
