<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>DOE prepared to use MOX</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>DOE PREPARED TO APPROVE USE OF MOX FUEL</H2>
<P>At <I>Monitor</I> presstime, the Department of Energy was preparing to
issue a document clearing the way for use of plutonium-based, or MOX
(mixed-oxide) fuel in commercial nuclear reactors.</P>
<P>A Final Environmental Impact Statement (FEIS) on plutonium &quot;disposition&quot;
options was expected to recommend that at least a portion, and perhaps as much
as 2/3 of the plutonium reclaimed from the U.S. nuclear weapons arsenal be
converted to fuel for nuclear reactors.</P>
<P>Because conversion of reactors and preparation of the MOX fuel would be more
expensive that conventional uranium-based fuel, DOE seemed prepared to pay the
utilities to use the hybrid fuel--a potential boon for utilities already facing
increased competition and aging nuclear reactors.</P>
<P>At least 17 utilities have expressed some interest in converting their
reactors to use MOX fuel, although only about 4 or 5 are expected to receive
final DOE approval for the concept.</P>
<P>Outgoing DOE secretary Hazel O'Leary will have 30 days to announce a final
decision on MOX use once the FEIS is released. She is expected to endorse the
MOX option.</P>
<P>Said NIRS executive director Michael Mariotte, &quot;We will join with
grassroots groups and citizens across the country to defeat the MOX proposal.
Use of MOX fuel would increase nuclear proliferation risks, undercut U.S.
efforts to stop a worldwide plutonium economy, allow operation of uneconomical
and unsafe nuclear reactors, put more plutonium and other highly-radioactive
elements into the so-called &quot;low-level&quot; radioactive waste stream, and
cause a nightmare of nuclear materials transportation.</P>
<P>This option must be stopped, and it will be stopped,&quot; Mariotte said.</P>
<P>Instead, the DOE must continue to research methods to contain the plutonium
found in nuclear warheads, Mariotte said. &quot;Spreading plutonium around the
United States, on railroad cars, on trucks, and out reactor emission pipes just
isn't acceptable,&quot; he added.</P>
<P>The U.S. government has for decades opposed the use of plutonium as a
nuclear fuel in an effort to convince other countries not to embark on a
plutonium-based method of generating electricity. Instead, the U.S. consistently
has called for plutonium to be carefully regulated and stored in a manner that
would preclude terrorist or other illegal seizures of the material.</P>
<P>By even considering the MOX option, the DOE is breaking that decades-long
commitment to nuclear non-proliferation, in favor of subsidizing a few nuclear
utilities whose reactors could not afford to meet competitive pressures.</P>
<P>To make matters worse, the DOE also is considering the a two-pronged
strategy for tritium production. One side would be construction of an
accelerator at Savannah River, the other side would be to allow commercial
reactors to produce tritium for nuclear weapons.</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>&quot;This  DOE plan would completely break down every argument
that there is a difference between commercial nuclear power and the nuclear
weapons complex,&quot; said Mariotte. &quot;In fact, once 'commercial' reactors
start producing materials for nuclear warheads, they are part of the same
military-industrial-utility complex that President Eisenhower warned us against.&quot;</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>&quot;Again, it will be the grassroots groups and concerned
citizens who will stop this nutty idea. People know what's best for their
communities and their lives, even when they have a hard time convincing DOE of
that.&quot;</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><B>WHAT YOU CAN DO</B></P>
<P>During December, call and fax Energy Secretary Hazel O'Leary and urge her to
reject the MOX and tritium-production options. Let the White House know as well.
Contact NIRS for more information.</P>
<P>Nuclear Monitor, November 1996</P>
<P><A HREF="mononl.htm"><IMG SRC="nirslog2.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A></P></BODY></HTML>
