<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Nuclear Notes, November 1996</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<H2>NUCLEAR NOTES</H2>
<H2>FROM THE CAPITOL CITY...</H2>
<P>*Embarrassed by the March 1996 <I>Time Magazine</I> story about the NRC's
lack of regulatory zeal, NRC Chair Shirley Jackson has taken several steps
recently that make NRC look like, gasp, an actual regulator:</P>
<P>.The NRC has told all utilities still using <B>Thermo-Lag</B> to complete
removal and replacement of the substance by the end of 1997. A number of
utilities had been holding out for a year 2000-date. The agency also rejected
the Nuclear Energy Institute's proposed fire protection rule rewrite, and
directed the staff to come up with a new version by the end of February 1997.</P>
<UL>
<LI>The NRC has told utilities to document, by early Spring, whether their
reactors are in compliance with their <B>Updated Final Safety Analysis Reports</B>
(a major problem at Haddam Neck and Millstone). Reactors not in compliance
apparently will have a very short time to get into compliance.
</LI>
<LI>Following up on the discovery of the use of porous concrete for the basemat
at Millstone-3, the NRC examined records and wrote to five utilities demanding
information about their use of <B>porous concrete</B>. The plants were: Beaver
Valley-1 &amp; 2; Fitzpatrick; Haddam Neck; North Anna- &amp; 2; Surry-1 &amp;
2; and Perry.
</LI>
</UL>
<P>On the other hand, at a recent Commissioners' meetings on containment
degradation, Chairwoman Jackson heard the following from NRC staff:</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>&quot;The key point is that the number of incidents of
degradation is increasing. That is an important point to note.&quot;</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>&quot;Corrosion has been found in the sand cushion area [of GE
Mark I reactors] which transitions from the embedded concrete just below the
vent pipes. That is on the outside surface of the steel shell....Also, inside
the wet well, near the free surface of the water, that is where the waster is in
contact with the steel shell. That is where corrosion has been found.&quot;</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>&quot;This is a picture looking at the dry well shell from the
outside, putting a camera inside the sand cushion area. It is a very small
opening, and it does show two extensive areas of rust...This picture shows the
steel shell area which is in contact with the sand cushion. The lower portion of
the picture, you see the sand cushion, and in the upper right-hand corner, the
interface goes right through the middle of the picture. You can see the steel
shell.&quot;</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>&quot;Now this is instructive. People think that structures are
built forever, especially those made out of concrete. One is built to last
forever, but this one clearly didn't. It is on the top of a dome somewhere on
the containment structure, and that is the extent of spalling of concrete that
was observed.&quot;</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>&quot;This rule [containment inspection] became effective...on
September 9, 1996. With an expedited implementation period, the inspections are
to be completed by all utilities by September of 2001...&quot;</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Chairman Jackson: &quot;Given the general and accelerated rates that you
talked about, how long would it take for there to be corrosion below some
acceptable wall thickness level or strength level?&quot;</P>
<P>Mr. Bagchi [NRC staff]: &quot;We can discover one tomorrow.&quot;</P>
<P>Jackson's [and staff's] conclusion: don't worry, it can all be repaired....</P>
<P>* The German corporation <B>Siemens Power</B> met with NRC officials in
late October to discuss the company's plans to get a Department of Energy
contract to produce MOX (mixed-oxide, or plutonium-based) fuel for commercial
reactors (see related story, this issue). Siemens already has a uranium fuel
production license for its Richland, Washington facility. The NRC says it told
Siemens it would need a new license to produce plutonium fuel, under 10 CFR 70.</P>
<P>In other Siemens news, an international boycott has been launched against
the company during December 1996 for its role in the construction of the
controversial Mochovce reactor in Slovakia. More than 400 organizations
worldwide have joined the effort. In the U.S., Siemens' primary consumer
products are Osram, Sylvania and Bosch lightbulbs and other lighting goods.</P>
<P>*The NRC has launched a new &quot;on-line discussion&quot; of the <B>Licensing
Support System</B> for a high-level waste repository (read: Yucca Mountain).</P>
<P>Anyone interested in high-level waste and/or Yucca Mountain should try to
get involved and get your views known as clearly as possible. The discussion is
taking place on the Internet, at http://lssnet.llnl.gov The discussion continues
through May 20.</P>
<P>*Whistleblower David Lochbaum has joined the <B>Union of Concerned
Scientists</B> in the position previously held by Robert Pollard. Lochbaum has
worked as a contractor at numerous nuclear plants, most recently Haddam Neck. In
1992, he and fellow engineer Donald Prevatte disclosed a generic problem with
Susquehanna's irradiated fuel pool with which the NRC still is grappling. NIRS
has worked with Lochbaum for several years, and we look forward to working with
him for many years--we knew there remained a reason for our offices to be next
door to those of UCS....</P>
<H2>...AND IN THE STATES</H2>
<P><B>District of Columbia: </B>The Office of the People's Counsel will hold a
meeting December 4, 1996 to discuss the proposed merger of <B>Pepco and
Baltimore Gas &amp; Electric Co</B>. A number of merger opponents will attend.
Among the key issues are how the proposed merger would affect utility
competition and how to protect Pepco ratepayers from costs associated with BG&amp;E's
Calvert Cliffs reactors. The meeting will be held at the Martin Luther King
Library, 901 G Street NW, Wednesday, December 4, from noon-2:30 pm.</P>
<P><B>Illinois:</B> An October inspection of LaSalle-2's pressure suppression
pool uncovered &quot;a significant inventory of foreign material&quot; including
a 3-foot by 3-foot rubber mat, a 3-foot by 3-foot gasket and a six-foot by
four-foot nylon bag. <B>Commonwealth Edison</B> believes the material has been
there since the reactor went online twelve years ago. The amount of material
would have clogged the Emergency Core Cooling System strainers by more than 50%,
according to the NRC, leading to doubt that the system would have worked if
needed. A similar level of material was recently found at New York's Nine Mile
Point-2 reactor.</P>
<P><B>Louisiana:</B> Fourteen prominent civil and human rights activists,
including nine members of Congress, sent a letter November 19 asking NRC Chair
Shirley Jackson to deny a license to the proposed <B>Louisiana Energy Services</B>
uranium enrichment plant.</P>
<P>Signers included Rev. Dr. Joseph Lowery, president of the Southern Christian
Leadership Conference; Rev. Dr. Joan Brown Campbell, General Secretary of the
National Council of Churches; Bishop Thomas L. Hoyt of the Christian Methodist
Episcopal Church; Marc Morail, Mayor of New Orleans; Actress Jane Fonda; and
Representatives John Conyers, Ronald Dellums, Cleo Fields, Jesse L. Jackson,
Jr., John Lewis, Cynthia McKinney, Eleanor Holmes Norton, Donald Payne, and
Maxine Waters--the newly-elected chair of the Congressional Black Caucus.</P>
<P>The letter said that President Clinton's executive order on environmental
justice has &quot;been largely ignored LES and the NRC,&quot; and that LES &quot;seems
doomed to become another example of an expensive, pollution emitting nuclear
facility that will never be profitable--all at the expense of two poor African
American communities.&quot;</P>
<P><B>Massachusetts:</B> The NRC waived a potential $100,000 fine on <B>Boston
Edison</B> for potential containment degradation at the Pilgrim reactor. The
reason for the waiver: the NRC said that the utility identified the problem
(which involved faulty circuit breakers) and fixed it within four hours.</P>
<P>Fair enough, except that the utility first identified the problem in 1991,
and again in 1993, and didn't even report it, much less fix it. And the problem
existed, according to the NRC, since at least 1988 and perhaps since reactor
start-up in 1972.</P>
<P>It appears the agency may not be learning anything from the
Millstone/Northeast Utilities travesty, after all....</P>
<P><B>Minnesota:</B> The Prairie Island Coalition has sued the State of
Minnesota over private meetings held by state agencies with <B>Northern States
Power</B> (NSP).</P>
<P>At issue are discussions several state agencies held with NSP on the
utility's settlement with Westinghouse on its lawsuit over faulty steam
generators. The Coalition was an interested party to that suit and has been to
court to obtain secret Westinghouse documents about steam generator problems.</P>
<P>NSP and Westinghouse would prefer that the terms of the suit, and especially
relevant documents, be kept out of the public eye. The Coalition suit charges
the state agencies did not keep records of their meetings with NSP, contrary to
state law.</P>
<P><B>New York:</B> The deal was announced with much fanfare and publicity:
the <B>Entergy Corporation</B>, which operates reactors in Mississippi,
Louisiana, and Arkansas, was moving to New York to take over the operations of
the <B>New York Power Authority's</B> troubled Indian Point and Fitzpatrick
reactors.</P>
<P>The reality proved a little different, however, and in early November, very
quietly, NYPA announced that the deal wasn't happening after all. Apparently,
the two sides just couldn't agree on terms of the contract, though no details
were released. NYPA will continue to operate its reactors and Entergy will stay
in the South.</P>
<P><B>Ohio:</B> Centerior Energy was hit with two major fines in October. The
first, for $160,000 was for employment discrimination at the <B>Perry </B>reactor.
Five workers, who were involved in litigation against Centerior as a result of
their exposure to radioactive material at the utility's Davis-Besse reactor,
were refused access to Perry, and thus could not be hired by a contractor. A
sixth worker, who already had been hired, was fired. The six took their case to
the Department of Labor, where their case is still pending. But the NRC decided
the employees' grievance was valid and issued the fine.</P>
<P>The second fine against Centerior was for $50,000 and stemmed for
uncorrected fire protection violations at the <B>Davis-Besse</B> reactor.</P>
<P><B>Pennsylvania:</B> University of North Carolina scientists have released
a new study that suggests higher levels of radiation were released during the
1979 <B>Three Mile Island-2</B> accident than so far have been revealed.</P>
<P>The researchers, led by Dr. Steven Wing of the UNC School of Public Health,
re-examined data from a 1990 Columbia University study which concluded the
accident was not responsible for increased cancer rates in the area, because the
radiation exposures were too low.</P>
<P>Rather than start with the utility's stated radiation releases, however,
Wing and his co-workers started with the health effects in the area. They found
that leukemia and lung cancer rates downwind of TMI were five to ten times
higher than upwind.</P>
<P>Said Wing, &quot;I would be the first to say that our study doesn't prove by
itself that there were high-level radiation exposures, but it part of a body of
evidenced that is consistent with high exposures. If you say that there was no
high radiation, then you are left with higher cancer rates downwind of the plume
that are otherwise unexplainable.&quot;</P>
<P>The researchers considered smoking and other factors, but did not find them
responsible for the increased cancers downwind.</P>
<P>Wing noted that some plant radiation monitors went off scale during the
accident.</P>
<P>Concluded Wing, &quot;This cancer increase would not be expected to occur
over a short time in the general population unless doses were far higher than
estimated by industry and government authorities. Rather, our findings support
the allegation that the people who reported rashes, hair loss, vomiting and pet
deaths after the accident were exposed to high level radiation and were not only
suffering from emotional stress.&quot;</P>
<P>Nuclear Monitor, November 1996</P>
<P><A HREF="mononl.htm"><IMG SRC="nirslog2.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A></P></BODY></HTML>
