<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>what you can do</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY><IMG SRC="nomore2.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
<H2>What You Can Do</H2> 
<P>During April 1996, we are encouraging grassroots citizens groups, student
groups, churches, unions and all others to join us in Chernobyl commemoration
activities.
</P>
<H3>Groups</H3>
<P>Local groups will be collecting relief supplies for Chernobyl victims,
including vitamins, over-the-counter medicines (aspirin, etc), food supplements
and baby food. These supplies will be sent to a central warehouse in the U.S.
and shipped to the Ukraine and Bellarus. </P>
<P>In order to further educate the public about the continuing nature of the
Chernobyl disaster, and about nuclear power generally, collection points for
these supplies will be as public as possible. These include outside the offices
of nuclear utilities, waste dump companies and other nuclear fuel cycle
corporations; at reactors and other nuclear sites, at churches, student unions,
and anywhere people gather. Groups may, for example, choose to collect outside a
nuclear utility office one day per week during April 1996, at a student union on
a different day, etc., and hold a press conference/rally on the final day to
announce the results and distribute educational materials. Such materials are
now being prepared. Contact NIRS at 202-328-0002 or
<A HREF="mailto:nirsnet@igc.apc.org">nirsnet@igc.apc.org </A>for more
information.</P>
<H3>Individuals</H3>
<P>Individuals wishing to help in this 10th anniversary Chernobyl relief effort
should check the list of local group activities to see if there is a group near
you already helping.</P>
<P>If there are no other groups near you, or if you are unable to join in with
a particular local group's effort, you may make a contribution directly to NIRS.</P>
<P>There are three types of contributions NIRS is accepting:</P>
<P>1. Contributions to NIRS to defray the costs of the Chernobyl + 10 campaign.</P>
<P>2. Contributions to NIRS which will be pooled together to purchase needed
supplies directly from the manufacturers. NIRS keeps 5% of such contributions
for our accounting and other overhead. The rest goes entirely to relief
supplies.</P>
<P>3. Contributions to NIRS which will be forwarded to Eastern European
environmental groups working to close reactors throughout Eastern Europe and the
former Soviet Union. Even very small contributions can make a big difference to
these groups.</P>
<P>In each case, contributions should be mailed to NIRS, 1424 16th Street NW,
Suite 404, Washington, DC 20036; 202-328-0002. NIRS is a 501(c)(3) organization;
all contributions are fully tax-deductible. Please be sure to indicate on your
check which of these efforts you want your contribution to be directed toward.
Thank you for your help.</P>
<HR> 
