<TITLE>Chernobyl Relief</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Preferred Customer">
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<P>
<IMG SRC="nomore2.gif">
<H1><STRONG>Chernobyl Relief: What is Needed</STRONG>...</H1>
<HR>

<P>
The Chernobyl nuclear accident of April 26, 1986 has had devastating
consequences on the people of Ukraine and Belarus in particular.
31 people, mostly firefighters, died almost immediately after
the accident. But the disaster's real toll is only now beginning
to come clear. Much of the radiation released by Chernobyl is
still in the area, soaked up in the ground, brought back to surface
by plant roots and livestock. Unlike other industrial catastrophes,
Chernobyl is truly an accident without end. 
<P>
Thousands of people were evacuated from a 30 kilometer (18 mile)
area around the stricken reactor shortly after the accident. Many
of these were simply resettled in other contaminated areas. Since
the accident, hundreds of thousands more were moved to other areas
because of high contamination levels. Even so, millions of Ukrainians,
Belarussians and Russians still live in contaminated areas, and
eat contaminated food.
<P>
Radiation not only causes cancers, it attacks the immune system,
making people more vulnerable to other diseases. Children are
particularly susceptible to radiation's effects. Today, Belarus
is spending 20% of the its annual budget on Chernobyl-related
costs; the larger Ukraine spends 4% of its budget. By comparison,
the U.S. Medicare program accounts for 13% of our annual budget;
our foreign aid program for less than 2%.
<P>
In the United States, we will be collecting needed supplies for
Chernobyl victims. With United Nations aid nearly non-existent,
it is time for the people of the world to respond to this tragedy
as generously as we respond to earthquakes, floods and other natural
disasters. The supplies we are collecting are needed to bolster
the immune system, protect the children, and alleviate the suffering.
<HR>

<P>
Specifically, we seek the following items. All goods must be in
the original, unopened packaging with a minimum remaining shelf
life of six months:
<P>
<STRONG>Vitamins:</STRONG> especially multivitamins (e.g. One-A-Day).
Brand names are not important. Also needed are specific vitamins,
such as Vitamin C (chewable for children and adult dosages, Vitamin
B complexes, Vitamin A and Vitamin E.
<P>
<STRONG>Over-the Counter Medicines:</STRONG> these include non-prescription
drugs such as aspirin (both children's and adult); ibuprofen (Advil,
etc.); acetaminopin (Tylenol, etc.); anti-bacterial ointments;
anti-fungal ointments; anti-diarrheal medicine; cold tablets and
formulas; cough syrups (children's and adults); and antacids (Rolaid,
Maalox, etc.). Either generics or brand-names are welcome.
<P>
<STRONG>Baby Food:</STRONG> this includes typical baby food such
as jars from Gerbers, Heinz, Earth's Best, etc; as well as boxed
baby cereals and other packaged foods.
<P>
<STRONG>Food Supplements:</STRONG> These include basic minerals
and other products designed to enhance vitamin intake and retention,
and detoxify and fortify immune systems. Suggested supplements
include zinc, calcium, selenium, garlic tablets or liquid (Kyolic,
etc.), and acidophilous capsules.
<P>
We will <STRONG>not</STRONG> collect normal canned food, any fresh
items, clothes or other bulky items, or anything not on the above,
targeted list. Let's collect what the people need.
<P>
Local organizations will be responsible for shipping collected
items to a warehouse in Dover, New Jersey, run by Children of
Chornobyl. We will provide full shipping instructions before April
1996. Because you will bear the costs of shipping, you may wish
to collect some funds to pay for this. If there are large donors
who wish to purchase significant amounts of supplies you may either
buy these directly, or send them to NIRS where we will work to
obtain goods from at warehouse prices. Note, contributions for
supplies made through NIRS are fully tax-deductible. NIRS keeps
5% of all such contributions to cover our administrative costs.
<P>
For more information, contact NIRS, 202-328-0002; fax: 202-462-2183;
nirsnet@igc.apc.org
<P>
Updated 2/5/96
<P>
