<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>stop a mobile Chernobyl</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY><IMG SRC="nomore2.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">
<CENTER><H1>STOP A</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H1>MOBILE CHERNOBYL</H1></CENTER>
<P>The Chernobyl nuclear accident of April 1986 was the world's worst
industrial and environmental disaster. According to the Public Health Service of
Ukraine, more than 125,000 people already have died as a direct result of
Chernobyl. Other estimates are lower, but still highly significant: for example,
writing in the April 1996 <I>Scientific American</I>, Yuri Shcherbak, Ukraine's
Ambassador to the United States and an expert in epidemiology, estimates more
than 30,000 have died. The Belarus government says thousands of people,
especially children, are suffering from various forms of cancer and other
disease, as a direct result of the Chernobyl calamity.</P>
<P>The Chernobyl accident resulted in the release to the environment of a
significant portion of the reactor's radioactive nuclear core. According to
various governmental sources, some 100 million curies of radiation may have been
released during the accident and afterwards. This radiation settled primarily on
a large area of Ukraine and Belarus, and, because it has been impossible to
fully evacuate people from hazardous zones, the radiation continues to
contaminate food and water supplies--making the accident a diaster without end.</P>
<P>Some argue that the Chernobyl reactor was an inferior design, and such an
accident could not happen in the U.S. While the Chernobyl design does have
shortcomings, the radiation containment system for the Chernobyl reactors was
modeled after that used in 24 U.S. nuclear plants--called General Electric Mark
I reactors. The system failed dramatically at Chernobyl; shortly afterwards, a
top Nuclear Regulatory Commission official estimated the 24 U.S. reactors using
similar containment systems had a 90% chance of failure during a severe
accident.</P>
<P>Nuclear reactors, whether in the Ukraine or in the U.S. are built to attempt
to withstand major nuclear accidents. Their goal is to keep highly radioactive
nuclear fuel from reaching the environment. Obviously, this didn't work at
Chernobyl and it might not in the U.S. either.</P>
<H1>A Mobile Chernobyl in the United States?</H1>
<P>Now, the United States Congress wants to begin moving that same highly
radioactive nuclear fuel from nuclear power plant sites to Nevada. The fuel,
once removed from the reactor core (where it becomes lethally radioactive), is
considered radioactive waste. To ease the financial problems of a few nuclear
utilities, which have run out of room to store their own radioactive waste, some
Congressmembers want to move this lethal material to an &quot;interim&quot;
storage site in Nevada, near Yucca Mountain, where Congress hopes a permanent
waste dump will be built.</P>
<P>This movement of deadly nuclear fuel would travel through 43 states, many of
our largest cities (New York, Chicago, Washington, Philadelphia, Los Angeles,
and more), our agricultural heartland, and ultimately could affect the 150
million or so Americans which live within 50 miles of one of these
transportation routes.</P>
<P>And to what end? Solely to move this high-level radioactive waste away from
the utilities which generated it, and to a state which has never had a nuclear
power plant. It is the ultimate in the &quot;not-in-my-backyard&quot; syndrome.
Rather than maintain this waste, guard it, ensure that it doesn't enter the
environment, the nuclear utilities want to move it across your backyard, down
your interstate, across your railroad tracks and through your food supply--all
so they can claim the nuclear waste problem is &quot;solved.&quot; Of course,
the problem wouldn't be solved; nuclear waste would continue to pile up at
reactors, it would just pile up on train tracks and highways as well.</P>
<P>Each large nuclear waste cask would carry the long-lived radiological
equivalent of some 200 Hiroshima-sized nuclear bombs. Can you imagine your local
emergency personnel being able to handle such a catastrophe if a cask like this
derailed in your neighhborhood?</P>
<P>What's more, once the waste is moved away from reactor sites, the title to
the waste--and the liability if an accident occurs--transfers from the utilities
to the taxpayers.</P>
<P>Fortunately, there is a better way, and that's to leave the deadly waste
where it is--where it was generated by nuclear utilities--until our nation has
had the opportunity to completely re-evaluate its radioactive waste policies.
</P>
<H1>What's your idea?</H1>
<P>But, so far, Congress has a different idea. Many Congressmembers are
supporting HR 1020 in the House, or S 1271 in the Senate, which would mandate
large-scale radioactive waste transportation, as early as 1998.</P>
<P>You can help stop this potential mobile Chernobyl. Call (202-224-2131) or
write (US House, Washington DC 20515 and/or US Senate, Washington DC 20510) and
urge your federal elected officials to <B>oppose</B> HR 1020 and S 1271. Call
(202-456-1100) or write (White House, Washington DC, 20500) President Clinton
and demand that he <B>veto</B> any bill which would put into effect large-scale
radioactive waste transportation to an &quot;interim&quot; nuclear dump.</P>
<P>Ask your friends and neighbors to sign the Don't Waste America petition,
which calls for an end to generation of deadly nuclear waste, and for an
independent commission to re-examine our nation's failed nuclear waste policies.
Call radio talk shows, write letters to the editor, and ask your friends to
become active as well. Ask your city and county councils to pass resolutions
against unnecessary and dangerous nuclear waste transportation. Together, we can
stop a mobile Chernobyl, and work to implement a sound radioactive waste policy.
On the 10th anniversary of the world's worst industrial/environmental disaster,
we must do no less.</P>
<P>For more information, contact: Nuclear Information and Resource Service,
1424 16th Street NW, Suite 404, Washington DC 20036; phone: 202-328-0002; fax:
202-462-2183; e-mail: nirsnet@igc.apc.org; web site: http://www.nirs.org or
contact: Greenpeace, 1436 U Street NW, Washington DC 20009, phone: 202-462-1177.
</P>
</BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
