<H1>NUCLEAR MALPRACTICE:</H1>
<H2>CONNECTICUT YANKEE ATOMIC STATION </H2>
<H2>and implications for earlier closure of Northeast Utilities' reactors</H2> 
<P><B>NUCLEAR INFORMATION AND RESOURCE SERVICE AND </B></P>
<P></P>
<P><B>MASSACHUSETTS AND CONNECTICUT CITIZENS AWARENESS NETWORK</B></P>
<P>By</P>
<P>Paul Gunter, Rosemary Bassilakis, and Deborah Katz</P>
<P>November 25, 1996</P>
<H2>Table of Contents</H2>
<P>Introduction          1</P>
<P>I.  Failure To Comply With Design Issues And Plant Safety Analysis   4 </P>
<P>II.  Utility Misuse Of Regulations Governing Modifications of Design   7</P>
<P>A.  Feedwater Regulating Valves</P>
<P>B.  Pipe Problems Undermining  LOCA Recovery     9</P>
<P>C.  More Piping Problems And Unanalyzed Conditions:  The CAR Fans          
11</P>
<P>D.  Containment Sump Screen Design Problems              13</P>
<P>E.  NIRS  Files Allegation With NRC                           15</P>
<P>III.  A Near Miss Accident                 16</P>
<P>IV.  Westinghouse Steam Generators At Connecticut Yankee             19</P>
<P>V. Tritium Releases Into The Environment               21</P>
<P>VI. The Decommissioning Of Connecticut Yankee              22</P>
<P>VII. NRC Has Deferred Its Responsibility To Enforce Regulations           
24</P>
<P>VIII.   Conclusion And Recommendations               26</P>
<P>About the Authors             <B>    </B><B> </B></P>
<H3>     INTRODUCTION</H3>
<P>The nuclear industry has an expression &quot;Luck makes a lousy safeguard.&quot;
</P>
<P>To a large measure as now revealed, the public's health and safety has
increasingly relied upon &quot;luck&quot; or chance at the Connecticut Yankee
atomic power station.  Recent revelations document crucial safety equipment
inoperable for the 28 years of the nuclear station's operation, design
miscalculations involving equipment vital to controlling the reactor core in the
event of a nuclear accident, gross mismanagement and a persistent neglect of the
station's safety standards,  misinstallation of components and failure to
maintain the station's safety features in conformance with its design, for
economic reasons hedging on the repair of  deteriorating safety-related
components and finally a near-miss accident.  These unresolved  issues and more
point to a public safety net that was never there for the New England
communities surrounding Connecticut Yankee. </P>
<P>The Connecticut Yankee atomic power plant on the Connecticut River in Haddam
Neck, CT is a 616-megawatt  pressurized water reactor commissioned into
commercial power generation in January, 1968. It is owned by a consortium of New
England electric utilities with the largest holding by Northeast Utilities. </P>
<P>Northeast Utilities (NU), based in Berlin, CT,  is the largest nuclear
utility in New England and through the employment of its wholly-owned
subsidiaries is the operator of  Connecticut Yankee (Connecticut Yankee Atomic
Power Co.) as well as the Millstone Units 1, 2, and 3 (Northeast Energy Service
Co.)  in Waterford, CT and  Seabrook Station (North Atlantic Energy Service
Corp.) in New Hampshire.  As a co-owner in Maine Yankee at Wiscasset, Maine, and
Vermont Yankee near Brattleboro, Vermont, NU arguably maintains a degree of
influence at these atomic power stations through each respective board of
directors.  </P>
<P>Historically, Northeast Utilities has been the subject of  long standing
community activist and health professional concerns because of the electric
utility's disregard of public health and safety;  most notoriously for periodic
large airborne releases of radiation from its Millstone Unit 1 station which
totaled 3 million curies in 1975 alone.&lt;1&gt;  More recently however, NU's
practices at  its Connecticut reactors provided a shock therapy to a
lackadaisical federal regulator, the Nuclear Regulatory Commission (NRC),  after
persistent company whistle-blower concerns publicly spotlighted safety issues at
the reactors and a U.S. Department of Justice criminal investigation was
initiated into the utility's operations at Millstone.</P>
<P>Before revelations of numerous safety violations, Connecticut Yankee was
rated as one of the nuclear industry's better-than-average performers, with a
life-time generating capacity of  75 %. These problems bring to light that plant
performance was achieved only at an increased risk to a public unaware of
numerous hazards literally built into the plant and shortcuts taken by a utility
determined to maintain its profit margin.</P>
<P>Connecticut Yankee was taken off-line on July 22, 1996 to address safety
issues involving the reactor's service water system to the emergency core
cooling system. Additional problems began surfacing at the reactor and NU
decided to further delay the restart.   In August, Connecticut Yankee commenced
an early refueling outage originally scheduled for September, 1996.   With its
three Millstone units already shutdown in unplanned outages and reactor restart
pending clearance from the NRC troubled reactor watch list, NU was spending $30
million a month to provide replacement power costs to its New England service
area.  </P>
<P>Northeast Utilities seeks to minimize the public safety impact of these
problems by framing their reactor troubles as issues of paper flow management
and whether the reactor remains an &quot;economic producer&quot; of electricity.
 During the summer of 1996, faced with increased NRC scrutiny, Connecticut
Yankee's joint owners requested that a company analysis be conducted to
determine the reactor's economic viability. The report's finding, released on
October 9, announced that  immediate closure was significantly cheaper than
operation till the end of the reactor's current license in 2007.    Connecticut
Yankee may now be permanently closed because its owners are unwilling to take
the financial risk of addressing the multitude of issues that pose a health and
safety risks to the public.</P>
<P>Even with the results of the company's economic analysis favoring immediate
shutdown, however, Connecticut Yankee spokespeople have stated that it is not a
foregone conclusion that the joint owners will ultimately decide to permanently
close the reactor.&lt;2&gt;  A number of  uncertainties provide disincentives to
early closure, including the underaccrulment of the reactor's projected
decommissioning costs and fear of the public and political perceptions of
permanently closing the only Connecticut reactor that is not on the NRC Problem
Plant Watch List.  </P>
<P>Indeed, Connecticut Yankee's deep-seated problems are not unique to this
reactor but symptomatic of a larger and more systemic problem running throughout
Northeast Utilities' management of all its reactors.   Under growing pressure,
the NRC is coming around to recognize this more profound concern not only for
the utility's proposed reopening and operation of the remaining Connecticut
reactors but also with the on-going operation of New Hampshire's Seabrook
nuclear generating station.&lt;3&gt;  </P>
<P>While the NRC's recent activities arising out of NU problems at its
Connecticut reactors have been aggressive, these actions have largely been
reactive to chronic safety-significant problems that have persisted through
decades of disregard to fundamental regulatory standards.  It is of great
concern that problems involving lack of documentation, inaccuracies in existing
documents, and the repeated violation of regulations governing documentation of
modifications to safety-significant features at the reactors could only have
occurred through the absence of any meaningful NRC regulatory oversight.  </P>
<P>The goal of this report is to advocate for the immediate and permanent
closure of Connecticut Yankee.  The report lays out a series of outstanding
public safety concerns that pertain to any Connecticut Yankee proposal to
return-to-service under a management re-organization plan to operate the plant 
more &quot;economically-efficient&quot; and to &quot;better document&quot;
reactor safety modifications.   This report outlines these significant reactor
problems to point to an underlying and more safety-significant managerial
attitude that would continue to jeopardize public health and safety if
Connecticut Yankee were allowed to come back on-line.  Of significant concern
regarding Connecticut Yankee and public health and safety, this report addresses
how undocumented conditions involving Connecticut Yankee design bases vs. the
reactor's as-built condition potentially affect Connecticut Yankee
decommissioning under current NRC regulatory policy.  </P>
<P>While the report focuses on Connecticut Yankee, the generic nature of NU
managerial approach to safety problems also extends to NU's other reactors. 
Similarly, the authors advocate the permanent closure of NU's Millstone 1, 2,
and 3 units already on the NRC problem plants list due a long history of
negligence, persistent mismanagement and chronic disregard for public health and
safety.   </P>
<H3>I. FAILURE TO COMPLY WITH DESIGN ISSUES AND PLANT SAFETY ANALYSIS</H3>
<P>All nuclear reactors licensed by the NRC must conform with safety  standards
governing operation under normal and emergency conditions. The  plant design
features that satisfy the NRC's safety regulations, along with the analyses
performed to demonstrate this compliance, are embodied in the  voluminous
Updated Final Safety Analysis Report (UFSAR) for each plant. </P>
<P>The operators are allowed to make changes to the plant under Code of 
Federal Regulation (10 CFR 50.59) so long as the changes do not constitute an &quot;unreviewed
safety issue.&quot; An ureviewed safety issue is defined as any activity which
increases the likelihood or consequences of a previously evaluated accident,
introduces a new type of accident or reduces safety margins at the reactor.  All
changes to the plant and revisions to the supporting analyses are required to be
periodically documented  in the UFSAR.  Information contained in the UFSARs is
used by the operator for emergency procedures, training, and as a baseline for
any future modifications of reactor systems and procedures.  </P>
<P>Revelations of long standing violations of the 10 CFR 50.59 process at
Northeast Utilities Millstone nuclear units not only brought increased
regulatory scrutiny to the three units at Waterford, CT but also disclosured NU
mismanagement and negligent practices at its Connecticut Yankee reactor.  </P>
<P>Early in 1996,  NU workers made public disclosures of practices at the
Millstone units documenting that the utility had failed to maintain complete and
accurate information in the reactor's UFSAR. At the risk of their careers within
the nuclear industry,  the NU employees  revealed that the Millstone units along
with a number of other utility operators were misusing the 10 CFR 50.59 process
to make changes to the UFSAR without adequately evaluating the potential safety
consequences related the performed activities at the reactors.  </P>
<P>Over the years, Northeast Utilities has acquired a sordid history of
harassing and intimidating conscientious workers who have brought forward safety
concerns at each of its nuclear units.  Over the past four years, NU has been
fined on three occasions at $100,000 for each violation as a result for
harassing employees who raised safety concerns. NU has been cited for creating &quot;an
unhealthy work environment, which did not tolerate dissenting views.''   In this
environment, NU management aggressively fostered a climate where engineering
problems dealing with safety issues were often approached by first waiting to
find an economical solution before officially reporting the problem. 
Consequently over the years, an indeterminate number of  safety problems at the
NU reactors have been left unaddressed and undocumented by the company.    As
such,  NU provides a clear example of an electric utility that has prioritized a
competition-first and safety-second approach to managing its nuclear power
plants. </P>
<P>A last straw fell in August of 1995, when NU employees filed an emergency
enforcement action petition with the NRC bringing forward allegations of
repeated safety violations during refueling operations at Millstone 1.  The
allegations charged that NU &quot;knowingly, willingly, and flagrantly&quot;
violated their license with the NRC through a 20 year old practice of offloading
the entire reactor fuel core into the plant's storage pond without fully
analyzing the operation's safety implications and ignoring a mandated  250-hour
cooldown period for burned atomic fuel  in order to expedite the procedure to
60-hours and cut company cost.  Workers complained that the expedited procedure
endangered their crews-- in one case the work environment was so hot that NU
employees working on the refueling floor of  the reactor pressure vessel had
their rubber shoes melt.</P>
<P>As a result of increased public exposure and federal scrutiny, an internal
NU Event Response Team was chartered to determine the causes for &quot;inaccuracies&quot;
contained in the Millstone Unit I UFSAR.  The company's own internal report
revealed that Millstone's safety evaluation &quot;<I>did not fully address
regulatory requirements</I>&quot; and that &quot;<I>NU did not see the UFSAR as
a document that was required to be accurate.</I>&quot; &lt;4&gt; (emphasis
added).  The report further indicated that  &quot;The long term pattern of
decisions and actions has generic implications for Connecticut Yankee and
Millstone Units 2 and 3.&quot;&lt;5&gt;   </P>
<P>After persistent company stonewalling of the employees' safety concerns at
Millstone, simultaneously evidenced that the NRC had long since turned a blind
eye to the procedure, the whistleblowers' went  to TIME magazine which published
a cover story (March 4, 1996) exposing this precariously dangerous practice at
Millstone and the failure of the federal agency to oversee operations at the
reactor. </P>
<P>The TIME magazine article flared into a significant public relations
embarrassment for the NRC.  The article exposed the NRC at best  as a federal
watchdog found sleeping in a nuclear junkyard, and at worst operating in
collusion with the nuclear industry to prioritize company profits over worker
and  public safety.</P>
<P>In response, NRC Chairwoman Dr. Shirley Jackson initiated an industry-wide
assessment  of licensee maintenance of their UFSARs and determined that an
additional 18 facilities were conducting similar refueling outages out of
compliance with their final safety evaluations.  </P>
<P>Other chronic structural problems and adverse-to-safety practices began to
surface at the Millstone units raising increased concerns about NU's ability to
competently operate any of its nuclear reactors.  In May, 1996 NU discovered a
32 inch by 9 inch hole in the Millstone unit 2 auxiliary building wall near
irradiate fuel pool reported to be roughly the size of a &quot;doggie door&quot;
in the radiologically controlled and supposedly pressure-tested  area of the
station.  The deficiency apparently existed for an extended time demonstrating
an inadequate surveillance testing program.   In July, 1996, it was disclosed
that during the construction of Millstone unit 3, NU in an effort to speed up a
lagging construction schedule, opted to use a fast-drying concrete rather than
the standard portland cement with its longer cure timemduring the pouring of the
reactor's foundation. The quick dry concrete is now eroding out of the reactor
building, raising issues of uncertainty as to the extent of the damage and
effect on reactor containment integrity. All three Millstone units have
repeatedly reported events involving operation outside of the design bases,
including an October 1996 report of the improper setting of the steam generator
safety relief valves at Millstone Unit 2. The deficiency, existing since the
reactor's initial startup in 1975, represented the potential for
overpressurizing the steam generators and invalidating assumptions regarding
steam tube ruptures. The fact that the problem went undetected during
Millstone's replacement of the steam generators demonstrates that NU's design
modification process has been deficient.    </P>
<P>The deficiencies displayed at NU's troubled Millstone units fingerprinted
the utility's systemic mismanagement practices that implicated operations at
Connecticut Yankee.</P> 
<H3>II.UTILITY MISUSE OF REGULATIONS GOVERNING MODIFICATIONS OF DESIGN</H3>
<P>During March  and April 1996, a special NRC inspection team assessed the
engineering and licensing activities at Connecticut Yankee with a focus on the
utility's processes used to identify, evaluate, and resolve technical issues.
</P>
<P>The NRC special  inspection stated,</P>
<P>&quot;The team identified a number of significant deficiencies in the
engineering calculations and analyses which were relied upon to ensure the
adequacy of the design of key safety systems at Haddam Neck.  In some cases,
design-bases calculations and analyses were incorrect and did not confirm that
the safety system functional requirements would be met.  Some of these errors
were long-standing, while others were recently introduced during modifications
to the facility... <I>These deficiencies revealed significant weaknesses in the
defense-in-depth principles that the NRC relies upon to ensure nuclear power
plant operation does not jeopardize the health and safety of the public. </I>&quot;&lt;6&gt;
(emphasis added)   Systems at Haddam Neck affected by these deficiencies
included the emergency diesel generators (EDG) and the emergency core cooling
system (ECCS).  Additionally, emergency operating procedures lacked guidance for
recovering the reactor from various accident conditions involving the manual
transfer from the immediate ECCS safety injection system to the necessary
long-term cooling function of the sump recirculation system for the ECCS to
maintain reactor core stability following an accident.     </P>
<P>NRC noted in the special inspection of Connecticut Yankee that NU had made
changes to the UFSAR without performing evaluations to determine whether the
modification introduced an increase in the likelihood or consequences of a
previously evaluated accident, introduced a new type of accident or reduced
safety margins at the reactor. This is required under the NRC's regulations
(10CFR50.59).  Several errors were discovered in  a number of drawings which &quot;create
the potential for the introduction of more significant errors in future plant
design changes and operating practices.&quot;&lt;7&gt;   The issue of faulty
evaluations and incorrect diagrams is of particular concern to the interests of
public health and safety during any future Connecticut Yankee decommissioning
operations which relyed upon them.  These diagrams and evaluations constitute
the blueprints and safety analysis to protect both worker and public during
decommissioning activities.</P>
<H3>A.  FEEDWATER REGULATING VALVES</H3>
<P>On July 9, 1996, NRC completed another inspection at Connecticut Yankee
Atomic Power Company as the result of identified design and licensing basis
discrepancies. The NRC's stated intent for this series of inspections was that
the licensee &quot;implement compensatory measures as needed to assure the
continued operability of components important to safe plant operation.&quot;&lt;8&gt;
  </P>
<P>The July inspection noted that on June 11, 1996, a design engineer at
Connecticut Yankee identified a component design deficiency that existed in the
feedwater regulating valves (FRV) with significant adverse safety implications. 
The feedwater regulating valves control the rate at which water from the
condenser is supplied to the steam generators.  The position of the FRVs is
controlled automatically to maintain the desired water level on the secondary
side of the steam generators.  Basically, the control logic balances feedwater
flow with main steam flow in order to maintain a constant level. An automatic
control is required since the main steam flow (and feedwater flow) varies with
the power level.</P>
<P>The FRVs must automatically close in event of a main steam line break. With
the FRVs closed, the containment pressurization terminates once the steam
generator boils dry (i.e., all the water in the steam generator is boiled off
through the broken steam line into the containment space).  If the FRVs do not
close, water will continue to be supplied to the steam generator and will
continue to escape as steam to the containment.  The ultimate consequence would
be containment failure due to overpressurization and the release of radiation to
the environment. </P>
<P>The engineer identified that the valve had not been evaluated for a
worst-case main steam line break condition and could not fully close against a
main steam line break for the affected steam generator. The NRC inspection team
subsequently identified  numerous opportunities, starting as earlier as 1981,
where the component's design safety function should  have been properly
validated or verified by Northeast Utilities as part of a required safety
evaluation for making modifications to the reactor's technical specifications,
as required by 10 CFR 50.59.  </P>
<P>NU had concluded in its safety evaluations that modifications did not
represent an &quot;unreviewed safety question.&quot;  Numerous modifications to
the reactor's technical specifications contained in the Updated Final Safety
Analysis Report had been approved by NRC  for the feedwater regulation valve. 
Despite these opportunities to detect this safety deficiency, the licensee made
no calculations or tests to justify that the feedwater regulation valves would
operate as intended to mitigate a main steam line break accident. </P>
<P>According to the NRC, in the event of a main steam line break accident,
failure of these safety significant components could  cause a condition that
exceeds the analyzed containment pressure and temperature design limits
cascading into a breach of containment and release of radiation to the
environment.  The NRC inspection further concluded, &quot;The failure to operate
the facility in accordance with the UFSAR is considered an apparent violation. A
lack of thorough reviews in past safety evaluations occurred because the
licensee failed to compare the FRVs design to that response necessary to
mitigate the consequences of an accident.&quot;&lt;9&gt;</P>
<H3>B.  PIPE PROBLEMS UNDERMINE LOSS-OF-COOLANT-ACCIDENT RECOVERY</H3>
<P>On August 10, 1996, the NRC completed an additional  four week inspection
into various aspects of Connecticut Yankee operations, maintenance, engineering,
and plant support. This inspection, released in September 1996, revealed that
for 28 years, a piping system that supports Connecticut Yankee's &quot;emergency
core cooling system has been too small the ensure that enough water would be
available to prevent a meltdown during a worse-case accident&quot; as reported
to the public in a Connecticut newspaper.&lt;10&gt;  </P>
<P>The NRC Inspection Report 50-213/96-08 noted concerns with the adequacy of
the analytical evaluations, plant design features and as-built conditions vital
to assuring an operable emergency core cooling system at Connecticut Yankee. 
</P>
<P>As a background, several systems are used at the Connecticut Yankee reactor
for  recirculation cooling to the reactor core following a potential
Loss-Of-Coolant-Accident exampled by a main steam line break, steam generator
tube ruptures or other reactor coolant piping system.  These recirculation
systems include the Residual Heat Removal (RHR) system, the High Pressure Safety
Injection system and the charging portion of the Chemical and Volume Control
system.   Immediately following an accident, the High Pressure Safety Injection
begins the refill of  the reactor vessel with coolant water drawn off of the
Refueling Water Storage Tank.  After the storage tank has been emptied to a
specified low water level during the injection phase, the RHR pumps and heat
exchangers are activated to recirculate spilled water collected in the
containment sump, a large concrete pit at the lowest elevation in the reactor
building.  The spilled coolant water is then recirculated back to the reactor
cooling system via the charging system consisting of three parallel pumps and
the high pressure injection system.  </P>
<P>The problem was identified by NRC as  inadequate &quot;Net Positive Suction
Head&quot;  (NPSH) involving  the potential introduction of steam vapor into the
RHR pump system causing a break in the vacuum and the pumps to &quot;cavitate&quot;.
 &quot;Cavitation&quot; of a pump occurs when air or low pressure vapor (the
combination of steam and water) is introduced or generated within the pump
system resulting in variable pump speeds and intense vibration causing the pump
to destroy itself along with the loss of its long term reactor cooling function.
 Under postulated accident conditions, the maximum containment sump temperatures
could reach as high as 252 degrees F.  Warmer water circulating up from the
containment sump system during the recirculation recovery phase from a LOCA
would have a tendency to flash to steam between the sump and the RHR pumps
causing the pumps to cavitate. </P>
<P>Since the reactor first started up 28 years ago, Connecticut Yankee has
relied on predicted containment back pressures and temperatures under accident
conditions to support RHR flow through the system's 8 and 10 inch piping.
However, the licensee's calculations for predicted temperatures and pressures
have been changing over time due to the discovery of errors.  When NRC
inspectors requested Connecticut Yankee to provide evidence to support its
reliance on containment back pressure, NU was unable to provide a clear
reference in the reactor's UFSAR or any other licensing documentation.  NRC
reported that &quot;A primary concern of the staff was the fact that the
containment overpressure relied upon was significantly greater than any
previously approved calculation.&quot;&lt;11&gt;    </P>
<P>Consequently, it was determined that Connecticut Yankee had operated for 28
years with its principle safety barriers seriously degraded and in an unanalyzed
condition that significantly compromised safety.  NRC inspection report 96-08
concluded &quot;for past operation of Haddam Neck in modes 1, 2, and 3 prior to
July 22, 1996 the long-term recirculation phase flowpath needed to mitigate
various LOCA's was inoperable&quot; and &quot;past analytical assumptions for
the RHR NPSH was not supportable by detailed evaluations prior to 1996, and once
completed there was inadequate assurance that NPSH requirements would continue
to be satisfied for the range of possible conditions as the containment
depressurized and the sump cooled down during the long term recovery period.&quot;&lt;12&gt;</P>
<H3>C.  MORE PIPING PROBLEMS AND UNANALYZED CONDITIONS:  THE CAR FANS</H3>
<P>Another piping issue involves the service water lines to the containment air
recirculation (CAR) fans.  The failure of these containment coolers would cause
emergency equipment to overheat and fail,  leading to core damage with
containment failure.  The CAR fans are the only credited source for the
Connecticut Yankee's heat removal system following a postulated core accident
which would generate very high temperatures inside the containment building. 
Four such fans are required by Connecticut Yankee technical specifications to be
operational. Vital safety-related components and systems, including the ECCS,
and their electrical power, instrumentation and control cables depend on the CAR
fans, as these components are qualified to operate within required optimal
temperature ranges.  The CAR fans are designed to cool the containment building
so that this equipment can operate to recover and maintain reactor stability
following an accident.  The CAR fans cooling coils are cooled by the station's
service water (SW) pipe system.</P>
<P>Up until its shutdown on July 22, 1996, Connecticut Yankee had performed 359
days of continuous operation when concerns arose over the structural  integrity
of  the service water cooling lines if they were ever challenged under accident
conditions. Connecticut Yankee had been reviewing the performance of the CAR fan
system and the SW lines under postulated accident conditions. As a result, all
four CAR fans were declared inoperable and the reactor was shutdown. </P>
<P>It was determined that the during a Loss of Coolant Accident (LOCA), with an
assumed loss of normal power, that cooling water flow through the SW lines would
be interrupted.  Past evaluations predicted that under accident conditions 
water in the SW line would immediately flash to steam but the force and pressure
generated was concluded to be acceptable.   It had been concluded earlier that
the CAR fans would likewise remain operational.  However, the re-analysis 
determined that a number of thermal-hydraulic phenomena occurring within the 6
inch diameter SW piping, including a steam driven water hammer involving 10,000
cubic feet of steam and a sizable water slug moving at a predicted 250 feet per
second,  were as much as ten times greater than earlier estimates. This was
recognized as a &quot;two-phase flow&quot; (both steam and liquid) through the
service water lines to the CAR fans. Connecticut Yankee had only analyzed a
single-flow condition only (liquid only).  It was determined that &quot;the
two-phase flow in cooling water systems associated with the containment air
coolers can significantly interfere with the ability of the containment air
coolers to remove heat under design-basis accident conditions, and can interfere
with the cooling of other safety-related components.&quot;&lt;13&gt; 
Consequently, the structural integrity of the SW lines to CAR fans came into
serious doubt.</P>
<P>&quot;The existence of excessive hydrodynamic loads in the CAR fan service
water cooling lines under postulated design basis accident conditions
constituted a condition in which the plant operated outside its design basis
since initial plant startup, and resulted in plant operation contrary to the
requirements of Technical Specifications&quot; concluded the NRC inspection.&lt;14&gt;
  The inspection report further stated that the cause for the functional
deficiencies of the CAR-SW system was &quot;a failure of the licensee to
maintain adequate control over the design-basis of the service water system.&quot;&lt;15&gt;
  According to NRC, Connecticut Yankee's violation to maintain CAR fan
performance &quot;had high significance relative to plant safety. With the
assumed failure of the CAR fan service water under postulated accident
conditions, a potential existed for the post accident loss of containment
cooling and longer term containment heat removal.  The postulated rupture of
service water piping downstream of the CAR fans would create the potential for a
leakage path that bypassed the containment, and result in the a release of the
post accident source term [radioactivity directly from the reactor core] through
the open service water system to the discharge canal and the atmosphere.&quot;&lt;16&gt;
</P>
<P>NRC concluded that &quot;service water piping supplying cooling water to the
CAR fans would not remain functional under accident conditions was an example of
an issue for which the design basis for the plant had not been thoroughly
reviewed or understood.&quot;&lt;17&gt;</P>
<P>The same NRC inspection report went on to identify additional deficiencies
at Connecticut Yankee which further jeopardized the successful performance of
the ECCS systems were it ever called upon in the event of an accident.</P>
<H3>D.  CONTAINMENT SUMP SCREEN DESIGN PROBLEMS</H3>
<P>Inspection Report 50-213/96-08 also documents NRC inspections of the
containment sump system to confirm design  information and operability
determinations. The purpose of the containment sump, the large concrete holding
tank at the lowest elevation of the reactor building,  is to collect water
spilling out of the reactor vessel through a broken pipe after a postulated
Loss- Of-Coolant-Accident. The Residual Heat Removal (RHR) pumps draw water from
the containment sump and recirculate this water back to the reactor vessel as
part of the Emergency Core Cooling System during the long term recirculation
phase following an accident.  The sump is divided into two sections; the normal
drainage sump and the RHR suction portion.  Each section is divided by a  low
wall and a vertical wire mesh screen.   The screen's purpose is to limit debris
transport that could potentially clog the ECCS system thereby inhibiting or
preventing reactor core cooling.</P>
<P>Since the early 1980's, NRC and the Connecticut Yankee have exchanged
generic communications pertaining to the questionable reliability of the
containment sump design due to the fact that significant volumes of various
types and sizes of debris (insulating material, rags, cardboard, etc.)  have
tended to collect in the sump area. The problem of debris collecting in the sump
area of nuclear power plants was originally addressed industrywide by the NRC as
an Unresolved Safety Issue number 43 (USI-43). In July, 1975, Connecticut Yankee
had to remove 6 fifty-five gallon drums of sludge and various types of debris,
including welding rods, baling wire, cardboard, and mop heads, from the
containment sump.  On November 18, 1980, NRC  requested that Connecticut Yankee
provide information on containment sump drawings showing important design
features and dimensions as part of the resolution of USI-43.  NRC again
requested Connecticut Yankee to respond under oath through the issuance of a
Request for Additional Information letter [10 CFR 50.54(f)] to address generic
safety issues which included the containment sump reliability issue. </P>
<P>Connecticut Yankee responded to NRC by stating that the containment
emergency sump is a standard design and continued operation applied. 
Connecticut Yankee reiterated its position that the containment sump was of
standard design in 1986.  </P>
<P>Between 1988 and 1993, the NRC issued two information notices (88-28, &quot;Potential
for Loss of Post-LOCA Recirculation Capability Due to Insulation Debris
Blockage,&quot; and 89-77, &quot;Debris In Containment Emergency Sumps and
Incorrect Screen Configuration,&quot; and one NRC bulletin (93-02, &quot;Debris
Plugging of the Emergency Core Cooling Suction Strainer&quot;).  Clearly, NRC
had identified to the industry that the potential blockage of the ECCS was a
significant safety hazard. However, the federal regulator did very little to
ensure that the industry heeded these warnings.</P>
<P>By 1989, the licensee had determined that that emergency sump drawings used
to identify screen sizes were hand drawings, not actual design prints. The hand
drawings were based on discussions with individuals involved with the root cause
analysis at the time, who eventually decided that the actual size of the screen
could not be determined.  A walkdown of the sump area in 1990 concluded that the
mesh screen size was 3/8 inches.  Connecticut Yankee then installed a chain-link
fence around containment sump area to eliminate large pieces of debris from
being thrown into the sump area.  Combined with regular inspections during each
outage, Connecticut Yankee felt that existing policies and practices were
adequate to ensure that materials that could enter through the containment sump
and clog ECCS strainers did not remain in containment. </P>
<P>In February, 1996, Connecticut Yankee completed a containment sump
operability determination on potential loss of coolant due to debris transport. 
It is apparent that Connecticut Yankee used generic utility information to
conclude operability based on the 3/8 inch mesh size.</P>
<P>In July, 1996, the NRC inspection determined that mesh screen size was
actually 1/2 inch and had a gap opening in the screen measuring 3 inches by 3
feet.  This condition alone could have prevented the effective operation of the
ECCS following a nuclear accident at the reactor. That same month, Connecticut
Yankee removed 5 fifty-five gallon drums of sludge and debris including plastic,
tie wraps, bolts and nuts, and a pencil. </P>
<P>The NRC determined that &quot;the licensee's design basis documentation book
did not have any specific design information related to the containment sump.  
In conclusion, neither the UFSAR or the licensee's design basis documentation
contained sufficient design information regarding the containment sump.&quot;&lt;18&gt;
  NRC concluded that Connecticut Yankee displayed various performance weaknesses
consisting of &quot;inadequate configuration management&quot;, &quot;less that 
aggressive actions in response to generic information&quot;, &quot;inadequate
operability determinations&quot;, and a &quot;lack of design basis information.&quot;</P>
<H3>E.  NIRS  FILES AN ALLEGATION WITH NRC </H3>
<P>In reviewing NRC Integrated Inspection Report 50-213/96-08 pertaining to
Connecticut Yankee  Containment  Sump Pump Screen Design, Nuclear Information
and Resource Service noted that the report indicated that in 1966 the licensee's
architect and engineer, Stone &amp; Webster,  proposed specific changes to the
reactor containment sump.  The report indicates that the proposed changes were
implemented by Connecticut Yankee &quot;but not reflected in design drawing
16103-59018 sheets 10 and 11.&quot;&lt;19&gt; </P>
<P>The NRC inspection report additional notes a Connecticut Yankee walkdown in
July, 1996 where a number of discrepancies identified  the misinstallation of
important features to the sump containment design including improper orientation
of the grating, missing tack welds, wrong screen mesh size, and a gap in the
mesh measuring 0.75 feet square.     </P>
<P>The concern arises with the repeated Connecticut Yankee's claims to the NRC
that  the reactor's sump was a standard design.  As previously presented, the
NRC inspection report  documents the October 13, 1982, Connecticut Yankee reply
under oath to a NRC Request for Additional Information issued under 10 CFR
50.54(f) on July 9, 1982.  The same conclusion was reached by the utility again
in 1986 after Connecticut Yankee had initiated Integrated Safety Assessment
Program (ISAP) topic 1.53, &quot;Containment Emergency Sump Performance&quot; to
resolve issues associated with Unresolved Safety Issue A-43 pertaining to
containment emergency sumps. In the completed ISAP report dated in December,
1986, Connecticut Yankee concluded that USI A-43  could be closed because it was
determined that the emergency sump utilized a standard design.</P>
<P>How could Connecticut Yankee justify closing out the unresolved safety issue
when in fact the Stone &amp; Webster design modifications had not only been
implemented, but misinstalled?  More importantly, a sworn correspondence by the
licensee constitutes a misrepresentation of material fact adversely affecting
the Emergency Core Cooling System, a vital piece of safety-related equipment. 
</P>
<P>As a result of this finding, NIRS has filed a formal allegation with the NRC
to initiate an investigation into Connecticut Yankee's treatment of this long
standing and unresolved public safety issue.</P>
<H3>III.  A NEAR MISS ACCIDENT</H3>
<P>Late in August, 1996, with the reactor in a shutdown mode, a sequence of 
events unnoticed by reactor operators occurred over a three day period brought
the Connecticut Yankee atomic power plant precariously close to a
Loss-Of-Coolant-Accident.  As the result of operator errors and inoperable
equipment, this near miss accident is of particular concern to public health and
safety, given the documented and undocumented conditions that were already
adversely affecting crucial safety systems of the reactor.  </P>
<P>While adequate core cooling was maintained throughout the event, an NRC
inspection team reviewing the accident determined that this was a significant
precursor event potentially affecting public safety by involving:</P>
<UL>
<LI>the inadvertent introduction of non-condensible nitrogen gas to the reactor
vessel which   displaced cooling water in the reactor 
</LI>
<LI> operators were unaware of the actual cooling water level in the reactor
vessel because   instrumentation (the reactor vessel level indication system and
core exit temperature   indicators) had been disconnected in preparation for a
refueling operation which was   subsequently rescheduled
</LI>
<LI> the reactor cooling system came within 52 minutes of the boiling off
temperature which   would have commenced the loss of coolant accident 
</LI>
<LI> the water level in the reactor vessel decreased to approximately 2 1/2
feet above the   point of Residual Heat Removal (RHR) pump cavitation with
possible failure
</LI>
<LI> if the nitrogen bubble had continued to grow, it would have caused
cavitation of the   RHR pump
</LI>
<LI> two important  pieces of emergency core cooling system equipment were
already   inoperable with a through-wall leak in the body of RHR heat exchanger
and a seized RHR   pump
</LI>
<LI> two inadvertent drain downs of the reactor cooling system occurred
potentially causing    RHR pump failure
</LI>
<LI> if the RHR system were lost, timely restoration of cooling water to the
reactor would   have been difficult and potentially unavailable 
</LI>
</UL>
<P>A chronology of events leading up to this dangerous condition was documented
by the NRC inspection team as follows;&lt;20&gt;  </P>
<P>August 22-   A non-licensed operator at Connecticut Yankee failed to
properly align valves while working on the Residual Heat Removal purification
system in service.  This mistake resulted in diverting approximately 500 gallons
of reactor coolant water to the refueling storage tank. </P>
<P>August 28-   Connecticut Yankee had been in the process of correcting
excessive nitrogen gas usage to the volume control tank and had isolated a path
to the Reactor Cooling System.  The licensee believed that a continuous vent had
been established and that the non-condensible gases in the upper reactor vessel
head were being vented.  A  non-licensed operator failed to follow procedure and
incorrectly opened a valve that injected both water and nitrogen gas into the
Reactor Cooling System.  When the valve was closed it did not properly seat,
allowing non-condensible nitrogen gas to continue to leak into the reactor
cooling system through a volume control tank. The nitrogen gas began to
accumulate in the reactor vessel and displace cooling water, forcing it into the
reactor pressurizer. </P>
<P>August 29-  Operators drained approximately 5000 gallons of reactor coolant
water  from the reactor cooling system to prepare for refuel activities. In
preparation to remove the reactor vessel head, operators disconnected the
reactor vessel level indicator system (RVLIS). Later in the day, the operators
implemented  a schedule change and 1000 gallons of cooling water was restored to
the reactor vessel when the decision was made to suspend refueling operation
upon notification of a joint owners' requested economic analysis of the reactor.</P>
<P>August 31-  The nitrogen bubble reached a point of equilibrium. </P>
<P>September 1-  The nitrogen  gas leakage was isolated.  RHR pump failed to
start and was determined to be seized. </P>
<P>September 4-  During a preventive maintenance activity,  operators
inappropriately diverted an additional 300 gallons of cooling water from the
Reactor Cooling System inventory to the containment sump. </P>
<P>Over the course of this extended event before the gas bubble was detected,
the water level in the reactor vessel  eventually dropped 4 1/2 feet coming to
within 2 1/2 feet of exposing the intakes for the two RHR pumps responsible for
preventing the fuel core from overheating during shutdown.    </P>
<P>The followup NRC inspection team critical of Connecticut Yankee's handling
of the accident identified many of the procedural inadequacies and failures to
follow procedures among the root causes for the event.  These operator
deficiencies and failures included  poor procedural quality, failure to
implement procedure, lack of a questioning attitude, inappropriate decisions,
lack of  instrumentation, inadequate training, poor implementation of generic
information, weak use of technical information, and inappropriate planning and
scheduling of activities without a thorough review of safety implications.
Additionally, NRC determined that essential equipment was in poor condition.
</P>
<P>Surprisingly enough, the NRC did not identify that a contributing factor to
this event was Connecticut Yankee's failure to follow the federal regulations as
specified under 10 CFR 50.59.  As stated earlier in this report, Connecticut
Yankee is required by 10 CFR 50.59 to evaluate all changes to the station's
physical configuration and condition or any changes to procedures described in
the UFSAR that govern how the plant is operated. Specifically, the licensee is
required to identify any &quot;unreviewed safety issues.&quot;  The refueling
process is described in detail in the licensee's UFSAR. Had Connecticut Yankee
fulfilled its obligation under 10 CFR 50.59, it would have identified that the
operators cannot take away reactor vessel level system instrumentation
indefinitely.  When NU postponed refueling after taking several steps including
draining the vessel and disconnecting instrumentation, they altered the
refueling protocol.   Leaving the reactor sitting in such a condition without
reactor vessel instrumentation is a graphic and disturbing example of an &quot;unreviewed
safety issue&quot; and in violation of the reactor's licensing basis.  This
event clearly demonstrated that the risk to the public does not go away just
because the reactor is shutdown, and that NU failed to properly manage that
risk. </P>
<H3>IV.  WESTINGHOUSE STEAM GENERATORS AT CONNECTICUT YANKEE</H3>
<P>Of the 5 reactors Northeast Utilities operates  four are pressurized water
reactors (Connecticut Yankee, Millstone 2 &amp; 3, and Seabrook).  The utility
also operates Millstone Unit 1 which is a General Electric Boiling Water
Reactor.  </P>
<P>Connecticut Yankee is a Westinghouse-designed pressurized water reactor
(PWR).  The fundamental characteristic of the PWR is that the reactor's primary
coolant raises steam in a heat exchanger called a &quot;steam generator.&quot;  
Each of Connecticut Yankee's four steam generators consist of a primary coolant
loop comprised of thousands of steam generator tubes directly circulating water
from the reactor under high pressure (approx. 2250 psi) and high temperature
(6000 F). The high pressure does not allow the water to boil in the primary
coolant loop thus enabling a more efficient heat transfer.  In order to be
effective heat exchangers, the tubes are 3/4 inch in diameter with the tube's
wall being as thin as a dime.  The heat is exchanged in the steam generator
where water is allowed to turn to steam though a secondary loop that exits the
reactor containment building to power the turbogenerator.  One of Connecticut
Yankee's first indications of advanced aging and serious erosion of safety
standards was the deterioration of the unit's steam generators, first indicated
by the company in January, 1986. </P>
<P>Virtually all the nuclear industry's PWRs,  including the NU units, are
experiencing this accelerating deterioration of steam generator tubes because of
susceptibility of the metal alloy used to fabricate this large component to a
routine operational environment of radiation and fatigue.  The NRC has reported
that cracking of steam generator tubes is surging in US reactors.  Cracking and
other forms of degradation have been identified by NRC as having serious safety
implications because these tubes constitute a major reactor coolant pressure
boundary. NRC continues to evaluate operational and repair criteria for damaged
steam generator tubes. However, NRC most recently documented that if as few as
15 of these tubes were to simultaneously rupture, a rapid
loss-of-coolant-accident in the reactor would outpace the Emergency Core Cooling
System (ECCS). This would result in a meltdown of the reactor core. Because the
steam generators are equipped with pressure relief valves from the secondary
loop directly to the environment, a rupture of the primary coolant loop also
results in a radioactivity release from the reactor core which bypasses the
large containment structure with significant risk of a rapidly ensuing
catastrophic accident.&lt;21&gt;  </P>
<P>The NRC has issued numerous warnings about steam generator deterioration. In
describing the situation, Commissioner Kenneth Rogers stated that &quot;Degradation
would decrease the safety margins so that in essence, we have a loaded gun, an
accident waiting to happen.&quot;&lt;22&gt;   However, current NRC requirements
and industry standards for inspecting steam generator tubes are inadequate to
detect unsafe conditions developing in nuclear power plants. The NRC admits that
neither itself nor the industry are currently able to predict how fast cracks in
tubes can grow, noting that in the duration of one 18-month operational cycle a
reactor can experience a hundred-fold increase in cracked tubes&lt;23&gt;.</P>
<P>However, the extensive repair or replacement of steam generators is a costly
burden to the PWR operator; for the larger units upwards of $300 million.  In a
competitive electricity market such a price tag can significantly affect a
utility's operation of deteriorating units.  On May 10, 1993, Connecticut Yankee
management and engineering met with the NRC and informed the regulator,</P>
<P>&quot;Current preliminary economic evaluations of the Haddam Neck plant
effectively preclude steam generator replacement.  As such, avoiding unnecessary
tube plugging (in existing steam generators) is imperative to ensure continued
operation of the Haddam Neck plant until the end of licensed life.&quot;&lt;24&gt;
 Connecticut Yankee's piecemeal actions to save money on deteriorating equipment
is viewed as part of the overall industry and regulator's &quot;cost beneficial
licensing action.&quot;  The NRC argued there was nothing to be done until the
federal agency settled the generic issues dealing with steam generator tube
repair. Consequently, after plugging a number of the deteriorated tubes, 
Connecticut Yankee went back into full power operation with its eroding steam
generators.  By early 1995, Connecticut Yankee discovered during the next
refueling outage that one of the plugged tubes in steam generator number 4 had
ruptured, apparently due to steam pressure leaking around the installed plug
repair&lt;25&gt;.  </P>
<P>Both NU and the NRC have gambled that the &quot;loaded gun&quot; would not
go off in the remaining 15 years of Connecticut Yankee' operating license.  
However, ongoing deterioration at  Connecticut Yankee and the other Northeast
Utilities PWR stations places the public health and safety at increased risk.
The problem of steam generator aging strikes at the very basis of reactor safety
at all of NU's units where a &quot;margin of safety&quot; at operating reactors
continues to erode. </P>
<H3>V. TRITIUM RELEASES INTO THE ENVIRONMENT</H3>
<P>Tritium is a radionuclide produced as a by-product of fissioning of fuel
elements in nuclear power reactors.  Tritium, the third radioactive isotope of
hydrogen, has a hazardous life of 12.5 years.  Although tritium occurs in nature
formed as a result of cosmic rays through the Earth's atmosphere, nuclear
installations are by far the largest source of radioactive hydrogen.  Tritium is
carcinogenic (causing cancer), mutagenic (causing genetic mutation), and
teratogenic (causing birth defects).  The environment and communities living
downwind or downstream of nuclear power plants can be considered to be in a &quot;tritium
effluent pathway&quot;.  Humans can be exposed to tritium through organically
bound tritium (OBT) by way of ingestion of contaminated plants and animals in a
tritium effluent pathway, in addition to direct uptake by inhalation of
tritiated water (HTO) vapor, absorption, or drinking of contaminated water or
the inhalation of tritiated gas (HT).  HTO is considered by the International
Commission On Radiological Protection (ICRP) to be 25,000 times more hazardous
in air than HT because of its mobility and uptake.   Because it is a low energy
beta emitter, tritium is very difficult to detect in air without expensive
equipment.  However while it is a &quot;weak&quot; radiocnuclide, unable to
penetrate human skin, once inside the body following the path for normal
hydrogen molecules through ingestion, inhalation, or absorbed, it can intimately
incorporate with the DNA structure of its host, causing considerable damage at
the most critical site for radiation exposure.  </P>
<P>Since no economically feasible process exists to separate and remove tritium
for regular hydrogen in the cooling water effluent at nuclear power plants, the
nuclear industry is not required to remove it.  Therefore, whatever tritium
accumulates in the cooling water is ultimately released into the environment,
either with the gaseous emissions to the atmosphere, or with liquid released to
the plant's cooling water source.  In Connecticut Yankee's case, this cooling
water source and discharge tributary is the Connecticut River.  </P>
<P>According to NRC records, Connecticut Yankee has released a total of 75,075
curies of tritium into the Connecticut River between 1974 and 1993. The Haddam
Neck reactor has the dubious distinction of releasing on the order of a
magnitude (ten times) more tritium in liquid discharges than any other nuclear
reactor in the United States including reactors twice its size.&lt;26&gt;</P>
<H3>VI. THE DECOMMISSIONING  OF CONNECTICUT YANKEE</H3>
<P>Once a decision is made to permanently close Connecticut Yankee, the issue
of what to do with the intensely radioactive facility must be addressed. This is
referred to as the decommissioning stage.  During decommissioning, the nuclear
fission reaction is stopped and the fuel is permanently removed and placed in
the fuel pool storage area, allowing that storage space has not already been
filled to capacity.  The remainder of the facility is highly radioactively
contaminated in the area of the reactor vessel. Contaminated areas must be
controlled to reduce worker exposure to radioactivity.  Under new NRC
regulations, NU has a number of options ranging from placing the defueled
reactor in storage to allow for radioactive decay or to begin the prompt
dismantlement of the nuclear station.  </P>
<P>The NRC issued its amended regulations as a final rule &quot;Decommissioning
of Nuclear Power Reactors&quot; in the Federal Register on July 29, 1996.&lt;27&gt;
  In a major change,  the amended rule now provides that nuclear power licensees
are no longer required to have an approved decommissioning plan before being
permitted to perform major decommissioning activities.  Under the new rule,
licensees are allowed to perform major decommissioning activities such as
segmentation, removal, transport, and burial of large radioactive components
(i.e. steam generators, large and small diameter piping, etc.) through the
application of 10 CFR 50.59.  The NRC has amended the 10 CFR 50.59 process to
provide the licensee with the option to include major decommissioning activities
under the same requirements as routine activities performed while the reactor
was operational.  As stated earlier in this report, the provision allows
operators to make modifications to physical features at the reactor and analysis
of safety issues, so long as the modifications do not constitute an &quot;unreviewed
safety issue.&quot;    As defined by 10 CFR 50.59, an ureviewed safety issue is
defined as any activity which increases the likelihood or consequences of a
previously evaluated accident, introduces a new type of accident or reduces
safety margins at the reactor. </P>
<P>However, in order to safely conduct any proposed activities under 10 CFR
50.59 and demonstrate that there are &quot;no unreviewed safety issues,&quot; a
licensee must have its design and licensing bases in order and updated with
regard to all previous changes to systems, structures, and components along with
any modifications made to their safety analysis. These previous modifications
are documented at a minimum through the reactor's Updated Final Safety Analysis
Report (UFSAR) and Technical Specifications. </P>
<P>As has been amply documented by this report, NU did not regard the UFSAR for
any of its Connecticut reactors as a document that was required to be accurate. 
The NRC identified in its special inspection report of July 31, 1996 that NU had
not been updating its Connecticut Yankee UFSAR. In some cases, changes were made
to the UFSAR without a 10 CFR 50.59 evaluation for &quot;unreviewed safety
issues.&quot; In other cases, changes were made to the station without even
documenting modifications in the UFSAR.  As a result, Connecticut Yankee's
design and licensing basis is in such disarray and so defective, that it can not
be solely relied upon to perform any current safety evaluations under 10 CFR
50.59 for either the purpose of restart or decommissioning.   </P>
<P>In preparation for restart, Connecticut Yankee initiated a comprehensive
Configuration Management Program (CMP) during 1996.  The CMP tasks included
reviewing all correspondence to and from the NRC to identify commitments and
then determining if these commitments were satisfied by the plant design and
operation. Safety systems were being evaluated under the CMP to determine if
these systems could adequately perform their required functions. Another CMP
task involved a major update to the UFSAR to incorporate literally hundreds of
physical changes made to the facility over the years that had not been reflected
in the plant's safety analyses.  When the recommendation to permanently close
Haddam Neck was announced in early October 1996, the CMP effort was essentially
disbanded without having completed any of its tasks.  The objective of the CMP
was to provide the necessary assurance that Haddam Neck complied with all safety
regulations prior to restarting the plant -- equal assurance is required to
ensure safety during decommissioning activities.</P>
<P>The NRC has stated in its amended decommissioning rule that the &quot;systems
required for maintaining the spent fuel in the spent fuel pool as well as the
operations required to contain the remaining residual contamination in the
facility and spent fuel pool are relatively simple.  Consequently, the
activities performed by the licensee during decommissioning do not have a
significant potential to impact public health and safety and these require
considerably less oversight by the NRC than during power operations.&quot;&lt;28&gt;
 </P>
<P>To the contrary, the authors of this report contend that NU, through its
common course of business over the operational life of the Connecticut Yankee
atomic power station and  other Connecticut reactors, has demonstrated the need
for intensified regulatory oversight of any subsequent decommissioning process
with an open and full public hearing process up front of any dismantlement or
decommissioning project. Absent an accurate updated UFSAR,  the licensee does
not have a reliable blueprint for disassembling the reactor.</P>
<H3>VII.  NRC HAS DEFERRED ITS RESPONSIBILITY TO ENFORCE REGULATIONS</H3>
<P>The fact that Connecticut Yankee is not on the NRC's Problem Plants list
despite the untimely disclosure of long-term non-conformance with safety
regulations is more evidence of the historical absence of NRC regulatory
oversight and enforcement over decades of reactor operation.   While the NRC has
conducted five evaluations of its reactor inspection program since 1989,  there
remains evidence of a serious lack of NRC regulatory oversight to prioritize
public health and safety interests over the commercial interests of the nuclear
utilities the agency is mandated to regulate.&lt;29&gt;   </P>
<P>An NRC Inspector General (OIG) report issued on May 31, 1996 revealed that
despite increased regulatory scrutiny in the form of stepped up inspections and
evaluations, the NRC staff determined that serious deficiencies persisted at
NU's Millstone units that had been identified in 1991.  The OIG reported that
the staff continued to document a general decline in the level of performance at
NU's Millstone site including failure to follow design procedures, failure to 
implement corrective actions, and failure to have operability determinations
completely incorporated into procedures.   A number of recommendations made by
managers at the NRC Division of Reactor Projects  to place Millstone on the NRC
Problem Plant Watch List are documented in the OIG inquiry.  In each instance,
the NRC Region I office failed to take action.  Eventually,  the units were
placed on the NRC Problem Plants Watch List in January, 1996.  As a result of
the OIG questioning, the NRC Executive Director of Operations, the Director of
Nuclear Reactor Regulation, and Region I Regional  Administrator admitted that
given the steady decline and poor performance indicators at the NU reactor site
, the NRC should have taken more aggressive action including placing the
reactors on the watchlist as early as 1993.  OIG additionally identified a
senior resident safety inspector at Millstone who stated in his opinion, NRC had
sufficient basis to place Millstone on the watchlist following a
safety-significant event in August, 1993 that demonstrated NU's disregard for
safety. </P>
<P>According to the OIG report, however, in 1991 NU hired corporate consultant
firm, LRS Incorporated, to develop a NU &quot;game plan&quot; to defuse negative
perceptions of the utility's poor performance being generated by the regulatory
agency with the suggestion of &quot;a full court press at all levels of NRC to
prevent the Millstone site from being placed on the troubled plant list.&quot;&lt;30&gt;
   According to the OIG interview of the NRC Region I Administrator, the plan
was made available to the NRC Regional I office, however, the Administrator
could not specifically recall from whom, when or how he had received the LRS
document or whether he subsequently discussed it with NRC staff.  The NU delay
strategy was apparently successfully until January 1996, when the units were
placed on the NRC watchlist.  </P>
<P>NU's tactics &quot;to defuse&quot; the federal regulator effectively
postponed NRC actions to uncover pervasive non-compliance with regulations
pertaining to the design and licensing bases of the reactors and take some
measure of appropriate enforcement action.  This effort was achieved at the
expense of the public's health and safety.   It is of tremendous concern that
delays in enforcement action by NRC either to bring the licensees into
compliance or permanently close the reactors constitute a serious deferral of
NRC authority to protect the public health and safety to the commercial interest
of the utility.  The public is rightfully concerned that this deferral of
enforcement action constitutes continued accommodation by the NRC of unsafe
industry practices in the economic interests of the nuclear licensees.</P>
<H3>VIII.  CONCLUSION AND RECOMMENDATIONS</H3>
<P>The public health and safety is significantly jeopardized by NU's negligent
practices, harassment and intimidation of  workers who seek to reveal and
resolve safety issues,  misrepresentation of filings and incomplete
documentation to safety records at its nuclear power plants.  Evidence uncovered
by the Office of the Inspector General pointing to utility efforts orchestrated
to deliberately confound and evade effective regulation by NRC raises further
questions and concerns that the utility is unfit to operate nuclear power
plants.</P>
<P>Therefore, the following recommendations are presented:</P>
<P>1)  NU's Connecticut Yankee Atomic Power Plant must be promptly and
permanently shutdown.  </P>
<P>The NRC should immediately revoke the operating licenses for the Connecticut
Yankee.  It is not economically feasible to bring the reactor to any kind of &quot;acceptable&quot;
safety standard.   The design and licensing bases for this aging atomic power
plant is in such disarray and so defective due to poorly documented and
undocumented conditions that current safety evaluations cannot be relied upon
for restart.   During NU's common course of business at its Connecticut
reactors, the utility has demonstrated gross mismanagement, negligence to
observe safety regulations and a concerted effort to obfuscate regulatory
efforts designated to protect the public health and safety.  These repeated and
serious violations represent a  breach of conditions for  the company's
operating license. </P>
<P>2)  Similarly, the operating license for Millstone units 1, 2 and 3 should
be permanently revoked by NRC.</P>
<P>3)  Criminal investigations of NU now underway by the Department of Justice
involving allegations of deliberate withholding of information and
misrepresentation of material fact should be expanded to include potential
wrongdoing at Connecticut Yankee Atomic Power Station. </P>
<P>NRC findings revealing NU mismanagement and negligence in identifying
serious deficiencies in the CY design and licensing basis dating back to the
initial startup of the reactor raise significant questions into the accuracy and
intent of NU operability assessments. The fact that repeated opportunities were
missed by the utility to catch mistakes adversely affecting reactor safety and
the public health  raises further questions with regard to the utility's intent
comply with regulations promulgated to protect the public health and safety. 
</P>
<P>4)  With the immediate closure of the Connecticut Yankee and Millstone
units,  the NRC should intensify its regulatory oversight of any subsequent
decommissioning process which would include an open and full public hearing
process up front of any dismantlement or decommissioning activities.</P>
<P>As stated earlier, Connecticut Yankee's design and licensing bases are in
such disarray and so defective, they can not be relied upon to perform any
further safety evaluations under 10 CFR 50.59 for the purpose of 
decommissioning. Effectively, NU does not have a workable blueprint to conduct
decommissioning activities that fully regard the safety of workers,  the public
and the environment.</P>
<P>5)  Northeast Utilities must be retasked to update Connecticut Yankee's
UFSAR, discontinued with the suspension of its comprehensive Configuration
Management Program (CMP) during 1996, and incorporate all physical changes that
have been made to the facility over the years not reflected in the plant's
safety analyses. </P>
<P>6) There should be a thorough and  independent review of  the accuracy of
UFSARs for NU's Connecticut Yankee and Millstone units before any subsequent
major activity such as decommissioning. </P>
<P>7)   A comprehensive review should be completed of  the NRC inspection
process under the auspices of the Office of the Inspector General to determine
how the NRC's  regulatory oversight missed the long-standing  problems at
Connecticut Yankee. The review should address inspection and oversight issues at
the levels of on-site inspectors, NRC Regional I Administration Office and the
Project Manager Office at NRC Headquarters in Rockville, Maryland.</P>
<P>ABOUT THE AUTHORS</P>
<P><B>Nuclear Information and Resource Service</B> (NIRS) founded in 1978, is
the Washington, DC-based nonprofit tax-exempt safe energy organization providing
information and assistance to media and grassroots concerns on the effects of
nuclear power and nuclear waste issues and renewable energy alternatives to
nuclear power. NIRS participates in a number of nuclear regulatory proceedings,
including rulemakings, enforcement actions, adjudication, and as an advocate for
industry whistleblowers and the public health and safety. Paul Gunter is
Director of the Reactor Watchdog Project.</P>
<P><B>Citizens Awareness Network </B>(CAN) is a non-profit public interest
group founded in 1991 with members located near the Rowe nuclear power plant in
Massachusetts, Vermont Yankee nuclear power plant in Vermont, the Connecticut
Yankee and Millstone nuclear power plants in Connecticut, and the Seabrook
reactor in New Hampshire. CAN is concerned with the entire nuclear fuel cycle
from the mining of uranium through reactor operations, decommissioning, and the
establishment of radioactive waste disposal sites.  Debroah Katz is President of
CAN and a resident of Shelburne Falls, MA.  Rosemary Bassilakis is a researcher
with CAN and resides in Haddam, CT.</P>
<P>Additional copies of this report can be reproduced or made are available by
contacting:</P>
